<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLYGAMOUS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RARE LOOK INSIDE THE LIFE OF A POLYGAMIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLORADO CITY, Ariz. _ It was 4:25 p.m. at Justin's house and
the welcome call ``Come to dinner!'' went out over the intercom.
From all over the 35,000-square-foot, 31-bedroom home the kids came
pouring into the cafeteria-size dining room.
</P>
<P>
   Boys in long-sleeve shirts and girls in long dresses ran and
hopped down a circular staircase from the two floors above. Infants
sucking on pacifiers sat contentedly on couches. Toddlers waddled
toward play balls in the corners of the big room.
</P>
<P>
   Justin, 45, sat and smiled amid the clang of silverware and
plates as many of his 10 wives and 28 children consumed the
contents of three casserole dishes of enchiladas.
</P>
<P>
   Justin is not his real name; he asked that he and his wives
remain anonymous in exchange for granting a rare glimpse of
polygamous life in this fiercely secretive community on the
Utah-Arizona state line.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lifestyle, he and his wives said, based on deeply held
beliefs about Earth and heaven and about the nature of man and
woman.
</P>
<P>
   It's one in which Justin's wives say they willingly give up
monogamy and privacy because they love living with their ``sister
wives'' and with many children growing up as brothers and sisters.
</P>
<P>
   And it's also one, Justin conceded, in which he and his wives
must work harder than most families to cope with dizzying
scheduling problems and occasional jealousies. They even have to
deal with such arcane issues as making sure they are producing a
diversified gene pool.
</P>
<P>
   It is, Justin said, a ``boringly normal'' lifestyle, even as he
hints that there is room for five more wives to join the fold _ and
that he might need to add to the house's dozen washers and dryers.
</P>
<P>
   Which is fine with Liz, wife No. 4 of the millionaire financial
consultant who built the $3 million mansion for his polygamist
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't bother me as long as I have my own room,'' said
Liz, an acerbic woman in her early 40s who speaks of her husband in
almost mystical tones.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Liz can't figure out why the fifth and sixth women who
married Justin flew the coop rather than stay and prepare
themselves for the highest part of the celestial kingdom _ the part
she believes is reserved for those in plural marriages.
</P>
<P>
   But Liz does have a theory: ``Number 6 was an only child and
found out she couldn't deal with this. And Number 5 could not
accept it when Number 6 became a reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Mormon pioneers brought their polygamous beliefs to the West in
the mid-1800s. But the practice was outlawed in 1896, under
pressure from the federal government, as a condition of Utah's
receiving statehood. Today, the estimated 50,000 current
practitioners are facing tough times.
</P>
<P>
   A group of ex-polygamist wives has been lobbying the Utah
Legislature to crack down on the practice.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, two members of Utah's prominent polygamist Kingston
family have been arrested on incest and child-abuse charges.
Published reports have linked residents of Colorado City and
neighboring Hildale, Utah, to extensive welfare fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Many polygamists living in the sparsely populated Arizona Strip
north of the Grand Canyon, believe it's all part of a concerted
effort by the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.
</P>
<P>
   They claim that the church, which went on record against plural
marriage in 1890, wants to drive polygamists further underground
before the world's press descends on Salt Lake City for the 2002
Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   So Justin said he wanted to clear up some popular misconceptions
about life inside the large, warehouse-like homes that were built
because of the inaccessibility of this area even in modern times.
</P>
<P>
   True, his lavish master bedroom may look fit for a queen, with
its Jacuzzi, fireplace and expensive hard-wood furniture. But
shortly after his two youngest wives, ages 24 and 26, stared
longingly at him in the dining room, Justin insisted that he's not
some testosterone-drenched madman bouncing from bed to bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a specific need for one of them to get pregnant,
you accommodate that,'' Justin said diplomatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``You also try to handle the other physical needs of the other
ladies. If you persist in neglecting someone, you're challenged by
all of them. Plus, the older ladies insist on having young children
in the house.''
</P>
<P>
   IT ISN'T ABOUT SEX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the plural-marriage lifestyle isn't about sex, said
Justin, himself raised in a polygamist household in Colorado City
with 32 siblings.
</P>
<P>
   It's about finding women who propagate a lifestyle, he said.
Women with skills such as sewing, cooking and gardening are much in
demand in the huge households.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Justin said, after one of Colorado City's oldest
patriarchs died a year ago, leaving behind nine wives, he was
approached by the community fathers about becoming husband to two
of them. He quickly agreed to bring in a 52-year-old and
45-year-old into the household.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, he became their ``husband'' only in a
fundamentalist Mormon interpretation of the word. Polygamists
typically marry their first wife in the law, then shy away from any
paperwork concerning the others, although the women normally take
the man's last name.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the problem of diversifying the gene pool to
address a common problem in polygamist communities where
intermarriage is common. Six of Justin's wives, who have borne most
of his children, were raised in mainstream _ monogamous _ Mormon
homes in Utah and Idaho. &QL; 
THE PECKING ORDER &QL; 
In most polygamist households, the pecking order among wives is
determined by the order in which they were hitched. That often
presents problems, as a patriarch's sexual urges typically are
centered on the youngest, latest arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a while to get over the jealousy and the feelings of
being left out,'' Liz said. ``But you can't live monogamy here and
have celestial life (after death) on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to buy in totally to the religion to make this
work.''
</P>
<P>
   And Liz, who has eight children with Justin in their 18 years
together and is an executive in his business, is a true believer.
She snickered when asked whether she would consider an arrangement
in which she had numerous husbands.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the nature of woman,'' she said. ``If she finds a
good man, she will stay with him forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Gloria, 52, quickly concurs. She came on board last year after
her polygamist husband of 36 years died. One of his nine wives, she
married when she was 15 and he was 56.
</P>
<P>
   ``One woman doesn't have the capacity to take care of one man
and the needs he has,'' Gloria said. ``I wouldn't have it any other
way. I love living with my sister wives and I can't live without
all the children around.''
</P>
<P>
   One of them, a little 2-year-old boy, walked clumsily up to
Justin at dinner time, grabbed his leg and yelled, ``Dad!''
</P>
<P>
   Another child was playing with a wet, white washcloth, which
Justin took from him after the child swung it wildly and almost hit
some other children. He went crying to his mother, who told him to
go back to Justin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want you playing with it,'' Justin said sternly.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' responded the child, who fell silent and wiped the tears
from his cheeks. &QL; 
NO CORPORAL PUNISHMENT &QL; 
Justin says there's no corporal punishment in the house, but there
is a liberal use of timeouts for children who act up. The 11 adults
reach a consensus on household issues and abide by it, he added,
since ``we can't have a dozen sets of rules here.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Justin said he does almost everything communally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We group kids by age and put them in rooms together,'' he
said. ``They are all brothers and sisters in this family, not half
brothers and half sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   He notes a framed picture prominently displayed on the wall in
the room of another of his wives. A group of six small children
beam at the camera, dressed in their Sunday best. Each has a
different mother.
</P>
<P>
   Justin also has bought seven vehicles for family use as needed.
No child in this household should expect a new car at age 16, if
ever. A lot of thought also goes into trips to the toy store.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never bring back a single ball here,'' he said with the
look of a man who has felt his children's pain. ``It's always six
of this or that.''
</P>
<P>
   The kids have quite a playground within the walls of the 5-acre
estate. There's a tennis court and a basketball court with six
baskets. There's a large trampoline and a grassy area big enough
for a football field. The back yard even hosted the community's
Fourth of July fireworks celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Justin said he seldom does anything individually with his
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always take three or four out with me to pull weeds or to
go over to our ranch in Nevada,'' he said. ``I got the brilliant
idea once to take the family to Disneyland.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be more than he bargained for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ended up taking groups over there all summer,'' he
chuckled. &QL; 
UNUSUAL HOUSEHOLD &QL; 
Justin's household is unusual in this plural-marriage community in
one significant way: Unlike most polygamists, he is a wealthy man
who apparently makes enough money to support a comfortable
lifestyle for him and his large family.
</P>
<P>
   That lifestyle also is supplemented heavily by the women, all of
whom work outside the house. Half of his wives have executive
positions in his business interests, Justin said.
</P>
<P>
   A full third of his house, where he entertains guests, features
elevated ceilings, a formal dining and sitting room and fine
furniture. His office and master bedroom are also in that area.
</P>
<P>
   Kayla, Justin's ninth wife, said she doesn't make it over to
that part of the house much. She also said she's still trying to
make amends with the rest of her mainstream LDS family after
deciding to become Justin's wife 4{ years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother gave me a secret code word to call him anytime I
want to leave,'' said Kayla, cradling her newborn child.
</P>
<P>
   She rolled her eyes in an ``as if'' look.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'll call,'' she said, a wide smile creasing her dimpled
cheek. Her sister wives at the table laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Liz deadpanned: ``We are all just a bunch of sniveling, whining
little boobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin just took it all in, a proud smile on his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised with the beauties of this lifestyle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for monogamous men because they are tied up in
the whims of one woman.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Mark Shaffer can be reached at 444-8057 or at mark.shaffer &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
