<HEADER>
A9307 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MCHALE-COLUMN-LAD     08-30 1326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MCHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIAZZA COULDN'T HAVE SAVED THIS SINKING SHIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ From the batter's box to the upper deck, there was
plenty of emotion Friday night in Mike Piazza's return to Dodger
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   There he was, the former Dodgers catcher putting up Hall of Fame
numbers for someone else. When Piazza homered in the sixth inning,
it was his fifth in eight games and 26th for the year. The fans
felt compelled to boo because that's what you do to the other team.
</P>
<P>
   After the 5-4 Mets victory, Piazza talked about the nervousness,
the crowd and the regret he has over the circumstances leading to
the May 15 trade that sent him to the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost like going on a roller coaster,'' Piazza said of
his first game back. ``You're scared before you get on it. Once you
get on, you realize it really wasn't so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza turned down baseball's biggest contract extension, six
years for $85 million. His handlers called it an insult. Now, a
month from free agency, he is unlikely to get anything near that.
</P>
<P>
   While the fans wonder what might have been, the truth is, even
if Piazza stayed in Los Angeles, the Dodgers would still be going
nowhere this year.
</P>
<P>
   They still would be underachieving because of the rudderless
trinity of Piazza, Eric Karros and Todd Zeile. They're all
excellent players, but leadership has never been their thing. They
still would have lost Ramon Martinez and Jose Vizcaino for the
season to injuries and Eric Young for 34 games with a strained left
thigh.
</P>
<P>
   And they still would be buried under a mountain of guaranteed
contracts for next season that will make rebuilding difficult
unless the new owners at Fox don't mind pushing the payroll to $80
million.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers already have committed $53 million to 12 players for
1999. Bobby Bonilla even has acknowledged the Dodgers can't trade
him with two years and almost $12 million left on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   So you're saying, ``Exactly. Bonilla and Gary Sheffield, two of
the guys the Dodgers got for Piazza, will make a combined $17
million next year. The Dodgers could have saved money giving Piazza
the $15 million over seven years he wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   But it would not have solved the team's most glaring needs. They
gambled that Martinez could return to be the No.1 starter after a
rotator cuff injury and got burned. This year he finally underwent
surgery when the right shoulder broke down again and they know he
won't be back until next June, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with Martinez was compounded when Chan Ho Park
failed to step up this year as the No.1 pitcher. And they knew deep
down that fired manager Bill Russell was right, that Hideo Nomo was
done, but they were so tied to his marketing potential that they
were shackled with his fading fastball. They should thank Nomo for
forcing them to trade him.
</P>
<P>
   What that all means is the Dodgers need Kevin Brown, who hasn't
lost for San Diego since May. He is a free agent. He also could get
$9 million-$10 million a season.
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation that the Angels are interested in
Piazza. Brown makes a lot more sense if they are serious about more
than a division title and a first-round loss in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Getting Brown still wouldn't address the leadership problems
that Boston's Mo Vaughn, another free agent, would solve. That's
$10 million more.
</P>
<P>
   Add it up and the Dodgers are in trouble, with or without Mike
Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage Clemens: Roger Clemens starts today for Toronto after
striking out 18 Kansas City Royals in his 3-0 victory last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He is 11-0 in 16 starts going back to his last loss May 29
against Cleveland _ matching the major-league high for consecutive
wins this season (San Diego's Brown) and franchise record for
consecutive wins (Clemens won his first 11 decisions with the Blue
Jays in 1997 and Dennis Lamp was 11-0 in 1985.)
</P>
<P>
   ``He was as close to unhittable as you can be,'' said the
Royals' Dean Palmer, who had one of the three singles. ``I don't
think he made a mistake the whole night.''
</P>
<P>
   As in his two 20-strikeout games, (vs. Mariners in '86, Tigers
in '96) he had no walks. He now has 209 strikeouts, four behind
league-leader Randy Johnson (213). He's also at 3,091 all-time,
just 26 short of Bob Gibson's 3,117 for 10th on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens clearly is making a case for an unprecedented fifth Cy
Young Award. Greg Maddux and Steve Carlton have four each.
</P>
<P>
   In 11 starts dating to July 5, he is 7-0 with a 1.04 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   All this after May 29, when he was 5-6 with a 3.50 era. Since
the July 31 trading deadline, when the Blue Jays talked about
moving Clemens to a contender, he is 3-0 in five starts with five
earned runs in 41 innings. Clemens is still uncertain about what he
wants to do next year, the third season in a four-year contract
worth $31.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Another purge: The Twins traded former Dodger Mike Morgan to the
Chicago Cubs this past week, and more deals are on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating loses of $10 million-$13 million this season,
Minnesota Twins management is hoping to trim the payroll from $27
million to at least $20 million. The expected retirement of Paul
Molitor ($4 million) will account for much of that.
</P>
<P>
   Next on the block is Bob Tewksbury, who on Wednesday made his
first start since July 14. Tewksbury is making $1.75 million this
season and will be a free agent. He too is not expected back in
1999 and the Twins will try to get something for him by Monday's
postseason trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   With Morgan gone, the Twins have options on two remaining
veterans for next season: catcher Terry Steinbach, who is scheduled
to make $2.3 million next year or be offered a club buyout of
$500,000; and Otis Nixon, who is scheduled to make $1.7 million.
There is no buyout on Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   It is believed Steinbach will be invited back and that the club
will not exercise its option on Nixon, who has played in only 90 of
the team's 130 games this season.
</P>
<P>
   Victory at last: Cleveland's Dave Burba was 10-5 in 17 starts
before the All-Star break. In his first eight starts after the
break, he went 0-4 with a 5.13 ERA before finally beating Seattle
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't worried that I wouldn't get another win,'' Burba
said, who has been bothered by elbow problems in the second half.
``When you win 10 in the first half, you figure you're going to win
11 eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   Burba and the Indians are talking about a contract extension,
but both sides have agreed to put off talks until the end of the
year. He has one year left on his contract and could demand a trade
at the end of the year. But he says that won't happen.
</P>
<P>
   News and notes: The Padres' Andy Ashby bailed Friday in his
third attempt to win No.17 and has lasted just 32/3 innings in each
of his past two starts. In those games he has allowed 16 runs and
19 hits.... Giants catchers have failed to throw out base stealers
in 20 of the past 22 attempts.... Devon White's 20 home runs for
Arizona are the most he has hit since he had 24 for the Angels in
1987.... Mark McGwire needs 30 walks in the final 28 games to break
Babe Ruth's record of 170 walks in 1923. He had two Friday against
Maddux, who came in with just 31 walks in 2112/3 innings.... The
Detroit Tigers have been outscored 121-57 in the first inning this
season.... The Orioles have dropped six straight and seven of eight
since opening the second half 30-7.... Finally, on the weekend of
the Little League World Series in Williamsport, Pa., Sean
Burroughs, star of back-to-back winners for Long Beach six years
ago, has been offered $2.1 million by the Padres. It is believed to
be the biggest bonus offered a high school draftee this year.
Burroughs, the Padres' No.1 selection, has the option of attending
USC, which opens classes this week. If he begins classes at USC,
the Padres lose his rights. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
