<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILLIPS PICKS UP PIECES WITH METS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A few years ago in another league and another
city, a heckler was all over Tony Phillips, and the language got a
little too personal. When Phillips was pulled from the game, he put
on his street clothes, went into the stands and duked it out with
the guy.
</P>
<P>
   Of incidents like that were a reputation made for Phillips. He
fought with opponents. He bumped with umpires. He clashed with
managers. He was arrested in August 1997 for buying $30 worth of
rock cocaine from a police informant at an Anaheim motel, leading
to a 10-day suspension that helped to undo the Angels'
division-title drive.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after half a season of unemployment, Phillips is back in
action with the New York Mets, desperate for a leadoff hitter who
could do to opponents what he has done to the Dodgers this weekend,
when he has reached base in eight of 11 plate appearances.
</P>
<P>
   And in every National League city there's a heckler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crackhead!'' somebody will yell.
</P>
<P>
   To which Phillips has a withering response.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shoe fits,'' he said, unleashing a cackling laugh,
Saturday at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In other words: It's true.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened. So what can you say? `Yeah _ and ...?
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake. I admitted the mistake. And I go on.''
</P>
<P>
   From which we might conclude that Tony Phillips, now 39 years
old, has changed, has grown up, has learned to walk away.
</P>
<P>
   Or that he hasn't changed at all.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips was a standup guy in his few months with the Angels,
the player most likely to face up to reporters' hard questions
after a defeat. It says something that so many people who know him
have rooted for his successful return.
</P>
<P>
   And he's a standup guy now, facing up to a hideous mistake,
completing a drug-diversion program that could lead to the
dismissal of cocaine charges, and setting out to prove himself to a
new team and a new league.
</P>
<P>
   Unsigned by the Angels, he turned down offers from four teams,
including the Mets, for $500,000 or less. He complained that clubs
were ``trying to get me for nothing'' and was taken to task by at
least one columnist. This columnist.
</P>
<P>
   I thought he should face facts: A baseball player with drugs on
his record is no longer worth the $1.8 million he made in '97.
Especially when he's older than some of the general managers he's
negotiating with.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips says now that money wasn't the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just the way they approached me,'' he said. They
approached him like a time bomb, trouble waiting to happen. He was
insulted.
</P>
<P>
   And Phillips was in no hurry. He went home to Scottsdale, Ariz.,
enjoyed the spring with his wife and two daughters, and ``was
playing doubleheaders _ 18 (holes) in the morning and 18 holes
after lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, the Toronto Blue Jays said the right things, Phillips
lowered his price, and on July 17 they became his fifth
major-league team. He hit .348 in 12 games for the Blue Jays before
the Mets traded a minor-league pitcher to acquire him July 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the one to judge him,'' said Mets GM Steve Phillips
(who was 18 when Tony Phillips broke into the majors with the
Oakland A's in '82). ``The legal system did.''
</P>
<P>
   And now the verdict is in on the Mets' decision. Outstanding
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine had used everybody from Brian McRae to
Luis Lopez as a leadoff hitter. Now it's Phillips and forget it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a true leadoff hitter. He doesn't have to get a hit to
make a difference,'' McRae said.
</P>
<P>
   Tell it to the Dodgers. Friday night, Phillips drew four
consecutive walks, one of them crucial to a three-run,
seventh-inning rally in a 10-inning game the Mets won 5-4.
Saturday, he already had a walk, a single and a double when he came
to the plate with two outs in the ninth and the Mets down a run.
</P>
<P>
   To a tired relief pitcher like Jeff Shaw, a little guy batting
in an exaggerated crouch is 175 pounds of sheer panic. Phillips
fouled off a fastball, then worked Shaw for a walk to keep the game
going.
</P>
<P>
   The next hitter, Edgardo Alfonzo, hit a two-strike home run to
win it 4-3. The Mets lead the NL wild-card race because of
Phillips, because of his high-decibel presence in a once-quiet
clubhouse and because of his knack for making something happen on
the field.
</P>
<P>
   He has reached base in 26 of the 29 games he has played for the
Mets. Only the late start will keep him from walking 100 times in a
season for the sixth time _ numbers you'd expect only from a guy of
Mark McGwire's dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to take a walk. That's the battle within the battle
for a leadoff hitter,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   If he has also learned to walk away from trouble, the Mets have
a winner at the top of the lineup. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
