r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     08-30 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS STING SHAW WITH NINTH-INNING HOME RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With a month to go, the Dodgers have nothing left
and neither does Jeff Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' part is predictable. They've been this way since
spring training. The Jeff Shaw part is alarming, but maybe it
shouldn't be.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's trail of blown saves continued Saturday afternoon when he
allowed a two-out, two-run, ninth-inning homer by Edgardo Alfonzo
which gave the New York Mets a 4-3 victory in front of 49,181 at
Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But the lost velocity and poor location which has plagued him
through a stretch of five appearances and three blown saves in the
past six games actually goes back to earlier this season when he
was every bit as dominant as Trevor Hoffman or Robb Nen.
</P>
<P>
   You just couldn't see the breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   Before he was acquired at the All-Star break from the Cincinnati
Reds, Shaw already had thrown 50 innings. That is almost a full
season for many closers.
</P>
<P>
   Couple that with 1042/3 and 942/3 innings the past two seasons
and it becomes clearer why Andres Galarraga, Andruw Jones and now
Alfonzo took him deep in the late innings in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, his ball didn't have nothing,'' said former Reds
teammate Lenny Harris, now with the Mets. ``He is not the same Jeff
Shaw I played with in Cincinnati.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw has been a standup guy throughout the meltdown, but he
refuses to blame anything but bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   However, when asked how much he pitched in Cincinnati, he said
quietly, ``A lot.''
</P>
<P>
   It's too late to slap Reds manager Jack McKeon or ask for Paul
Konerko back. Besides, Shaw doesn't escape blame.
</P>
<P>
   With the lowly Reds, there were few rewards other than saves.
Even when the back-to-back games started to mount during some
meaningless weekend in Pittsburgh, Shaw took the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Taking one for the team meant never taking a day off even if it
sounded self-centered on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very rare that I am not going to go out there if there
is a save to be had,'' said Shaw, who has 38 saves this year after
recording 43 in 1997. ``Even if my arm is dragging on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining all that to Brian Bohanon was worthless. He is still
wondering how one of baseball's top closers can blow his past two
starts.
</P>
<P>
   After outpitching 18-game winner Tom Glavine for seven innings
last Monday, Bohanon took on Al Leiter, the National League leader
in earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   For eight innings he battled, allowing 11 hits but just two
runs. He was at his best in the fourth when he pitched out of a
bases-loaded, no-out jam.
</P>
<P>
   He struck out Jermaine Allensworth, then began a double play
when Luis Lopez bounced back to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the eighth, he walked Mike Piazza and Brian
McRae, but struck out Allensworth again and retired Lopez on a
grounder to third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say, this is so frustrating, I am beyond
words,'' said Bohanon, who would like to take a few more victories
into next winter's free-agent market. ``I go into every game
thinking I am going to win. But things just aren't happening.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged he wasn't as sharp as he was in Atlanta. ``I
didn't have the good fastball and my location was off. But I
battled. You can always count on that. I can't blame Jeff Shaw, he
is one of the best closers in the game. It's a tough stretch for
him and the team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers really needed to sweep the Mets to feel they belong
in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   They entered the series with a chance to win four straight for
the first time this season. Now they have dropped the first two of
a four-game series to New York, which is eight games ahead with 26
to play.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw told manager Glenn Hoffman that he was fine even though he
pitched two innings in Friday night's 5-4 loss. That game was not a
save situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antonio Osuna said he had a sore arm so I wasn't going to use
him,'' Hoffman said. ``But Jeff knows himself better than most
pitchers. If he says he can go, I have to believe him.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw came in leading 3-2 and retired the first two batters. Then
Tony Phillips walked for the sixth time in the series. On a 2-2
count, Shaw threw a fastball to Alfonzo, the one he doesn't have
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't throwing nearly as hard as he had earlier in the
season,'' Harris said. ``After the second pitch I could tell
something was different. I told the guys don't swing so hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
