<HEADLINE>
SHEFFIELD SPRAINS THUMB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield could miss the rest of the series with the New
York Mets after suffering a sprained left thumb batting in the
first inning of Dodgers' 4-3 loss.
</P>
<P>
   It is the same thumb that forced Sheffield to miss all but 63
games during the 1995 season. He underwent surgery to repair a torn
ligament.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, Sheffield sprained the right thumb and
missed several games.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Sheffield injured the thumb swinging the bat in the
first inning. He dropped the bat in obvious pain, but stayed in the
game until the fourth. Sheffield went 0 for 2 with one strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're calling it day-to-day, but we have to see how
it feels (today),'' manager Glenn Hoffman said. ``It's been a
trouble spot in the past, but we think this is minor.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, who hit a three-run homer Friday, was 4 for 16 on the
homestand with a homer and six RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard time: The Dodgers' problems certainly haven't been
Trenidad Hubbard's fault.
</P>
<P>
   He has scored a run in the past six games, including a
first-inning homer Saturday. He has a hitting streak of seven
games.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard, a part-time player his entire career, has been the
Dodgers' starting left fielder since the beginning of the
homestand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I am, a role player, but that doesn't mean I have
to play like that,'' said Hubbard, who has hit safely in his past
19 starts (27 for 74, .364. ``It means coming to the park every day
thinking you are going to do something in the game. The game should
always be your focus, whether that means the first inning or the
ninth.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits: Mets starter Al Leiter allowed three home runs
Saturday (Hubbard, Raul Mondesi and Bobby Bonilla, back-to-back in
the second). He had allowed only four homers over 1482/3 innings in
22 starts before Saturday.... Mondesi and Bonilla were the fifth
Dodgers duo this season to hit back-to-back homers. Sheffield and
Eric Karros did it last Sunday off Greg Maddux in Atlanta.... Tom
Prince started in place of Charles Johnson and threw out Jermaine
Allensworth attempting to steal second in the second inning. Prince
has thrown out 9 of 21 baserunners (43 percent) attempting to steal
on him this season.... The Dodgers are 3-3 in their past six games,
all decided by one run.... Scoring change: Karros was charged with
an error on his throw to the plate Friday night when Rey Ordonez's
fielder's choice scored Mike Piazza from third base for the winning
run in the 10th inning.... John Olerud was 1 for 18 against
left-hander Scott Radinsky before hitting a three-run homer that
tied Friday's game in the seventh.... Dodgers right-hander Ismael
Valdes will make his first start since July 27 on Tuesday against
Philadelphia. Valdes, sidelined with a strained left-side muscle,
threw in the bullpen before the game. Darren Dreifort, Tuesday's
scheduled starter, will move to Wednesday. Even though they have an
off-day Thursday, the Dodgers say they will use a six-man rotation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
