<SLUG> BC-GLF-SENIORPGA-IRWIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRWIN MAKES HIS MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL HARBER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD _ It will be the battle of the I's Sunday when the final
round of the $1 million BankBoston Senior Classic begins at the
lovely Nashawtuc CC.
</P>
<P>
   The first I is Hale Irwin, the closest thing to a sure thing on
the Senior Tour. Irwin marched through Concord like Sherman marched
through Georgia, fashioning a course record-tying 8-under-par 64
Saturday. His 11-under 133 total is good enough for a share of the
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The second I is Joe Inman, who has been playing professional
golf for a quarter century but has only one PGA Tour victory in his
portfolio, the 1976 Kemper Open. Inman backed up his first-round 67
with a 66 to stake his claim on the top spot.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the first time he will be in the final pairing of a
PGA tournament in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to savor every minute of it,'' said Inman, who
earned a spot on the Senior Tour by finishing fifth at Qualifying
School last November. ``Am I going to be nervous? Sure. Yes, Hale
is the favorite. If I were a betting man, I'd put my money on him.
But Denver beat Green Bay and the Yankees don't have to win the
World Series. The best team doesn't have to win. I'm just tickled
to be in this position.''
</P>
<P>
   The two are the only players on the Senior Tour with last names
that begin with I. At Tour stops, often their lockers are side by
side. Both wear glasses and more than a few times Inman has been
mistaken as Irwin by autograph seekers.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no comparision in their games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has no holes in his game,'' said Inman of his playing
partner. ``I don't think Hale is afraid of me. I'm just happy to be
in this position.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin has to be considered the favorite Sunday. Consider his
finishes this year. He's played in 15 tournaments and has a top 10
finish in each of them. Five times he has won and five times he has
claimed second place.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Irwin has been dominant. He's been over par in only one
tournament _ the US Senior Open, where conditions are more rigorous
than your average Senior Tour stop. He has been under par in every
other tournament and is an aggregate 145-under through 15-plus
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin already has passed the $2 million mark this year
($2,101,750) and should have no problem topping his Senior Tour
record of $2,343,364.
</P>
<P>
   There is no truth to the rumor that Irwin didn't play his best
on Friday so that he could get an early tee time Saturday. Why
would he need an early finish? So he could make kickoff of last
night's Patriots game to see his nephew, Heath Irwin, play for New
England?
</P>
<P>
   As for the tournament, Irwin says it's still anyone's ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still is not my tournament. There's plenty of golfers that
can still win,'' he said. ``If I'm not aggressive (Sunday) somebody
else will be.''
</P>
<P>
   If both Irwin and Inman falter, lurking in the wings at one
stroke back is Al Geiberger (67), and at 136 is a fivesome that
includes Norwood's Allen Doyle (66), David Graham (68), Ed
Dougherty (69), Gibby Gilbert (69) and Frank Conner (71).
</P>
<P>
   First-round leader Bobby Stroble (73) along with Kurt Cox (66)
and Jay Sigel (69) are at 137.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin came within inches of setting the course record when his
30-foot birdie putt on the final hole seared the cup. He played the
front nine in 3-under 33, but it was chopsticks compared with the
Stradivarius back nine, a five-birdie masterpiece for 31. The back
nine was as friendly as his backyard.
</P>
<P>
   Inman, who fashioned a 67 on Friday, came up with a birdie on
the 511-yard finishing hole for his piece of the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin was pleased with his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really hit the ball better today. I got a lot of rust out of
my swing,'' said Irwin. He is referring to his two-week layoff and
he called his play ``uninspiring'' through the first nine holes of
the tournament, which he played in even par Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a better day. I needed a round like this,'' said Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his succes, Irwin said he is having problems with
distance control with his irons. ``I was continuously short on my
shots today.''
</P>
<P>
   But his putting certainly made up for any shortcomings. He
knocked in birdie putts of 12 feet on No. 3, 6 feet on No. 5, and
10 feet on No. 6 on the front nine. On the back side, he drained
birdie putts of 15 feet on No. 10, 12 feet on No. 13, 30 feet on
No. 15, 8 feet on No. 16 and 12 feet on No. 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``My play was a little more aggressive, especially my putting.
(Friday) I was wishing them in. Today I made a better effort with
the putts. The greens' speed is good, where the putts won't get
away from you.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, he hopes the tournament doesn't get away from him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
