<SLUG> BC-SPT-DRUGS-CREATINE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATINE: WHAT'S THE DOPE?  
 PERFORMANCE ENHANCER APPEARS SAFE FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN AND NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's Friday night at the Zuka Juice in north Phoenix,
and Larry McDermott is sipping his creatine-laced strawberry
smoothie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worth the extra 49 cents,'' the 34-year-old bodybuilder
said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Valley, in Arizona State University's athletic
facilities, containers of powdered creatine sit for the closely
monitored use of its athletes.
</P>
<P>
   And as the Mercury prepares for its WNBA Championship Series
game against Houston, one of its stars, guard Michele Timms, has
acknowledged she has reaped the benefits of the
performance-enhancing supplement.
</P>
<P>
   The three are a testament to the widespread popularity of
creatine, which finds itself in the news again in light of Mark
McGwire's acknowledgement that he uses another popular
over-the-counter substance, androstenedione.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're comfortable with distributing it because we know we
don't abuse it,'' ASU strength coach Rich Wenner said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike anabolic steroids, creatine is not a banned substance,
nor is it a drug. It is an amino acid found naturally in animal
proteins like meat and fish. In the body, it is found mostly in
muscles, where it plays a major role in energy production.
</P>
<P>
   Most studies on creatine have been positive. Athletes find it
provides energy and enhances their strength during training and
speed in conditioning. Some users report muscle strains, cramps or
dehydration, but overall, most believe the benefits outweigh the
side effects.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest argument against creatine is that there may be
long-term side effects, which have not been studied because the
supplement is relatively new.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chances are it's going to be fine,'' said Margaret Pederson, a
Phoenix-based dietitian. ``But why use something when you don't
know 100 percent?''
</P>
<P>
   Creatine's popularity is high in the Valley and in the rest of
the country. Athletes at the high school, college and professional
levels use it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen it,'' Greenway High School baseball Coach Ted Blake
said. ``Kids are looking for something, anything that is a quick
type of muscle enhancer where they don't have to work as hard. We
recommend kids don't take it. I tell my players, `You've not seen
the long-term effects.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns, Coyotes and Cardinals don't provide creatine to their
athletes but are aware that some use it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our official stance is no stance,'' Cardinals trainer John
Omohundro said. ``We don't advocate it. We don't ban it. It's sold
over the counter. We can't stop it. But it's buyer beware.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks have it available, strength and conditioning
coach Jeff Forney said, ``but we don't push it one way or the
other. We give them all the information, then it's their choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Forney said three or four Diamondbacks use it.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State makes it available to its athletes, but its use
and distribution are closely monitored, Wenner said. Approximately
15 football players use it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started taking it, I felt a little increase in
energy and felt a little stronger,'' ASU football center Grey
Ruegamer said. ``I could work out longer. But I think after a while
of taking it, your body gets used to it.'' &QL; 
Cheap, easy to get &QL; 
Creatine is available in pill, powder or liquid gel. It can be
purchased from a variety of sources: nutrition stores, the
Internet, fitness magazines and even juice bars like Zuka, which
offers it as a drink supplement for 49 cents a teaspoon.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the country's most popular athletes are users: McGwire,
Baltimore Orioles outfielder Brady Anderson and Denver Broncos
tight end Shannon Sharpe, who is a spokesman for a company that
distributes it.
</P>
<P>
   Five pro teams _ the Miami Heat, the Chicago Bears, the New York
Giants, the Cincinnati Reds and the Tennessee Oilers _ told ``USA
Today'' recently that more than half their players use it.
</P>
<P>
   Business has been brisk, and sales of creatine are expected to
top $200 million this year. A monthly supply typically runs $30 to
$35.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a natural food substrate,'' Suns strength and
conditioning coach Robin Pound said. ``It's not a drug. It's in
your body.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mix-up on creatine is that it supplies extra energy for
your body. It's not just lift weights, get huge. It helps you with
endurance. It gives you better stamina so you can work out longer
at higher intensities. Therefore, you get better results. It is
valid. The stuff does work.''
</P>
<P>
   Pound emphasized that creatine should be part of a good diet and
be taken within certain limits. &QL; 
Swimmer opposed &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Phil Whitten, 55, a master swimmer and editor of the
Arizona-based ``Swimming World,'' is a longtime crusader against
the performance-enhancing drugs used by the Chinese and the former
East Germans, and has devoted several lengthy stories to creatine.
Several years ago, he said, he tried it himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the only thing it made me do was make me retain some
water and gain some weight,'' said Whitten, who trains about 90
minutes a day at the Phoenix Swim Club. ``Maybe it doesn't work for
older people, or maybe you have to train harder than I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Swim Club Coach Pierre LaFontaine said he has not urged
any of his swimmers to use it. When he was a coach in Canada a few
years ago, LaFontaine said, his swimmers often used it on a
prescribed cycle of three weeks on, four months off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good thing,'' said LaFontaine, who in the late
1980s worked at the Phoenix Swim Club and coached Michele Smith,
the Irish Olympic medalist who recently was banned by the
International Olympic Committee for providing a drug test sample
that included a curious masking agent: whiskey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my kids here are pretty young,'' he said. ``As we
approach the Olympics, we might go ahead with it, just for an edge.
I feel if we give it all now, we have nothing to progress from.'' &QL; 
`Be smart about it' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Creatine began to be used about two years ago in swimming, which
has been plagued by drug abuse at the world-class level for the
last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Internationally, creatine has been part of many athletes' diets
for several years. Timms, of Australia, said Australians have used
it since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used it before the (1996) Olympics, and we used it before
the World Championships, because when you have such a heavy
schedule, it helps you,'' Timms said.
</P>
<P>
   Australia Olympic officials provide guidelines for when and how
to use creatine, Timms said.
</P>
<P>
   Pound, too, emphasized that those using it should be smart about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that you take certain dosages while you're
eating well, living a healthy lifestyle and not eating a lot of
garbage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Creatine first gained attention during the '92 Olympics, when
British athletes acknowledged using it.
</P>
<P>
   It got some unwanted attention last year after speculation that
it was a factor in the deaths of three college wrestlers. But last
April, the Food and Drug Administration said creatine ``did not
appear to be a major factor'' in the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Frankie, a Washington High School health and physical
education teacher who also trains world-class and professional
athletes, has sought as much information as he can about creatine. &QL; 
Alternative to drugs &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I like about it, it gives the athlete an alternative
way from illegal drugs,'' he said. ``I don't discourage creatine.
It's legal. It's out there, and they're doing research on it. Kids
using steroids, enhancement drugs, are not going to come forward,
so they're at risk all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take great amounts of anything, you'll be at risk. Any
time you do that, the body isn't producing at those levels. There
may be some consequences. I would caution any parent to pay
attention to what is going on and the amount that is being used. A
(popular) philosophy is if a little bit is good, then a whole lot
must be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's a hell of an alternative to putting your head in the
sand and kids using steroids. This is not even close to a steroid,
not even in the same ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, ``no negative side effects have been
documented in scientific literature,'' the American College of
Sports Medicine said recently, adding that ``the verdict is still
out over longer periods of time.''
</P>
<P>
   The closest thing to a negative study was a report that came out
in the ``Lancet,'' a British medical journal, saying circumstantial
evidence linked creatine ``to the deterioration of kidney functions
in a 25-year-old man with a pre-existing renal problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the debate rages on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I compete (in power lifting) drug free,'' Wenner said. ``So
when you're in your 30s, you know when you do something and it
works. I took the stuff and went, `Wow.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Blake said, ``I don't think it has a place in high school
athletics. I think any time they're taking something and don't know
the long-term effects, you're playing with a loaded gun.'' &QL; 
Staff writers Richard Obert, Don Ketchum, Steve Schoenfeld and Bob
McManaman contributed to this report. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
