<HEADLINE>
FRESHMAN TAILBACK IMPRESSES IN SCRIMMAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With 105 players rotating in and out _ starters and reserves,
true freshmen and redshirt freshmen, even walk-ons _ UCLA coach Bob
Toledo declined to evaluate specific players following Saturday's
scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   Except one.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was one person who stood out,'' Toledo said. ``Our
freshman tailback.''
</P>
<P>
   DeShaun Foster.
</P>
<P>
   A 205-pounder from Tustin, Foster figured he'd get a few
carries, but no more or less than veteran tailbacks Jermaine Lewis
and Keith Brown. Little did he know Toledo planned to test him
against the first-string defense, in live action, with 1,500 fans
scrutinizing his every step.
</P>
<P>
   Foster responded with 74 yards on nine carries and was more
impressive than Lewis (two carries, five yards) or Brown (five
carries, nine yards). He ran inside and outside, against the
first-string defense and the second string, and finished with five
double-digit gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get him with the first group and see what he can
do,'' Toledo said. ``He was a big focus for me. I wanted to test
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got a good grade.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't based solely on yardage, either. A sore groin and turf
toe have limited his repetitions in practice, but Foster's greatest
obstacle is the offense itself _ recognizing audibles and
pass-protection schemes.
</P>
<P>
   The more he learns, the less he thinks. And the less he thinks,
the better he runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, I'm running tentatively,'' he said. ``Today, I was
just running. I feel good about the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect him in the starting lineup against Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the third (tailback),'' Toledo said. ``The other kids did
a good job and deserve to be first-team. They're both starters.
(Foster) is second-team.''
</P>
<P>
   Other notables: Reserve inside linebacker Ryan Nece has
impressed the coaches after an offseason switch from safety. With
Ramogi Huma injured (groin), Nece is starting alongside Tony White.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve cornerback Damian Allen had one interception Saturday
and could have had a second. ``I guess that's why he's not a
receiver,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Freddie Mitchell (two catches, 18 yards) has
established himself as the No.1 punt returner.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman cornerback Julius Williams played with Allen on the
second team, ahead of Ryan Roques.
</P>
<P>
   Roster update: Reserve place-kicker Zak Haselmo informed Toledo
on Saturday that he has quit the team and will enroll at a junior
college.
</P>
<P>
   Haselmo, a redshirt freshman, was not invited to training camp
so UCLA could use his roster spot to evaluate walk-ons. His
departure is noteworthy for two reasons: it leaves the Bruins with
one scholarship kicker, Chris Sailer, and it frees a valuable
scholarship for next year's recruiting class.
</P>
<P>
   Walk-on Adam Griffith, a freshman from Gardnerville, Nev., is
the backup kicker.
</P>
<P>
   Get out of the kitchen: To prepare for the sweltering heat in
Pasadena, Houston and Miami, the Bruins are practicing at 11:30
a.m. every Tuesday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them that if they think this is hot, they're sorely
mistaken,'' Toledo said Friday. ``The Rose Bowl will be at least 20
degrees hotter. It'll be miserable in Houston and even worse in
Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   Kickoff against Texas is 12:30 p.m. The Houston game will be
played on the Cougars' home field, not the air-conditioned
Astrodome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
