<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BUFORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IDLED BUFORD BATTLES ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He admits he's in pain physically, but Damon Buford said that
pales in comparison to the anguish of sitting out games during the
stretch run. The Red Sox outfielder was placed on the disabled list
Friday with a rib injury, which originally occurred in Minnesota
last Saturday night when Buford struck out in the eighth inning. He
played Tuesday night and pinch ran Wednesday before the pain became
too unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it hurts,'' said Buford. ``It's nothing I've ever done
before so I don't really know. I just know that the first couple of
days it hurt to cough, or laugh, or sneeze, or do anything. It's
not as bad anymore so it's getting better every day. It's just
painful when I do certain things like rolling over in bed or
sneezing or laughing real hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old veteran, who hasn't committed an error this
season and has a career high nine home runs and has tied his career
high with 39 RBIs, is a key component in the Red Sox' success. Any
extended absence would put the club in a bind. But Buford believes
that when he's eligible to come off the DL, he will be ready to
return. Buford said what was strange is that he sustained the
injury last Saturday but it didn't affect him right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt fine the next day I played,'' he said. ``Then it got
worse as the night went on. I could feel it as the night went on
and then it hurt too bad to play anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been taking therapy, including ice, muscle stimulation
and, anti-inflammatories and said it has been hard to be on the
sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time in my whole career I've been on the DL and
it's been twice this year so I already can't play a whole month out
of the season,'' he said. ``That's real hard to deal with. That's
one thing I've always prided myself on is playing all the time or
at least always being available. It's hard to just not even be
available. There's nothing you can really do. At least it happened
on the baseball field and not doing anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Buford said he has a pretty substantial threshold of pain, but
this injury became unbearable quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can feel it getting better every day,'' he said. ``I'm
usually pretty good with pain. This is something that I won't rush
because it's too late for setbacks. I have to take my time. I can
ride the bike and lift weights. I can pretty much do everything.
It's just the adrenaline of the game and having to fire it real
quick (that could lead to problems if he came back too quickly).
Two weeks off will be good. It's encouraging to feel better. It's
encouraging to know that when I sneeze now, it's only a five on the
pain scale instead of a 10. And it's only been four days. Another
10 days it should be all right. I know that as long as I can't
sneeze, I can't swing a bat. That's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Until he's able to play again, Buford said he'll spend the time
when he's not rehabilitating cheering on the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great year,'' he said. ``We started winning in
spring training. You don't ever put too much stock in spring
training but we came out and started winning early in the year and
it's carried over the whole time. There hasn't been too much drama
around the clubhouse. When you win the whole time, it kind of makes
things easy.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he's found the Boston fans unique in that no matter
how well the team does, Red Sox fans are permanently pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like it,'' he said. ``I kind of
almost went through it, though, in Texas in 1996 and we were going
for our first pennant and they had never won it before. They had
been in the lead a couple of times. Then they'd say, `Texas always
fades when the heat comes.' We almost did lose it but we ended up
winning and it changed the attitude of the city regarding the
baseball team. It's more intense here. The negativity in Boston is
more intense. It's just interesting to see, to experience. As
players we have confidence. Even a guy like Jim Corsi, he's from
the area so he's grown up with it. Even Billy Broadbent (the Sox
video coordinator), he's waiting for the worst thing in the world
to happen. I think we just have to concentrate on getting to the
playoffs and then go round by round.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
