r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-RAIDERS-AZR     08-30 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-RAIDERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUNEUP LIKE TEXTBOOK FOR CARDS  
 SCORE IN FINAL MINUTE OVERCOMES RAIDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Their last drive was textbook, even for the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals kept the ball for more than six minutes, scoring
in the final minute to win a game the same way they lost so many
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie running back Michael Pittman's third touchdown, a
4-yarder with 44 seconds left, gave the Cardinals a 21-14 victory
over the Oakland Raiders on Saturday before 31,858 fans at
Oakland-Alameda County Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' first drive was even more impressive. Quarterback
Jake Plummer completed all eight of his passes for 61 yards,
running back Adrian Murrell ran for 26 yards and the Cardinals went
84 yards in 18 plays, a march that lasted 10 minutes and 40
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a clinic,'' Cardinals wide receiver Rob Moore
said. ``That's how you draw it up _ dink, dunk, take what they give
you and keep our defense off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was more impressed than the Cardinals' first-team
defenders, who, according to defensive tackle Eric Swann, didn't
break a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive starters played only two series, giving up only
one first down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really excited about this season,'' Swann said. ``I have a
little saying: `The Cardinals are going to be great in '98.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, who finished the preseason with a 2-2 record,
will find out how good they are beginning next week when they open
the regular season in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There still are a few pieces of the puzzle missing,'' Swann
said. ``Actually, there is a big piece of the puzzle missing. But I
have faith things are going to get done.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to unsigned first-round draft pick Andre
Wadsworth, the defensive end from Florida State who was the third
pick overall.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the negotiations said the two sides had a
lengthy conversation Friday and expect to talk again this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're closer,'' one source said. ``I think we're going to get
this done. ''
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the Cardinals didn't play any preseason game with
all of their top offensive skill people on the field at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Eric Metcalf missed two games. He returned
Saturday and started in place of Frank Sanders, who didn't make the
trip because of a back injury. Wide receiver Rob Moore and fullback
Larry Centers also missed a game each.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't keep Plummer from having a terrific preseason. He
completed 69 percent of his throws (46 of 66) for 491 yards and
four touchdowns. His passing rating was almost off the charts at
105.6.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hope he can get started (in Dallas) the way he did the
last two weeks,'' offensive coordinator Marc Trestman said of
Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to anoint him yet, but he's going to get us out
of a lot of jams when we're struggling,'' Murrell said. ``He has so
much poise.''
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, Plummer hit his first 11 passes against Seattle and
17 of the first 19.
</P>
<P>
   He said Saturday was the first time he had ever left a game
without an incompletion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to go out there and go one more series,'' Plummer
said. ``But I think Coach (Vince) Tobin was pretty happy the way we
went out and put together 20 plays and a score. That is exactly
what this offense needs to do. When we do that, we know something
is working.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer was replaced by third-team quarterback Stoney Case, who
was sacked four times and lost two fumbles, one that the Raiders
turned into a score.
</P>
<P>
   But Case hung tough in the fourth quarter, even after a late hit
by defensive end Aundray Bruce knocked his left shoulder (his
non-throwing shoulder) out of place for one play. He returned and
led the Cardinals to a score, a 4-yard run by Pittman with 12:42
left in the fourth quarter that tied the score at 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was ugly, but it was good at the same time,'' said Case,
who completed 15 of 25 passes for 158 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals got the ball a final time with 7 minutes left.
Case drove the Cardinals 58 yards in 14 plays, including nine runs
by Pittman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tough hoss,'' Case said of Pittman, who finished with
38 yards on 17 carries. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
