<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ANGELS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX STORM ANGELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was no masquerade Saturday afternoon at Fenway Park. No
Yoda mask, no borrowed No. 41 jersey from a teammate twice his
size, no double takes from Mo Vaughn, and no pained looks from his
manager.
</P>
<P>
   That merry prankster, Pedro Martinez, came as himself Saturday,
and as usual there was no shortage of entertainment _ or
excellence.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a plastic brace to protect his left knee, and working
with a swiftness that suggested the belief that he could defeat not
only the Angels but the elements, Martinez withstood two rain
delays to beat Anaheim, 6-1, before 32,519 in Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Awesome, wasn't it?'' said shortstop Nomar Garciaparra, in
appreciation of the fact that the actual playing time Saturday was
just 2 hours 7 minutes, to go along with the 43-minute and
six-minute delays that interrupted action.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the rain delay,'' Garciaparra said, ``he got his second
wind. It was like he was ticked off at the rain and took it out on
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez joined David Cone of the Yankees and Tom Glavine of the
Braves as the major leagues' only 18-game winners this season. He
allowed the Angels seven hits, all singles, six of which came in
the first three innings, struck out eight, and went to just four
three-ball counts. He walked just one.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who has allowed one run or less in 16 of his 28
starts, reduced his league-leading earned run average to 2.67 and
raised his strikeout total to 208, one behind Roger Clemens and
five behind Randy Johnson, who now works in the other league.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was nasty and abusive out there,'' said Angels shortstop
Gary DiSarcina of the Billerica DiSarcinas. ``I've never seen him
throw so many breaking balls on the corners.''
</P>
<P>
   If Martinez needed a campaign manager for his second straight Cy
Young Award, he could do worse than DiSarcina, who struck out
twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made me feel like a Little Leaguer out there,'' DiSarcina
said. ``We just have to move on. He was just incredible today. He's
probably the best pitcher I've seen since coming to the big
leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   John Valentin and Troy O'Leary each homered and doubled off
Black Jack McDowell as the Red Sox, facing a pitcher with a scarred
elbow for the second straight night, built a 6-1 lead through four
innings for Martinez, who gave up his only run on three singles in
the second but escaped further damage when Garret Anderson was
doubled off second on Matt Walbeck's shallow fly to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's got runners on base,'' said Darin Erstad, who had
one of the Angels' seven hits but failed to get the ball out of the
infield on his other three trips, ``it's turn out the lights.
Everything's a little sharper, a little harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely a competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   The twilight drama then turned on whether the Sox would be able
to squeeze in the win before the rain gave the umpires other
thoughts. Play stopped for the first time in the middle of the
fourth inning, and pitching coach Joe Kerrigan acknowledged there
was some concern whether Martinez would resume pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the delay had gone more than an hour, we wouldn't have sent
him back out there,'' said Kerrigan, who not only had the usual
concerns about a pitcher's arm going tight during a long break, but
also fretted about Martinez's knee, which he injured last Sunday
when he stepped between the hole he made during his delivery and
that made by Twins pitcher Brad Radke. ``We got him a stretch, we
got him on the bike, then we went out and did some long toss.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the second delay had been longer, we wouldn't have let him
go back out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he was conscious of the knee while he pitched, but
it never became more than a minor irritant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the rain,'' he said. ``The rain feels good on my
body.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's win, coming after the Sox had absorbed back-to-back
losses to the A's and Angels, helped the team maintain its
eight-game advantage over the Texas Rangers in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why he's out there, to stop the bad days,'' Valentin
said. ``That's when he's really tough, when you try to go after him
and you're losing the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was asked if he'd given any thought of breaking out the
Yoda mask again, as he'd done Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope,'' he said with a twinkle. ``That was Corsi.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
