<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-WNBA-FINALS-GAME2-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCURY CAN'T CLOSE DEAL  
 BLOWS 12-POINT LEAD; COMETS FORCE GAME 3 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Mercury Coach Cheryl Miller said Game 2 of the WNBA
finals would be beyond war, more like Armageddon. And it seemed
like the end of the world afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Not just because Phoenix scored only seven points in the final
12:24, including overtime, to surrender a 12-point lead in dropping
Game 2, 74-69. Or even because the defending champion Houston
Comets (30-4) now have new life that the Mercury (22-13) will find
hard to extinguish in a decisive Game 3 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It was Armageddon because of the toll exacted on both teams and
an emotionally wrought sellout of 16,285 at the Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Gillom, for the first time ever, hid in the training
room away from the media, literally sick to her stomach from a
3-for-15, eight-point performance that she felt let her team down.
Houston's Sheryl Swoopes had to cut an interview short and be
helped from the podium because of cramps in her calves and
hamstrings. The price of 21 points for the Mercury's Michele Timms
was scratches on the neck and a gouge under one of her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Coach Van Chancellor gave thanks for the two-day break
between Games 2 and 3, saying he was too spent to take the bench
any sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the furor, the most calm person was the least likely
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who picked up her second technical foul of the finals
and 13th of the season, was almost serene in her assessment, her
voice rising only at the suggestion of depression over one that got
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seriously, did you not expect Houston to get back in this
game?'' she asked. ``C'mon, they're champions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comets played that way when it was darkest, after trailing
for the final 12:50 of the first half and all of the second to the
brink of an embarrassing straight-game elimination.
</P>
<P>
   When Timms scored the last of her team-high points with 7:24
remaining, the Mercury had its largest lead, 62-50, and little
reason deep in the heart not to start the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   But strange things began to happen after Gillom blocked a shot
by Janeth Arcain into the hands of Comets backup center Yolanda
Moore, who scored her only basket.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-11 Arcain cooled off the 5-7 Timms, whose damage was
primarily against 5-5 Kim Perrot. And though the Mercury created
decent shots for Timms and the struggling Gillom, they wouldn't
fall and were not followed, allowing the Comets to run better than
they had all series.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Cooper, the two-time league Most Valuable Player,
leading scorer and fourth-best free throw shooter, made only half
of her six tries from the free throw line in the final 6:24. But
those combined with a 7-foot hook, break layup after a Swoopes
block and three-pointer at 1:25 were 10 of Houston's points in a
16-2 run to a 66-64 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had to step up,'' Cooper said. ``I'm the league MVP
and I have to play like the league MVP.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix, behind for the first time since 13-12, stayed composed
despite the onslaught. Backup guard Kristi Harrower made a running
7-footer on the baseline for a tie, then Gillom rebounded a miss by
Tina Thompson with 31 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   After a timeout, Timms worked the clock to 10 and three passes
later had to force a three-pointer that bounced off the side of the
rim.
</P>
<P>
   Overtime was scoreless for 1:41 before Swoopes tipped away a
pass that started Cooper on a break layup. It was a lead the Comets
never lost.
</P>
<P>
   A short Gillom jumper made the score 70-69 halfway through
overtime, then Swoopes made a big-time 17-footer in heavy traffic
at 1:02. When Cooper was not whistled for landing on Timms off a
shot with under 30 seconds, Phoenix was out of chances and was
forced to win a rubber game, as in the best-of-three semifinals
against Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran the offense and executed perfectly, ran time off the
clock, but we've got to get a rebound,'' said Timms, three points
shy of her WNBA scoring high. ``We just didn't crash the boards,
and that really hurt us in the clutch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did get 12 points up on them, and that's the way we're
going to look at it. As a positive thing rather than we got 12
points up and they came back and bit us in the bum.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
