<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEFFERIES `THANKFUL' TO BE WITH ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Gregg Jefferies joined the Angels on Saturday at Fenway
Park with 11 years of major-league experience, two All-Star Game
appearances and a .292 career lifetime batting average.
</P>
<P>
   But he also came with all the humility of a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're in first place,'' said Jefferies, who started in left
field and batted leadoff Saturday. ``They don't need me. They got
to first place by themselves. I'm not going to come in here and
show them this or that. These guys are tremendous players. I'm very
thankful to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferies, 31, was acquired Friday from the Phillies in exchange
for a player to be announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't pushing for it, but I heard rumblings the last four
days,'' Jefferies said of the trade. ``Obviously, I'm very excited.
I loved the guys in Philly, but they wanted to move in a different
direction. They're building with a youth movement, and that's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferies was highly touted when he reached the majors at age 20
with the Mets in 1987, but he didn't quite live up to the hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first broke in in '87, I was supposed to be the next
Mickey Mantle,'' he said. ``I can't live up to that. You're talking
about one of the greatest players of all time. I've been in the
majors 11 years and I'm 31. I'm proud of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferies' best season came in 1993 with the Cardinals when he
hit .342 (third in the NL) with 16 homers and 83 RBI in 142 games.
</P>
<P>
   To make room for Jefferies on the roster, the Angels optioned
outfielder Reggie Williams to Double-A Midland. Williams will
rejoin the team Tuesday in Cleveland when rosters are expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Palmeiro and Todd Greene also were affected by the
acquisition of Jefferies because they had been getting time in left
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to (Greene, Palmeiro and Williams) this morning,''
manager Terry Collins said. ``I told them Gregg Jefferies can help
us. He's an outstanding offensive player. And you never know what's
going to happen. Someone could run into the center-field wall today
and you'll be our starting center fielder tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Taming the Monster: Fenway Park's Green Monster does not
intimidate center fielder Jim Edmonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to run over there and pay attention,'' Edmonds
said. ``It's not that big of a deal. You have to know right away
where it's going when the ball bounces off the wall and just go
from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds said he likes Fenway better than Yankee Stadium and
Tiger Stadium _ two of the other old parks _ but it's not a good
hitter's park for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough place to hit for a lefty, it's 380 (feet) to
straight-away right field,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Green Monster is added incentive for a
left-handed hitter to hit to the opposite field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could make you a better hitter,'' he said. ``But it's tough
to change your swing for one place.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds hurt: Edmonds had to leave the game after three innings
Saturday because his bruised ribs were bothering him. Edmonds, who
hurt his mid-section Aug. 21 crashing into the fence at Edison
Field and aggravated the condition Thursday crashing into the fence
at Yankee Stadium, went for precautionary X-rays after the game.
Results were not available.
</P>
<P>
   Comeback expert: Nobody was more upset with Troy Percival's
Friday night performance (one inning, three runs in 7-6 Angels win)
than Percival. But Percival has been through rough outings in the
past and managed to bounce back, which makes him able to thrive as
a closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Troy Percival could not handle nights like last night
...,'' Collins said. ``I'll tell you something, Troy Percival wants
the ball tonight so bad he can taste it.''
</P>
<P>
   Also: Darin Erstad has not hit a home run since July 10 at
Seattle off Mariners' Jamie Moyer.... The team that has scored
first has lost every game on the Angels' road trip.... Gary
DiSarcina moved past Bob Boone and into fifth place on the Angels'
all-time list for games played Saturday with 969.... Since Edmonds'
sixth-inning double Thursday in New York, the Angels have had 28
consecutive singles without an extra-base hit.... Wednesday's game
at Cleveland has been changed to a 4:35 p.m. PDT start to
accommodate ESPN.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
