<HEADLINE>
CORKS SHOULD BE POPPING, BUT GOLDEN CHANCE MISSED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON - It should be over.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA champions should be flying home as heroes to a downtown
pep rally or parade.
</P>
<P>
   Michele Timms should be the first to hoist the trophy overhead,
after the heroic game she played.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Miller should be snapping her suspenders and saying it
ain't bragging if you do it. The coach had predicted months ago
they would _ remember? _ back when Miller identified the gender of
the league title, promising Phoenix fans the Mercury would ``bring
that bad boy home.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be over.
</P>
<P>
   As champs _ how good does that sound? _ they should be popping
corks.
</P>
<P>
   They had led by 12 points. Only 7{ minutes remained.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game'' _ and the title _ ``was ours,'' Mercury guard
Kristi Harrower said.
</P>
<P>
   The visitors in the orange uniforms had outworked and outplayed
the defending champion Houston Comets in Game 2 of this galactic
showdown. After a nine-point scoring run, the Mercury led, 62-50.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's star players, Cynthia Cooper _ the two-time league
Most Valuable Player _ and Sheryl Swoopes hadn't panicked, but you
could read the worry on their faces. The sellout crowd sensed it
was slipping away.
</P>
<P>
   In the huddle, during a timeout, Mercury players were wide-eyed.
Some glanced at the scoreboard to verify the score. Yes, it was
true. They almost could reach out and touch their dream. They were
``that'' close. They could ``taste'' it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Mercury quit rebounding. Suddenly, the Comets began
running, and scoring _ six, eight, 10, 12, 13 points in a row. The
game grew as tight as the knot of Miller's necktie. Swoopes.
Cooper. Cooper. Cooper. Doesn't the woman know she should be tired?
She is 35 years old. The turnabout was startling, breathtaking.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Mercury players sat in the chapel-like quiet
of their locker room, trying to digest what had just occurred. It
is the same locker room where the Suns had contemplated the end of
the 1994 season after losing to the Houston Rockets in Game 7 of
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Before Saturday's game, Bryan Colangelo ran into Rockets owner
Les Alexander. As the two shook hands, Colangelo thought of the
disappointment he has experienced in this building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of those (Rockets) series,'' Colangelo said, not to
Alexander, ``still make me ill.''
</P>
<P>
   After this one, a 74-69 overtime loss, Jennifer Gillom felt ill,
literally. Her teammates pasted on smiles for the cameras. They
reminded that the series isn't over, which is true. The Mercury has
another chance.
</P>
<P>
   But the players felt heartsick, and they should. They had
cornered the champs. They had them leaning against the ropes.
Unable to deliver the knockout punch, everything changed. Mercury
players needed no one to remind them they might not have another
opportunity as golden as this one.
</P>
<P>
   One can put two spins on this game, which was exciting and
entertaining from beginning to end. The Comets showed the heart of
a champion, corny as that phrase sounds. Or the Mercury blew a game
it ``should'' have won.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is what effect, if any, the loss will have on
the team's psyche. In this curious format, Game 3 won't be played
until Tuesday. If the series were ``Gone With the Wind,'' Scarlett
could have said Saturday, ``The day after the day after tomorrow is
another day.''
</P>
<P>
   How will the Mercury respond? Should the players be heartened,
or disheartened? If they are cut from the same competitive cloth as
Timms, who played 42 minutes and scored 21 points and guarded the
league MVP, this team will be OK.
</P>
<P>
   She is a resilient player, as tough in this league as they come.
After the game, Timms' cheek was nicked. She wore two long red
scratches on her throat like a necklace. ``I think we tried to
protect the lead, instead of trying to win the game,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   How about the scratches?
</P>
<P>
   ``Physical game,'' she said with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Know how you cut your cheek?
</P>
<P>
   I liked her answer. ``Yeah, I was driving to the basket,'' Timms
said. ``I got to the foul line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was worth it.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
