<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-LONGWOOD-HAARHUIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAARHUIS A SINGULAR SENSATION IN SEMIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE _ Paul Haarhuis has built his reputation on doubles.
</P>
<P>
   Haarhuis and his partner Jacco Eltingh have won 43 career
doubles titles, including seven this year, including Wimbledon and
the French Open. They are the only doubles team in the open era to
win all four Grand Slam crowns.
</P>
<P>
   But it was in singles that the unseeded Haarhuis made a
statement Saturday, defeating third-seeded Cedric Pioline, 7-5,
3-6, 6-3, in the semifinals of the MFS Pro Championships at
Longwood Cricket Club to reach his first singles final since losing
to Michael Chang at Indian Wells in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Haarhuis will play Chang, the No. 4 seed, who defeated qualifier
Sebastien Grosjean, 7-5, 4-6, 6-3, in last night's second
semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   There were three service breaks in the third set; Chang two, the
last in the eighth game, to go ahead, 5-3. Chang served out,
knocking away two break points and winning on his first match point
when Grosjean hit a forehand long.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good tennis, not an easy point to be had,'' said the
22d-ranked Chang, who hasn't won a tournament this year and has
been in three finals. ``Grosjean is a tough player, he's dangerous
the way he plays, especially with his serve. He doesn't look like
he generates much on it but he does. I felt I played good tennis,
although it was a tough match for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Chang has a 6-1 record vs. Haarhuis, someone he's hit with in
practice. ``Paul's not easy and he's had a real good week,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Haarhuis was ranked 19th in singles in 1995, 25th in 1996, and
then dropped to 71 when the 1997 season concluded. Now he's at 85
and his better days in singles have passed.
</P>
<P>
   Haarhuis has played only 11 tournaments this year. He gained a
wild card into the MFS Pro, mainly for doubles, which he and
Eltingh won last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some seasons you play less than other seasons,'' said the
32-year-old Dutchman, whose only singles title came in Jakarta in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play as much this year; my wife and I had a child in
February, and I didn't play the first six weeks and I didn't win
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then in March I got injured, basically for the first time
in a long time, and I couldn't play until the French Open. You lose
points and your form isn't as good.''
</P>
<P>
   Haarhuis broke Pioline at love in the eighth game of the third
set, as Pioline hit three shots wide, two on his backhand, and
Haarhuis socked a forehand winner up the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came up with some good shots,'' said Haarhuis, ``and I
tried to stay aggressive and I came up with some good shots on the
first serve to save some break points. He returned well and I had
to make some aces.''
</P>
<P>
   Haarhuis had 12 aces, something he couldn't quite believe. Three
came in the final game of the match.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth game, Haarhuis held off two break points before
closing out the match on his second opportunity. He reached that
last point when Pioline's backhand volley found the net, and won
with a service winner to the backhand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played a good match,'' Pioline said. ``He took all the
chances and it worked. He's got a good serve and he's trying to
come in all the time so you never know if he's going to come in and
go to the net. It's difficult to choose what shot you want to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's good on the serve-and-volley with a very good backhand.
He knows how to play every shot so I tried to mix them up. I
basically went after his backhand.''
</P>
<P>
   Haarhuis won the first set when Pioline double faulted for a
break in the 12th game, just his second double fault of the set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played a couple of bad points, including on that double
fault,'' Pioline said, ``so I gave him the first set.''
</P>
<P>
   The match, lasting an hour and 55 minutes, was quite even.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good match from the start, with no easy games for him
and no easy games for me,'' Haarhuis said. ``It looked like we
matched each other well.''
</P>
<P>
   Pioline won the second set, breaking Haarhuis in the ninth game
when he managed just one point on his serve.
</P>
<P>
   Haarhuis had to avoid Pioline's ability to open each side of the
court with his groundstrokes. ``He has a heavy forehand and a heavy
backhand and he can pull away the court,'' Haarhuis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to take the ball on the rise, especially on my
backhand side, and play fast so he'd be on his back foot trying to
hit those shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Haarhuis is looking for the $45,000 winner's check.
</P>
</TEXT>
