<HEADLINE>
`LAWN' A GREAT PLACE TO BEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Desert landscaping is in vogue among those who place
the environment at a premium.
</P>
<P>
   Using native plants in a yard conserves water, invites wildlife
and is extremely attractive to those who have been in the desert
long enough to appreciate it. A well-kept grass lawn may be
beautiful in the eyes of some beholders, but it certainly isn't
native to the desert.
</P>
<P>
   I came to the desert in the 1970s, planted grass, saw the error
in my ways and converted. Well, compromised. There's some rock,
some flowering shrubs, cactuses and other low-water consumers. A
drip system maintains the shrubs.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, for a variety of reasons, the yard became wildlife
habitat. A little nightshade, some Mexican sandbur, some weeds I
can't identify _ about everything except Russian thistle.
</P>
<P>
   The neighbors were so impressed that they entered my lawn in the
Worst of Phoenix Contest. I believe I'll win. The size of my weeds
(desert habitat) alone should do it.
</P>
<P>
   I knew I was harboring wildlife in this exotic paradise,
especially ants. But Saturday morning I discovered that there was
much more.
</P>
<P>
   I put off everything until it reaches epidemic proportions. In
my wisdom, I scheduled a house painter and lawn people at the same
time. At 5:45 a.m., people started showing up.
</P>
<P>
   The painter, who had started the day before, was preparing to
spray. The Hernandezes were working the lawn. That's when the
problem arose. Ramon pointed out the bees and hornets.
</P>
<P>
   They were everywhere in the desert habitat (weeds). You don't
expect to see honey bees and yellow jackets hanging out together.
Perhaps they were interbreeding. At least, they were socializing.
It was a big party, too.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, when we were examining the situation, the bees and
hornets got surly. Everyone headed for the hills. I went one way,
the lawn people another and the indignant painter another. He said
he'd sue if he got stung. I offered to buy him a bottle of whiskey.
That soothed his savage breast.
</P>
<P>
   I got great advice from a lady across the street, who was
preparing her investment property for new prospects. She said to
spray the area with a combination of soap and water. It keeps the
beasts from flying. It helped.
</P>
<P>
   But about that time, the painter told me to stay inside or
outside the house. He had to tape shut the doors and windows to
spray the place. I have been trapped inside, away from my desert
paradise. All of them wish me gone. I can hear from the inside that
the ants bit the lawn persons. The painter is threatening to paint
my windows.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps grass would be a better option. Who wants javelina in
their yards? Especially bees? &QL; 
Dove season begins &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dove season opens Tuesday. It lasts through the 15th of
September. In the southern part of the state, the shoot is in the
morning only. In the north, it's all day.
</P>
<P>
   No matter which area you're hunting, you need a Harvest
Information Stamp. It is an attempt to give the U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service information on migrating birds. Game and Fish
offices offer them for free.
</P>
<P>
   This should be a great dove season. The Powers Butte Wildlife
Area south of Buckeye is packed with doves, and the juniors-only
hunt should be decent next Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Youth through age 15 are eligible. They will be given a special
place to shoot if they're drawn for a spot. An adult must accompany
them.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call 789-3236. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
