<HEADLINE>
IN PRIME TIME, SWOOPES TAKES LEAD ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Sheryl Swoopes was channel surfing Saturday morning
and came across Sheryl Swoopes.
</P>
<P>
   Not in a Clean Shower commercial or with that bratty little girl
for Nike, but on ``Hang Time,'' an NBC teenage sitcom with the
non-Title IX premise of a boys basketball team with a female star.
The episode was about a lost rare coin and basketball campers lost
in a storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``People got to see a different side of Sheryl,'' Swoopes said.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday afternoon, on the same network, the nation saw the
basketball side of Swoopes, who transformed what appeared to be a
lost opportunity into a heart-pounding victory.
</P>
<P>
   Her 13 rebounds, bettering a pro career high of 11 set two days
earlier, and four points in overtime helped the Houston Comets
subdue the Mercury, 74-69, in Game 2 of the WNBA finals.
</P>
<P>
   The frontcourt trio of Swoopes, Tina Thompson and Monica Lamb
all reached double-figure scoring (38 points combined) to
supplement 27 from league scoring leader Cynthia Cooper. Cooper had
29 in Game 1, but her teammates combined for only 22 in a 54-51
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got down about 10 points (12), the only people who
believed we could come back were our fans and us,'' Swoopes said.
``We always believed we could win this game. It never crossed my
mind that we weren't going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Swoopes limped off the interview platform with help,
telling Cooper she in severe pain. The team physician, Jon Divine,
later explained, ``If you imagine what it feels like to wake up in
the middle of the night with a cramp, that is what happened up
here. Cramps are pretty painful.''
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes missed the first 19 games last season after giving birth
and made her WNBA debut against the Mercury, which now probably
wishes that she were a stay-at-home mom.
</P>
<P>
   Shaking off 3-for-14 shooting in Game 1 as if it never occurred,
Swoopes was 7 for 16 for 14 points, offsetting her six turnovers
with five assists. She also added two steals and a pair of blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Her sizzling 17-footer at 1:02 of overtime bumped the Comets
back ahead by three, allowing the defending champions to close the
door with defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``They blew the lead because we started to play defense,''
Cooper said. ``During the timeout (before a free throw that put the
Mercury ahead by 12), we said, `Let's rebound the ball and get the
job done on defense, and everything else will fall in place.'
</P>
<P>
   ``When we walked onto the court, we were committed to that. We
didn't say, `Let's make a three-pointer or a great jump shot' like
Sheryl did. We got it done on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston managed a slim rebounding edge, 36-33, with most of the
boards from Swoopes and Thompson (12). That was in contrast to a
41-32 rebounding deficit in Game 1. The Comets shot 43.1 percent, a
considerable improvement from Thursday (32.3).
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes needed no aid in leaving the Compaq Center, unlike in
early July, when she was hospitalized because of to dehydration.
And unlike Aug. 4, when a stiff neck kept her out of the second
half against Utah. That was the same week that Cooper went public
with her complaints about lack of team play.
</P>
<P>
   Few think the Comets will continue to force the Cooper-Swoopes
marriage next season, but one game remains before a possible
divorce.
</P>
<P>
   If they win a second title, maybe they keep it together for the
kids (of Houston). Lose, stamp on irreconcilable difference and
flip a coin to decide whom to keep: Cooper at age 35 or Swoopes at
27. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
