<HEADLINE>
HARROWER IMPRESSES COMETS COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Houston Coach  &UR; Van Chancellor didn't even take a swipe
at
 &UR; Kristi Harrower's name in discussing what he expects from the
Mercury in the decisive Game 3 of the WNBA finals on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how (No.) 4 can play any better,'' Chancellor said
after his Comets escaped with a 74-69 overtime win Saturday to
force a tiebreaker. ``I don't want to slaughter her name.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrower, the 5-foot-4 backup to Mercury starting point guard
 &UR; Michele Timms, almost killed the Comets' title repeat aspirations
with a career-high 12 points. She and Timms, with 21, were the only
Phoenix players in double figures as center  &UR; Jennifer Gillom was
held under her regular season average for the third consecutive
game.
</P>
<P>
   With five points, including the second of her three-pointers,
Harrower led a 12-2 Mercury run that opened a 62-50 lead with 7:24
remaining. And her running 7-footer at the one-minute mark were the
final points before overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Kim) Perrot ran at me, so I just took it to the key,'' said
Harrower, who had seven points in Game 1 and now has scored almost
as many points as Gillom (23-19) in the series. ``She nearly kicked
me out of bounds to start with. That's the way I have to shoot them
on a runner because they're just giants inside.'' &QL; 
Briefly &QL; 
The second WNBA postseason tour will be to Brazil for three games.
Dates and players are yet to be announced, but a pre-tour camp will
begin Sept. 19 with practices divided between the 1999 expansion
cities, Orlando and Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star team that toured Europe last fall included Timms.
Chancellor, the two-time WNBA Coach of the Year, will direct the
Brazilian tour that includes a game against Polti, for whom the
Comets'  &UR; Janeth Arcain also plays.
</P>
<P>
   WNBA President &UR; Val Ackerman said the Minnesota franchise has
achieved its required 5,000 season ticket sales before a Tuesday
deadline. Earlier, Orlando passed that hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   A site for the first WNBA All-Star Game, to be held in mid-July
1999, has not been selected, but it will be a league city, Ackerman
said. Attendance leaders Washington, New York (where the league
office is located), Phoenix and Houston are the leading
candidates. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
