<HEADLINE>
TILLMAN MAKES PRESENCE FELT AGAINST RAID ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Veteran wide receiver  &UR; Kenny Shedd of the Oakland
Raiders knew all about Cardinals rookie safety  &UR; Pat
Tillman's &UR; reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Tillman knocked him groggy on a crossing pattern early in
the fourth quarter Saturday, and Shedd learned firsthand in the
Cardinals' 21-14 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard about this guy all week, that he's supposed to bring
the wood,'' Shedd said. ``He hit me pretty hard on that one, but I
wasn't going to let him stand over me as I was knocked out. I have
to admit I was a little fuzzy. He laid a good one on me. It was
solid.''
</P>
<P>
   Late in the third quarter, Tillman, a seventh-round pick from
Arizona State, had his first interception. He picked off a pass
from  &UR; Donald
 &UR; Hollas that was intended for fullback  &UR; Randy Jordan. &UR; Tillman
returned it nine yards to the Raiders 43 to set up the game-tying
score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to do something that was worth all my (friends and
family) coming out,'' said Tillman, a native of San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Tillman finished the preseason as the team's leading tackler
with 25, including a team-high nine against the Raiders. &QL; 
Playing with pain
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback  &UR; Stoney Case won't forget the late hit Raiders
defensive end  &UR; Aundray Bruce put on him in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce was called for roughing the passer, giving the Cardinals a
first down at the Raiders 17.
</P>
<P>
   But Case had to leave the game for a play because of an injury
he first thought was a dislocated left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't put it back in,'' Case said. ``Then, right when the
doctors got to me, I was able to maneuver and get it back in.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bruce) took four steps and pounded me. It was excessive. He
knew the ball was gone.'' &QL; 
Knockout punch
</P>
<P>
   Rookie running back  &UR; Michael Pittman not only scored three
touchdowns, he also made a crushing block on the Raiders'  &UR; John
Henry
 &UR; Mills on the opening kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so hyped,'' said Pittman, who attended Fresno State, 2{
hours south of Oakland. ``I didn't care if he was bigger than I
was, I just tried to put my helmet to his chest. He fell to the
ground, and I jumped on him. I blew him up.'' &QL; 
Short shots
</P>
<P>
   After gaining only 28 yards on 23 carries a week ago, the
Cardinals rushed for 100 yards, twice as many as the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   When Cardinals linebacker  &UR; Jamir Miller had a sack early in the
second quarter, the Oakland native celebrated by doing a bump and
grind. ``That's just doing the thing,'' said Miller, who played two
series.
</P>
<P>
   Raiders backup defensive tackle  &UR; Chuck Osborne, &UR; out of Arizona,
had three sacks, two forced fumbles and seven tackles. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
