<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERIES WIN OVER YANKEES SHOWS ANGELS' METTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the third time in four years the Anaheim Angels will enter
September in a strong position to reach the playoffs. The big
question in the land of Disney is whether this finally will be the
year the Angels return to the postseason, a place they haven't
visited since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The signs point to this year being different for the Angels,
whose clubs of 1995 and '96 are best remembered for fading down the
stretch. The current Angels, under the aggressive eye of Manager
 &UR; Terry Collins, are scrapping and playing with far more confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not here to make a statement or send a message,''
Collins said during the Yankees series. ``We're simply trying to
win a pennant. We should be loose. Nobody expects us to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Victories in three of five games at Yankee Stadium last week
indicate these Angels are not about to bow to anyone. In fact, it
came very close to being a five-game sweep for Anaheim, which lost
the last game in 11 innings and the other in the bottom of the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know how we feel about each other and what we are doing,''
shortstop  &UR; Gary DiSarcina said, ``and I think it's something to be
proud of the way we're playing these guys. I mean, it's a pressure
cooker. Every guy they send up there can do some damage. You can't
give them an extra out. You have to keep grinding, and the key is
not to be intimidated.''
</P>
<P>
   This Anaheim club is a far cry from the one Angels President
 &UR; Tony
 &UR; Tavares categorized just two years ago as soft and too worried
about looking good at the beach. The Angels, who still have a
battle on their hands with second-place Texas, are giving the
appearance that they are not prepared to be compared to the '95 and
'96 clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can put it in our back pocket as a confidence booster if we
run into tough times,'' added DiSarcina, among the most underrated
shortstops in the game. ``I also don't think that in 1995 or '96
we'd have hung in against a team of this caliber. We were a little
too young then. We'd have been intimidated. Experience is an
important factor.'' &QL; 
One true blue man &QL; 
Former Los Angeles Dodger General Manager  &UR; Al Campanis, who passed
away a few weeks ago, probably was the most miscast person in
baseball in the past 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   A true champion for the rights of minorities in baseball,
Campanis' hard work was basically forgotten because of several
misstatements made during an interview on Nightline with Ted Koppel
more than 10 years before his death.
</P>
<P>
   At his recent funeral in Southern California, the credo Campanis
lived by was printed on the back of his eulogy. It was titled
``Anyway.'' See Beyond the Boxscore for the full text. &QL; 
Downsizing the Unit &QL; 
There is growing frustration in Seattle, where the front office is
watching  &UR; Randy Johnson pitch the way he did in winning the Cy
Young Award in 1995. Johnson was 9-10 with a 4.33 ERA for the
Mariners before being traded to Houston on July 31. He has since
gone 5-1, with a 1.17 ERA for the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing to see that someone's performance can turn around
so abruptly as Randy has made his,'' Mariners assistant GM  &UR; Lee
Pelekoudas said. ``It makes you wish he had shown the same
intensity and drive when he was with us that he is showing now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read in spring training where Randy said, `What's the
incentive to work hard?' He was being paid $6 million to do a job
here. I would think that would help anyone's work ethic.''
</P>
<P>
   The strong belief is that Pelekoudas was not just speaking for
himself but Seattle's front office, as well. &QL; 
GM for LA? &QL; 
With Los Angeles seemingly in tent on hiring a real general manager
for the 1999 season, the top-shelf candidates include (in order)
 &UR; Jim Bowden of Cincinnati and &UR; Dave Dombrowski of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Those with an outside chance (not in order) include  &UR; Bob Watson,
formerly with the Yankees, Baltimore assistant  &UR; Kevin Malone,
Atlanta assistant  &UR; Dean Taylor and Mets assistant  &UR; Omar Minaya. One
possible dark horse is  &UR; Kevin Kennedy, who came up as a manager in
the Dodgers system.
</P>
<P>
   Current interim GM  &UR; Tommy Lasorda, who turns 71 Sept. 22, now
insists he does not want the demanding position. Several sources
indicate Lasorda is eyeing the post of club president, a much
cushier position.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a job for a younger guy,'' Lasorda said. ``I really
enjoy it, but it's just too much. I'll be 71 next month. If I was
10 years younger, I would really love to have it.'' &QL; 
Sad but true &QL; 
A regrettable situation arose in Denver last week in which a local
member of the Baseball Writers Association of America (BBWAA) was
seen taking an item out of Colorado outfielder  &UR; Dante Bichette's
locker.
</P>
<P>
   While the Rockies were on the field taking batting practice, a
time when the clubhouse is closed to all media, Denver Post
columnist  &UR; Mark
 &UR; Kiszla took a vial of Androstenedione, the suddenly controversial
nutritional supplement, out of Bichette's locker.
</P>
<P>
   Kiszla's punishment was having his BBWAA privileges revoked for
the remainder of the season, with a review for the 1999 season to
take place during the World Series. In a time when relations
between players and reporters are becoming more strained, it was
noteworthy to see the BBWAA's leadership take such swift and
effective action.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies will refuse to issue Kiszla credentials, basically
banning the columnist from Coors Field. Major League Baseball
executives were pleased to see the BBWAA police itself with such
authority. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
BEYOND THE BOX SCORE &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; The credo the late Al Campanis, longtime Dodgers executive, lived
 &UR; by:
</P>
<P>
   ``ANYWAY''
</P>
<P>
   People are unreasonable, illogical and self-centered. Love them
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   If you do good, people will accuse you of selfish ulterior
motives. Do good anyway.
</P>
<P>
   If you are successful, you win false friends and true enemies.
Succeed anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The good you do today will be forgotten tomorrow. Do good
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Honesty and frankness make you vulnerable. Be honest and frank
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   People favor underdogs but follow only top dogs. Fight for some
underdogs anyway.
</P>
<P>
   What you spend years building may be destroyed overnight. Build
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   People really need help but may attack if you help them. Help
people anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Give the world the best you have and you'll get kicked in the
teeth. Give the world the best you've got . . . anyway! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE HIT LIST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; He's keeping his priorities consistent: Florida owner/blight  &UR; Wayne
Huizenga recently paid $7.5 million for a house on Nantucket
Island. His current roster of Marlins, a despicable farce that is
called the defending World Series champions, combined earn less
than that figure.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Was the electric chair considered? When asked what he planned
to do with his outfielder's glove now that it has been mutually
decided the  &UR; Todd Hundley-as-outfielder experiment is officially
over, Hundley offered this: ``Burn it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Further proof of how the great home run chase of '98
 &UR; is affecting the season: For the first time since Three Rivers
Stadium opened in 1970, the Pittsburgh Pirates sold out consecutive
regular season games last weekend. The attraction?  &UR; Mark McGwire
was in town.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Kiko Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; How could anyone pass on this one:  &UR; Kerry Would, the horse, won
and paid $5.80 at Chicago's Hawthorne Race Course two days before
 &UR; Kerry Wood, the pitcher, beat Cincinnati last week.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Great Lines Dept. presents: From  &UR; John Lopez of the
``Houston Chronicle:'' ``The Astros have a 9{-game lead on the Cubs
with 31 games remaining. France has surrendered its flag on
less.'' &QL; EXTRA BASES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Let's not forget that  &UR; Ken Griffey Jr. could have been joining
McGwire this season as the only players with at least 50 home runs
in three consecutive seasons. Griffey, who hit 56 last year and is
on pace for 53 this season, finished with 49 in 1996. He hit a home
run on Sept. 6 that year that was wiped out because the game was
called before it went five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Let's also hope National League managers and coaches remember
Cincinnati second baseman  &UR; Bret Boone when it comes time to voting
for Gold Gloves. Boone is on pace to lead the league in fielding
percentage for the second straight season. Amazingly, he never has
won a Gold Glove.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's  &UR; Andruw Jones, at 21 years, 125 days, became the
youngest player ever to hit 20 home runs and steal 20 bases in the
same season. Houston's  &UR; Cesar Cedeno previously held the record at
21 years, 181 days in 1972. One note: Cedeno hit 20 homers and
stole 55 bases. Jones has 23 home runs and 20 steals.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland Manager  &UR; Art Howe did his pre-game radio interview
Wednesday while sitting in the only red chair among the 33,871 at
Fenway Park's otherwise sea of green seats. It's the historic seat
deep in right field, the one where  &UR; Ted Williams blasted a
500-foot-plus home run in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati's  &UR; Dmitri Young entered the weekend with 42 doubles,
nine behind the club franchise record and the major league record
for a switch-hitter, both held by  &UR; Pete Rose.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago White Sox are so jacked up over their young
prospects that they recently sought additional money to field an
instructional league program that will work in conjunction with the
Diamondbacks and Colorado in Tucson. &QL; THE RUMOR
MILL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With center field serving as a hole in their lineup, the
Colorado Rockies last week dispatched scout  &UR; Dan Gladden to
Minneapolis to watch potential free agent  &UR; Bernie Williams of the
New York Yankees. The Rockies also have an eye on  &UR; Brian Jordan of
St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego basically has decided on a three-man rotation for the
playoffs. The three are  &UR; Kevin Brown,  &UR; Andy Ashby and
 &UR; Sterling Hitchock.  &UR; Joey Hamilton will replace Hitchock if the
Padres open the playoffs against right-handed-heavy Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Struggling Los Angeles pitcher  &UR; Carlos Perez, acquired from
Montreal on July 31, may be asked to move to the bullpen. If so,
Perez said, in no uncertain terms, that he will ``retire or ask for
a trade. . . . Why are they talking stuff about me already? They
don't even know me.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado pitcher  &UR; John Thomson, who looked like a lock to win 15
after his first start in April, is tinkering with a change-up. If
mastered, it will only make Thomson a better pitcher in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the Calgary Cannons in the Pacific Coast League
may keep  &UR; Jim Abbott from being called up to the White Sox sooner
than he expected. Calgary is close to clinching a playoff berth and
probably will need him to advance. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
