<SLUG> BC-BBN-BREWERS-LEFEBVRE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREWERS HIT TING COACH RETURNS TO LIFE HE LOVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - When Milwaukee Brewers Manager Phil Garner called Jim
Lefebvre about a month ago, it had nothing to do with the pitching
machine Lefebvre sold to Garner last year for his son, Ty, now a
freshman baseball player at Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers had just fired Lamar Johnson as their hitting coach,
and Garner wanted to know whether Lefebvre was interested in the
job. Lefebvre, who lives in Scottsdale, said he would think about
it, talk with his family, consider the options. In other words,
wait. But Lefebvre pretty much knew the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had started to realize that it gets inside your bones and
your blood, and it never really leaves,'' said Lefebvre, the new
Brewers hitting coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'' was wearing the uniform again, being part of a team,
competing _ the only life he knew for more than 35 years as a
player, coach and major and minor league manager. Lefebvre, who
managed the Phoenix Triple-A team in 1985 and 1986 and went on to
manage Seattle and the Chicago Cubs from 1989 through 1993, last
experienced ``it'' in 1995, when he was Oakland's hitting coach.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the intense, energetic Lefebvre, 56, was far removed
from the game. He calls himself an ambassador for Major League
Baseball International, but what he really does is missionary work,
teaching and preaching the gospel of baseball abroad.
</P>
<P>
   He worked on Firebirds broadcasts for two years. He sells
pitching machines. He co-founded Athletes for Youth, an anti-drug
organization, and helped start a unique facility in Scottsdale he
said provides high-performance, Olympic-type training for young
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Lefebvre said he valued the time spent with his wife, Ruth, and
four children (his oldest son, Ryan, is a Minnesota Twins
broadcaster). Being away from the game ``let the air clear,'' he
said. But he knew he would come back. All he needed was his
family's blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said to go where your heart is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He followed his heart and his cheesehead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being part of a ``team,'' representing a ``team,'' those are
the days I cherish,'' Lefebvre said in the visitors dugout at Bank
One Ballpark on Saturday. ``You miss the competitiveness. It never
really left. You try to block it out, but you miss those moments.''
</P>
<P>
   Lefebvre, who co-wrote a book, ``The Making of a Hitter,'' with
his father, is acutely sensitive to being a midseason replacement.
Johnson was popular with the players, some of whom believe he was
made a fall guy. But Garner wanted someone more forceful.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt about it, he found him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely a hands-on guy,'' third baseman Jeff Cirillo
said of Lefebvre. `I like that intensity, that fired-up attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Garner said, ``I wanted a big name that had credibility and a
long track record of teaching. A guy that's aggressive. He fit the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend to go from one extreme to the other. I thought Lamar
Johnson was a good hitting coach, but he had sort of a quiet
demeanor. Studious. More laid-back. Now I've gone the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Lefebvre likes to say he didn't leave but was ``on sabbatical.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife asked me how I felt,'' he said, ``and I said after
three days, it was like I never missed a beat.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
