r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-UMPIRES-BICKLEY-A     08-30 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMPIRES ARE DRUNK ON POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can hold grudges. You can play favorites. You can eat
yourself into the grave.
</P>
<P>
   You can squeeze a pitcher, invent your own strike zone, act like
a dictator presiding over a Third World country.
</P>
<P>
   You have no fear of punishment. You never worry about demotions.
You are appointed for life, a member of baseball's Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   You are an umpire. And you are drunk on power.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Mark McGwire argued a questionable called third
strike and was thrown out of the game. In the first inning. By a
rookie umpire who almost incited a riot, prompting fans to throw
debris on the field, halting the game for nearly 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   His name was Sam Holbrook, and if McGwire ends up with 60 home
runs when the season ends, he will go down in infamy.
</P>
<P>
   Now, rules are rules, and no one likes to see an umpire with a
face full of loogey. But McGwire is singularly responsible for the
rebirth of baseball, the man who triggered this delicious season of
swat. He is not known as a hothead, a man who hadn't been ejected
in more than a year. If ever a scenario screamed for a little
tolerance and common sense, this was it.
</P>
<P>
   More than 47,000 people were at Busch Stadium on Saturday.
Surely, a few were attending their only game of the season. They
came to see McGwire. They ended up with Holbrook. &QL; 
Most pressing issue &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As baseball tries to right the ship and ride a new wave of
popularity into the next millennium, plenty of issues are on the
agenda, from androstenedione to bench-clearing brawls to the
dysfunctional concept of revenue sharing. But nothing is more
pressing than reeling in the men in blue.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a blanket indictment because there are competent,
conscientious umpires who know their place in the game. But they
are a minority, and in a season already marred by an abundance of
bad calls, the problem is growing.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't think an umpire can influence the outcome of a
game, know this: A few years ago, a study was done on umpires who
worked behind the plate a minimum of 75 times over a three-year
period. In the American League, walk rates varied from 5.6 per game
to 8.11 depending on the umpire. Strikeouts per game ranged from
10.4 to 12.2. Runs scored varied from 7.8 to 9.8.
</P>
<P>
   That's too much subjectivity for any sport that wants to be
taken seriously. And it's too much ambiguity for any athlete to
swallow without an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the hypocrisy of umpires. Any commentary
regarding balls and strikes warrants an automatic ejection, a credo
that umpires rigorously enforce. And yet they blatantly ignore and
disrespect the strike zone as described in the same book of rules.
</P>
<P>
   In short, they have taken over the game. &QL; 
Sacred strike zone &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Bud Selig wants to make a lasting imprint on the
commissioner's office, he should start with umpire reform. Declare
the strike zone a sacred entity. Demand uniformity and consistency
from the home plate umpire. Appoint an independent office to judge
umpires on merit, along with the power to send blatant offenders to
the minor leagues. Require a certain fitness level because hustle
calls are part of the game, and there's no room for Jabba the Hutt.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is that somewhere along the line, baseball messed up. It
allowed union boss Richie Phillips, a well-coifed blowhard, to
carve an impenetrable niche for his men. It relinquished enough
power for the umpires union to grow strong and ornery, a lethal
combination.
</P>
<P>
   It will take a full-blown assault to regain control. But for the
sake of baseball, it's time for the umpires to get out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1997, after the Roberto Alomar spitting
incident, the umpires went public with their new strategy. They
said it was time to get tough. In a revealing statement released by
Jerry Crawford and Don Denkinger, they explained that ``tolerance
in baseball is leading to total anarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   They were right. The problem is tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Tolerance toward umpires and their bloated sense of importance. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-98 0118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
