</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-JELLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JELLS HOPES TO CATCH ROSTER SPOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ Dietrich Jells left Foxboro Stadium Saturday night
confident he would get a good night's sleep. The Patriots'
third-year wide receiver had no idea whether his stellar effort in
New England's final exhibition game was enough to convince coaches
to look include him on the 53-man roster. He certainly has given
them something to think about.
</P>
<P>
   And he could not have done so at a better time. Entering last
night's contest against the Philadelphia Eagles with only one
catch, for 12 yards, Jells staged the team's best offensive showing
with two catches for 59 yards, both going for touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   The first was a 50-yard post-pattern from third-string
quarterback Tom Tupa. ``I was tired at first, but (Tupa) called a
post, so I livened up real quick,'' he said. ``I knew I had an
opportunity to get the ball, so I said, `I have to get the ball.'''
</P>
<P>
   Both scores came after Jells fumbled on the second half kickoff
at the New England 6. He managed to recover his own fumble, but the
miscue left the Patriots deep in their territory, and they gave the
ball up three plays later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pleased (with Jells). He did a great job when he had his
opportunities and came through,'' said coach Pete Carroll. ``And I
liked that he bounced back after missing the kickoff. We obviously
put him back there to see what he could do there, too.''
</P>
<P>
   As to whether that was enough to earn Jells a roster spot,
Carroll said, ``I don't know. We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Jells was claimed by the Patriots off waivers Aug. 21, 1996 from
the Kansas City Chiefs, the team that originally drafted him (sixth
round) that season. He entered this season's training camp with one
reception in each of the last two seasons. He had one start in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   And if getting opportunities the last two seasons has been
difficult, it was downright improbable this season. The Patriots _
a team with a relatively young receiving corps _ entered training
camp with 12 wide receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Last night's effort, he said, was a matter of getting an
opportunity. He declined to speculate as to whether he thought
there would be more. ``I try not to worry about that,'' he said.
``Whatever is going to happen, happens. I can only control what I
can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Jells said he knew chances would come last night because the
roster was down. ``Before we had a lot of receivers,'' he said.
``They were giving different people a lot of looks. My mindset for
this game was to make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the botched kickoff, Jells said the same scenario
occurred last season against Denver. ``I got my opportunity (on
the) kickoff, and I dropped the ball and it was the first one I did
all year. I said to myself that I can't squander these
opportunities. But I got other opportunities and I made the most of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jells said he would sleep well Saturday night because he was
bound for his hometown of Pittsburgh Sunday. He didn't even know
when the final roster would be trimmed. But he said he hopes to get
to the point where he isn't battling for a roster spot each season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come into every season fighting for my life, basically,'' he
said. ``Wherever I'm at, I just want an opportunity to contribute.
It's so hard being a fifth receiver. All your opportunities are on
special teams, unless someone gets hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole thing is to get in and make plays. Before I said I
wanted to start this year, and that was unrealistic. My goal now is
to start one game, and then go from there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
