<HEADER>
A9332 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ONFOOTBALL-PATSED     08-30 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ONFOOTBALL-PATSEDWARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWARDS STILL A MYSTERY IN BACKFIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ If Darth Vader was coaching the New England
Patriots instead of Pete Carroll, he might assess No. 1 draft
choice Robert Edwards's performance Saturday night thusly:
</P>
<P>
   ``Impressive. Most impressive. But you are not a Jedi yet!''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the running back out of Georgia made his first
extended appearance of the summer count for something in the
Patriots' final exhibition game, a 24-7 win over the Philadelphia
Eagles, but how much he can be counted on remained an unanswered
question when the night's work was concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards did enough in the first half to make clear that he has
something his contemporaries in New England do not, which is
quickness into the hole, but he did not do enough to make clear
that he has what it takes to come out of those holes in the same
fashion or to make anyone forget the man who used to run through
those holes _ the gone but not quite forgotten Curtis Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards carried 15 times for 38 yards against a Philadelphia
defense that is, to be kind, something less than formidable. That
defense was 25th against the run a year ago and is no better this
season, yet in the first half, when the starting units were facing
off, it held the Patriots to a by-now-familiar 2.2 yards a carry
(18 rushes for 39 yards) and Edwards to 34 yards on 13 carries, a
2.6-yard average.
</P>
<P>
   On the upside, Edwards's troublesome groin did not seem to
hamper him for the first time since mid-July. On one play, in fact,
he bolted loose for a 9-yard gain. He regularly got into the holes
faster than either Sedrick or Harold Shaw, his competition for the
starting halfback job.
</P>
<P>
   On the downside, Edwards averaged 2.5 yards a carry for the game
and finished the summer averaging 2.8 (21 carries for 58 yards), in
keeping with the team's sad rushing performance throughout the
exhibition season.
</P>
<P>
   In five exhibition games, the Patriots rushed for 501 yards on
176 carries, a per-rush average of 2.85 yards. That is nearly a
yard and a half per carry less than Martin produced a season ago,
when he was hurt most of the time and still finished with more than
1,000 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The offense has been saying that rushing average is less
important than the fact that they have been having fewer runs for
negative yardage than a year ago and have been, according to
lineman Max Lane, gaining the tough yards when they needed them.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, that was true on a third-and-1 at the Eagles 6
on the game's opening drive. Edwards gained 3 tough yards to set up
a touchdown pass from Drew Bledsoe to Troy Brown for a 7-0 lead.
Later in the first quarter, Edwards did the same on a third-and-2
situation, bursting through for 9 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, in the second quarter Edwards failed on third and 2
at the Eagle 7, gaining but 1 yard, and then was stopped for no
gain trying to go wide after Carroll decided to go for it on fourth
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to learn at this level everybody is fast,'' Edwards
said. ``That situation called for a pound (it) run.''
</P>
<P>
   Added all together, what did Saturday night's performance tell
us about Edwards and New England's running game as the season
opener in Denver looms a week from Monday?
</P>
<P>
   It tells us that what Darth Vader would have said is true.
Robert Edwards is different from the backs with whom he's presently
sharing the position. He has more quickness, softer hands when
catching the ball out of the backfield, and what some coaches call
``shake,'' which is the ability to make an initial tackler miss
from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   But what we do not know is what we nervously want to know. We do
not know if he can run anything like Martin, because he hasn't yet.
But his chances have been limited by a sore groin, so who can say
he will or he won't? We do not even know if he can run well enough
often enough when the Patriots need the tough yardage that Lane
said they'd been getting all summer, because although he did it on
two occasions Saturday night, he also failed on two others. So
there you have it.
</P>
<P>
   With the season opener eight days away, then, what we know about
the Patriots running game in the post-Curtis Martin Era is what we
knew on July 19, the day training camp opened.
</P>
<P>
   We know the Patriots have a big, quick back from Georgia who was
taken with the 18th pick in the draft to replace the most
productive back in Patriots history.
</P>
<P>
   We know he is big, fast, and prone to injury, judging by his
track record both at Georgia and this summer.
</P>
<P>
   We know he gets into the hole in a hurry, as he did Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   We know he is different from his competitors for the job, which
is a polite way of saying he is better in some way that may be hard
to explain but which is undeniable once he has the ball in his
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, there are things we don't know.
</P>
<P>
   What we don't know is if Edwards can come out of the majority of
those holes in as big a hurry as he went into them.
</P>
<P>
   What we don't know is whether his body will hold up.
</P>
<P>
   What we don't know is if he will gain yardage at the clip Martin
once did or at the clip Reggie ``One Yard'' Dupard once did.
</P>
<P>
   What we don't know, in the end, is if he is the man for the
difficult job he'll be handed at some point this season, which is
to replace a guy who averaged more than 1,200 yards rushing a
season the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of fact, not even Robert Edwards knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm aware of it (the pressure of replacing Martin) but I'm not
feeling it,'' Edwards said. ``If I go into it and do the best I can
and perform up to my ability, I know I can help the team one way or
the other. No one's trying to be the star.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a noble stance, but it makes you wonder, because anyone
who is honest about New England's running game can say little more
than Edwards did Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the simple statistical fact is this: Teams that have
a 100-yard rusher win 70 percent of the time, while teams that have
a 300-yard passer win 35 percent of the time. What we know at the
moment is that the Pariots most assuredly have a 300-yard passer.
So, as is often the case in life, what we don't know worries us
more than what we do know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-98 0122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
