u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-CANTY-BO     08-30 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-CANTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANTY NOW COZY ON CORNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ On the Eagles' first play of the game Saturday
night, running back Charlie Garner swept right end, gained some
yards, and then was met _ no, hammered _ by New England cornerback
Chris Canty. It was a new Canty, a physical Canty.
</P>
<P>
   Three plays later, Philadelphia quarterback Bobby Hoying threw a
swing pass to Garner in the flat and once again Garner was met _
no, smashed _ by Canty, causing Garner to fumble. It was a new
Canty, a bruising, confident Canty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a routine play,'' said Canty, ``but it was also a
matter of being physical, too.''
</P>
<P>
   A modest Canty? Most certainly, a new year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Garner coming across and our (defensive) line was
getting great pressure,'' said Canty, when pressed to say more
about the play that caused a turnover four plays into the game.
``Then I saw Hoying look out to Garner ... and I just reacted, kind
of before the ball was thrown.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last year.
</P>
<P>
   Garner caught Hoying's pass and ``I don't think he saw me until
it was too late,'' Canty went on. ``And I just tried to tag him
best I could.''
</P>
<P>
   All manner of questions abound about the New England running
game, the New England offense, the New England ability to score
points but, truly, there is only one major question on defense _
can Chris Canty play right cornerback in the National Football
League? If Canty can do the job, the Patriot defense may be
approaching the complete package.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Canty's rookie year, the cornerback was tentative,
unsure, soft, and had an attitude problem, finding the adjustment
from All-American at Kansas State to nickel back at New England
very difficult. And when the Patriots traded last year's right
corner, Jimmy Hitchcock, to Minnesota, Canty's name seldom came up
in the discussions about Hitchcock's replacement; it was either
first-round draft choice Tebucky Jones or veteran Steve Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Canty? Just a blitzer from the outside in the Patriots' nickel
and dime pass defenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm focused more this year,'' said Canty, who for so long last
season seemed like an outsider on a Patriots defense that was tight
and close and intimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more concentrating on details. I'm more everything.
Another thing is I'm getting more in sync with Willie (Clay),
Lawyer (Milloy), and Ty (Law). Those guys have been together for a
while and they know how each other plays, and I'm the new guy, but
I'm getting in sync now.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as the physical play, though, it is the change in
Canty's attitude that is most evident. There has been a dramatic
turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough for me last year,'' said the cornerback. ``When
you come off from being an All-America and, basically, doing
whatever you want to do on the field, to being a part-timer, and
having a set role, it was kind of shocking. I think it takes a
tough guy to come and realize what his role is and I kind of got
that toward the end of the season and into the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Canty doesn't say what he might have said last year _ ``bring on
Steve Israel and bring on Tebucky Jones, too'' _ and only says that
he welcomes the competition. The coaches will decide who plays
right cornerback for New England, said Canty, ``and hopefully it
will be my job. The coaches will decide and all I can do is go out
and play hard for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Words like that are as much a contrast from the 1997 Canty as
the two brutal hits he put on Garner. Indeed, it is a new Canty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-98 0124EDT &QL; 
