<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY STREAK SNAPPED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ The Columbus franchise undoubtedly is built around
U.S. national team forward Brian McBride, but he has a sidekick who
very well may wrestle away the league's MVP award from the Galaxy's
Cobi Jones, the apparent front-runner after last week's eight-point
performance against New England.
</P>
<P>
   Stern John, an emerging 21-year-old from Trinidad &AMP; Tobago's
national team, scored his league-leading 18th and 19th goals of the
season to lead Columbus to a convincing 3-0 victory over the Galaxy
in front of 19,633 at the Rose Bowl Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The victory ended Los Angeles' winning streak at four games, and
gave the surging Crew its fifth victory in five games to clinch a
playoff spot in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, L.A. defeated Columbus 4-2, thanks to a
three-goal performance from Martin Machon. But in defense of
Columbus, the Crew was without U.S. national team members McBride,
Brian Maisonneuve, Thomas Dolley and goalkeeper Juergen Sommer.
</P>
<P>
   John, who broke McBride's single-season scoring marks set in
1996, is chasing Jones for the MLS point lead. He improved his
total to 41, putting himself only two points behind Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy, which appeared to be rolling into the playoffs after
scoring 16 goals in its past four games, was shut out for the first
time since June 29, and for only the fourth time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with second-place Chicago getting only a point in a 3-2
shootout victory over Kansas City, Los Angeles needs any
combination of L.A. wins or Chicago losses equaling five standings
points (instead of seven before Saturday) in order to clinch its
second Western Conference regular-season title in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles, which had won its previous four games with Paul
Caligiuri and Joe Franchino as its outside backs, went to Greg
Vanney and Ezra Hendrickson, who have been regular starters most of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   It really didn't matter who started defensively, however. Los
Angeles couldn't find the net, despite outshooting Columbus 11-7.
</P>
<P>
   The Crew got on the board when midfielder Andy Williams
continued his consecutive-game assist streak, recording an assist
for a league-record sixth straight game. He had two first-half
feeds for Columbus, one with help from Galaxy defender Steve
Jolley, however.
</P>
<P>
   Williams moved along the right side in the 31st minute, looking
to feed McBride, who was marked closely by Jolley. Williams
attempted to float a pass over Jolley, but the quick-footed Galaxy
defender retreated in time, keeping himself in front of McBride
with plenty of time to clear the ball away.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of clearing the ball from danger, Jolley tried to bring
the ball down with his left foot. He mistimed the cross, allowing
the ball to bounce to his left in front of McBride, who only had
Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin Hartman to beat. Hartman came out to
challenge, but McBride took a high bounce and sent a delicate chip
over Hartman's head into an open net for a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who didn't do much work for either point, sent a
simple crossing pass above the penalty arc for John in the closing
minutes of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   John calmly controlled the ball at the top of the box in the
44th minute, keeping himself clear of Galaxy defender Robin Fraser.
Neither Fraser nor Hartman expected what happened next _ a quick,
perfectly placed right-footed strike to the upper-right corner to
give John his 18th goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   John sent the Galaxy fans home in the 79th minute, scoring on a
breakaway to beat Hartman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
