<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TALE OF TWO TEAMS, TWO DIRECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ But first, a word about the opponent. Three,
actually: God help 'em.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, we've known that feeling around here, haven't we? I think
back to the Rod Rust season, when wretched execution performances
would be followed by reasonably indecipherable explanations
concerning the disaster we had just witnessed. We knew before the
season started what it was like to feel helpless, hapless, and
hopeless. Saturday night the Philadelphia Eagles showed as close to
nothng as a team could show, and only the dynamics of exhibition
football kept the score as close as 24-7. The Eagles were never,
not for one nanosecond, in this game.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone knows what the Eagles are in for this season, it is
Irving Fryar. ``I've gone through years when we were 1-15, 2-14,
right here in New England,'' he points out. ``It's been tough for
us. We haven't played well. We've made it tough on ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Irving is now a man of the cloth, so he'd appreciate your input
with the Almighty.
</P>
<P>
   Now, then ...
</P>
<P>
   Your New England Patriots are neither helpless, hapless, nor
hopeless. They ought to be pretty good. Whoever wishes to take
credit for the grocery shopping has given the coach a
reasonably-stocked cupboard, so much so that Sunday is going to be
an agonizing one for coach Pete Carroll and his staff.
</P>
<P>
   For it is cut-down day. When the players reassemble for Monday's
practice, they will be doing so with eight fewer bodies than were
present for Saturday night's easy dispatch of the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the coaches are satisfied with the preseason,''
observes middle linebacker Ted Johnson, he of the new long-term
contract. ``There are going to be some difficult decisions for the
coaches. We are well-stocked at certain positions. We are going to
lose some good players.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some tough decisions,'' confirms Mr. Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   The major area of concern, of course, is the same one everyone
had going into the final exhibition contest. If you think you're
already on some sort of sensory overload on the subject of the
running game, I've got bad news. You ain't heard nothin' yet. The
running game is likely to be Topics A, B, C, and perhaps everything
through X in the days leading up to next Monday night's season
opener against the World Champs in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Most other areas appear to be in good shape. Things might not
have looked too rosy after the first two exhibition games, but the
Patriots were lucky because the extra exhibition game created by
the Dallas game in Mexico City turned out to be a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really took five weeks to get it done this time,'' says
Carroll. ``I never would have wished for five (games) when it
started. Now I think we can be a real good team, and the best thing
is that we have a big upside. We're nowhere near as good as we can
be.''
</P>
<P>
   There shouldn't be any question about their mental preparedness.
When last seen in serious combat, you may recall, they were on the
losing end of a bitterly-fought 7-6 score in Pittsburgh. A loss
like that in a game like that kind of hangs around in your brain
for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a real sense of urgency in this camp,'' maintains
Johnson, who, at 25, is settling into a classic leadership role.
``That was a tough loss. With the exception of one play (the broken
play that turned into the Steeler touchdown), we feel we left it
all out there on the field that day. Now we have an offense that is
trying to establish an identity and a defense that wants to
continue where it left off. We've got a good defense, but we need
to play well right away. Historically, we start off a little slow
on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   It's truly amazing how the Patriots' image has been transformed.
From the eight-touchdown-passes-to-eight-different-receivers start
of last year the Patriots have evolved into a team where you
honestly think of its defense first and its offense second. By the
end of last season the Patriots had become one of the premier
defensive teams in football. The basic worries are all about the
offense, specifically concerns about what happens when the play
calls for something other than a pass.
</P>
<P>
   Through 82 regular season and playoff contests, Drew Bledsoe has
averaged 38 passing attempts a game. It is an article of faith that
this number must be reduced if he is to enjoy life in the NFL
without the benefit of wheelchairs and painkillers. The exhibition
season offered little evidence that the desired reduction in
passing plays will take place in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   However the offense shakes down, the defense should keep the
Patriots in most games until Drew finds a way to get the team into
the end zone. At any rate, we won't have to wait long to gauge the
state of the Patriots' universe. Denver is the ultimate New England
nemesis. Not to be negative, but the Patriots haven't beaten this
team since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the idea that we're opening with them,'' says Johnson.
``It will be good to test yourself against the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, let's get going. If these guys are going to wake up
hurting from a football game, it might as well be after a game that
counts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-98 0130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
