<DOCNO> NYT19980830.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9343 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-EAGLES-B     08-30 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-EAGLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS GAIN GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ The goals for the final exhibition game were
simple: Come out of the contest healthy, let the so-called bubble
guys compete for the final few roster spots, and watch No. 1 draft
pick Robert Edwards show some fraction of the talent of Curtis
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   It's debatable whether all goals were accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, who closed the exhibition schedule Saturday night
with their third straight victory, a 24-7 romp over the hapless
Philadelphia Eagles, will head to Denver for the Sept. 7 season
opener relatively healthy, although Marty Moore was carried off the
field (cracked rib; out 4-6 weeks) with just over two minutes to
play.
</P>
<P>
   And the coaches did gather more information on some bubble guys
for making their roster decisions by Sunday's 4 p.m. deadline.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, Edwards showed himself to be some fraction of Martin.
A small fraction. The rookie, who had been out the past three weeks
with a sore groin, had 15 carries for 38 yards _ not to take the
starting job away from Sedrick Shaw, who gained 47 yards on 13
carries with the second team.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pete Carroll announced after the game that Shaw will start
against Denver, but ``we'll use him (Edwards) in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The bright spots in the win were Drew Bledsoe and the defense,
which held the Eagles to 159 net yards, only 56 on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took us five weeks to get it done this time,'' said
Carroll, referring to his team's expanded exhibition schedule. ``I
would never have wished for the five games when it started; as it
turned out, we needed them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a big upside. We can see there is a whole lot of room
for improvement. We need to get going.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a brief performance for Bledsoe, who played only the
first two series. But he was sharp, missing on only two of his
seven passes and tossing his first touchdown pass, a 3-yarder to
Troy Brown on the Patriots' first drive to make it 7-0.
</P>
<P>
   The first-team defense continued to assert itself as a strong
unit, stuffing the Eagles running game and causing huge problems
for quarterback Bobby Hoying, who had to throw under constant
pressure in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Other meaningful aspects of the win:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Dietrich Jells, the forgotten man of the receiving corps, had
a strong game, catching two second-half touchdown passes, one a
50-yard connection with third-stringer Tom Tupa, the other a
9-yarder from Scott Zolak.
</P>
<P>
   Jells, fighting for a spot on the team, made some other big
plays on special teams.
</P>
<P>
   He recovered a fumble on an Eagle punt return with 1:06
remaining in the third quarter at the Philadelphia 27-yard line.
That set up the short Patriots scoring drive that culminated with
Zolak hitting Jells from 9 yards out.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Jells downed a punt at the Eagles' 5.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; The Patriots' second team mounted an 82-yard drive under the
direction of Tupa in the third quarter. The drive featured the
longest run of the exhibition season _ a 19-yarder by Sedrick Shaw
against the Eagles' second team. With that play, Shaw made up for a
fumble on the previous series, a mistake that didn't please
Patriots coaches.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Veteran Mike Jones was credited with one sack and played well
with the second team. Whether his performance won him a job remains
to be seen, for offsetting that showing was a fine effort by
second-year defensive lineman Brandon Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; The game also marked the return of Tebucky Jones, the
Patriots' second first-round pick, who got plenty of reps in the
second half. He did nothing notable, positive or negative.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots defense set the tone for the night on the second
play of the Eagles' first possession when, on a screen pass to
Charlie Garner, who had just gained 10 yards on the first play from
scrimmage, right corner Chris Canty popped the ball loose and it
was recovered by Willie Clay at the Philadelphia 41-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' first-team offense, which looked a little
different with Edwards starting at running back and Troy Brown
starting over Shawn Jefferson at wide receiver, ran off an 11-play
drive that consumed 5:29 and culminated with the 3-yard scoring
pass, on which Brown was spotted by Bledsoe at the last possible
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, it was Edwards and more Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   On the Patriots' first series, the rookie carried six times for
12 yards. His return to the lineup started with a 3-yard loss on
first and 10 from the 41.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the first play I took a pretty good pounding, but then I
settled in and thought I did pretty well,'' said Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards then caught a 5-yard pass from Bledsoe and ran tough
thereafter, including a 5-yard burst up the middle on second and 6
from the 12.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, meanwhile, was clicking from the outset. He went to
Terry Glenn for passes of 8 and 14 yards during his brief
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards ran even better on the second series, showing more
confidence with twisting moves and cutbacks. He ran for 4, 6, and 9
yards as the Patriots made a first down, but then Bledsoe couldn't
find anyone open on a third-and-4 and the Patriots were forced to
punt.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, Edwards was later stopped cold on fourth and 1
from the 6-yard line midway through the second quarter, ending a
34-yard drive. The Patriots seemed to purposely give the ball to
Edwards in tough yardage situations, also handing it to him on
third and 3 for a long yard the play before he was stopped on
fourth down.
</P>
<P>
   ``That situation (fourth and 1) called for me to pound the
football,'' said Edwards. ``I should have taken it under and got
the yard.''
</P>
<P>
   The prettiest play of the half was Zolak's long ball to Glenn,
which went for 50 yards to the Eagles 15. Zolak thus had done what
Bledsoe could not through five exhibition games _ hit Glenn deep.
That led to Phil Dawson's 27-yard field goal with 11:13 remaining
in the half. It was Dawson's third straight field goal since being
signed before last week's game.
</P>
<P>
   It was 10-0, and the Patriots were on their way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-98 0149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980830.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9344 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      08-30 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
At this rate, Randy Johnson may never lose a start at the
Astrodome.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Better yet, opposing teams may never score a run.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson pitched his third shutout at home and struck out a
season-high 16 on Friday night as the Astros pulled out a scrappy
2-0 victory over the Pittsburgh Pirates before a crowd of 40,709.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's 27 (scoreless innings at home) in a row,'' Astros
manager Larry Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   But who's counting?
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, acquired from the Seattle Mariners on July 31, set a
club single-game record for strikeouts by a lefthander and recorded
the most strikeouts by an Astros pitcher since Nolan Ryan fanned 16
Giants on Sept. 9, 1987. Johnson fell two K's shy of the
club-record 18 set by Don Wilson in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   There was one primary word Johnson's teammates used in
describing his latest performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow,'' second baseman Craig Biggio said. ``He was totally
dominant.''
</P>
<P>
   The Big Unit needed an intensity-filled performance Friday as he
and Pittsburgh righthander Francisco Cordova matched scoreless
frames for the first five innings. Brad Ausmus broke the gridlock,
beating a throw to home plate on the first of two fielder's-choice
RBI grounders by Biggio.
</P>
<P>
   In three Astrodome starts, Johnson (5-1) has allowed no runs, 17
hits and three walks while striking out 37. He had 10 strikeouts
through five innings against the Pirates and capped off the
impressive display by striking out the side to end the game.
Johnson scattered seven hits and did not allow a walk while
throwing 133 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cordova is a heck of a pitcher,'' said Johnson, whose
major-league totals this season include 274 strikeouts and five
shutouts. ``He kept their team in the game the whole time and just
made it tougher for me. I have no leeway to make a bad pitch. I
have to stay focused the whole game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pittsburgh is a very disciplined, scrappy team. Those are the
teams that make me work extremely hard, because they're in the game
the whole time and make you throw a lot of pitches. It doesn't give
me any room for error.''
</P>
<P>
   In snapping the Pirates' nine-game winning streak, the Astros
won for the 16th time in their last 21 games and remained 10 games
ahead of second-place Chicago in the National League Central. They
also matched last year's victory total of 84 and established a
franchise record for wins in August with 19.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't come easy, however, as Cordova (12-11) continued to be
an Astros nemesis, scattering four hits and one run over seven
innings. In 11 career appearances against the Astros, Cordova is
3-2 with a 2.69 ERA. He pitched 5 scoreless innings Friday before
Ausmus doubled to lead off the sixth inning, advanced on a balk and
scored on Biggio's grounder, beating second baseman Kevin
Polcovich's throw to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Ausmus' sixth-inning hit, the Astros managed just a
single by Moises Alou in the second and Dave Clark's two-out double
in the fourth off Cordova.
</P>
<P>
   Ausmus and Biggio repeated their sixth-inning scoring play with
an almost identical one with one out in the eighth. Ausmus reached
base to begin the inning on a bunt to the third-base side that
reliever Mike Williams couldn't handle. One batter later, Ausmus
took second on a third-strike wild pitch from Williams to Johnson
and advanced to third on a throwing error by Pittsburgh catcher
Jason Kendall. Biggio drove in the run with a grounder to shortstop
as Ausmus once again beat the play at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Pirates,'' Dierker said. ``This is the way we
remember them last year. It's hard to score against them. They're
tough. Cordova still has us mystified.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Johnson had the Pirates guessing as he seemingly
gained strength as the game progressed. His 16 strikeouts eclipsed
Mike Cuellar's previous club mark of 15 by a lefthander _ set
against St. Louis in 1966 _ and marked Johnson's 98th career
double-digit strikeout game, moving him past Sandy Koufax into
second place on the all-time list. Nolan Ryan holds the record at
215.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had his velocity back,'' Ausmus said. ``He's probably
thrown as many or more pitches than anyone in baseball this year.
When you're a strikeout pitcher, you have to throw a few extra
pitches. Maybe (Thursday's day off) helped him out. It showed on
the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates' biggest scoring threat came in the eighth when they
put runners at first and third. Adrian Brown singled with one out,
and Kendall singled to right field, with Brown advancing to third
on an error by Clark. Johnson ended the threat by getting Kevin
Young to pop out to first baseman Jeff Bagwell in foul territory.
</P>
<P>
   With the Astros clinging to a one-run lead, Johnson knew it was
far from over. During their nine-game winning streak, the Pirates
had scored 72 runs and were batting .336 as a club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize I have to be focused the whole game,'' Johnson said.
``With a one-run game, the tying run is coming up every inning. It
made me stay focused. It's easy to go out there flat late in the
game. The next thing you know, a couple of guys get on base, a bad
pitch here and there, and it could have been a different ballgame.
Of all the games I've pitched for the Astros, I really felt the
most comfortable than any other I've pitched.''
</P>
<P>
   After three straight home shutouts, who can tell?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
