<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9346 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW--COMETS-HNS &LR;      08-30 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW--COMETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
If you've got game, who needs rapport?
<TEXT>
<P>
   By FRAN BLINEBURY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   The most surprising scene of the day had nothing to do with the
Comets' 12-point comeback in the last seven minutes of the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a twisting, double-pumping scoop drive through traffic
by Cynthia Cooper. It wasn't a pull-up, 15-foot, BB-shot,
line-drive, clutch jumper by Sheryl Swoopes.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't another of the tireless dozen rebounds pulled in by
the thoroughly professional Tina Thompson, one of the handful of
critical hustle plays down the stretch by Janeth Arcain or anything
that happened in front of the 16,285 screamers who nearly
overloaded the micro processors and caused a meltdown at the
Laptop.
</P>
<P>
   The photo op of the afternoon came midway through the postgame
news conference, held on a makeshift stage in a back hallway, when
Swoopes was suddenly overcome by cramps in her leg and needed
assistance. Up popped Cooper from the next chair to provide her
body for support.
</P>
<P>
   How symbolic of the Comets' first two years of existence. Cooper
_ this time quite literally _ carries the burden on her shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   How ironic, because it was one of the few times all day when the
pair of stars works in tandem.
</P>
<P>
   So the ``she-peat'' is alive.
</P>
<P>
   Comets find themselves
</P>
<P>
   At least until Tuesday night, when Swoopes and Cooper can resume
the race to beat the Phoenix Mercury or each other into submission
first.
</P>
<P>
   This one ended up with tingling good feelings all around and a
1-1 tie in the WNBA finals because the Mercury plummeted faster
than in a Norwegian January, and the Comets did what they do better
than any other club in the toddling league _ battled right down to
the finish.
</P>
<P>
   Just when Michele Timms dropped in a free throw to give Phoenix
a 62-50 lead with 7:24 left in regulation, Team Turmoil appeared
finally ready to burst like the seams in a fat man's pants.
</P>
<P>
   But what the Comets lack in overall harmony, they more than
compensate for in individual ability. Which either says something
ugly about the quality of talent in the league or speaks volumes
about their scouting department.
</P>
<P>
   For in a matter of just minutes, the team that had been kept on
its heels for more than three-fourths of the game was running
around and past its opponent as if the Mercury were playing with
its shoes in concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Center Jennifer Gillom, who suffered through 3-for-15 shooting,
never could get untracked for Phoenix. Timms, who poured in 21
points, had her faucet turned off, and all of the second-chance
tries on offensive rebounds that had allowed the Mercury to keep
the upper hand dried up.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there was Cooper (27 points) making end-to-end dashes
to convert on the fast break. There was Swoopes (14 points, 13
rebounds, five assists) coming off screens to gather in passes and
hit that jumper that is straighter than a laser beam. There were
the Comets, streaking across the sky again in the fashion that
built that gaudy 29-3 record before they were shut down in Phoenix
two nights earlier.
</P>
<P>
   No lack of atmosphere
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make you wonder how good they truly could be if
Cooper and Swoopes ever got it through their heads to play this
game together rather than continue to engage in their schoolgirl
antics of ``who gets to be Michael Jordan,'' which is partly why
the Comets fell 12 behind.
</P>
<P>
   Case No. 1: Late in the first half, Cooper jacks up a wild
25-foot heave of a 3-pointer that misses everything while Swoopes
stands wide-open on the right wing.
</P>
<P>
   Case No. 2: Early in the second half on a break, Swoopes does
not wait for Cooper to fill the lane for a pass and does a 360-spin
move, slamming into defender Kristi Harrower and resulting in a
lost opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   You could lock Bill Clinton and Ken Starr in a gym and see more
assists and smiles. And still this team wins. To the delight of the
happy, howling fans.
</P>
<P>
   Quibble with the basketball, if you must. But I've got news for
you. Val Ackerman's WNBA product is more fun, more entertaining,
more alive than David Stern's game. Maybe that's because real
people can afford to attend. Real people who aren't afraid to sweat
and yell their throats raw. Consider it a challenge to all the
corporate freeloaders and the River Oaks crowd whenever the NBA
lockout ends next Christmas. To paraphrase John Lennon: Just rattle
your jewelry, and let us know you're out there.
</P>
<P>
   This was one more comeback, one more chapter in their growing
legend, one more bid for the ``she-peat.''
</P>
<P>
   They keep doing it their way. So Cynthia Cooper and Sheryl
Swoopes live to fight another day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
