<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9489 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MTV-REMAKE-MEDIA-500&AMP;     08-30 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTV-REMAKE-MEDIA-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING THE `M' BACK IN MTV 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   About a year ago, Judy McGrath, the president of MTV, sat in her
funky office 25 floors above Times Square, wondering about changes
she felt percolating among America's 12- to 34-year-olds, the
audience that hr network serves.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our business, there's nothing worse than missing a
moment,'' she said. ``And I sensed some moments changing out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   MTV's researchers sensed it, too, and from the voluminous data
they piled on Ms. McGrath's desk, one sentence jumped out at her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone had said, `I would rather give up food than give up
music,''' Ms. McGrath recalled. ``It struck me that I hadn't seen
something like that for a long while. Hip-hop had been, undeniably,
a big, tribal rallying thing, but now I felt like all music was
coming back onto the cultural radar screen in a big way.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, MTV has made something of a comeback on that
cultural radar screen, too. After a few years of attention for
programs like ``Real World'' (a video verite show following
young-adult roommates thrown together for a year), the cartoon
``Beavis and Butt-head'' and the dating show ``Singled Out,''
starring Jenny McCarthy, MTV seemed to have strayed too far from
music.
</P>
<P>
   So Ms. McGrath began steering it back, and the results are
starting to show. Since January, MTV has seen its Nielsen ratings
rise with its primary audience. In the second quarter, those
ratings were 22 percent higher than in the corresponding quarter of
1997. For the third quarter to date, they are up 21 percent, to
0.57 from 0.49 (each full rating point equals 610,980 viewers).
</P>
<P>
   Larry Gerbrandt, an analyst with Paul Kagan Associates, the
media research and consulting firm in Carmel, Calif., said he had
projected an increase in MTV's net revenue of $522 million this
year, up from $473 million in 1997, and a gain in its cash flow to
$231 million from $223 million. Laura Walker, an analyst with First
Boston, forecast even higher revenue and cash flow growth, to $570
million and $280 million, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Hatch, a media analyst with Warburg Dillon Read, said
MTV's advertising growth this year would be ``in the 20 percent
range, which is on the high end even for cable networks.''
</P>
<P>
   MTV's advertising growth is strong each year because the network
delivers a heavy concentration of teen-age and young-adult viewers
that is available almost nowhere else.
</P>
<P>
   MTV has more competitors than ever. The emergence of Time
Warner's WB, a broadcast network dedicated to the 12- to
34-year-old group, has nibbled at MTV's audience. Although VH1 has
seen its audience grow older (its median age now is 30.5 years), it
sometimes draws MTV fans. And the continuing popularity of music by
young black artists _ hip-hop, rhythm and blues, and rap _ has made
Black Entertainment Television, or BET, a bit more of a rival.
</P>
<P>
   All of which led MTV to become ``more music-centric,'' said Tom
Freston, the president of MTV Networks, a unit of Viacom that
includes MTV, VH1, Nickelodeon, Nick at Nite and TV Land.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The re-focusing began last summer, when Ms. McGrath hired Brian
Graden, who had helped discover the scandalously irreverent cartoon
``South Park'' for Comedy Central, as director of development. She
asked him to generate pilots for music-based shows. ``We started
reminding everyone we had to treasure the `M' in MTV,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   By December, she had promoted Graden from director of
development to executive vice president in charge of all
programming. In January, they began shifting the schedule so that
music, not lifestyle shows or comedy, dominated prime time.
</P>
<P>
   By then they had also given the go-ahead to a half-dozen new
shows, which began appearing in April. In ``Artist Cut,'' a
performer describes the creation of a video or song. In ``Say
What?'' printed lyrics are overlaid on a video. ``Fanatic'' takes a
fan to meet and interview a musician or group he or she idolizes.
And ``BIOrhythm'' gives a biographical sketch of a musician without
narration, using the artist's music and the music that influenced
him, intercut with interview snippets, video footage and printed
captions.
</P>
<P>
   In formulating these programs, Graden said, the idea was ``to
imagine new and expressive ways you could present music on
television,'' aside from stringing videos together or presenting
Top 20 countdown shows.
</P>
<P>
   The new shows also serve to promote artists, which can only help
MTV's relationships with the music industry. ``Our primary
relationship is with the audience, but next in importance is with
the managers, record companies and artists,'' Ms. McGrath said,
adding that they often misunderstand MTV's focus. ``I get these
calls saying things like, `I hear MTV only wants black-and-white
videos now,' or something like that, and it's so frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   To improve music-industry relations and bolster the
music-centric strategy, Ms. McGrath two weeks ago hired Tom
Calderone as head of music programming and talent relationships. He
had been a consultant to radio stations, advising them on what
music to play, primarily in the alternative-rock genre.
</P>
<P>
   Rock genres have been in something of a creative lull for
several years, eclipsed by hip-hop, rhythm and blues, and rap.
Indeed, MTV has a show called ``Jams Countdown,'' featuring
viewers' favorite rhythm and blues and hip-hop songs, as well as
``Total Request,'' a countdown show for all types of music.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't say, `Let's go after those genres,' instead of
others,'' Graden said. ``It's just that the mainstream embraced
those genres. We're in a very rhythmic time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-98 1648EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980830.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9490 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CBS-NFL-MEDIA-ART-775     08-30 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CBS-NFL-MEDIA-ART-775&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
603-1036.)
</HEADLINE>
  
 Can Football Revive CBS?  
(ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)(lh) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget all those quarterbacks surrounded by 300-pound charging
linemen: When the National Football League season starts this
Sunday, the real pressure will be on the executives who call the
plays at CBS. And they don't get to wear helmets.
</P>
<P>
   The contract that CBS signed in January to bring the NFL back
after a four-year absence from the network is surely the most
scrutinized deal in recent television history: an eight-year, $4
billion commitment for a package of American Football Conference
games. At $500 million a year, the deal is more than a 100 percent
increase over the $217 million a year that NBC had been paying for
the same package.
</P>
<P>
   CBS executives have characterized the deal as a strategic coup
that they hope will be the linchpin to a resurgence in profits for
television's once-dominant network, which has recently posted
annual losses of $50 million to $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, critics of CBS _ mainly executives at NBC, now
out of NFL television _ call the deal financially irresponsible and
predict that CBS will begin losing $100 million to $150 million a
year on football alone.
</P>
<P>
   The football broadcasts come at a critical time for the network
and for Mel Karmazin, the president who owns 1.1 percent of CBS's
stock and who was the driving force behind the deal. Only last
Thursday, CBS announced a reorganization that included cost-cutting
measures calculated to save $180 million. Among the moves announced
were layoffs of 200 to 300 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Cost-cutting measures have been announced at both NBC and ABC
this summer; but given the questions surrounding the size of the
football deal, the moves at CBS were seen in some quarters as
preparations for Hurricane Pigskin.
</P>
<P>
   CBS executives forcefully denied that the cost-cutting was
related to the football deal, just as they have forcefully
asserted, in the face of contentions that they overpaid for NFL
games out of desperation, that their contract is sound and that the
deal will, in the words of Karmazin, ``make a dollar'' for CBS.
</P>
<P>
   One week before the first slate of Sunday afternoon games, Sean
McManus, the president of CBS Sports, is not backing away from that
rosy analysis of the deal. ``We're right on target,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers that give him confidence, McManus said, come from
increased advertising sales at both the network and CBS-owned
stations, revenue generated from an exchange of commercial time
with CBS affiliates, reduced costs for advertising in other media
to promote CBS shows and anticipated benefits to CBS's prime-time
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   The latter was among the biggest reasons CBS thought it had to
reacquire the NFL. Without it, the network had almost no
programming that attracted young male viewers. ``Over the last few
years, young men had really left us,'' said Leslie Moonves, the
president of CBS Television. ``At the least, football will get some
of that blood flowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those still skeptical about CBS's positive numbers is Dick
Ebersol, the president of NBC Sports, who said, ``CBS is practicing
a form of mathematics with which none of my professors was familiar
_ because they didn't have enough beads in their abacus.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC is the network most familiar with CBS's football package
because it owned it for 33 years. That relationship ended in
January when NBC declined to match CBS's bid. Ebersol said NBC did
not think the package could be worth more than $300 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Wolzien, a neutral observer as a media analyst for Sanford
C. Bernstein, pointed out that NBC had a special incentive for
disparaging the CBS deal: ``NBC said no way would they spend that
much, so they're trying to prove the rightness of their vision.
Still, this is a tough go for CBS. I'm projecting they'll lose $50
million on football this year.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be significant, because CBS's payments to the NFL
will rise over the length of the contract. The network is actually
paying the least amount this season, an estimated $350 million. The
later payments will be especially huge, but CBS is counting on
advertising revenue to increase over time.
</P>
<P>
   McManus said, ``The true value to CBS is not going to be felt
for four or five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said, there is reason to be optimistic about
this season. CBS is getting better prices for commercial time
during the AFC games than NBC did, he said. Advertising industry
publications have estimated that CBS is getting about a 10 percent
increase, a figure NBC questions. McManus declined to comment on
the figure, but CBS's private estimates are that it will do even
better than that, an executive close to CBS said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   One reason CBS may be doing better with ad sales, McManus said,
is that the AFC teams are finally perceived to be fully competitive
with those in the NFC, whose games are broadcast by Fox.
</P>
<P>
   CBS estimated that NBC sold ads in its package for about 15
percent less than Fox did, a disparity that CBS regarded as unfair.
But Ebersol pointed out that advertisers prefer to be in games that
reach the country's 10 biggest cities. The NFC has eight teams in
those cities; the AFC has three.
</P>
<P>
   What might help CBS in selling the games is simply that they are
new to it. When NBC pried the National Basketball Association games
away from CBS starting in 1990 for $600 million, the bid was
labeled dangerously high. But NBC, which extended the deal in 1993
for $750 million and again last year for $1.75 billion through
2002, found aggressive new ways to sell the games and made a huge
profit. CBS says it is doing the same thing with football this
year.
</P>
<P>
   McManus pointed to $45 million in new business that CBS has
attracted from Nasdaq, Southwest Airlines and other companies. But
Ebersol said that $25 million to $30 million in new business was
typical every year.
</P>
<P>
   McManus said he was also counting on about $40 million in a deal
the network made with affiliates to exchange commercial time in
other parts of the CBS schedule. Then there is about $25 million
that CBS is counting on saving from money it has been spending in
other media to promote its programs, which it now thinks it can do
during games.
</P>
<P>
   Some competing network executives question whether CBS can
really count on the $40 million in cash from its complicated deal
with its affiliates. And the questions about CBS come from more
quarters than just NBC. ABC and Fox were not happy either when CBS
started off the NFL negotiations with its pre-emptive bid for the
AFC. In effect, the NFL used CBS's urgency to set the price for
every package.
</P>
<P>
   One senior executive from a competing NFL network said CBS's
approach was amateurish. ``They didn't have to go in that high,''
the executive said.
</P>
<P>
   But CBS was fighting for nothing less than survival, at least in
terms of perception. ``The perception when CBS lost football was
that it was a second-class network,'' Moonves said.
</P>
<P>
   Always encumbered by being the network with the oldest audience
_ in a business where advertisers pay premiums to reach younger
adults _ CBS has been disastrously deficient in reaching younger
men. Just adding the young men from NBC's AFC audience last year
would improve CBS's reach among men by 60 percent to 90 percent,
CBS says its research estimates.
</P>
<P>
   McManus said CBS carefully calculated the value of the NFL
before it made its huge bid. Crucial was the benefit to the
stations CBS owns, seven of which are in cities with AFC teams.
Those stations are adding many tie-in programs to the football
games _ coaches' shows for example. If the stations gain in local
market share, that will help justify the price, McManus said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, if CBS gains younger male viewers for its prime-time
shows, the football deal will help pay for itself. David Poltrack,
the executive vice president of CBS Research said, ``As little as a
10 percent increase in male viewers, spread around prime time,
could generate a substantial profit increase.''
</P>
<P>
   If that success came because CBS had a breakout hit show, the
increase in advertising revenue could make up a large bit of the
football price all by itself, though CBS has not had a hit with
young male viewers in years. CBS is hoping that by promoting its
shows during the football games, viewers will at least start to
sample CBS shows.
</P>
<P>
   But the promotional value of sports has always been one of
television's biggest imponderables. CBS had the Winter Olympics
last year, yet no show the network promoted during that event
developed into a hit. And Sunday football presents some special
problems for CBS's program promotions.
</P>
<P>
   First, there are questions about the duration of any promotion's
effect. Can a Sunday football game really be used to promote, say,
CBS's new martial arts show, ``Martial Law,'' on Saturday nights,
six days after the last tackle is made?
</P>
<P>
   Promotions during Sunday football are most effective for shows
on Sunday nights. But Sunday is already CBS's best night. Its top
show, ``60 Minutes,'' is almost certain to be helped by direct
lead-ins from football. But how many football fans can be delivered
to ``Touched by an Angel'' and CBS's Sunday movie, which mainly
appeal to women?
</P>
<P>
   CBS does have some Monday shows with male stars, including
``Cosby,'' ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' and the new ``Benben'' show.
But all those shows will run against ``Monday Night Football'' on
ABC, which presumably would be a stronger draw to fans who watch
football on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Poltrack questioned that, citing statistics that showed that
only 30 percent of the younger men watching the AFC on Sunday tuned
in to ``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that while promotional effect diminishes as days
pass, viewers could be at least made aware of shows. Thus, if a
younger man sees a promotion for ``Martial Law'' on Sunday and
happens to be scanning channels the next Saturday, he might find
the show and remember he had seen the commercial for it.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens in terms of the profit and loss this season,
CBS executives say they think they did the right thing to get back
into business with the NFL, because network television is becoming
more and more dependent on one-of-a-kind event programming. They
pointed to the deal Fox signed with the NFL four years ago, which
was then ridiculed as recklessly overpriced at $395 million a year.
But, even though Fox eventually took a $350 million write-off on
losses related to football, the NFL deal by every other assessment
was a huge success, helping to put Fox on the map as a network.
</P>
<P>
   Chase Carey, the chairman of Fox Television, said in a speech in
June that NBC's decision to pass on the NFL deal ``will go down as
one of the defining moments of recent network history,'' one, he
said, that NBC is likely to regret.
</P>
<P>
   With the NBA, the Olympics and other sports events still in
their grip, NBC executives are convinced that their network can
survive easily without football. The question, as Ebersol and other
NBC executives see it, is whether CBS can survive with it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
