<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9497 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-CRISIS01-COX     08-30 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CRISIS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL CRISIS DEEPENS AS COMMUNISTS VOW TO OPPOSE
CHERNOMYRDIN
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin and the opposition-led
parliament were headed for a political showdown Monday after the
Communist Party said it would vote against the nomination of Viktor
Chernomyrdin as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise announcement Sunday night came only hours after the
Kremlin and parliamentary leaders had forged a tentative
power-sharing agreement to form a new government and begin coping
with Russia's deep financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The domestic political turmoil increased the chances President
Clinton will arrive Tuesday for a two-day summit with Yeltsin with
no permanent Russian government in place.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative deal reached Sunday would have meant an
unprecedented surrender of some powers by the imperious Yeltsin to
the parliament. But it appeared to unravel, leaving Russia where it
began the day, on the verge of economic collapse and with no one
clearly in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov said his party would
vote Monday against the confirmation of Chernomyrdin, who served as
prime minister from 1992 until being sacked by Yeltsin last March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chernomyrdin is an accomplice with Yeltsin in the destruction
of the past five years'' of Russia's economy, Zyuganov said in an
interview on Russian television.
</P>
<P>
   The Communists, with 138 seats in the 450-member Duma,
parliament's lower house, also announced they would vote en bloc
against the power-sharing deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Duma's third largest bloc, the 51-seat Liberal Democratic
Party led by ultra-nationalist Vladimir Zhirinovsky, also announced
its opposition to Chernomyrdin and to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The 45-seat Yabloko bloc in parliament, which advocates
Western-style reforms, also announced it would oppose Chernomyrdin
and the agreement. Its leader, Grigory Yavlinsky, said it suspected
the power-sharing deal would be scrapped by the Kremlin after
Chernomyrdin's confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the three blocs control enough seats to defeat
Chernomyrdin. But he could still win enough votes for confirmation
Monday, especially if the vote is taken by secret ballot, which
would make party discipline hard to enforce.
</P>
<P>
   If the Duma were to fail three times to approve Yeltsin's
nominee for prime minister, the president must under Russia's
constitution dissolve the Duma and call new elections, which aren't
scheduled to take place until late 1999. Then, Yeltsin also can
install Chernomyrdin as prime minister without the approval of
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   In his TV appearance, Zyuganov said that he was willing to
continue negotiations with the Kremlin. That suggested the
Communist leader's outspoken antagonism is a bargaining tactic as
parliament seeks more power.
</P>
<P>
   The political machinations over the weekend overshadowed
Russia's economic crisis. Outward signs of public anxiety subsided
as banks and financial markets were closed.
</P>
<P>
   But polls show there is widespread public skepticism that
Russia's current political leaders can pull the country out of its
troubled times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a nice scenario, the coalition, all factions agreeing to
cooperate to solve Russia's problems. But look at the factions and
the differing views of the people involved. Even if an arrangement
is agreed upon, how quickly will it be able to implement (economic)
solutions? How soon before one faction or another gets angry and
breaks off?'' said Sergei Markov, director of Institute for
Political Studies, a Moscow research center.
</P>
<P>
   After a party caucus late Sunday, Zyuganov said the Communist
bloc in parliament was unwilling to accept an agreement that
offered no assurances that Yeltsin or Chernomyrdin would adhere to
the power-sharing arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, the document is not guaranteeing anybody anything,''
Zyuganov said.
</P>
<P>
   The Communists and other hard-line factions in the Duma are
seeking to obtain seats in the cabinet for at least several of
their members and gain a meaningful role in formulating government
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Under the three-page agreement drafted after frantic weekend
talks, Yeltsin would retain control of the security forces with the
right to fill three key posts _ the ministries of defense, foreign
affairs and internal security. In exchange, he would agree for the
first time to seek Duma approval of most other cabinet
appointments.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Yeltsin would agree not to dissolve the Duma, and
parliamentary leaders would refrain from taking a no-confidence
vote on the prime minister's government.
</P>
<P>
   While falling short of what they had sought, the document seemed
to represent a breakthrough for the opposition, stymied for years
by the broad constitutional powers possessed by Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin was scheduled to meet Monday with Chernomyrdin to
discuss the weekend negotiations with parliament leaders. The
Kremlin said Yeltsin would probably make his views known on the
political negotiations after that meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview taped Friday but not aired in full
until Sunday, Yeltsin said it was premature to change the 1993
constitution, which gave him sweeping, almost dictatorial, powers.
</P>
<P>
   But he advocated a constitutional commission representing all
political factions to consider amendments. Yeltsin said such a
commission ``would need much time,'' perhaps as long as a year, to
complete its work.
</P>
<P>
   Since Yeltsin fired Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko and his team
of economic reformers on Aug. 23 and reinstated Chernomyrdin to the
job, speculation has been rampant that Yeltsin would either resign
or become a figurehead president, handing over most
responsibilities to Chernomyrdin, 60.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, 67 and ailing, said in the television interview that he
would not quit and that it would be ``impossible'' to remove him
from office before his term ends in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin said Sunday his confirmation as prime minister was
critical to Russia's ability to prevent an economic collapse.
</P>
<P>
   He said the ruble, which has fallen in value as much as 50
percent in street trading over the past two weeks, ``is hanging on
a thin thread.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin has appointed three respected reformers _ cabinet
members Boris Fyodorov and Mikhail Zadornov and Central Bank
Chairman Sergei Dubinin _ to a commission charged with forming an
anti-crisis plan.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin said: ``Time must not be lost. ...A country should
not live without a government for a single day. Instead we keep on
talking for weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
