<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Aug. 31, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cool air with low humidity will spread across the Great Lakes
into the interior Northeast as a cold front moves gradually off the
Northeast Coast. A broken area of showers will linger near the
front in New England, especially over the mountain of New Hampshire
and Maine. Otherwise, a mixture of sunshine and puffy clouds will
prevail across the region.
</P>
<P>
   High surf will lash parts of the Southeast Coast as Hurricane
Danielle begins to curve out to sea 250 miles miles east of the
Georgia coast. Most of the Southeast will be hot and humid. A few
strong thunderstorms will form during the afternoon from the
interior Gulf Coast states to the southern Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   A sprawling low-pressure zone centered over the southern Gulf of
Mexico will be surrounded by bands of heavy thundershowers. A few
of the bands may brush the Texas and Louisiana coasts as well as
parts of southern Florida.
</P>
<P>
   A cluster of thundershowers will move through the southern
Missouri Valley near a front separating hot conditions over the
southern Plains from cooler air to the north. Another front marking
the leading edge of an autumnal air mass will promote a few showers
from the Dakotas to northern Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Unusually hot weather will persist in many areas west of the
Rockies. Near record heat is expected in parts of the interior
Northwest. Offshore winds will send hot air toward the normally
cooler coastal areas from Oregon to southern California. Farther
east, scattered afternoon thunderstorms will form over the central
and southern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: When Summer Ends
</P>
<P>
   Near record heat will occur in many areas west of the Rockies
this week. Yet, among the official keepers of climatological
records, summer in the northern hemisphere will end Monday, the
last day of the three warmest months of the year. For many, the
traditional end of summer will come a week from Monday on Labor
Day. But the beginning and end of a season is an astronomical
event, not a meteorological one. Astronomers, sticklers for
precision, will declare an end to summer at 1:37 a.m. EDT on Sept.
23, when the direct rays of the noontime sun shift into the
southern hemisphere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
