<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-NEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE ENGINEER TESTS LAW ON ENCRYPTION CODE  
 WEB COMPANY RIDES INITIAL-OFFERING WAVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles Booher was hardly surprised last month when two agents
from the Department of Commerce knocked on his door in Silicon
Valley and handed him a federal subpoena. In fact, he had been
expecting it ever since he first made his data-encryption program
available on the Internet in the summer of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department is investigating whether Booher's
software, which is called Secure Office and is intended to protect
the privacy of computer files by scrambling the data, violates U.S.
export law. The rules require Americans who distribute encryption
software internationally to obtain an export license; making
software available on the Internet is considered international
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Booher acknowledges that few people have downloaded the software
from his Web site at www.filesafety.com. But a big number of users
was not his real goal.
</P>
<P>
   Booher, a software engineer at Phase Metrics Corp. in Fremont,
Calif., who wrote the encryption program in his spare time, said he
posted the program to challenge the export rules.
</P>
<P>
   Encryption has been a hotly debated issue in Washington lately,
with the Commerce Department, the FBI and other agencies arguing
that powerful data-scrambling programs put high-technology
espionage tools in the hands of criminals, spies and terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   But Booher is among the software developers who contend that
their right to write encryption code is protected by the First
Amendment and that the technology is already easily available
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is not whether this stuff is going to exist,''
Booher said, ``but who will develop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Monika Wasiewicz, the Commerce Department agent in charge of the
case, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Booher was supposed to testify to a federal grand jury in San
Jose, Calif., last week, but the session was canceled because too
few jurors showed up. Booher's testimony is supposed to be
rescheduled for this week.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
<P>
   WEB Company Rides Initial-Offering Wave
</P>
<P>
   For any curious observer of the business world who sits before
Mark Cuban, president of Broadcast.com in Dallas, the most pressing
question is not the state of media on the Internet or the future
direction of his company, which transmits audio and video
programming over the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   The question is probably: What was going through his mind on
July 16 as he watched the stock price of his company shoot from $18
to $74 before settling at $62.75, the best first day for an initial
public offering in history?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God, this is really, really cool,'' he remembers
thinking as he sat in the New York offices of Nasdaq and watched
the numbers ticking higher and higher. By the end of that first
day, the company's valuation exceeded $1 billion, and his personal
net worth _ on paper, at least _ rose to $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been married, but I guess that feeling I had that
day was similar to what a groom would feel at the altar,'' Cuban
said. ``I've never been the No. 1 draft pick for the NFL or NBA,
either. Actually, that's probably even closer to the point.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban, 40, was making the rounds in Manhattan last week with his
business partner, Todd Wagner, 38, after the so-called quiet period
when principals in newly public companies are not permitted to
publicly discuss the stock.
</P>
<P>
   It was an interesting week to be touring Wall Street. By the end
of last week's widespread market carnage, shares of Broadcast.com
were trading at $44.375, down $6.625 on Friday alone. That was
still well above the company's offering price but off more than 29
percent from its first-day close.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban said he remained inspired by his vision of the mythic
``94-year-old lady'' who may have bought shares at $74. ``I want to
make her look like a financial genius,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA NAPOLI
</P>
</TEXT>
