<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AD-COLUMN-765&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NFL AD WAR, SPONSORS PLAYING TOUGH DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even if the National Football League season that begins in six
days offers fans one close, hard-fought clash after another, it
will be difficult to match the intense, high-stakes preseason
skirmishing between the networks showing the games and the
advertisers sponsoring them.
</P>
<P>
   The huge increases in fees being paid by four networks for
rights to the telecasts of pro football for the next eight seasons
spurred them at first to consider selling commercial time at rates
25 to 30 percent higher for 1998-99 than for 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   But when executives at the agencies handling media chores for
marketers countered that _ to paraphrase the assertion made by
George Foreman in Meineke muffler commercials _ they weren't going
to pay a lot for this season, the increases the networks asked for
were held to much lower levels, an estimated 8 to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people may have casually mentioned, `Oh, the advertisers
will pay for it,''' said Steve Grubbs, executive vice president for
national broadcast buying at the BBDO New York unit of Omnicom
Group, ``but that's one thing you don't say.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he added, ``the costs are nowhere near what was
projected before negotiations began.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, always healthy give and take, and not a
small amount of posturing, in the annual negotiations between
networks and advertisers. The networks' hands are strengthened by
the fact that football remains the mainstay for marketers seeking
to reach male consumers in the important fall and Christmas
shopping seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a certain degree, we're a business of no surprises,'' said
Jon Mandel, co-managing director and chief negotiating officer at
Mediacom, the media services unit of Grey Advertising in New York.
``And football is still one of the best programs on television
because you know what you're going to get: the ratings it delivers,
the demographics it delivers, which are hard to replicate.''
</P>
<P>
   Another selling point for the networks is the power of live
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important element to me when I buy an ad in any
medium is the attention and involvement of the audience,'' said
Gene DeWitt, chairman of DeWitt Media Inc., a leading media buyer
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still jump up and down and shout at the screen while
watching football,'' he said. ``That's good.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, marketers must perceive that they are
getting value for the hundreds of millions of dollars they spend
with the networks that own the rights, which are now the ABC and
ESPN units of Walt Disney Co.; CBS, owned by CBS Corp., and the Fox
Broadcasting Co. division of News Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football is a big, important vehicle for advertisers as long
as pricing stays within reason,'' said John Muszynski, senior vice
president and executive director for the national television buying
group at Starcom Media Services, a unit of the Leo Burnett Co. in
Chicago. ``Otherwise, they're going to re-evaluate whether the NFL
is still something they need.''
</P>
<P>
   The most fervent opposition to paying significantly more for
commercials during the 1998-99 season came from Detroit automakers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even without that, prices were unlikely to rise steeply
because ``the national broadcast network marketplace has been soft
in general,'' said Larry Blasius, senior vice president and
director for national broadcast at TN Media, a unit of True North
Communications in New York.
</P>
<P>
   And a policy change by the NFL, requiring the networks to end
segments known as ``enhancements'' _ brief sponsored moments like
scoreboards and replays _ may have discouraged smaller advertisers,
Blasius said.
</P>
<P>
   One agency executive, however, said he was pleased with the
elimination of the enhancements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes the telecasts `cleaner' for viewers and therefore
more valuable to those advertisers remaining with football,'' said
Peter Chrisanthopoulos, president for broadcast and programming-USA
at Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide, a unit of WPP Group PLC in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football is the pre-eminent sport on television,'' he said,
``garnering the largest ratings and reaching the largest number of
men. With reasonable prices advertisers feel comfortable with, not
in proportion to the increases in the rights fees, they continued
with the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, commercial time on pro football games for September and
October is, to use an expression of the TV advertising marketplace,
very well sold.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Mandel of Mediacom put it, chuckling: ``The market is
softer than the networks planned. But we'll turn on our TVs and
there it will be _ advertising.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That will be particularly true on Jan. 31, when Fox is to
broadcast Super Bowl XXXIII. Marketers have already bought about 70
percent of available time during the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I understand, the Super Bowl is sold out in the
first half and maybe in the first three quarters,'' said Grubbs of
BBDO New York, who added that he has bought spots for ``the usual
suspects'' like the Pepsi-Cola Co. unit of Pepsico Inc. and Visa
USA, as well as ``some other people I can't talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Time on Super Sunday is being marked up much more steeply than
spots during regular-season games as a result of what Grubbs called
``the `Seinfeld' effect'' _ that is, the eye-popping rates,
averaging $1.5 million to $1.7 million, for each 30-second
commercial during the ``Seinfeld'' finale in May.
</P>
<P>
   Some advertisers are paying an estimated average of $1.6 million
for each 30-second spot in Super Bowl XXXIII, up 23 percent from
the average cost of $1.3 million for each such spot in Super Bowl
XXXII.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though I don't know if you should believe everything you
read,'' said Muszynski of Starcom, referring to those reported
average prices, ``the Super Bowl is still an incredibly powerful
vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   And as Blasius of TN Media noted, Super Sunday has increasingly
become ``a platform for advertisers to showcase their new and best
creative work.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the networks can bring back one enhancement for regular
season games: a ``commercial showcase'' for Super Bowl-style spots
_ priced at Super Bowl rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
