<SLUG> BC-TV-COP-ART-325&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX CRIME REPORTER IS NO TV SMOOTHIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Mike Sheehan is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(Duplication warning: Also filed in ``f'' category) 
(mk) 
 By CHARLIE LEDUFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the world of television news, the impending doom
of deadline can be measured by the number of reporters in
overpriced suits scurrying about the newsroom like billiard balls
without a pocket.
</P>
<P>
   At a quarter-to-five, the newsroom at Fox 5/WNYW-TV is at a
muted frenzy. A self-important junior reporter with padded
shoulders gripes to someone of little influence that his stories
never make the first segment. Another reporter, in a pink skirt,
voices her displeasure, in language that would make a longshoreman
blush, at a script she has not written and says is not up to her
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Above the din, seemingly unaware, Mike Sheehan, the hard-boiled
crime reporter, sits at his terminal, waiting for the one
illuminating line to pop onto his screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy's a sicko,'' he says in a voice more Jimmy Breslin
than Tom Brokaw. ``How do you sexually assault a 5-year-old?''
</P>
<P>
   Sheehan, 50, is not your typical television reporter. ``I ain't
the most handsome horse in the stable,'' he says. He looks funny on
camera, like a normal guy with his graying hair and aging face, the
Irish jowls and a thick New York tenor.
</P>
<P>
   Off-camera, his dialogue is so salty it could cure fish. He
claims it is that tongue, that certain New York sensibility, the 25
years on the streets as an undercover officer and then as a
homicide detective, that has at least gotten him close to the big
time.
</P>
<P>
   He may be underestimating himself. He is in the big time, one of
the most recognizable crime reporters in New York, and it is
precisely his sleuthing skills that got his face on television in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admit that the Damon Runyon thing works for me,'' he said
over a beer at Phoenix Park Pub on East 67th Street after filing
his report on the child abuser. ``A little Dashiell Hammett works
on New York news. People like that, the cop-speak. Words like
nabbed, nailed and collared. I'm one of the only true `born and
bred never left town' New Yorkers on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is much more than the tough-guy image that makes someone
like Mike Sheehan a bona fide reporter. It is his extensive
contacts within law-enforcement circles and his ability to
reconstruct a crime. Crime is still the bread and butter of tabloid
and local television news. But crime is down and the Giuliani
administration is stingy in doling out information. In a sense,
this plays to Sheehan's strengths. Detectives call him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought detectives do exactly what reporters do,''
said Robert Daley, a former foreign correspondent for The New York
Times, who served as the deputy commissioner of public information
for the New York Police Department in 1971 under Mayor John
Lindsay. ``They both go out and talk to people and find out what
the hell is going on. The difference is, a reporter is stopped at
the police line.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheehan says that with fewer sensational crimes, storytelling
becomes even more crucial. ``It's a dog and pony show,'' he said.
``Child molesters. Floaters. Missing people. There's not a whole
lot of bodies out there these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be able to stretch, to dance, what they call
filling air. What I'm able to bring to the viewer in a situation
like that is a rundown of what detectives are doing behind the
tape.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, there are a few others like him. The New York Daily
News has a police reporter, John Marzulli, a former officer.
WNBC/Channel 4 recently hired Scott Weinberger, who is being billed
as a former police officer from Florida, although NBC officials,
asked last week, would not say what city in Florida. The New Yorker
magazine recently hired a mole within the NYPD, a man who writes
under the pseudonym Marcus Laffey. The assistant to Laffey's agent
demanded a list of questions before he would get in touch with his
boss about getting in touch with his client.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sheehan is from the old school. No handlers. No agents.
Shoot from the hip. Last Monday, Sheehan awoke at 6:30 a.m. at his
home in TriBeCa, put on the kettle and tuned his radio to 1010
WINS-AM Radio. He turned on the television, flipped through the
morning talk shows, read the papers, checked his two pagers. He
dressed himself in tasseled loafers, a blue Oxford shirt, orange
tie and put his gold detective's shield _ badge No. 421 _ in his
pocket. He kissed his wife and lumbered off to work.
</P>
<P>
   It has been the same routine since he joined Fox six years ago.
It wasn't a bad transition for the man who as a detective worked
the John Lennon case, helped crack the Preppy Murder (the Robert
Chambers case) and the Central Park Jogger case.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made me an offer, so what was I going to do? Turn it down
and kick myself in the head for the rest of my life?'' he asked
himself after a third beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest part was convincing some of the past pinheads and
pencil-necked geeks'' _ journalists with college credentials but
little street knowledge _ ``that I wasn't some dumb slob, but a
trained investigator who knows the streets.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The son of an Irish immigrant from County Cork, Sheehan grew up
in Yorkville on 97th Street and Madison Avenue, graduated from
Manhattan College and began his police career as a student
infiltrator at Columbia University in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, he was the first journalist to report the arrest
