<P>
   DIANA-MEMORIAL _ PARIS _ Parisians and tourists have been
invited to join a candle-lit procession to the Pont de lAlma to
commemorate the first anniversary of the death of Diana, Princess
of Wales. A ceremony will be held at 12:26 a.m. (local time) today,
to mark the moment when Dianas limousine hit the 13th pillar of an
underpass on a right bank expressway. Her companion, Dodi Fayed,
and the driver, Henri Paul, also died. The ceremony is being
organized by a private association, Paris Odysee, after the royal
family informed the British embassy and Paris city council that
expressions of grief should be limited to personal reflection.
(Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   with/ PBP-DIANA-CHARITY _ It's been one year since Diana's
death, and charities galore have been set up in her name. How much
have they raked in? Have local charities noticed a boost?
(Grantham, Palm Beach Post). 30.
</P>
<P>
   DIANATV _ ATLANTA _ NBC's two-hour documentary salute to
Princess Diana on the first anniversary of her death is THE tribute
to watch, with insightful insiders' accounts and fresh, seldom-seen
video and photos. Produced by Oscar winner Richard Attenborough
(``Gandhi''). Grade: A-. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DIENGLAND _ Dateline to come _ Diana is remembered with a
saintly glow by her countrymen. (Campbell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CRISIS MOSCOW Confronted by the country's economic
turmoil and with no one clearly in charge, the Kremlin and leaders
of the Communist-led parliament forged a political truce Sunday
designed to allow a new government to begin coping with the crisis.
The agreement would smooth the way for the Duma on Monday to
confirm Viktor Chernomyrdin as prime minister before the arrival
Tuesday of President Clinton for a summit with President Boris
Yeltsin. The compromise seeks to end a week of uncertainty over who
is running Russia as the ruble plummets in value and consumer
prices rise. The document, reached during frantic weekend
negotiations, would force Yeltsin to relinquish some of his
extensive powers. But it does not go as far as Communists had
sought. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: To move by 4 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   The stories RUSSIA-CLINTON and RUSSIA-BOX setting up President
Clinton's scheduled arrival in Moscow, orginally scheduled for
Monday papers, will now move Monday for Tuesday papers.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   DDN-COX-ISSUELESS_ DAYTON, Ohio _ When Republican candidate for
governor Bob Taft unveiled a major initiative to help financially
strapped families make ends meet, the event didn't make the late
evening news in the state capitol. A burning hay field, a store
running out of lottery tickets and a three-day-old report about
vandals hitting a suburban school did. Likewise, when Democrat Lee
Fisher released a health care proposal that will be a centerpiece
of his campaign, it did not initially make the airwaves _ and only
one major newspaper ran the story on page one the next day. In 10
weeks, Ohioans will choose their next governor. The winner will
face a daunting list of challenges _ school funding, electric
utility deregulation, HMO reform, prison overcrowding, privatizing
public services and tax reform. But for most voters, perhaps the
only contact they will have with the candidates will be through the
million of dollars in paid TV advertising that will flood the
airwaves during the final weeks leading to Nov. 3. (Miller, Dayton
Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   GLENN-SCIENCE _ WASHINGTON _ At T-minus two months to the space
shuttle launch of Sen. John Glenn, the scientific value of his
mission seems likely to remain dwarfed by the towering romance of a
first-generation space hero's historic return. (Montgomery, Cox
News Service 950).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moved by Dayton in advance.
</P>
<P>
   HPLANE _ Reporter Ian Trontz is going to Biloxi this week to hop
aboard a 12-hour hurricane tracking plane. (Trontz, Pam Beach
Post).
</P>
<P>
   SUNSCREEN-LEGEND _ ATLANTA _ Did you hear the one about the kid
who went blind from getting sunscreen in his eyes? Well, it didn't
happen. At least not from what anyone can tell. Seems as if the new
urban legend got started on the Internet, and it continues to
proliferate. For the record, you won't go blind from using
sunscreen. (Hill, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
