<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: INTERNET SEARCH SYSTEM; BRA FOR WOMEN AFTER HEART SURGERY;
DETECTING FAKE VIDEOTAPES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ind., Conn.)  (lb) 
 By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Searching the Internet is inevitably an exercise in information
overload.
</P>
<P>
   Type a single word and you are likely to get thousands of hits,
only a handful of which are pertinent to your actual field of
interest. Adding an extra search term can often make things worse _
instead of narrowing your search, you can end up with even more
hits.
</P>
<P>
   But what if you could pose a question to the search engine in
plain English, in the same way that you might pose a question to
the research librarian at your local library? And what if the
search engine could understand the question, and respond to it
precisely, just as an all-knowing librarian would be able to reach
for the right book on the reference shelf?
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Dahlgren, a computational linguist, and her colleague,
Edward Stabler, contend that they have built exactly such a search
engine, which they recently patented.
</P>
<P>
   The system, dubbed Inquizit, is based on natural-language
searching, which means that it retrieves and stores information in
much the way that people talk.
</P>
<P>
   The system is built in part on a set of principles Ms. Dahlgren
laid out in her 1988 book, ``Naive Semantics for Natural Language
Understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We model the way people interpret the meanings of a word _
through context,'' Ms. Dahlgren said. ``We search on meaning by
using grammar and structure and semantics. Every word has
associated with it a set of beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Ms. Dahlgren said, a query such as ``What kinds of wood
are bats made of?'' would probably yield documents having to do
with baseball bats and hickory.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, a query using identical key words with vastly
different meanings _ ``Do bats live in the woods?'' for example _
would yield documents about species of bats that live in trees.
</P>
<P>
   But don't other search engines, like Ask Jeeves
(www.askjeeves.com), already rely on natural-language retrieval?
Ms. Dahlgren says no.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these pseudo-natural-language searches, you write the
sentence and they throw away the little words and then do a
standard Boolean search, possibly with some statistics thrown in,''
she said. ``But they are essentially all pattern matchers. Since
they don't actually figure out what the query means, they end up
with enormous over-retrieval.''
</P>
<P>
   During a recent visit to the askjeeves.com site, the query
``What kinds of wood are bats made of?'' turned up 10 sites,
including three devoted to the actor James Woods, two that sold
golfing equipment, and encyclopedia entries on ``bat,'' ``bats''
and ``wood.''
</P>
<P>
   The query ``Do bats live in the woods?'' turned up six hits,
including a site selling softball and baseball equipment, a site
that features major-league batting-average records, and a link to
the Death Clock site, ``the Internet's friendly reminder that life
is slipping away.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dahlgren acknowledged that others, like Microsoft, are
trying to develop true natural-language programs. But she said the
difference between her approach and that of Microsoft was that she
and Stabler had hand-built their vast linguistic dictionary _ an
undertaking that took nearly 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft is trying to write dictionaries automatically by
searching machine-coded dictionaries,'' she said. ``We actually
built the dictionary by hand, as opposed to throwing a machine at
the problem so we wouldn't have to sit down and write up all these
linguistic rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft declined to comment on Inquizit's technology and on
Ms. Dahlgren's assessment of its own approach.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, Inquizit has been financed by an Army research grant,
private investors and ``sweat equity,'' according to Ms. Dahlgren.
So if Inquizit has discovered the Holy Grail of search engines, why
hasn't it been gobbled up yet by a Microsoft or Yahoo?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking to companies whose names you would recognize,''
said Taylor Hawke, director of marketing for Inquizit. He said that
the company planned to license its technology but that it was
considering setting up its own Internet search engine.
</P>
<P>
   Inquizit, which is based in Santa Monica, Calif., received
patent No. 5,794,050.
</P>
<P>
   Bra for Women After Heart Surgery
</P>
<P>
   Mary Whisman had open-heart surgery a few years ago, as did her
daughter and her daughter-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that women have this terrible problem that men
don't have,'' Mrs. Whisman said. ``Store-bought brassieres push
terribly on the place where they put the wire in after they open up
your sternum.''
</P>
<P>
   So Mrs. Whisman has patented a brassiere for postoperative
open-heart-surgery patients.
</P>
<P>
   Its main feature is a roll of soft padding that sits underneath
the breasts, and keeps the bra from pressing directly against the
sternum area. The bra, which opens in front, holds each breast in a
separate cup and features wide, padded straps, according to Mrs.
Whisman.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Whisman, who lives in North Vernon, Ind., said she hoped to
license patent No. 5,782,670.
</P>
<P>
   System to Detect Fake Videotapes
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a way to verify whether those videotapes of alien
spaceships are authentic.
</P>
<P>
   Harlan Brothers, of Branford, Conn., has patented a video-camera
encryption system that uses Global Positioning System satellite
receivers to encode videotape with the time and place it was taken.
The tape is then played back on special equipment that decodes and
displays information about the time and place.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the case of UFOs, you would be able to know whether the
tape was doctored in any way,'' Brothers said. ``Of course, that
doesn't stop anyone from staging an event.''
</P>
<P>
   Brothers, who is seeking to license patent No. 5,799,083, said
the technology had more pedestrian applications, such as
documentation for insurance purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Patents are available by number for $3 from the Patent and
Trademark Office, Washington DC 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-98 1733EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
