<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Monday, Aug. 31. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-RDP (Moscow) _ With great fanfare, Kremlin aides and
Russian lawmakers announce a new accord that would ease the bitter
standoff over power-sharing between President Boris Yeltsin and the
Communist-dominated parliament. But within a few hours, the much
celebrated breakthrough, intended to pave the way for Viktor
Chernomyrdin's approval as prime minister, broke down, as leading
political leaders squabbled petulantly on national television. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ASSESS (Moscow) _ News analysis: Judging by how the grand
and improbable alliance between Russia's westernized leadership and
its Communist critics exploded _ on television, spectacularly, in a
crossfire of accusations and threats _ one might think these people
hadn't a clue about what to do with their country. One would almost
be right. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-FLOOD (Xinzhen, China) _ On the plight of flood victims in
north China. In this far-north region known for early winters of
thick ice and bitter cold, the flood waters that now cover
thousands of villages will not recede for more than a month. So
huge numbers of refugees will face the winter's daily subzero
temperatures without a permanent home. By Elisabeth Rosenthal. With
map, sidebar CHINA-ARMY. 1,700 words.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   EPA-TESTING (Union Dale, N.Y.) _ The Environmental Protection
Agency is gearing up for the most ambitious and methodical regime
ever proposed to test chemicals for harmful side effects. By John
H. Cushman Jr. 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DEMS (Washington) _ In the two weeks since President
Clinton acknowledged his relationship with Monica Lewinsky, the
tension and uncertainty within the Democratic Party have not
diminished but have intensified as its candidates gear up for the
general election campaign. By Richard L. Berke. 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NORTHWEST-DAKOTA (Grand Forks, N.D.) _ Almost everything in
Grand Forks, North Dakota's third-largest city, depends in some way
on Northwest Airlines. Northwest delivers the mail here. It brings
medical supplies for the hospital, flowers for the florists, even
goldfish for the pet stores. No other passenger airline flies in or
out. For the rest of this spread-out, wide-open state, this single
airline has become an umbilical cord. By Pam Belluck. With
NORTHWEST-STRIKE.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-ASSESS (New York) _ News analysis: What the stock market
is trying to say about the economy. The sharp selloff in stocks has
led a growing number of people on Wall Street to wonder whether the
stock market, often a leading economic indicator, is forecasting a
recession in the United States. By Ed Wyatt. 1,400 words.
</P>
