u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIANATV-COX     08-30 0375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIANATV-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Finally, a royal TV treatment (Grade: A-)
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a brief interview midway through NBC's classy new tribute to
the late Princess of Wales, a waiter at a midscale London
restaurant recalls serving dinner to Diana and her young sons,
Princes William and Harry. After he recited the specials that
weren't on the menu, Harry asked, ``Did we get to hear about those
because we're special?''
</P>
<P>
   To which Harry's mum replied, ``You're going to get a special
smack in a minute.''
</P>
<P>
   You hear that little anecdote, so grounded and appealingly
resonant to every parent, and think: Where was that woman a year
ago in all the grief-drenched media coverage, the breathless
beatification and obsession with scandal and driver Henri Paul's
blood alcohol level and the paparazzi and Goodbye Already,
England's Rose?
</P>
<P>
   Much of the coverage a year ago was done on the fly, while this
special _ simply titled ``Diana'' (8 tonight on NBC) _ has been
lovingly crafted over several months. Actor-director Richard
Attenborough, Diana's long-time confidant and adviser, narrates and
produced the tribute with miniseries mogul Robert Halmi
(``Scarlett,'' ``Gulliver's Travels''). With its respectful
approach and avoidance of scandal, it could have been gushy and
gooey, but instead it's cleareyed and clearheaded.
</P>
<P>
   There are interviews with intimates who spoke out little or not
at all at the time of her death, including Diana's childhood nanny
and boarding school headmistress (who recalls teenage Diana's utter
lack of interest in fashion and preference for trousers and a
``tatty pullover'' or, as we'd say, old sweater).
</P>
<P>
   It's details like that, filtered through insiders' insights,
that help bring Diana to life as a real human being, not some cheap
icon fulfilling some mass need. (The big-name interviews with
Hillary Rodham Clinton and others don't add as much understanding
as Diana's acupuncturist and the like.) Add to that an abundance of
seldom seen photos and footage that somehow missed being in
everyone else's tribute package, and you have TV's one don't-miss
Diana anniversary special.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
