<DOCNO> NYT19980830.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9530 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-FLOOD-ART-2TAKE     08-30 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-FLOOD-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEFT HOMELESS IN FLOODS, NORTH CHINESE FACE BITTER COLD OF WINTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CHINA-ARMY) 
(ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   XINZHEN, China _ Sparrows still weave through the sky and the
scent of flowers fills the air, but Sun Dianfeng and the other
flood refugees now living in the cramped dusty classrooms of this
village's elementary school are consumed with worry about the
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Next to a rag-tag collection of beds and mattresses, 16 families
from the nearby village of Xinkaikou stacked the supplies they
moved here before the churning Songhua River dissolved their
fragile mud-brick homes: some quilts, a winter coat, a television
set, a pile of red peppers. In the school's dirt playground, Sun's
four milk cows competed for space with the other villagers' pigs,
chickens and dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Since the flood evacuees arrived two weeks ago, local officials
have given them instant noodles and health workers have shown them
how to purify the now-contaminated water. But their looming problem
is one that no official can readily solve: In this far-north region
known for early winters of thick ice and bitter cold, the flood
waters that now cover thousands of villages will not recede for
more than a month. So huge numbers of refugees will face the
winter's daily subzero temperatures without a permanent home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't dare to think about how we'll cope with winter,'' said
Sun, a thin man shaking his head as if to rid himself of a bad
dream. ``I won't have time to rebuild my home before the frost.
And, anyway, I have no savings at all.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference last Tuesday, Ma Shujie, vice governor of
Heilongjiang province, where this village is situated, said that as
many as half a million people might have to spend the winter in
100,000 heavy tents provided by the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will insure that no one freezes to death,'' Ms. Ma said.
</P>
<P>
   The floods that have raged through central and northeast China
for the last month have destroyed billions of dollars of crops and
more than 8 million homes. Large dikes, maintained by the
government and reinforced by the Army, have kept urban areas out of
harm's way. But the smaller dikes that protect tiny villages like
Xinkaikou have been breached in many places, leaving millions of
mostly poor Chinese farmers with no crops to sell and nowhere to
live.
</P>
<P>
   Calamitous floods are a frequent occurrence in central China's
Yangtze basin, but rare here in China's far northeast, where
residents and local governments alike were unprepared for a flood
the likes of which had not been seen for over 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   Although more land has been flooded in the vast Yangtze basin,
Heilongjiang faces a huge and particularly difficult relief effort
because its typical mud-brick homes are easily destroyed by water
and the first frost is only a month away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are located in a frigid area, so we must give disaster
relief soon,'' Ms. Ma said.
</P>
<P>
   The vice governor said that her hope was that one third of the
province's 2 million flood refugees could move in with relatives
and another third would have a chance in the next two months to
rebuild, with government help.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the rest, we have no choice but to provide them with
tents,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last four weeks in Heilongjiang, 74,000 villages have
been hit by floodwaters, 820,000 homes have collapsed and 750,000
have been badly damaged, Ms. Ma said. As of last Tuesday, as many
as 500,000 people were living outdoors, mostly in remote areas, she
said. One quarter of the land in the province has had its crops
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials seem overwhelmed by the task facing them. In
Songbei township, which encompasses Xinkaikou village, one quarter
of the 20,000 residents have been left homeless by the floods and
2,500 acres, mostly fish farms and corn or soy bean fields, were
submerged when four small dikes broke two weeks ago. Like
Xinkaikou, many of the hardest-hit villages are on broad flood
plains that lie between the river's edge and large government-built
dikes several miles inland. Their protection consisted of makeshift
dikes they constructed and maintained themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its needs, Songbei, across the river from Harbin, the
provincial capital, has received only a bit more than $4,000 worth
of aid from the government relief agency, mostly in the form of
instant noodles and bottled water, said Chang Kexin, 29, the deputy
township head of Songbei. He serves as commander in chief of the
local flood control and resettlement effort.
</P>
<P>
   Chang said that the 4,000 people from Songbei who were evacuated
just before the river destroyed their homes are now all staying
with relatives or friends, or in school buildings. All have basic
shelter, food and medical care. But many will have to move once
school classes resume on Tuesday, and Chang said that relief
shipments of food have been slow in arriving.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city and provincial leaders are very concerned, but they
were not well prepared,'' Chang said.
</P>
<P>
   Chang said he expected that 300 villagers from Songbei would
spend the winter in tents, and health workers were preparing for
the time in October when the waters recede and remnants of villages
re-emerge, in conditions ripe for epidemic diseases like cholera
and plague. Sewage systems have washed out into the river and onto
the farmland, wells are contaminated and the wet conditions, he
said, will increase the concentration of rats.
</P>
<P>
   Timely evacuations meant that relatively few people died
nationwide _ 3,004, according to the latest government statistics.
But for the farmers in these counties, the past two weeks have been
a nightmare and the future remains unfathomable.
</P>
<P>
   In Minzhu township, just downstream from Harbin, Yang Wei, 17,
and her cousin Wang Lishan, 18, listlessly fished on Thursday from
the top of some submerged farm buildings _ a pigsty and a storage
shed _ now islands in a muddy brown river. A makeshift bridge of
planks led from the dry elevated road, over the flood water, to the
rooftops. Old shoes, bottles and clothes dotted the muddy ground.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Yang, wearing jeans and with cropped hair, pointed to the
spot across this vast expanse of water where only two weeks before
her family had grown vegetables. Between the tops of weeping
willows, she pointed out the partly collapsed house in Qianwukesong
village that had been her home.
</P>
<P>
   About two weeks ago, the Qianwukesong village head told Ms. Yang
and her parents to leave. They moved their 20 piglets to a
relative's house on higher ground. But the family had not completed
the move when the fast-rising river forced its way up a nearby
tributary, flooding out 2,000 families in five villages. The water
moved in so swiftly that Ms. Yang's family only had time to grab
their television, some bedding and grain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our village is normally far away from the Songhua,'' said Ms
Yang. ``We never expected this.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Ms. Yang, her parents and her cousin are living with the
relatives _ eight people in a two-room house. They say it is too
crowded to stay there but they will not be able to repair their
house before winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what we'll do this year,'' said Ms. Yang. ``We
have only our summer clothes and no money. All our hope hangs on
the pigs. Lots of people have moved to relatives farther away and
they don't want to return here.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
