<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980830.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9532 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-FLOOD-ART-2NDTA     08-30 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-FLOOD-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 XINZHEN, China: return here.' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In all, 20,000 people in Minzhu were ordered to evacuate, said
Xing Zhi'an, a township Communist Party official. But he said it
was hard to keep track of those whose homes had been destroyed
since many had gone to relatives near and far.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be one small village of 20 families,'' he
recalled. ``We can't find the village or the families now.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing atop the county's main dike along the Songhua, built of
packed earth in 1939 to withstand a ``50-year'' flood, he was proud
that it had not been breached.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there were many leaks,'' he said, ``And the risk is not
over yet. The dikes are weakened since the flood has lasted so
long.''
</P>
<P>
   All along the river, water was seeping though weak spots in
waterlogged government-built dikes that were never intended to
withstand such pressure, leaving roads flooded out and fields and
courtyards far behind the still-intact dikes looking like soupy
marshes.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing compared with the devastation on the flood plains.
At Xinkaikou, for example, the only protection had been a small
village dike at the river's edge. On Aug. 14, with the river
rising, local officials told the people that their dike could give
way and urged them to move.
</P>
<P>
   Meng Xiangmin immediately stored her refrigerator, her clothes,
and even the liquor and cigarettes for her small village store at a
relative's house and moved with her husband and daughter to the
elementary school, one of four in the area being used to shelter
flood victims. On Aug. 16, Sun Dianfeng packed up his cows, some
quilts and his most valuable possession _ a black-and-white TV set
_ and walked them a mile to the safe side of the big dike.
</P>
<P>
   That night, the smaller dikes yielded to the raging brown
waters, which collapsed the two thatch-roofed buildings that had
been home to Sun and his family and ruined the corn and soy beans
that he had been about to harvest.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the river, whose width here has expanded from one mile
to four, lapped at the big state dike. The water has stopped
rising, but it will take more than a month for it to fall back to
safe levels. And the only traces of what had been the village of
Xinkaikou are three tin rooftops visible in the distant water.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
