<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9534 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIOLIN-PRODIGY-ART-68     08-30 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLIN-PRODIGY-ART-680(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE VIOLIN ODYSSEY OF AN ALL-AMERICAN BOY PRODIGY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)  (ART ADV: Photos of Joshua Bell as a child and Joshua Bell today
are being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(js) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Although child prodigies may seem to be a
characteristic phenomenon of contemporary musical life, they are in
fact nothing new; they have simply received increasing attention
with the growth of worldwide communications media in recent
decades. And although great scrutiny has fallen on the
psychological perils of prodigyhood and the difficulties of
parlaying an early start into a mature career _ problems that have
potentially worsened because of that very media attention _ those
pitfalls are by no means inevitable or insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of Joshua Bell, the superb American violinist, who
began performing widely in his teens but, despite the boyish
demeanor he retains at 30, has long since established himself as a
mature artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my point of view, there really wasn't any kind of
transition to make,'' Bell said recently in his Manhattan
apartment. ``I never started to play 100 concerts a season until
much later, and I had worked my way up, each season playing a
little more. I didn't win an international competition that
suddenly, overnight, I had this kind of `career,' which can be
daunting for a lot of young people. I didn't feel pressure from my
parents, my teacher or anybody, and I always loved to play.''
</P>
<P>
   So with smooth sailing behind, there was promise of only the
same ahead. In a bit of fine-tuning some six years ago, Bell
replaced his first Stradivarius, an odd, problematic instrument,
with a better one, and everything seemed to be in place for an
untroubled mature career.
</P>
<P>
   But now Bell is caught up in a flurry of activity unusual for a
concert violinist, and some are sure to wonder whether a midlife
crisis has set in, at a prodigiously early age, to be sure. He
recently switched record companies from Decca/London (leaving by
his own choice, he said, unlike so many other artists the label has
dropped) to Sony Classical.
</P>
<P>
   The Sony connection, like many another Sony alliances these
days, was made through film, specifically ``The Red Violin,'' a new
movie directed by Francois Girard, which is to open the Venice Film
Festival on Thursday and the Toronto International Film Festival a
week later. For this eventful tale of a fictional violin carried
through three centuries and three continents, Girard recruited his
friend Bell as artistic consultant, violinist on the soundtrack and
even body double.
</P>
<P>
   Sony came to be involved, as did composer John Corigliano, whose
proven ability to compose effectively in the styles of past
centuries seemed tailor-made for the project. One thing that
emerged was a substantial work for violin and orchestra, ``Red
Violin Chaconne,'' which Bell has performed in concert and recorded
for Sony.
</P>
<P>
   The connection thus established, Sony swept Bell into another
project, a Gershwin program that it had been developing with the
composer and conductor John Williams. What, you may well ask, did
Gershwin write for violin? Nothing of real solo substance.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here is ``Gershwin Fantasy,'' a Sony contribution to the
flood of new recordings celebrating the 100th anniversary of the
composer's birth next month, consisting of arrangements: a fantasy
on ``Porgy and Bess'' by Alexander Courage, a film composer, and
reworkings of Gershwin songs by William David Brohn and Jonathan
Tunick, Broadway composers, all with orchestra, and a modest
expansion of the Three Piano Preludes by violin virtuoso Jascha
Heifetz, a friend of Gershwin's. And Monday evening, Bell is to
perform the fantasy at Tanglewood, in Lenox, Mass., with the Boston
Pops led by Williams, who conducts the London Symphony and plays
piano on the recording.
</P>
<P>
   So has Bell, in classical-music lingo, gone commercial?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem with record companies' wanting to make a
profit,'' he said. ``But that's not what this is about. My
so-called crossover projects are actually very interesting to me
musically.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film was very exciting for me to do. I love the idea of
music for movies. It was definitely a departure, but it was also
musically very interesting to be involved with the composer.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The composer evidently also found the relationship interesting.
``I came away with a terrific feeling about his commitment and his
integrity,'' said Corigliano, who is as thoroughly established in
the purely classical realm as in film scoring. In fact, he added,
although he had never been tempted to write a violin concerto and
had turned down offers to do so before working with Bell, he now
plans to add two or three movements to ``Red Violin Chaconne'' to
make a full concerto.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Gershwin project, Bell's explanation was just as
simple and straightforward: ``That was also very exciting for me.
I've always loved Gershwin, and I've always felt that there was
never enough Gershwin to play, for violinists.'' The affection
shows in the recording, and in Bell's hands, the violin seldom
sounds out of place in this earthy material: no mean feat.
</P>
<P>
   The project was largely a brainchild of Williams. ``I had
conducted Sarasate's `Carmen Fantasy' for violin and orchestra so
often with the Boston Pops,'' he said, ``and I always wished there
was a comparable piece based on an American opera.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, if any violinist is to lay claim to the
quintessentially American Gershwin, the Indiana-born Bell would
have to be a prime candidate. Prodigy or not, he has never quite
fitted the American stereotype of the violinist as being slightly
exotic in manner if not in origin. Didn't all those past masters
come from St. Petersburg or Odessa or somewhere in the Baltics?
Aren't all the rising stars of Asian descent? Can a Briton or an
American succeed today without the gimmicky weirdness of Nigel
Kennedy or Nadja Salerno-Sonnenberg?
</P>
<P>
   Bell has been dogged by a counterstereotype of his own: the
all-American boy. And that is hard to get around it, even now that
he has become a full-fledged international artist of the first
rank. He lives unostentatiously with his girlfriend of six years a
few blocks south of the Empire State Building, which dominates the
view from their windows. He chose the area, like the earlier one he
lived in, farther downtown, partly to avoid the music crowd. He
plays tennis or golf whenever he can.
</P>
<P>
   His handlers try to spice up his image a bit, pointing out that
he likes to hop to Atlantic City, N.J., for bouts of gambling. And
genuine temperament is obvious in his performances. Yet he comes
across in conversation as basically just a really nice guy.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps what needs revising is not so much the image of Bell as
the popular image of Indiana, tied as it is to auto racing and
basketball. As it happens, Bell could hardly have been born in a
more propitious spot in 1967 than Bloomington, the home of Indiana
University, with its vast and excellent school of music. Indeed,
those so inclined might see the hand of fate at work. Bell's
parents had just moved there, his father having accepted a position
in the university's psychology department.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents loved music, but they moved there not even knowing
that there was a music school,'' Bell said. ``They stumbled on it,
really. So I grew up in a nice environment, going to concerts,
going to a normal school, playing sports. As a kid, it was a good
place to be.''
</P>
<P>
   But this kid also took up the violin at 5, and fate, if such it
was, had seen to that eventuality as well, when Josef Gingold
resigned as concertmaster of the Cleveland Orchestra in 1960 to
teach at Indiana University. Gingold, who was born in Brest-Litovsk
in 1909, when that Belarussian city was part of Russia, and died in
1995, was a brilliant, kindly and beloved teacher. He was also
active in nurturing a larger violin culture in Indiana, which
eventually included the prestigious International Violin
Competition of Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Bell had no need of that competition. In 1980, at 12, he started
studying with Gingold. At 14, he won the Seventeen Magazine/General
Motors Competition and made his orchestral debut with Riccardo Muti
and the Philadelphia Orchestra. While already involved in courses
at the university, he finished high school in three years. His
career simply took on a life of its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gingold was not involved in careers at all,'' Bell said. ``In
fact, he had no idea of the ins and outs of what goes on today to
make a solo career. But he was just such an inspiration. The joy of
music and of the violin that he felt and exuded was incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bell moved to New York nine years ago, he worked with
Gingold less often. ``He became like a grandfather to me,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bell speaks about himself and his career with reticence, in
short, halting sentences. On the subject of the violin, he spins
out long, flowing paragraphs as though they were melody itself.
</P>
<P>
   He plays a 1732 Stradivarius named the ``Tom Taylor,'' for a
19th-century owner in England. ``The later Strads, like this one,
have a touch of the lower, deeper Guarneri quality, which I like,''
he said, ``though they have to compromise a bit on some of the
sweet quality of the earlier ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell bought the instrument to replace his starter Strad, an
eccentrically shaped (rounded, guitarlike) and intractable
instrument, which was called various things, he said, among them
the ``Thalidomide.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever others may think of his activities of the moment, he
admits to no change in his priorities. His contract with Sony, he
said, also allows for more standard classical fare.
</P>
<P>
   He has already recorded a concerto written for him by Nicholas
Maw, which, like ``Red Violin Chaconne,'' awaits release. Next year
he is to record the concertos of Sibelius and Goldmark, and chamber
music projects are being worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recording, frankly, is not my favorite thing to do, and I'm
never particularly happy with the results,'' Bell said. ``It's the
way records are done, it's the permanence, it's a lot of things.
You do it over and over again. I like just shooting for it in a
performance. I really love the performance atmosphere, the risk
taking.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the risks Bell takes these days is to perform his own
cadenzas, or solo flourishes, in concertos, though he tends to
prepare them thoroughly beforehand rather than simply improvise.
``I really enjoy writing, and someday my dream would be to write a
piece of music,'' he said. ``So far, I've just fooled around at
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he is thinking of replacing the cadenza that
fits so integrally into Mendelssohn's revered E minor Concerto with
one of his own. The cadenza, he suggests, is not the strongest part
of the piece, which, on the whole, he reveres as much as the next
fiddler. He realizes, of course, that he might well be
``crucified,'' in his word, by the critics for such iconoclasm, as
he may be for his present ``commercial'' efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``With reviews, it's just like with everything else in life,''
he said. ``As long as you're honest, you can't go wrong. That way
you never have to cover your tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Lincoln, another all-American boy, could hardly have
said it better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
