<HEADER>
A9538 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-DIANA-REVIEW-NOTEB     08-30 1515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DIANA-REVIEW-NOTEBOOK-1089&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIANA: DOCUMENTARIES ONE YEAR AFTER HER DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Program listings are at end of review. Time and channels are
for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(ll) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On MTV, Diana, Princess of Wales, is seen as a pawn in a chess
game who makes some clever moves and attains the status of a queen.
On NBC's documentary ``Diana,'' Richard Attenborough all but
canonizes her. On the History Channel, she is called ``unbalanced''
and ``manipulative.''
</P>
<P>
   And on the Sunday edition of ``Today,'' Jodi Applegate sat
outside Kensington Palace, Diana's last home, and posed a hesitant
yet central question. ``Do you feel comfortable saying things you
couldn't say a year ago?'' she asked Tom Corby, a royal biographer.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was not a saint, and she died very sadly, during an affair
with a playboy,'' Corby said of the princess, though only after
carefully noting that Diana was a wonderful mother and had made a
lasting contribution with her campaign against land mines.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, exactly a year after her death, the glut of Diana
specials and news reports continues. It began over the weekend and
includes at least eight programs, full-length documentaries and
segments of newsmagazines to be shown on Monday and Tuesday. And
though there is an unrelenting sameness to most of them, a few
realistic human variations are sneaking into the mawkish, one-note
tale of St. Diana. The first anniversary of her death has brought,
if not a backlash, at least a swing of the pendulum away from the
heavens toward a more earthly reading of her character.
</P>
<P>
   Her public life, of course, began as a fairy tale; every program
offers that stock reminder while replaying scenes of the royal
wedding. And in the end, hers will always be a genuinely
heartbreaking story. It is the middle of the tale that is
undergoing a subtle alteration.
</P>
<P>
   And just as the start and finish played out primarily on screen,
with Diana's wedding and funeral two of the world's most watched
television events, now the first-anniversary coverage becomes one
communal public biography created largely on television. This
televised fairy tale taps into important qualities of storytelling:
the comfort of familiar images; the need to keep stories alive by
altering them to suit the moment.
</P>
<P>
   This anniversary moment carries an aura of strained attention
rather than spontaneous interest, as the Diana story competes with
hotter reports about the Lewinsky scandal and international
terrorism. However muted the public remembrances (even in England),
the television coverage has been cranked up anyway. All three of
Monday's network morning news programs are scheduled to include
live reports from London.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC program ``Good Morning America'' sent its anchor, Lisa
McRee, there. MSNBC's flood of coverage, heavily promoted under the
rubric ``Diana: The First Anniversary,'' includes five different
Diana-theme hours of ``Time and Again,'' its series of clips from
the NBC News archive, and an elaborate Diana section Web site
(www.msnbc.com) that includes a video tour of the Diana museum on
her family estate.
</P>
<P>
   On every program, certain required images repeat themselves with
the consistency of ``Once upon a time ...'': Diana sitting alone in
front of the Taj Mahal; Diana dressed in the protective face mask
while working to ban land mines; the security tape of Diana and
Dodi Fayed, their backs to the camera, leaving the Ritz Hotel just
before the accident that killed them.
</P>
<P>
   With this overload of reports, themes heralded as new quickly
become commonplace: the impact of Diana's death on the the royal
family (a warmer Prince Charles); the future of her son Prince
William (rarely mentioned without being compared to Leonardo
DiCaprio); how Diana manipulated the press (a drastic change from
the cry that the paparazzi killed her, which immediately followed
the accident).
</P>
<P>
   Even reports about the continuing investigation into the car
crash has come down to: Who let the drunken Henri Paul drive? The
most elaborate report on the investigation is on Monday's ``48
Hours,'' which details the way Fayed's father, Mohammed, is now
blaming the bodyguards, and how they are blaming him.
</P>
<P>
   In this scramble for something new, the worst program may be the
most prominent and hyped, NBC's hagiographic ``Diana,'' with
Attenborough as on-screen narrator. This overblown tribute includes
interviews with Diana's former nanny, with the American who hired
Diana as her children's nanny, and with the former headmistress of
Diana's school. We learn that as a schoolgirl Diana won a tiny
trophy for ``helpfulness.''
</P>
<P>
   As we watch a Diana commemorative doll being painted by hand,
Attenborough says: ``There are as many ways of mourning our lost
princess as there are mourners to grieve. What is shoddy and
incongruous to one is appropriate and tasteful to another.'' His
saccharine tone glosses over the rank commercialism that so many
news reports have considered in recent days. A year after Diana's
death, such blind reverence seems unrealistic and dated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diana'' does offer the irresistible, unavoidable gift of
hindsight that now colors every bit of old film. Shown in a joint
television interview while they were engaged, Diana and Charles are
asked whether they are in love. ``Of course,'' the 19-year-old
Diana exclaims, sounding vaguely insulted at such a preposterous
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever `in love' means,'' Charles adds coolly, as bells and
whistles go off in every viewer's head.
</P>
<P>
   Because we know the outline of the Diana story so well, it seems
ready made for ``Biorhythm,'' the MTV biography series that has no
narrative voice, only images, film clips and music. Words on-screen
offer a skeletal narrative, which is all Diana really needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biorhythm'' begins with a quotation from the princess: ``My
life is a chess game. The chess theme is carried through in legends
on-screen, as Diana gains popularity and power even while losing
her marriage.
</P>
<P>
   This program has the wit and irreverence to show Camilla
Parker-Bowles, Prince Charles' longtime mistress, riding her horse
toward the screen while the theme from ``The Good, the Bad and the
Ugly'' plays in the background. Does anyone need to be reminded
that Diana nicknamed Mrs. Parker-Bowles ``the Rottweiler'' and
blamed her for the collapse of the royal marriage?
</P>
<P>
   Along with ``Biorhythm,'' ``As It Happened: When Diana Died,''
by the History Channel, is the best of the specials. It is the
smartest and most balanced, though at times it is downright cranky.
Produced in England, it offers a reminder that there has always
been a pro-Charles, anti-Diana contingent there, rarely heard from
in the United States.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ingrid Seward, editor of Majesty magazine, says of the bad days
of the royal marriage, ``For Prince Charles it was a horror because
he's never had to deal with anyone as emotionally unbalanced as
Diana.''
</P>
<P>
   Where most specials go into raptures at Diana's public displays
of emotion, here historian David Cannadine says acidly, ``At the
end of the day you cannot hug your way through history.'' Of
course, as Corby did on ``Today,'' all are careful to note Diana's
good qualities. (Corby, also seen on the History Channel, was once
a press spokesman for Buckingham Palace, which Diana came to
consider enemy turf.)
</P>
<P>
   And in a strange but valuable paradox, this documentary takes a
critical view of last year's media frenzy, even while engaging in
this year's version. Ian Hislip, the editor of Private Eye
magazine, puts it bluntly. ``The media had pretty much thrown its
brains out the window,'' he says, and agreed to go along with the
``mass hysteria'' of mourning.
</P>
<P>
   At times this program goes too far the other way, failing to
grasp that the excesses of a year ago mirrored what happens in real
life: You don't speak ill of the dead when the coffin is before
your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as an antidote to simplistic sainthood, taking a more human
view of Diana's frailties as well as her strengths makes sense. It
was, after all, her ability to seem human as well as royal that
most people embraced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biorhythm'' ends with a slow-motion image of Diana, a sad
frown gradually turning to a sly, triumphant, enigmatic smile. An
image that, iconic and mysterious, says a great deal about this
moment, as Diana's legend continues to evolve.
</P>
