</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ARMY-655&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOOD RELIEF OFFERS BELEAGUERED CHINESE ARMY SHOT AT REDEMPTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CHINA-FLOODS) 
(nk) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARBIN, China _ It had been a bad year for the People's
Liberation Army. First, it faced accusations in the United States
that it was involved in a plot to direct contributions to the
Democratic Party in exchange for easier access to American
satellite technology. Then, in July, President Jiang Zemin
subjected the army to an unprecedented public scolding, charging it
with smuggling and ordering its generals to sell off their many
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the floods, offering the promise of redemption.
</P>
<P>
   With hundreds of thousands of soldiers as the backbone of the
nation's defense, this summer's record breaking floods have
provided the scandal-prone PLA with both a challenging battle _ and
a golden opportunity for image burnishing.
</P>
<P>
   At Harbin's river-front Stalin Park, 3,000 soldiers have spent
the last two weeks shoring up a mile-long stretch along the Songhua
River, including a crucial but tenuous section of dike that
protects this major industrial city in China's far northeast. A few
hundred feet away, citizens have been gathering at the park gates
to watch the dike-building effort, conducted in full public view
with an almost theatrical flare.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers sing songs about courage as they march across the
wide plaza to the river. Their green fatigues, bright orange life
jackets and brilliant red flags stand out against the white wall of
sandbags reinforcing the dike.
</P>
<P>
   Every night, all over China, television news shows feature
images of heroic soldiers _ evacuating children, hefting sandbags
onto a crumbling dike, forming a human chain chest-deep in the
water to hold a river at bay.
</P>
<P>
   This week many newspapers carried features on Guo Jiancheng, a
young officer who gave his life vest to a soldier who could not
swim, and was himself then swept away.
</P>
<P>
   There are now 278,000 soldiers fighting floods along the Yangtze
River in central China _ the biggest mobilization of military
personnel in that area since the Communists took power in 1949 _
and another 100,000 in the northeast, mostly along the Songhua and
Nen rivers here in Heilongjiang province. It is a return to the
grassroots for an organization that in recent years has seemed less
a military fighting force and more a big business.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers have been living in the park since Aug. 16, when
their first risky task was to build up the original dike, which was
on the verge of being submerged, with sandbags. They finished the
job in the nick of time: On Aug. 23 the river rose more than seven
feet above flood level, and since then the original dike has been
entirely under water.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers also built two back-up dikes several feet inland
from the original structure.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, with water levels holding steady, the river's swift
murky waters frequently squeeze through. Col. Yu Zhongsheng said
his soldiers had plugged 50 to 70 leaks since they arrived. The
swollen river was exerting so much pressure on these man-made
walls, he said, that water inevitably seeped through.
</P>
<P>
   A large pump pulled water back into the river from a muddy pool
between the first and second dikes. Women in white coats used
plastic jugs to scoop up water that has strayed inside the dikes
and returned it to the river.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic effort has not been lost on the people of Harbin,
where life in the city has remained fairly normal throughout the
floods. After work, many stop by the barricade at the park's main
entrance to take in the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, we are very grateful to the soldiers because we know
how exhausted they must be by now,'' said Han Xue, a 24-year-old
shop assistant who had paused at the barricade with her girlfriend
during an evening stroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some thing have recently hurt the image of the PLA and this
has definitely improved it,'' said Sun Jian, a college student.
``In peacetime they have nothing to do. Now they've had a chance to
show their true colors.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Behind the barricade, Colonel Yu and his troops had settled in,
transforming the park into a mini-military camp with tents for
sleeping, eating, clinics, communications stations and even
entertainment. They expected to be camped here for another few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials have praised the army on television and
military leaders have publicly sung the troops' praises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officers have played a commanding role and set examples for
their subordinates on the front line,'' said Gen. Ma Qukuan this
week in Beijing. ``They have displayed the revolutionary spirit of
fearing neither hardship nor death.''
</P>
<P>
   And, at least here in Harbin, which has been saved by the
soldiers, the desired message has been absorbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``On one hand, this is a People's Army and this is their job,''
said Li Xin, a college student. ``On the other, it reminds us that
only a small part of the army is involved in corruption.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
