<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: ARTIST GOES SOLO; ALBEE PREMIERE IN LONDON; RETURN
TO RADIO DAYS; PICASSO IN L.A. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Great Britain)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Maya Lin, who vaulted to prominence as an artist when
she won the competition to design the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in
Washington while still an undergraduate at Yale in the early 1980s,
will have her first solo museum exhibition in New York beginning
Tuesday. The show, ``Maya Lin: Topologies,'' runs through Oct. 31
at the Grey Art Gallery of New York University, 100 Washington
Square East, Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   It uses perspectives provided by advanced technologies to focus
on relationships to landscape. Its 15 works in glass, wood and wax,
adapted from computer-enhancing imaging and microscopy as well as
aerial views of Earth from airplane and satellite, are accompanied
by prints, drawings and models for projects that function
independently as art objects. Information: (212) 998-6780.
</P>
<P>
   Opening Night
</P>
<P>
   While New York awaits the passing of Labor Day to open the
floodgates of the fall cultural season, autumn at the acclaimed
Almeida Theater in London begins Tuesday with the world premiere of
an Edward Albee play. Titled ``The Play About the Baby,'' it is an
exploration across generation and gender of the relationship of
four people. Howard Davies directs. The show runs until Oct. 10.
Information: 011-44-171-359-4404.
</P>
<P>
   Pastimes
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Once upon a time, when only a handful of visionaries
owned television sets, people relied on their radios, which
furnished them with entertainment like ``The Adventures of Sam
Spade'' and ``Murder at Midnight.'' A chance to return to those
days and their live sound effects, original music and inventive
commercials arises Tuesday night, when previews of ``W-WOW! Radio''
begin off-Broadway at the Martin R. Kaufman Theater, 534 W. 42nd
St.
</P>
<P>
   The show, a presentation of the Cranston and Spade Theater
Company, consists of two 1946 radio episodes: ``The Blood Money
Caper,'' from the ``Sam Spade'' series, and ``The Man Who Was
Death,'' from ``Murder at Midnight.'' Information: (212) 279-4200.
</P>
<P>
   Movable Feast
</P>
<P>
   With canvases like ``Girl Before a Mirror'' and ``Three
Musicians,'' the Los Angeles County Museum of Art will open a major
exhibition of paintings, drawings, sculptures, collages and prints
by Picasso. Beginning on Sunday and continuing through Jan. 4,
1999, ``Picasso: Masterworks From the Museum of Modern Art'' draws
on the holdings of that museum, which has one of the world's most
comprehensive Picasso collections. Nevertheless, only about 15 of
the more than 90 works in Los Angeles are regularly on view in New
York. Information: (323) 857-6000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
