<SLUG> BC-VIOLIN-CONTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAR-REACHING MUSICAL LEGACY OF A MENTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)   (With VIOLIN-PRODIGY)  
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joshua Bell has done much to create a link between the violin
and the state of Indiana in the minds of music lovers. But no one
has done more along those lines than Bell's mentor at Indiana
University, Josef Gingold, who died in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Among Gingold's many achievements, he was a founder of the
quadrennial International Violin Competition of Indianapolis, and
he served on the jury of its first four contests, from 1982 through
1994. The next competition runs from Sept. 11 to Sept. 27 and
includes 51 contestants from 19 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking the cachet of a big name in its title, this event has
not achieved a profile in the popular imagination comparable to
that of, say, the Van Cliburn Competition. Yet in the violin world,
it holds a status comparable to the Cliburn's in the piano world,
and on average it has at least as good a track record in terms of
the quality and subsequent careers of its winners. They are Mihaela
Martin (1982), Kyoko Takezawa (1986), Pavel Berman (1990) and
Juliette Kang (1994).
</P>
<P>
   This year the winner will get a new gold medal dedicated to
Gingold and bearing his likeness, which was unveiled at a memorial
concert for him in 1995. ``The names of Josef Gingold and
Indianapolis will thus be linked together for all time,'' Thomas
Beczkiewicz, the competition's founding director, said then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
