<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-ALBRIGHT-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT IN BOSNIA URGES MORE RECONCILIATION EFFORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright slept Sunday night in this city's refurbished Holiday Inn,
its shell-cratered walls now repaired, right beside what was once
Snipers' Alley. Her overnight stay was meant to be a dramatic
symbol, U.S. officials said, of the distance Bosnia has come since
Washington intervened to end the vicious war in late 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But most of Albright's long day in Bosnia and neighboring
Croatia was devoted to pressing divided peoples _ Serbian, Croatian
and Muslim _ to make the still-artificial and bitterly divided
Bosnia closer to the multiethnic democracy envisioned in the Dayton
Accords.
</P>
<P>
   With international attention now concentrated on the fighting in
nearby Kosovo, U.S. officials are deeply concerned about Bosnia's
next big test _ full-scale elections in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 12 and 13, Bosnians will vote for the three joint
presidents of their country, as well as the presidents and
parliaments of its two constituent parts, the Bosnian Serb Republic
and the federation between the Croats and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   The number of U.S. troops patrolling Bosnia has gone up from
6,900 to 8,500 with rotations carefully staggered for this election
season, Pentagon officials said, to prevent any new violence.
</P>
<P>
   Most important to U.S. officials will be the contests among the
Bosnian Serbs. Washington wants these elections to confirm the
political decline of hard-line Serbs who still support Radovan
Karadzic, who has been indicted on war-crimes charges, and to
ratify the pro-Dayton line of the woman who broke with Karadzic
after he anointed her as the Bosnian Serb president, Biljana
Plavsic.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Plavsic is a committed Serbian nationalist, but in the last
18 months she has worked to get the benefits of compliance with
Dayton _ $100 million of U.S. aid this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   In the east Bosnian, Serb-held town of Bijeljina on Sunday,
Albright openly campaigned for Mrs. Plavsic and her ally, the
Bosnian Serb prime minister, Milorad Dodik, who face strong
opposition from Karadzic's party. U.S. officials also openly
support Zivko Radisic, a Plavsic ally running against Karadzic's
right-hand man, Momcilo Krajisnik, for the Serbian seat on the
three-man joint Bosnian presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, opening an electrical substation rebuilt with U.S. aid
money, pointed to it as a benefit of working with the West to carry
out the Dayton accords.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should be very proud _ it's a great message to run on,''
Albright told Mrs. Plavsic.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Plavsic praised the substation, but seemed less
enthusiastic about the Albright embrace in the elections,
observing, ``The other side, they blame us for too much
cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   In her news conference there, and in a speech Sunday night to
mostly Croatian minorities who have returned home to Sarajevo after
fleeing the war, Albright was explicit about how U.S. aid would be
distributed.
</P>
<P>
   The Bosnian Serbs began to get aid only after Mrs. Plavsic and
her allies grudgingly embraced Dayton a year ago. They knew,
Albright said, ``that Dayton means jobs, reconstruction and a
normal life _ in other words, Dayton pays.''
</P>
<P>
   The elections, she said, offered a ``clear, consequential
choice'' between those who support Dayton and those who do not.
</P>
<P>
   All Bosnians should vote to tell the world the future they want,
Albright said. But she added, ``Whatever the outcome of the vote,
we will provide assistance only to those communities that help
implement Dayton, by welcoming refugees, by making joint
institutions work, by upholding justice and the rule of law.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Albright acknowledged that the problems of Bosnia were rife,
lasting and disturbing. ``Bosnia's peace is not yet
self-sustaining,'' she said. ``A reversal of progress in Bosnia is
still possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright and her officials said that all three groups _ Serbian,
Croatian and Muslim _ were too slow to accept the return of
refugees, and that some Western countries, like Germany, were
pressing too hard for refugees to return before their villages were
willing or ready to accept them.
</P>
<P>
   The war uprooted more than half Bosnia's population, and nearly
1.7 million people still live elsewhere, unable or unwilling to
return home. About 450,000 have come back, but many to areas where
they are part of the majority.
</P>
<P>
   The Bosnian Serb republic has taken back only about 2,200
Muslims and Croats since the war ended. The Croatian authorities
have failed to protect returnees, and the Muslims have done
relatively little to allow refugees to return to what was once a
vibrantly multiethnic Sarajevo, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   And the Serbs in particular have labored hard to protect
indicted war criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Sunday, in Zagreb, the Croatian capital, Albright
clashed openly with President Franjo Tudjman over his reluctance to
accept the fact that the Bosnian Croats live in another country,
and over his repression of independent media at home.
</P>
<P>
   Tudjman rejected her charges, saying that ``the main problem in
the cooperation between the United States and Croatia is the
problem of Bosnia,'' and that he had a constitutional obligation
``to take care of Croats outside the Republic of Croatia.''
</P>
<P>
   He also insisted that the state-controlled television, which
journalists meeting Albright described as being in the complete
control of his office, merely reflected the political balance of
the elected Parliament. The legislature is dominated by Tudjman's
party. Albright urged the journalists to work with the weak
Croatian opposition for democratic change.
</P>
<P>
   Croatian state television has intervened in the Bosnian
elections by attacking the incumbent Croatian member of the joint
Bosnian presidency, Kresimir Zubak. He has broken with the Bosnian
affiliate of Tudjman's party.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the situation in Kosovo, where President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia is using harsh measures to try to end a
civil war, Albright renewed a warning of possible retaliatory air
strikes by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Albright will meet the NATO commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, on
Monday in Sarajevo to discuss NATO plans. She clearly intends to
remind Milosevic that the West is serious about demanding a halt to
the burning of villages and creation of refugees, especially with
winter approaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tragedy of watching the people expelled from their homes
and the various killings are not something the United States and
its European allies can tolerate much longer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, NATO is divided about using force over Kosovo and
opposes the independence that most of Kosovo's majority ethnic
Albanians would prefer. Some of the alliance's member nations say
they want a U.N. Security Council resolution authorizing force
before NATO uses it. Thus Western threats of force so far have
proved hollow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
