<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-OWEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORIC HOTELS HOLD SOME DEAR LEGENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In case you are shopping for a late-summer vacation hotel, these
suggestions are offered:
</P>
<P>
   The Luma Hotel looks out on the Gulf of Naples in the Italian
community of Amalfi. Among those who have enjoyed the view were
Richard Wagner, Mussolini, Otto Von Bismarck and Henrik Ibsen.
Wagner based one of his operas on this locale. Ibsen wrote ``A
Doll's House'' in the Luma, when he wasn't ringing room service for
another helping of pasta e fagioli.
</P>
<P>
   Even measured against these historic hotels, you have to be
impressed by the Menger Hotel in San Antonio, Texas. Teddy
Roosevelt, Babe Ruth, Ulysses S. Grant, Robert E. Lee, Lillie
Langtry, Sarah Bernhardt, Oscar Wilde and O. Henry are among those
who signed the guest register.
</P>
<P>
   Before the days of air conditioning, windows of the Menger were
thrown wide in hopes of catching a breeze during the Texas summers.
Half an hour before lunch or dinner, all the waiters and busboys
would form a line at one end of the dining room. Then, waving fans,
they would advance slowly across the room, hoping to chase most of
the flies out the window. As they advanced, they would all sing or
hum the same chant. And the hungry guests were alerted that
suppertime was near.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanley Hotel at Estes Park in Colorado holds a lingering
fascination for two reasons. The original owner, who also created a
steam-powered automobile, drove one up the long, steep flight of
stairs into the hotel, to prove that the Stanley Steamer wouldn't
explode when the driver leaned on the throttle. ``The Shining'' was
filmed in the vacant, echoing corridors of the Stanley Hotel.
Author Stephen King was also inspired to write the book because of
the topiary ``animals'' that inhabit the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   We've stayed at the Algonquin in Manhattan and listened for the
literary ghosts of Dorothy Parker, Robert Benchley, Edna Ferber and
Alexander Woollcott.
</P>
<P>
   And what did historic people eat in historic hotels? We can only
assume they ate the blue-plate specials that were often variations
on roast pork or chicken casseroles. The chef at the Menger Hotel
might have served:
</P>
<P>
   Shoo-fly Pork
</P>
<P>
   2 or 3 boneless pork tenderloins (about 4 pounds total)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons thyme leaves
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup plus 2 tablespoons dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup plus 1 tablespoon soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of powdered clove
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, put through press
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon powdered ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 jar (10 ounces) currant jelly
</P>
<P>
   Plunk pork tenders into oven dish or pan. Rub with dry mustard
and thyme. Moosh together one-half cup sherry, one-half cup soy
sauce, the cloves, garlic and ginger. Slosh this over the meat and
let everything vegetate for a few hours, turning the tenders
occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Pour off the marinade, but reserve. Return pork to the same pan
and shove into a 325-degree oven for an hour, basting occasionally
with the marinade.
</P>
<P>
   Slice the pork into medallions and serve with a sauce
constructed from jelly simmered in a pan for 2 minutes with 1
tablespoon of soy and 2 tablespoons of sherry.
</P>
<P>
   Serves six to eight. The guests in my hotel like these pork
tenders with oven-browned potatoes. Peel the spuds, cut each into
three or four sections, cover with olive oil, sprinkle with garlic
salt and pepper and roast in the same oven for about 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   At the Vittoria Hotel in Sorrento they might have served:
</P>
<P>
   Caruso Casserole
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces medium egg noodles
</P>
<P>
   2 whole chicken breasts (four pieces)
</P>
<P>
   2 chicken bouillon cubes
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup plus 2 tablespoons canola oil (or melted butter)
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup plus 2 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   1 can (1.5 cups) evaporated low-fat milk (or half and half)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sherry
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon celery salt
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon marjoram flakes
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon season salt (or Beau Monde seasoning)
</P>
<P>
   16-ounce jar or can sliced mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup slivered almonds, toasted
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fresh minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup shredded cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   Simmer (do not boil) the chicken breasts in water to cover just
until a slight bit of pink still shows when you make a slice
through the middle. If you boil the bejabbers out of the bird you
are going to have tough, stringy chicken and Enrico will not be
amused.
</P>
<P>
   Cool chicken, remove skin if it had any, and cut the meat into
bite-size pieces. Pour 2 cups of the chicken water into a measuring
jar and add the bouillon.
</P>
<P>
   Cook the noodles in boiling salted water, drain, rinse under hot
water and reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large, heavy saucepan. Stir in the flour and
when you have a smooth paste stir-cook another minute or so, then
gradually add the chicken broth and the milk or cream. Also add the
sherry, salt, celery salt, marjoram flakes and season salt.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, stirring constantly, until the sauce thickens. Add to the
pot the cooked noodles, chicken, mushrooms, almonds and parsley.
Moosh everything around then dump into a 9-by-13-inch baking dish
that has been lightly oiled.
</P>
<P>
   Cover the dish with foil and bake at 350 degrees for 35 minutes.
Remove foil, scatter cheese over the top of the casserole and bake
another 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serves four operatic tenors or six sopranos.
</P>
<P>
   John Owen writes ``The Intermediate Eater'' weekly for the P-I.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
