<SLUG> BC-PALESTINIAN-EXECUTION-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIAN FIRING SQUAD EXECUTES TWO BROTHERS IN THE GAZA STRIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SERGE SCHMEMANN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip _ A Palestinian firing squad carried out
the first executions under Palestinian self-rule Sunday, shooting
two brothers convicted of killing two brothers from another family
three days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Though the killings were essentially a fight between two
families, the accused men were members of security organizations
and had apparently used their official weapons in the shootings.
That roused a storm of protest throughout the Gaza Strip among
Palestinians fed up with the members of security forces who strut
around with pistols and Kalashnikov assault rifles, often firing in
the air or using the weapons to threaten civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Both victims were popular leaders in the Fatah movement of
Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, and members of a huge
family, the al-Khalidis, further fanning the anger. Portraits of
the victims, memorializing them as ``faithful martyrs,'' were
posted on walls. Protests over the weekend paralyzed Deir al Balah
in central Gaza, home of the al-Khalidi brothers. Fatah called for
a strike throughout Gaza on Monday if the killers were not
executed.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, head of the Palestinian Authority, was faced with the
prospect of a serious rebellion in his own movement, a rebellion
against his security services and a potentially violent feud. He
ordered a swift military trial and approved the executions of the
brothers, Raed and Mohammed Abu-Sultan. A third brother, Faris, was
also sentenced to death. His sentence was commuted to life in
prison, apparently to maintain the balance of two executions for
two victims.
</P>
<P>
   Two Palestinian human-rights groups, B'Tselem and the
Palestinian Human Rights Monitoring Group, issued news releases
that condemned the executions and called for the abolition of
capital punishment by the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Nabil Abu Zaid, a Fatah official from Deir-al-Balah who
witnessed the trial and executions, said 120 people gathered in the
police headquarters here to see the executions. They included
authority officials, elected members of the Palestinian Legislative
Council, Fatah officials and relatives of the slain brothers.
</P>
<P>
   The condemned men were taken out shackled, handcuffed and
blindfolded and were granted their last wish for a drink of water
before reciting final Muslim prayers, Abu Zaid said. Ten masked
uniformed police officers lined up, five for each condemned man,
and shot them at 2:45 p.m. Witnesses shouted, ``God is great!''
and, ``Long live justice!''
</P>
<P>
   Hours later in the Fatah headquarters in Deir-al-Balah, Abu Zaid
sat surrounded by friends and colleagues, all in a state of
excitement and shock over the chain of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinian people are in general fed up with all these
people carrying guns,'' he said. ``We want to stop this. At
weddings, at wakes, they always pull out their guns and shoot in
the air, they threaten people. And now they shot our best Fatah
activists.''
</P>
<P>
   The notion that the summary trial and quick execution violated
legal norms and civil rights was beyond the concern of the men. To
them the Palestinian Authority had exercised justice that would
have otherwise been left in the hands of the al-Khalidi clan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will there be more executions?'' a middle-age man asked.
``This is up to President Arafat.''
</P>
<P>
   The others gave consenting nods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want more executions,'' the man said. ``We want to
give the lesson to stop the killings and the easy use of arms.''
</P>
<P>
   As night fell relatives of the slain brothers, Mohammed, 30, and
Majdi, 32, gathered at a dusty lot to receive condolences. The
older brother of the slain men, Bassam al-Khalidi, said he had
issued strict instructions to his relatives, including 2,000 young
al-Khalidi men, that there was to be no more bloodshed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A senior official of the United Nations office in Gaza and
fluent in English, al-Khalidi said he and his slain brothers were
not even part of the dispute and had gone only to talk with cousins
who said they had been threatened in a quarrel over a woman. After
the brothers had spent time with the cousins, he said, the Abu
Sultan brothers appeared and started firing on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must say that when I saw those men executed I was
satisfied,'' al-Khalidi said. ``I never dreamed in my life that I
would feel like this. When they ordered fire, I turned away and
cried for my brothers. I guess justice was done, although actually
there is no justice. My brothers were innocent, and they are
criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 Palestinians have been sentenced to death by the
Palestinian Authority in the four years since it first took power
in the Gaza Strip and West Bank. Arafat has not allowed any other
executions to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   That the first executions he ordered were over the misuse of
firearms by his security forces is certain to be noted by the
Israeli government, which has repeatedly contended that the
Palestinian police have been issued personal weapons far in excess
of the 7,000 allowed for Gaza in the Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
   There is also mounting anger among Palestinian civilians over
the proliferation of security forces, of which Arafat has created
at least 12.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed Abu Sultan was a member of military intelligence. Raed
was a bodyguard to a general, and Faris was a political guidance
officer with a security force.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the police and security forces, however, have largely
served as a means of absorbing the huge numbers of unemployed young
men. Most members are not issued arms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
