<HEADLINE>
HOW PRESIDENTIAL SCANDALS HAVE INFLUENCED THE MARKET THROUGH
HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: As analysts roam far and wide in their efforts to
explain the stock market's recent swoon, Yale Hirsch's Smart Money
newsletter has distinguished itself by providing a historical
analysis of market reactions to presidential scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The only conclusion to be drawn from this research going back to
the Ulysses S. Grant administration is that major White House
scandals are always bad news for stock investors.
</P>
<P>
   The cause-and-effect relationship is debatable, of course, but
the month between the Dow Jones industrial average's record close
on July 17 and President Clinton's grand jury testimony was a rocky
experience for the stock market. Interestingly enough, the market
rallied on the day the president testified. The Dow turned in its
fourth-best gain of the year and followed that with another strong
showing the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, it has been a wild roller-coaster ride for
Wall Street. And if the past is prologue, stock market players
should brace for continued bouts of heavy weather until the latest
presidential problem is resolved. As Casey Stengel was wont to say,
you can look it up.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't come all wrapped up in a neat little package in some
cases, but the advent of scandal and stock market sinking spells
are in close enough proximity to challenge your belief in
coincidences.
</P>
<P>
   After the Reagan administration's Iran-Contra scandal broke in
late 1986, it was less than a year before the resounding crash that
climaxed a brief but brutal bear market that cost the Dow Jones
industrial average more than one-third of its value from August to
October of 1987.
</P>
<P>
   From the time of the Nixon-era Watergate scandal marked by the
``Saturday Night Massacre'' in October 1973, the Dow lost 40
percent during an ensuing 12-month bear debacle. The oil-embargo
crisis was obviously a contributing factor, but some historians
contend President Nixon's weakened position made OPEC hard-liners
more aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   From Watergate you have to go back a half-century to find
another incidence with enough taint to be blamed as a stock market
depressant. The Teapot Dome scandal broke during the Calvin
Coolidge presidency but was a creature of the Warren G. Harding
administration. Its market consequences, though, were relatively
modest compared with the experiences of the Nixon and Reagan eras.
President Harding died in August 1923, but it wasn't until six
months later that revelations of Cabinet-level corruption in 1922
surfaced. Over the next three months, the market lost 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Before that bit of unpleasantness you have to go back 50 more
years to the Grant regime, which saw four Cabinet officers involved
in scandal. The major market gauge back then was the Cowles index,
which declined more than 20 percent from February to November 1876.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the (independent counsel Kenneth) Starr report likely due
in September, the market is highly unlikely to turn bullish,''
Smart Money advised subscribers in its September issue. ``Let's
face it, if it weren't for the top 100 largest capitalization
companies, everyone would be acknowledging that we're in a bear
market. Shall we speak louder? BEAR MARKET!''
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead toward next year, Hirsch said it would depend on
Asia and Russia finding miracle cures for their economic ailments
and President Clinton's ability to weather his storm. If all turns
out well, he said, the current experience will be limited to
correction status.
</P>
<P>
   If worse comes to worst, however, things could get ugly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-98 1852EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
