<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9561 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASHCROFT-CRITICIZE-2N     08-30 0185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASHCROFT-CRITICIZE-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ lode, struck gold.
</P>
<P>
   He called for Clinton's resignation. A few weeks later, he
compared the president to a ``sexual predator.'' Slowly, a kind of
political critical mass began to form and Ashcroft came to be in
demand.
</P>
<P>
   He pretty much has had the field to himself. Most of his
colleagues remain cautious, either because they think events should
just unfold without their help or because they are uncertain about
the public's mood on what course Clinton _ and Congress _ should
follow.
</P>
<P>
   And that's where Ashcroft's outspokenness about Clinton _ from
the heart, but carefully choreographed for maximum effect _ has, so
far at least, given his presidential hopes momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``You define your objectives and you've got to understand the
process,'' Merritt said. ``What are the levers and the leverage
points in the system? What are the things that tell me that this
guy could be a national player?
</P>
<P>
   ``Or, more important, what stuff will the press cover?''
</P>
</TEXT>
