<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Write your resume in the right language  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Have you ever received an e-mail message that was a
bunch of symbols and scrambled letters? If so, you've seen what
could happen to your e-mailed resume if it's not formatted to be
read by your potential employer's system.
</P>
<P>
   When I get messages in MIME format, for example, I see screens
upon screens full of squares, capital A's and other characters. If
it were your resume, I couldn't read it.
</P>
<P>
   Some hirers say they continue to prefer resumes printed on
paper, but many organizations are accepting, if not expecting,
e-mailed resumes and job applications.
</P>
<P>
   If you use e-mail or send your resume as an attachment to an
e-mail, be sure what you send is computer-friendly to your intended
recipient. Call the organization's human resource office or, in a
smaller company, your potential boss, and ask what computer
language, word processor or both you should use.
</P>
<P>
   Many large companies use scanning technology to screen resumes.
If their scanner can't read your message, your application won't be
channeled to human eyes. And, even if human eyes are the first to
see your e-mail or attachment, it's worthless if it's unreadable.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of hiring executives this summer by OfficeTeam, a
staffing service, found that two-thirds had no preference as to
what resume format applicants used. (Their choices were mail, fax,
e-mail and ``in person.'')
</P>
<P>
   Some of those surveyed said they wanted a hard copy to follow an
e-mailed or faxed resume. Your choice of paper, layout and typeface
can boost your professional appearance, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Another point: When you use both e-mail and hard copy, you may
need two slightly different resumes. Italics, boldfaces,
underlining and other desktop publishing features that look great
on paper may not be read well in e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
