<SLUG> BC-ASHCROFT-CRITICIZE-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY SCANDAL IS PUBLIC RELATIONS WINDFALL FOR JOHN ASHCROFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Within minutes of President Clinton's remarkable
televised admission about his sexual affair, Sen. John Ashcroft was
on two television networks _ a third also wanted him _ ripping the
speech apart.
</P>
<P>
   This past week, as he barnstormed the country raising money for
his undeclared presidential campaign, he showed up again, this time
on three network political talk shows, to bash the president some
more.
</P>
<P>
   In the seesaw world of Washington politics, the bane of
Clinton's presidency has become a public relations bonanza for
Ashcroft's presidential ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to give an honest point of view that I think needs
expression,'' Ashcroft said. ``To the extent that producers of
these shows feel like they want to have that view aired, they call
me. And if they call, I answer.''
</P>
<P>
   And he does, frequently.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Ashcroft's so telegenic. He often looks as if his
starched white collar is buttoned just a bit too tight. But the
White House sex scandal has turned the once-little-known Missouri
Republican into a card-carrying member of the capital's chattering
class.
</P>
<P>
   And he seems to be everywhere lately. Talk radio. The Sunday
morning television talk show circuit. The 24-hour cable networks.
He's joined a rotating cast of pundits, pollsters and
ex-prosecutors to weigh in as the conservative counterpoint on
Clinton's problems.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington parlance, Ashcroft, the minister's son who rides
motorcycles, writes and sings gospel music, and scathingly
criticizes the president, has the ``buzz.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is `buzz?''' said Mark Merritt, communications director
for Lamar Alexander's 1996 presidential campaign. ``An almost
imperceptible momentum that culminates when a significant number of
people seem to `coincidentally' come to the same conclusion at the
same time.''
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion in Ashcroft's case, Merritt said, is that ``he is
trying to establish that he is able to lead the conservative
movement, that he is willing publicly to take them where they want
to go and not straddle the fence on the key issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Carin Pratt, executive producer of CBS News' Sunday
morning show, ``Face the Nation,'' said: ``He says some pretty
strong things.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's not clear yet whether Ashcroft's sudden celebrity
reaches beyond Washington's political salons.
</P>
<P>
   He won a presidential straw poll in South Carolina in May. But
earlier this month he barely registered a blip in an Iowa survey of
whom likely Republican voters would support for their party's
presidential nomination. He was at the bottom, separated from the
leader, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, by a dozen other possible
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   And that's after several trips to Iowa in the past year, along
with New Hampshire, South Carolina and other key presidential
primary states.
</P>
<P>
   But Terry Jeffrey, who managed Pat Buchanan's 1996 presidential
campaign, said early surveys should not be taken too seriously
because the presidential field still is unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   Farther down the road, said Jeffrey, editor of /{Human Events,/}
a national conservative weekly, ``It will be easier to drive his
name recognition higher in Iowa and New Hampshire, where people are
conscious of the fact that we are heading into an election cycle,
than it will be in places where people are not as politically
aware.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if Ashcroft's profile outside Washington remains low,
his pocketbook is brimming. A year's worth of traveling _ just
about every weekend and every congressional recess _ has swollen
his Spirit of America leadership PAC by more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   He will need about $20 million in his campaign account by Jan.
1, 2000, if he intends to become a serious candidate for the White
House, most knowledgeable observers agree. Ashcroft said last week
that he probably would decide by the end of the year whether he
will run.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, he has spent the past 12 months trying to solidify
his natural base among the Republican Party's social conservative
wing. He was among the first prominent Republicans to call for
Clinton's resignation if the allegations about his romantic
involvement with Monica Lewinsky, the former White House intern,
proved to be true.
</P>
<P>
   Which they did, and now talk of resignation is treated as a
serious possibility.
</P>
<P>
   But Ashcroft said it first, back in February. It got him a
flurry of attention in the media and a round of applause from the
conservative groups he has been wooing for presidential support. It
also triggered a steady climb to higher political visibility. And
for a generally unknown senator with dreams of the Oval Office, it
was the kind of publicity not easily bought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lewinsky provided the first major opportunity for John to step
up on the national stage on a consistent basis, and he took that
opportunity,'' said Keith Appell, an Ashcroft media adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after satisfying his socially conservative supporters, he
has made a move to broaden his appeal with a national economic
plan. And Iowa is where he is making his first move, with a
two-week blitz of feel-good television ads touting his ideas. The
centerpiece is a tax cut, through a restructuring of the tax code,
and a spending cut of more than $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft first broached the subject in January in a Washington
news conference. His plan then, more vague on some details, got
notices in the business and political media, and a few paragraphs
in newspapers around the country.
</P>
<P>
   But less than two weeks later, Lewinsky's name became a
household word. And not long after that, Ashcroft, who has mined
the moral center of his party for support like a prospector in
search of the mother lode, struck gold. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
