u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DEMOCRATS-100     08-30 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DEMOCRATS-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S PROBLEMS AFFECTING DEMOCRATIC CAMPAIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Mo., Ore., Texas, Ala., N.C., S.C., Colo., Ariz.)  (See also CLINTON-STARR) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the two weeks since President Clinton
acknowledged his relationship with Monica Lewinsky, the tension and
uncertainty within the Democratic Party have not diminished but
have in fact intensified as its candidates gear up for the general
election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Clinton's disclosure is beginning to undermine the
drive to put forth a full-throated Democratic agenda, according to
Democratic candidates and strategists, who say there is a growing
consensus that the party has all but forfeited its prospect for
closing the 11-seat gap and winning back control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some of these Democrats fear that the party could even
suffer a net loss of well over a dozen seats, making any climb back
into the majority a very arduous effort _ and one that could take
years.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Roxanne Qualls of Cincinnati, a Democrat in a tight
contest for the House, expressed frustration that as she tries to
discuss Social Security, health care and education, the press and
the Republicans want only to bring up Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not helpful to me and it's not helpful to the voters
because the issues aren't focused on,'' Ms. Qualls said.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democratic candidates around the country are putting
distance between themselves and Clinton, leaving party leaders in
the uncomfortable position of backing candidates who do not want
their party's president to travel to their states or districts. In
this crucial start of the fall campaign season, when it is
especially important that the party display a united front,
Clinton's disclosure has exacerbated tensions between the president
and party stalwarts like Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., the House
minority leader, who last week forcefully condemned Clinton for
``reprehensible'' behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The president himself was described by several people who have
had conversations with him in recent days as dejected and worried
that the matter could take a toll on the outcome in November and
his influence on Capitol Hill. Clinton has talked with senior
Democratic lawmakers, aides said, seeking to reassure them about
the elections and his own ability to function.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he's as much worried about November as he is
about his job _ it's all wrapped in together,'' said one adviser
who spoke several times to the president last week. ``You do not
want this to snowball and get out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the defensive and unsettled posture of many Democrats,
party leaders put on a brave face in public. They insist that
fund-raising is holding steady, and they cling to polls showing
that Clinton's job approval ratings remained strong. Another sign
bringing them hope is that several contenders said the Lewinsky
matter had not come up in their races; even some Republicans said
it was too soon to tell whether it would emerge as a pivotal issue.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Democrats around the country said they were far more
dispirited than when the Lewinsky matter surfaced in late January,
when many in the party rallied around Clinton and went on the
attack against Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The swirl of publicity over Ms. Lewinsky has left the
administration on the defensive, with White House officials
insisting that no Democratic candidates had asked Clinton to stay
out of their states.
</P>
<P>
   The officials also said that state parties in Ohio, New York and
Rhode Island, expecting that some candidates might cancel visits by
Clinton, called the White House last week and said that they would
like the president to be the featured guest at their fund-raising
events.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent Democrats said they had never before experienced a
time when many of their party's candidates were scolding the
president, and openly weighing whether they would want him to
campaign for them.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he would want Clinton to campaign on his behalf,
David Wu, a lawyer locked in a House race in Portland, Ore.,
hesitated and said: ``It's clearly a tough one. The future's really
hard to see, and I think it will turn very closely on what's in a
Starr report.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed further about a trip by Clinton, Wu said, ``I'd ask him,
`Who's paying the transportation costs?''' He would agree to a
visit, he said, if Clinton emphasized only issues and ``if we could
cut enough of a deal'' so Wu's campaign would not have to pay too
much.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, Rep. Charles Stenholm, a conservative Democrat, late
last week began broadcasting a television commercial that
criticizes Clinton. After a narrator cites Clinton's veto of
defense projects for the district, Stenholm says: ``I've always
believed in doing what is right for the people of the 17th
District, regardless of what the president says, or what the
leaders of my own party are saying. And that will never change.''
</P>
<P>
   In closing, the narrator says: ``Charlie Stenholm. Our values.
Our Congressman.''
</P>
<P>
   Though most Republican candidates until now let Clinton's
troubles speak for themselves, there are signs of an increasing
willingness to take on the president directly.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Gil Aust, a Republican running for the House in
Alabama, began broadcasting a commercial urging Clinton to resign.
As slow motion excerpts from Clinton's address to the nation about
Ms. Lewinsky appear on the screen, the announcer intones: ``The
headlines tell the story. President Clinton lying to the American
people.'' The commercial does not even mention Aust's opponent,
Rep. Robert Cramer.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Page, a Republican seeking a House seat in North Carolina,
began running a commercial about the Lewinsky matter several days
ago. And the South Carolina Republican Party has created a series
of radio advertisements about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Even Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas, chairman of the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee, said he understood why some
candidates did not want to be seen with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The candidates just aren't comfortable appearing with the
president at this point,'' Frost said. ``It's natural that
politicians are always nervous about what's going to happen in an
election.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Struggling to put the best face on the Democrats' predicament,
Steve Grossman, the party's national chairman, said: ``The events
of the last couple weeks clearly have the propensity to shift our
focus away from the grassroots organization and voter turnout
programs that we would like to be doing every day, to another set
of issues.'' But Grossman said he did not see ``any tangible
evidence in all the fund-raising results I've seen'' that the
Lewinsky matter was dampening contributions to the party.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Alan Secrest, a Democratic pollster, said he was seeing
evidence of ``an ebbing in Clinton's personal appeal,'' especially
among women under 50, a crucial voting bloc. ``Many Democrats have
reached the point of exhaustion in defending the president,''
Secrest said. ``Very few of my clients are rushing to the ramparts
to defend him.''
</P>
<P>
   And one of the Democratic Party's most successful fund-raisers
said that he feared a drop in contributions. The donors who were
coming forward now, he said, were the ones the party could always
rely upon.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're not going to get now is the fence sitters who
would be very active if they thought we had a chance of winning the
House back,'' the fund-raiser said. ``In the fall campaign you want
a crusade going. But we've lost a tremendous amount of momentum _
and incentive for people to open up their wallets.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lewinsky matter has also stirred tensions among Democratic
leaders. Clinton, for one, was described by associates as furious
at Gephardt's comments to reporters early last week that he did not
rule out the possibility that the president could be impeached.
After speaking with Democrats who were concerned about the
sharpness of his remarks, Gephardt toned down his comments.
</P>
<P>
   Though some Democrats argued that Gephardt's remarks were useful
in pre-empting criticism that party leaders were motivated only by
partisan calculations, others said they were concerned that his
comments allowed Democratic candidates to distance themselves from
the president.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Romer of Colorado, general chairman of the Democratic
Party, said candidates who do not want to be associated with
Clinton were ``playing the margins,'' meaning they fear it could
cost them a few critical percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   But several Democratic candidates said they hoped that voters
could separate Clinton's troubles from their own campaigns. Steve
Owens, a lawyer who is seeking a House seat from Arizona, said he
called the White House last week and asked for the president to
visit his district.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be honored to have him in,'' he said. ``And I'd be right
there with him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
