</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARY U.S. OFFICIALS WATCH RUSSIA, AND WAIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-RDP and RUSSIA-ASSESS) 
(js) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Administration officials warily monitored the
maneuvering to form a new government in Moscow Sunday, disturbed by
possible signs of backsliding on Russia's commitment to tough
economic reform but reluctant to render a verdict until new
personnel and policies are in place.
</P>
<P>
   Officials avoided definitive comment in advance of President
Clinton's arrival in Moscow on Tuesday, for fear of appearing to
take sides in what promises to be a delicate negotiation among
various factions in Moscow over the next several days.
</P>
<P>
   The official administration line on Sunday was that the Russians
themselves will have to sort out the approach they take to finding
an exit from the economic and political morass Moscow now faces.
Until then, the Clinton administration will make clear its own
policy preferences but will not attempt to broker a truce among
competing Russian power centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to see how it all plays out,'' Lawrence Summers,
the deputy treasury secretary said on the CBS news program ``Face
the Nation.'' ``What is crucial is not words at this point but
actions the Russians are able to take at what is a critical
juncture for them and their management of the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said that Washington is discounting much of what it is
hearing from Moscow as political posturing in the midst of an
effort to create a governing coalition. Engaged in the competition
for power are those loyal to President Boris Yeltsin, the business
oligarchy, the resurgent Communists, regional power brokers and
advocates of broad economic reform measures endorsed by the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will give our opinion of the course they choose, but we are
not going to do it before we have a government in place and have a
chance to sort out what the real policies are,'' the official said.
He said that the United States does not know yet whether Viktor
Chernomyrdin, the acting prime minister, will be confirmed by the
Russian Parliament by the time Clinton arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Until Chernomyrdin is confirmed, the official added, the
administration would not comment except to signal what policies it
would find objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   Undesirable actions would include efforts to bail out failing
banks, granting additional credits to state-run enterprises,
flooding the market with newly printed rubles and ``other actions
that could clearly have inflationary effects,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration would welcome, he said, programs that allow
market forces to work, even if the short-term impact is painful,
and new measures to insure an economy that functions under the rule
of law rather than Kremlin fiat.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to see what the terms are, what kind of
economic plan Russia actually carries through on the ground,'' said
Summers, who will travel to Moscow for the summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Another senior administration official, also speaking on
condition of anonymity, said that he hoped Clinton's arrival this
week would put pressure on Yeltsin and Chernomyrdin to stick to the
difficult path of reform rather than accept compromises as the
price of remaining in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a lot of back and forth,'' the official
said. ``But what we really don't know is where Chernomyrdin's heart
is. It's really do or die now. Does he understand he can't go back
to the old ways?''
</P>
<P>
   But until the direction Moscow takes becomes clear, he added,
Clinton and his senior advisers are going to ``try to avoid getting
sucked into everyday speculation'' about who is in power and what
they might do.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, who is leaving his post as the
U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, described the compromise
deal being negotiated in Moscow as a ``very favorable
development.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' Richardson said the
United States was prepared to to continue and even expand its
financial aid to Russia, if the government proceeds with reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're prepared to do more,'' Richardson said. ``As long as
there's economic reform, we're going to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who returned to Washington Sunday from his vacation on
Martha's Vineyard, participated in several conference calls with
senior staff aides and his national security team, White House
officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
