<SLUG> BC-NORTHWEST-DAKOTA-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINE STRIKE TRIES THE PATIENCE OF NORTH DAKOTA 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NORTHWEST-STRIKE, moving in `f' category) 
(lb) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND FORKS, N.D. _ People here figure they can handle almost
anything.
</P>
<P>
   After the thundering flood waters that last year forced the
evacuation of the entire city _ all 50,000 people _ what could faze
them? But the pilots' strike that has grounded Northwest Airlines
since Saturday morning is already trying people's patience.
</P>
<P>
   It marooned Joe Larson in Minneapolis and made him miss his
grand-nephew's wedding. It is causing Ron Boonstra to bow out of
his fertilizer company's annual training session in Peoria, Ill. It
may keep out-of-state students from the first week of classes at
the University of North Dakota. And it threatens to put the kibosh
on one of Grand Forks' biggest events this year: the national
women's amateur slow-pitch softball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everything in Grand Forks, North Dakota's third-largest
city, depends in some way on Northwest Airlines. Northwest delivers
the mail here. It brings medical supplies for the hospital, flowers
for the florists, even goldfish for the pet stores. No other
passenger airline flies in or out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll affect just about every one of us,'' said the Grand
Forks mayor, Pat Owens. ``People don't usually come here unless
they fly. Now we're land-locked.''
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of this spread-out, wide-open state, where the
prairie rolls on forever and the rural roads are like miles of
string threading tiny towns like beads, this single airline has
become an umbilical cord. The only other commercial carrier that
flies in and out is United Airlines, and it runs only a smattering
of commuter flights, no more than 30 seats, from three cities _
Fargo, Bismarck and Minot.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, afraid of a Northwest strike, Gary Ness, the
executive director of the state Aeronautics Commission, sent a
letter to 20 airlines, begging them to route a few planes North
Dakota's way. He got no takers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ness predicts that the economic cost of the strike will be
about $365,000 a day statewide _ and that's only counting the cost
to travel-related industries like travel agents, hotels and
car-rental companies. No negotiations were planned Sunday between
the pilots and Northwest's officials.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't measure the cost, for example, to the North American
Bison Cooperative, which each day flies about $10,000 worth of
buffalo on Northwest to New York and Boston, where butchers turn it
into steaks and buffalo burgers. ``I imagine we'll have to give up
on most of it,'' said Dennis Sexhus, the chief executive officer,
who says the Northwest shipments represent about 5 percent of his
bison business.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't account for the frustration of people like Bill
Antongiovanni, a salesman of nuts, bolts and screws, who was
supposed to be taking his 4-year-old granddaughter, Taylor, to stay
with him in Bakersfield, Calif., while her parents in Fargo
prepared for the birth of a new baby. After hours on the phone,
Antongiovanni, 56, booked the only flight he could, out of
Billings, Mont., a 10-hour drive away.
</P>
<P>
   But for North Dakota, the potential cost is almost more painful
than the actual loss. It's not only the North Dakotans who want to
fly elsewhere, but can't. It's the people who won't come.
</P>
<P>
   Not many people come to North Dakota to begin with. With 2.9
million visitors a year, it has the fewest of any state, said Bob
Martinson, the director of the North Dakota Tourism Department. The
outlet malls in Freeport, Maine, home of L.L. Bean, get more
visitor traffic in a year than all of North Dakota does.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of those national weather guys can destroy us in a
30-second piece _ `Snowstorm in North Dakota' _ as though we're the
only state that has winter,'' Martinson said.
</P>
<P>
   The state has been trying to promote tourism any way it can,
aware that drivers don't tend to stumble upon North Dakota on their
way to somewhere else. It has jumped on the Lewis-and-Clark
bicentennial bandwagon, hoping to lure visitors to see where the
explorers spent a long winter in 1804-1805. It is playing up its
Wild West image and American Indian heritage, especially in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But the strike may have already dealt a setback to the state. A
group of European travel writers are supposed to fly in on
Wednesday for a state tour. ``If we miss that window, we lose the
whole winter publication time,'' Martinson said. ``They won't be
coming back until the spring.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some towns try to draw visitors (and free labor) to
potato-picking festivals. And then there is Norwegian tourism in a
state where every third resident has a Norwegian ancestor.
</P>
<P>
   There is a huge Norwegian festival in Minot in October. And
Grand Forks has been wooing groups of Norwegians to visit Red River
Valley farms where ``they are just amazed at the 6 feet of black
soil,'' said Char Brekke, the manager of Brekke Tours in Grand
Forks. ``They enjoy going to the cemetery and seeing all these
Norwegian names on the tombstones,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Forks is also capitalizing on a wave of flood tourism.
City tourism staff hop aboard tour buses and show people where the
water was.
</P>
<P>
   There is a flood exhibit at the museum, and a new restaurant,
the Red River Cafe, has built a brick wall inside its dining room
that is the height of the water during the flood. The idea, said
James Tsismanakis, the executive director of the Convention and
Visitors Bureau, is that ``you're sitting there and in a sense
you're under water.''
</P>
<P>
   Without people flying into Grand Forks, these and other economic
generators could languish. Steve Johnson, the executive director of
the Grand Forks Regional Airport Authority, figures that without
Northwest's four jets and three small flights run by its commuter
arm, Mesaba, each day, the city will lose at least $50,000 a month
in airport fees. And hotels like the C'mon Inn are already getting
a few cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond tourism, people here worry that the strike will bring
the loss of a kind of cross-country pollination _ people coming to
the state and North Dakotans venturing out for all sorts of
global-village reasons. The mail can be trucked in. Businesses can
send and receive items by Federal Express. But when the nearest
jets fly into Winnipeg, Manitoba (a two-and-a-half-hour drive) or
Minneapolis (five hours), that puts a damper on things.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest is ``not just the economic lifeline _ it's the social
and cultural lifeline also,'' said Hal Gershman, who runs a chain
of liquor stores called Happy Harry's Bottle Shops, and is active
in civics and culture in Grand Forks.
</P>
<P>
   Gershman, whose daughter, a student at New York University,
caught the last plane east on Thursday night, is supposed to fly
Northwest to New York himself next week for a meeting of the Wine
and Spirits Guild of America.
</P>
<P>
   Gershman is concerned that the strike may thwart several
upcoming Grand Forks cultural events: an exhibit by a New York
painter, a reading of a play scheduled for Broadway, and the debut
of a children's show traveling from Washington. Already, he said,
the strike has canceled a visit by a philanthropic foundation that
was expected to give generously to the city's science center.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of thing can set a project back for a long time,''
Gershman said. ``There's probably 80 of these things in town right
now, important business meetings, churches bringing in speakers,
lawyers coming in to look at a merger. And how many people have put
projects on hold?''
</P>
<P>
   But the bigger fear is that once the strike is over, Northwest
will be forced to cut back some of its routes and will sacrifice _
what else? _ North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern is that we continue to be served by Northwest, a
national airline, and not be downgraded to a regional airline,''
Gershman said. ``You fall off the screen on certain things when you
do not have a national airline serving your city. I think that's a
major economic, social and cultural threat to all of North Dakota.
Are you a destination, or are you not?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
