<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIANA-YEARLATER-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE `DIANA FATIGUE,' BRITONS HONOR THE PRINCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: TV-DIANA-REVIEW)  
(mk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALTHORP, England _ Glenice and Gordon Phillips were not able to
get entrance tickets but drove 30 miles all the same Sunday to this
verdant, walled estate just to place a small bouquet of white
flowers outside the wrought iron gates at the family seat of Diana,
Princess of Wales.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still miss her,'' said Phillips, the 49-year-old owner of a
car repair shop, as he arrived at Althorp House, for more than four
centuries the home of the Spencer family, to which Diana was born.
Her body was returned here after the car crash in Paris that killed
her one year ago Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a year in which the British monarchy _ shaken to its
roots by the public outpouring of grief for Diana _ has sought with
characteristic caution to redefine itself. But it has also been a
year in which Diana's memory has begun to shed some of the saintly
adulation inspired by her death.
</P>
<P>
   Preparations for the anniversary seemed muted, reflecting what
some newspapers have called ``Diana fatigue'' even as they, like
most television stations, have filled columns and air time with
memorials to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, it shocked everybody that so many people joined in
the mourning, but we are typically British: We pull back,''
Phillips said, as other Diana admirers who had been able to
purchase the scarce $16 entrance tickets to Althorp House made
their way along a long driveway toward an artificial lake called
the Oval, where she lies buried on a leafy island. ``And that's our
interest today _ to show that we have not forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Lorna Fox, 47, who had driven five hours from Dorset on the
south coast to Althorp, 70 miles north of London, agreed that many
Britons had retreated some way from last year's readiness ``to be
emotional, to cry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our natural instinct is to be reserved, but we need people to
care,'' she said. ``We are not out there giving and loving
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirroring the nation's debate, though, Ronald Stanton, a
52-year-old taxi-driver from nearby Northampton awaiting his
passenger, an Italian journalist, said enough is enough.``People
should let it go now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillipses and others were among thousands who sought Sunday
to commemorate Diana's memory as the formal anniversary of her
death approached.
</P>
<P>
   At Kensington Palace, Diana's one-time London home, hundreds of
people brought flowers, evoking the enormous floral tributes of one
year ago, though foreign tourists appeared to outnumber the
Britons.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, moreover, was the last day that Althorp House, with its
museum to Diana and memorabilia, was open to public visits this
year. The $16 entrance fee has drawn accusations that Earl Spencer,
Diana's brother and the jealous custodian of her memory, is
profiting from her tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   But estate officials said they were expecting a full 2,500
visitors _ the maximum permitted each day since the estate and
exhibit opened their doors to paying visitors on July 1, which
would have been Diana's 37th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   At Westminster Abbey, where Elton John sang and Earl Spencer
inveighed against the press and the monarchy at Diana's funeral
service on Sept. 6, 1997, only the briefest of prayers mentioned
Diana by name Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Queen Elizabeth and the visiting prime minister, Tony Blair,
were among dignitaries at Sunday prayers at Crathie Church, near
Balmoral Castle _ the royal retreat in Scotland where Queen
Elizabeth often vacations and where, one year ago, she remained
secluded following Diana's death as Britons clamored for her to
mourn with them. In an echo of last year's royal reticence, the
anniversary was mentioned only obliquely at Crathie Church Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hear our prayers for those grieving the loss of a loved one,
in circumstances known to the world but only experienced by a
few,'' said the Rev. Robert Sloan.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Of that few, though, virtually every intimate player in the
Diana saga _ part national tragedy, part soap opera _ has been
reforged in the year since her death.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Spencer, the hurt and angry crusader whose voice from
Westminster captured a nation's rage and hurt, soon showed a
different side. He became embroiled in a messy divorce in South
Africa that cast him in a far less heroic light.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Charles, the heir to the throne, has assiduously tried to
reshape his image. Once cast in villain's garb as Diana's distant,
faithless former husband, he has sought to show himself as the
caring single parent of the royal princes _ William, 16, and Harry,
13. They accompanied him to the church service Sunday near Balmoral
Castle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's because of William and Harry that people feel for him,''
said Lesley Alabaster, 36, a police officer who came with her
family to Althorp Sunday. ``He has been seen to be more
accessible,'' she added, reflecting on Prince Charles' improved
popularity ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Charles has even ventured to break a taboo that _ at the
time of Diana's death _ seemed likely to be permanent. He has
introduced his elder son to his longtime companion, Camilla
Parker-Bowles, who has yet, however, to achieve broad public
acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Camilla, Princess of Wales _ Never,'' said one message left
with the flowers outside Kensington Palace Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The queen has, in a more limited way, displayed a slight
loosening of her dour and distant manner in response to the clamor
for a caring royal visage following the death of ``the people's
princess,'' as Blair dubbed Diana after her death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The queen has got a long way to go,'' Mrs. Alabaster said.
``She's not the people's queen.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Glenice Phillips put it, Britain's royal family ``has
just got to get its act together if it wants the backing of the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   In apparent recognition of such sentiments, Buckingham Palace
recently appointed a highly paid communications director, Simon
Lewis, to mold the royal image. Ben Pimlott, a royal biographer,
wrote in Sunday's Sunday Times newspaper that, arguably, ``the
Windsors have got it right for the moment. However, if the monarchy
wishes to stay in business, not for years, but for generations, it
will have to think beyond the appointment of a communications
director.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Diana's own image _ and what seemed like a cult of
admiration reinforced by over 7,000 web sites chronicling
conspiracy theories about her death _ has begun to emerge from
near-saintliness, at least in the eyes of some religious figures.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Coggan, a former archbishop of Canterbury, stirred protest
this month by calling Diana a ``false goddess'' with ``pretty loose
morals.''
</P>
<P>
   At her family's ancestral home, though, there was still the
sense of loss among those who had come to remember, many of them
people who had booked tickets as soon as they were first advertised
last January because they wanted to be here on this particular day.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was just a wonderful person like we would all like to
be,'' said Barbara Gill, 51, who described herself as a housewife
from Northampton.
</P>
<P>
   And one of the hand-written cards with the lilies and daisies
and carnations outside Althorp's walls offered its own explanation
of Diana's early death. ``God must have run out of angels,'' it
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
