<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFCWEST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite setbacks, 49ers look to contend for another championship
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. _ The free agent defensive end the San
Francisco 49ers lured here with a $4 million-a-year contract still
walks with a pronounced limp and his offseason knee surgery will
keep him sidelined until mid-October. The offensive tackle who cost
them a second-round pick in next year's draft was injured, lost his
starting job, suffered an emotional meltdown, went AWOL and is
suspended for three weeks. The running attack is one sprained ankle
away from disaster, the kicking game is a huge question mark and
Jerry Rice's first appearance won't come until Sunday's
regular-season opener.
</P>
<P>
   So pencil in the Niners to win their 13th NFC West title in 16
years and to extend their league record for consecutive seasons
with 10 or more victories to 16.
</P>
<P>
   ''Despite whatever has gone wrong, we've got things going in the
right direction,'' said linebacker Lee Woodall just before San
Francisco broke camp. ''One of the things we've become pretty good
at around here is dealing with adversity. Plus we still have a lot
of talent . . . enough to win the division and contend for the
Super Bowl again.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodall figures to be half-right, at least, in the prediction
department.
</P>
<P>
   Given the lack of quality in the NFC West, where the 49ers had
the only winning record in '97 and captured the title by a whopping
six games, San Francisco could again wrap up the crown before
December and should win 10-12 games simply by showing up every week
at the appointed time and place.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule is rated as the NFL's second-easiest and the Niners
face an NFL-low four playoff clubs from last season. Just six
opponents were plus-.500 in '97 and while the 49ers have slid
closer to the pack in the NFC West, none of their division
opponents are prepared yet to seriously challenge their
superiority. It's hard to imagine, even some of the team's veterans
conceded, the Niners going worse than 6-2 in the division.
</P>
<P>
   Such a cakewalk, however, hardly assures that coach Steve
Mariucci's team will make a strong showing in the playoffs. San
Francisco hasn't been to the Super Bowl since the '94 season and,
because of a glaring lack of depth, that streak likely will
continue.
</P>
<P>
   Offseason additions like middle linebacker Winfred Tubbs,
cornerback Antonio Langham and tight end Irv Smith stopped the
graying of the San Francisco roster but still might not be enough
to keep the first hint of silver from Mariucci's dark hair.
</P>
<P>
   ''The drop-off (from the starters) is fairly precipitous,''
Mariucci allowed in preseason. ''Our second-line people haven't
played well. Like a lot of teams, we're going to hold our breath at
some positions.''
</P>
<P>
   A dire lack of able-bodied veterans on his offensive and
defensive lines actually could send Mariucci into hyperventilation.
Former Green Bay defensive end Gabe Wilkins and onetime Denver
offensive tackle Jamie Brown were high-profile acquisitions who
have yet to set foot on the field. There is no proven backup to
tailback Garrison Hearst and tackles Derrick Deese and Dave Fiore
are dubious.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers will rely on a defense that annually rates among the
NFL's premier run-stop units, an offense that will feature more
three-wide receiver alignments and the brand of confidence that
comes from having ruled the NFC West roost for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until somebody in the division can prove it on the field,''
said wide receiver Terrell Owens, ''we're still the team to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
