<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FSUADV-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Classic kicks off with FSU, A&AMP;M
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ When Florida State takes the field
tonight at Giants Stadium, you'll forgive Chris Weinke if he takes
an extra moment to enjoy the spotlight. After all, it took him
eight years to get here.
</P>
<P>
   After a six-year hiatus from the sport and one year as a backup,
college football's oldest sophomore (26) will finally get a chance
to show if he's still got it when No. 2 Florida State meets No. 14
Texas A&AMP;M in the Kickoff Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard to say exactly what I'm going to be feeling,'' said
Weinke, who hasn't started a game at quarterback since his senior
year in high school in 1989. ''I know I'll be nervous. Anyone who
says they are not going to be nervous for a game of this magnitude
is going to be lying. I don't know how I'm going to react. For the
most part I'm a clam guy but this is something I've been waiting
eight years for.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinke, a native of St. Paul, Minn., was considered the nation's
best high school quarterback in 1989. He signed with Florida State
but decided to try baseball when the Blue Jays gave him a $375,000
bonus. After six years of bouncing around the organization, Weinke
decided to give football another try. Florida State coach Bobby
Bowden, as promised, had a scholarship waiting for him.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State has not started a sophomore quarterback since
1986, but Weinke is no ordinary sophomore, said Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know everything about him except how he'll play in the
game,'' said Bowden, who begins his 23rd season at FSU. ''He's got
all the tools and the biggest thing is his maturity. I would be
surprised if he doesn't do well but we have to remember that our
last three or four quarterbacks all really struggled in their first
few games.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, Florida State's quarterbacks have had a tough
time finding their comfort level in their first year as the
starter. The Seminole offense places significant demands, both
mentally and physically, on the position. Weinke says he wants to
break this pattern and will do it with preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been watching film all spring and summer trying to
anticipate everything they'll throw at me,'' said Weinke, who threw
only 13 passes as a true freshman last season. ''But you always
know there will be surprises. The question is how I will handle
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinke is making his debut against one of the nation's better
secondaries as the Aggies held their opponents to just 150.3 yards
passing per game last season. He has also been nursing a sore toe
and a sore shoulder over the past two weeks. Neither, he said, will
affect his play.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State has not lost a season-opener since 1989, when
Southern Miss and Brett Favre knocked off the Seminoles 30-26. In
fact, Bowden is 19-3 in opening day games as the Seminoles coach.
The Aggies, who were 9-4 last season, present enough problems to
make this game very close, said Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a dangerous game for us because we're nowhere near
were we need to be,'' said Bowden. ''But if we might as well find
out now if we've got what it takes to be a championship team. If we
don't, we'll find out Monday night.''
</P>
<P>
   KICKOFF CLASSIC: FLORIDA STATE VS. TEXAS A&AMP;M
</P>
<P>
   When/where: 8 p.m., Giants Stadium, East Rutherford, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   TV: ABC (Keith Jackson, Bob Griese, Lynn Swan)
</P>
<P>
   1997 records: Florida State 11-1; Texas A&AMP;M 9-4.
</P>
<P>
   1998 rankings: Texas A&AMP;M is No. 14 in the Associated Press
writer's poll and No. 15 in the ESPN/USA Today Coaches poll;
Florida State is No. 2 in both polls.
</P>
<P>
   Series: Florida State leads 3-0. The last meeting was a 10-2 win
over the Aggies in the 1992 Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches: Bobby Bowden is 208-51-4 in 22 seasons at Florida
State, 281-83-4 overall; R.C. Slocum is 83-25-2 in 10 seasons at
Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   Players to watch (1997 stats): Florida State _ QB Chris Weinke;
RB Travis Minor (112 carries, 664 yards); WR Peter Warrick (53
catches, 884 yards); LB Lamont Green (85 tackles). Texas A&AMP;M _ QB
Branndon Stewart (111/196, 1,429 yards, 10 TD); RB Dante Hall (973
yards rushing); LB Dat Nguyen (130 tackles).
</P>
<P>
   Game notes: Florida State has won eight straight season openers
and the Seminoles are 19-3 on opening day under Bowden....The last
time Florida State opened the season in the Kickoff Classic (1993),
it went on to win the national championship....Texas A&AMP;M is again
favored to win the Big 12's Southern Division. The Aggies return
eight starters on offense and six on defense....As a kick returner,
Texas A&AMP;M's Dante Hall has averaged 9.4 yards per touch....After
struggling early in the 1997 season, Stewart threw for 901 yards in
his last five games....The strenghth of the Texas A&AMP;M defense is a
secondary that allowed only 150.3 yards passing per game.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Texas A&AMP;M is a quality opponent but it can't match
Florida State's overall speed and superior talent. This one could
be close for a half but the Seminoles will wear the Aggies down in
the fourth quarter. Florida State 42, Texas A&AMP;M 17.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
