<HEADER>
A9579 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MENTAL-DSCRIM-COX     08-30 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTAL-DSCRIM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Managed care blocking some treatments
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Helen Meeks of Gainesville, Ga. has wrestled with
depression off and on since she was an adolescent. Now she's
confronting another adversary: managed care.
</P>
<P>
   Meeks, through Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Georgia, has a
managed care plan known as a point-of-service plan. It allows
members to get some benefits for using a health provider not in the
network.
</P>
<P>
   But in Meeks' policy, there's an exception: mental health.
</P>
<P>
   Meeks' therapist, a licensed clinical social worker, isn't in
the network, and the insurance won't pay a dime for those visits,
unlike those for general medical care.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unfair,'' says Meeks, an educator. ``I don't think
they'd single out diabetics or people with cardiovascular
disease.''
</P>
<P>
   So Meeks pays $65 a week out-of-pocket because the therapist
``has made a real difference,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   For years, such gaps have routinely separated the benefits for
physical health and mental health. Some company plans, in fact,
don't cover mental health care at all. Many others place rigid
conditions on care.
</P>
<P>
   For employers, managed care's restrictions have delivered
savings on their mental health bills. They also have delivered
drastic changes in services for emotional and addiction problems _
a benefits revolution that experts say has a greater impact than
that for physical health care.
</P>
<P>
   Patients have to jump through more procedural hoops to get
treatment. And that has led to widespread complaints about managed
care.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Sammons of Murrayville knows the hassles.
</P>
<P>
   Sammons first had to battle her HMO to keep seeing the same
psychiatrist. Then, in July, her Blue Cross plan moved her to a
generic medicine instead of the brand-name drug she had been taking
for her attention deficit disorder.
</P>
<P>
   But she suffered major side effects, including a swollen,
ulcerous tongue. Sammons, a sales rep, is still trying to return to
her brand-name drug.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross Vice President Charlie Harman says that while generic
drugs are often the first option for HMO patients, the plan does
consider appeals for the brand-name drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're making me run through a whole lot of hoops,'' says
Sammons.
</P>
<P>
   A national study shows that while more workers had mental health
coverage in 1995 than in 1991, employers put more limits on those
services. Restrictions included capping the number of outpatient
visits, as well as requiring a higher co-payment.
</P>
<P>
   This disparity infuriates patients and their advocates, who have
rallied to enact several anti-discrimination laws. In fact,
lobbying work by the Georgia Psychological Association and the
Mental Health Association of Georgia pushed state Insurance
Commissioner John Oxendine to issue a directive for POS plans to
cover out-of-network care. Meeks plans to discuss that directive
with her insurer.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross' Harman says the company is in compliance with state
law, that a POS plan doesn't have to cover nonnetwork mental health
therapists.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, ``parity'' proposals have passed in dozens of states
and nationally. Congress in 1996 required benefits plans to have
equal dollar spending limits for mental and physical health care.
</P>
<P>
   And Minnesota enacted a full parity law for the insurance
policies it regulates. Despite yelps from insurers and employer
groups about the cost, health premiums increased by about 1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, legislation passed this year requires that coverage
for mental health and substance abuse, if offered by an employer,
be the same in some areas as for physical health _ including annual
out-of-pocket limits and deductibles and restrictions on the number
of therapy visits or hospital days. The law applies only to
companies with regular health insurance _ those that don't
self-insure their benefits.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 percent of Americans with job-based insurance belong to
self-insured plans, which are exempt from states' regulation under
a federal law known as ERISA. Only Congress can lift that exemption
for employers with self-insured plans.
</P>
<P>
   Real-life examples of parity, such as in Minnesota, show that
equalizing benefits won't balloon costs, says Ron Bachman of the
consulting firm PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that this is going to bankrupt all small employers is
pretty hard to believe,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for substance abuse coverage are pushing for national
legislation barring insurance plans from imposing stricter limits
on addiction treatment than for other medical services.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers raise the argument on higher premiums and insist that
alcohol and drug-abuse treatment often doesn't work. But Dr. Robert
Morse, a psychiatrist at the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn., says,
``Treatment works for many people. We need the opportunity to be
able to continue treatment (for alcohol and drug abuse) like we
would with any other disease.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation's backers say the premium increase would be
negligible, about $1 a month on average.
</P>
<P>
   While the parity debate simmers, some consumers would welcome
any coverage _ even with uneven benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Hoffman works for a real estate company in metro Atlanta
that doesn't have a group insurance plan. She has tried to get a
policy on her own, but has faced a barrier since telling agents she
takes depression medications.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't find anyone to insure me because I take
anti-depres-sants,'' says Hoffman, who buys the medication
out-of-pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mental health is extremely important to me,'' Hoffman says.
``It's flabbergasting they won't insure me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
