<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980830.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9580 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DDN-ISSUELESS-COX     08-30 1432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DDN-ISSUELESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Malaise, lack of coverage attributing to political messages
being lost
 &HT;    By Tim Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ When Republican candidate for governor Bob Taft
unveiled a major initiative to help financially strapped families
make ends meet, the event didn't make the late evening news in the
state capitol.
</P>
<P>
   A burning hay field, a store running out of lottery tickets and
a follow-up report on vandals hitting a suburban school did.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, when Democrat Lee Fisher released a health care
proposal that will be a centerpiece of his campaign, it did not
initially make the airwaves, and only one major newspaper ran the
story on page one.
</P>
<P>
   In 10 weeks, Ohioans will choose their next governor. The winner
will face a daunting list of challenges _ school funding, electric
utility de-regulation, HMO reform, prison overcrowding, privatizing
public services and tax reform.
</P>
<P>
   Each issue in some way touches the lives of Ohioans. But for
most voters, perhaps the only contact they will have with the
candidates and their positions will be through the million of
dollars in paid TV advertising that will flood the airwaves during
the final weeks leading to Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Political observers and professionals say many factors affecting
the political climate _ from a cynical public, to a sound economy,
to a change in the way politicians go about their business and the
media covers it _ combine to make the campaign seem virtually
issueless.
</P>
<P>
   It's not always been that way.
</P>
<P>
   At this point in the last hotly contested campaign for an open
governor's seat _ the 1990 race between Republican George Voinovich
and Democrat Anthony J. Celebrezze Jr. _ voters and the media had
been inundated with information. One single issue book put forth by
Voinovich, detailing his proposals for economic development and job
creation, stacks higher than all of the material presented so far
by Taft and Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current attitude seems to be 'don't get too many people
angry' _ and constantly check the polls,'' said Herb Asher,
professor emeritus of political science at Ohio State University.
``It's an odd election when managed health care _ admittedly an
important issue but one that the republic will survive _ becomes
the only flash point.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When times are good, people do not feel a need to get
something out of government,'' added Jim Tilling, a leading
Republican strategist. ``Health care is getting some attention
because it is something people deal with almost every day. But
there is less fear about other major life issues, such as a job
loss, than there has been in other elections.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just a good economy making things seem quiet.
</P>
<P>
   When Democrat Richard F. Celeste and Republican Clarence J.
Brown squared off in an open governor's race in 1982, seven
commercial television stations had Statehouse bureaus. Today, only
one remains, Dayton's WHIO-TV (Channel 7), along with Ohio Public
Television. Even the major commercial TV stations in Columbus,
which used to have separate Statehouse and government bureaus, have
dropped those offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether we want to admit it or not, a lot of attention to a
campaign, and it's more so early in a race, can be driven by the
presence or lack thereof of TV,'' said Robert Richman, former
campaign manager for Fisher. ``If people see it on TV, even if it's
just a snippet, they think 'this is important' or they learn
something _ sometimes something so simple as the fact that there is
a a big election this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting for even those ``snippets'' can be intense and there is
elation with even modest victories. When Taft announced his
proposal for a ``Kids' Card'' that would allow parents of young
children to receive discounts at participating retail stores, he
stood outside a children's store surrounded by toys and diapers.
</P>
<P>
   One Columbus TV crew filmed the event. It failed to make the
late evening or late night news, but a brief report did air on the
station's 5 p.m. newscast.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of women roll right into that show from Oprah, so we
were pretty pleased about that,'' said Brett Buerck, Taft's press
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just campaign events that are being treated
differently, according to veteran government officials and
observers. Mike Dawson, Gov. Voinovich's press secretary, has a
keen sense of the public mood but he was even taken aback recently
after releasing a one-page letter from Voinovich to federal
officials urging that tax dollars not pay for Viagra prescriptions
except for medical necessities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The phone rang off the hook,'' he said. ``Just about every TV
station in the state called.''
</P>
<P>
   None called a week later when Voinovich issued a detailed
position paper on managed health care.
</P>
<P>
   Pete O'Grady, a Statehouse lobbyist and former chairman of the
Ohio Democratic Party, said it's incorrect to blame public apathy
and media indifference for the lack of fire in a campaign. While
there are differences between Taft and Fisher, their positions on
several key issues _ including school funding and health care
reform _ are similar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a major campaign where one candidate says
something and the other says 'me, too,' '' O'Grady said.
</P>
<P>
   At a July press conference where Fisher and his lieutenant
governor running mate Michael Coleman made strong comments in favor
of the death penalty, one campaign volunteer in the room whispered,
``Where are the Democrats?''
</P>
<P>
   O'Grady said Democrats ``realized that taking positions out of
the mainstream was costing them elections. Remember, this is about
winning. (President) Clinton showed that the Democrats could win
the presidency by moving to the center and that's where we are
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Weaver, a Republican political consultant working in Ohio
and other states, said Clinton has also ``increased the cynicism
factor. His conduct has sparked such intense partisan fighting that
people are turned off. That generally results in disinterest in
other issues and lower voter turnout.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver said people tend to vote when they are ``angry about
something,'' but they are more disappointed with Clinton personally
than angry about policy. ``I think the current mood helps
incumbents, but it does not increase turnout,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Gans, director of the Committee for the Study of the
American Electorate, noted that even in states that made special
efforts to increase turnout in the spring primary, fewer people
voted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem we have is not procedural but motivational,'' he
said. ``There is not quick fix for what ails the American political
system.''
</P>
<P>
   So what will we see in the remaining 10 weeks of a major
campaign, where voters will also be picking a successor to U.S.
Sen. John Glenn, who is retiring after 24 years?
</P>
<P>
   The two leading candidates for governor say it's incorrect to
label the electorate disengaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still early,'' Fisher said. ``But everywhere I go people
come up to me and have important issues on their minds. The debate
will pick up.''
</P>
<P>
   Taft admits he's been at times disheartened by the lack of
attention paid to some of his initiatives, but said, ``Voters will
tune in when they are ready and they will have the information
there to absorb and make a sound choice.''
</P>
<P>
   But much of that information will have been distributed in small
chunks and TV ``sound bites,'' rather than as complete packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candidates have learned that voters tend to go with someone
they trust, someone they feel good about,'' said Democratic
political consultant Gerald Austin. ``Talking directly about an
arcane government policy doesn't get you there.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, so far both major gubernatorial campaigns have tried to
portray their candidate as pro-family, responsible leaders with the
experience to take over state government. Both have hired TV
consultants who have done hard-hitting TV ads in the past, and both
candidates in previous elections have run such spots, but for now
it's a kinder, gentler campaign while each focuses on raising money
and trying to enthuse their party faithful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may get hard-hitting at the end,'' said consultant Richman,
``but what this election is all about is convincing voters that
when a crisis arises, or a major policy decision has to be made,
which candidate is going to do what's best for your family. That's
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Miller writes from the Columbus (Ohio) bureau for the Dayton
Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
