<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9581 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DI-ENGLAND-COX     08-30 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DI-ENGLAND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: One year later, England still embraces its 'Rose,'
but not as tightly
 &HT;    By Colin Campbell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, England _ The protracted first anniversary of the
Princess of Wales's death is just about over, and her country seems
to be getting back to normal again. A year ago _ around the time of
Diana's funeral _ the British turnout and the soul-searching grew
so massive that even I, a visiting American who arrived caring very
little about the royals or their soap opera, found myself
thunderstruck and wondering excitedly what it all meant. At the
very least, a media orgy of unprecedented grossness was going on.
Beyond that, the winds of social history seemed to be blowing in
directions that were simultaneously democratic, sentimental,
Mediterranean, anti-royal, pro-youth, pro-women, modern, cultic _
in a word, un-English, or at least contrary to the picture most of
us have of this country.
</P>
<P>
   I've been back in England for several days now, feasting on the
endless daily papers and reading so many clever pundits who've been
opining on Diana that I think I'll scream if I have to read another
word about her. But one thing is as clear as the lovely late-summer
skies: Britain's pre-Diana mentality has reasserted itself.
</P>
<P>
   Of course the tabloid press is as hysterical and Dianaphilic as
ever _ and as phony in the way it pretends to speak for everyone.
But the more thoughtful media have been quite balanced and
exploratory.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Gallup poll showed that only 6 percent of the British
public planned to mourn for Diana, though majorities still admire
her and want to see a hospital renamed in her honor. Nearly half
consider the Diana thing overblown.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't say her memory has subsided into that of your
garden-variety dead beautiful superstar, but plainly rational
discourse has reasserted itself. It is now common and permissable
(as skeptics felt it was not, a year ago, in the time of the
``grief police'') to ignore Diana, to focus on other stars and news
and tragedies, to express dissent, cynicism, etc. A national auto
safety group has even complained that a ``Go Slow for Diana'' plan
(in which her fans will drive at a snail's pace today) may cause
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Much else around here also strikes me as having reverted to the
muddling, male-run middle way. Prince Charles, deep in the doghouse
last fall, has made a bit of a comeback, while his chilly mother,
Queen Elizabeth, has taken pains to appear more caring and with-it
(her Rolls recently slid up to a McDonald's). The royals have hired
hipper p.r. people, and the pendulum
</P>
<P>
   has swung _ though I'm sure the Windsors still impress even many
monarchists as disappointingly mouldy.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair, for his part, who seemed so in tune
with last year's anguish and hopes (he dubbed Diana ``the people's
princess'' and linked her seamlessly with his ``New Labor'' image
for a ``New Britain''), has gone all quiet and tactful. People like
Blair now imply it's best to be reserved again for ``the boys,''
Charles' and Diana's popular sons.
</P>
<P>
   Diana's briefly heroic brother turned out to be a cad,
reportedly treating his wife even worse than Charles treated Diana.
As for her dead boyfriend's rich Egyptian father, he has been
pushing flaky conspiracy theories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diana fatigue.'' ``The mourning after.'' ``Ocean of treacle.''
``Candle-in-the wind doggerel.'' ``Vulgar exploitation.'' Those are
typical reflections in the British press these days _ amid many
references, of course, to Diana's smile and flaws and good works.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's flower-mountains and mass interest in Diana were
astounding. Less mountainous, yet still striking, have been this
anniversary's laborious revivals of her story, ``iconography,''
political vibrations, ``legacy,'' victimization, clothes, souvenirs
_ not to mention all the industries that have profited from her,
even in death.
</P>
<P>
   But the tidal wave has obviously passed, and most of Diana's
memorial Sunday supplements have no doubt already been chucked out.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Campbell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
