<DOCNO> NYT19980830.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9583 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN-SCIENCE-COX     08-30 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-SCIENCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glenn's upcoming mission likely to be long on nostalgia,
scientific discovery
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - At T-minus two months to the space shuttle launch
of Sen. John Glenn, the scientific value of his mission seems
likely to remain dwarfed by the romance of a first-generation space
hero's historic return.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and advocates cannot help emphasizing the adventure of
the 77-year-old Glenn's return to space over the possibility that
experiments done on him in orbit could offer clues to the human
aging process.
</P>
<P>
   Even NASA Administrator Dan Goldin admits he was thrilled by the
prospect of letting the first American in orbit go back up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that this nation owes Sen. Glenn his second flight,''
Goldin said. ``This man is an outstanding pilot and astronaut.
Science is one aspect, giving him his second flight is the other.
One doesn't outweigh the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldin insisted that Glenn's experiments be peer-reviewed and
declared ``cutting-edge'' research worthy of a place on the space
shuttle, but at the same time he was exhilarated by the symbolic
power of flying a national icon who is edging near 80. ``It shows
that NASA still has the courage to do bold things. I'm excited
about the fact we take on the tough tasks. I think it's a statement
that we're a vital agency that's willing to explore. Very, very
important.''
</P>
<P>
   The science itself isn't expected to say anything bold. The
National Institutes of Health, and its subset, the National
Institute on Aging, convened a pair of conferences last year to
evaluate Glenn's proposal and agreed that studying an elderly man
in microgravity would be a worthwhile experiment. But not because
they're hoping for some earth-shattering results that might unlock
the mysteries of growing old.
</P>
<P>
   It will be months before any results are known, and perhaps
years before any meaning can be discerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody except the insiders will take note of the scientific
results,'' said John Logsdon, director of the Space Policy
Institute at George Washington University, and a proponent of
Glenn's flight.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Sprott, who as associate director of the Biology of
Aging department in the NIA was instrumental in evaluating the
worth of Glenn's space mission, said the best anyone can hope for
is something unusual. If Glenn's body reacts the same as those of
younger astronauts then scientists may be left with a ``where do we
go from here?'' problem. But if some part of Glenn's body, from his
bones to his muscles to his cardiovascular system, does not weaken
the way they do in younger space travelers, then the experts could
have a strong signal for where to devote their attention.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Sprott said the Glenn flight will have been
extremely valuable to geriatric science. For the public relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago it was difficult to get 20 people in a room to
take it seriously,'' said Sprott, who left NIA recently to become
director of the Ellison Medical Foundation, which specializes in
elderly research. ``This gets the whole issue enough attention to
start having aging taken seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all that attention is positive. Critics of the
science, many of whom support Glenn's flight anyway, call the
studies a `fig leaf' excuse for letting Ohio's senior senator have
another space ride after years of devoted public service in which
he amassed formidable Washington clout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there any reasonable expectation that medical care is going
to change from this?'' said John Pike, director of space policy for
the Federation of American Scientists. ``Almost certainly no.''
</P>
<P>
   Pike, who supports Glenn's flight for its heroic value, said
sending just one elderly man into space for a few days isn't
``completely bogus,'' but it's not realistic to think ``this is
going to be good for little old ladies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Real science doesn't work like that. It is infinitely more
incremental than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprott is indifferent to such criticism. ``I don't really feel
bad about the science,'' he said, ``recognizing that we're dealing
with'' the first subject.
</P>
<P>
   He joins Logsdon in the view that Glenn's involvement in the
space program is worth the public relations bonanza, even if the
science remains shadowed by Glenn himself. Logsdon said the
scientific effort is a ``plausible'' use of NASA resources that can
withstand the scrutiny of vast public attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will stand up as well as it has stood up so far,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of the debate, Glenn stays steadfastly focused on the
scientific purpose of his flight. Even if everyone else talks about
the unparalleled public attention NASA now enjoys. He acknowledges
that his trip could change the way the elderly are viewed, but that
is as much as he's willing to contemplate outside the scientific
realm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe that what I'm doing on this will be the toe
in the door that opens up a whole new area of research for NASA
into the future that they haven't been into before,'' Glenn said in
an interview earlier this summer. ``I see myself as part of that
scientific cutting edge, in a new area.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA has long known that astronauts exhibit the same general
degradation of their bodies after prolonged weightlessness that is
the hallmark of growing old on earth. Though, for young astronauts
the changes reverse upon returning from space. But it was Glenn
who, upon learning of this, pressed NASA to send him into space to
see if an already aged body continues to weaken after nine days in
weightlessness.
</P>
<P>
   So, did NASA consider sending just any elderly man?
</P>
<P>
   No, Goldin admits.
</P>
<P>
   And as Glenn's old friends from Project Mercury, America's first
manned space program, say, no one else would have made this flight
happen. It took Glenn's name and his muscle as a senator to get
NASA even to look at it. But all that is good.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think we were going to the moon,'' for all the
attention, said original astronaut Wally Schirra, 75. ``But the
space program needs it desperately, not to go to Mars, just to keep
public interest in the space shuttle.''
</P>
<P>
   Schirra, who spent 11 days in orbit during Apollo's first manned
mission in 1968 and has no desire to go back, said the science is
``not as significant as the publicity,'' but said having Glenn go
up is a good start on the study of aging and weightlessness.
</P>
<P>
   The two other surviving Mercury astronauts agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the surface it makes good sense,'' said Scott Carpenter,
71, who was Glenn's backup for the first orbital flight in 1962.
``We have an awful lot of baseline data on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter, who has jokingly offered to be Glenn's back up again
``though I'm sure he'd break a leg this time,'' said the science
``is not a fig leaf.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he added, ``it will be a good trip for John. Naysayers
are like vandals. They have always existed in the face of
scientific endeavor and imagination, but by and large they are
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Cooper, 73, another of the Mercury Seven who echoed
Carpenter's pleasure in seeing Glenn fly again, said science
experiments are always open to debate before they've been done. And
the same is true of space flights. He said the parallels between
growing old and being in space for extended periods is a topic ``it
certainly doesn't hurt to look'' at.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know,'' he said. ``We may find out something really
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
