<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9585 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TITANIC-FRENZY-COX     08-30 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TITANIC-FRENZY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stores will throw parties as the wraps come off Titanic
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rose: ``I don't see what all the fuss is about.''
</P>
<P>
   Cal: ``You may be blase about many things, Rose. But not
Titanic!''
</P>
<P>
   (Kate Winslet, Billy Zane in an opening scene from ``Titanic'')
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Blase? Please. They haven't yet invented the word for
how opposite of blase this all is.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: Blockbuster never extends its store hours, but that
all changes at 12:01 a.m. Tuesday, when ``Titanic'' finally comes
out on video and the huge chain's metro Atlanta stores stay open
for business and partying till 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Media Play in Alpharetta, Ga. is staying open for an
unprecedented 36 straight hours to sell ``Titanic.'' But stragglers
beware. By Tuesday evening, the stock could be depleted, and, even
more tragic, the ``My Heart Will Go On'' karaoke contest will be
long over.
</P>
<P>
   Best Buy in Duluth, Ga. has 2,500 copies of the Winslet-Leonardo
DiCaprio weeper to sell _ and no real idea of how long that initial
supply will last. Like all the big chains, Best Buy encouraged
buyers to reserve copies, but will sell the two-cassette package to
anyone as long as stock holds out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can process that many customers, I expect to sell them
all the first day,'' said general manager Bill Smith. ``I expect
them to be lined up to get in when we open.''
</P>
<P>
   What, no women and children first?
</P>
<P>
   ``Only if Leo's going to come to our house and smooch her on the
cheek,'' said Marietta, Ga.'s Mary Schaffer with a laugh, pointing
to her 11-year-old daughter, Shauna. ``Then maybe I'll go stand in
line at Blockbuster at midnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember life before ``Titanic''? OK, then, remember way, way
back last winter, when the biggest concern anyone had was scoring a
ticket to the biggest movie of all time? The film was long (three
hours plus, meaning fewer daily showings), the fans intensely loyal
_ Shauna and her twin brother, Derek, have seen it a combined 15
times, for instance _ and the theaters, it seemed, were always
full.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's video release brings some promise of relief _ plus a
whole boatload of new concerns. Priced to buy at $19.99 to $24.99
in most stores, ``Titanic'' may still be out of allowance reach of
its core audience of Leonardo-loving girls. (It's a scientific
fact: A recent survey of girls ages 8 to 15 rated him the person
they'd most like to crash their slumber party.)
</P>
<P>
   But what if the rental supplies run out?!
</P>
<P>
   ``Blockbuster has a guarantee that you can rent it,'' Lindsey
Gall, 12, said with absolute certitude. ``If I can sneak out, I can
walk over there at midnight 'cuz I live close.''
</P>
<P>
   She was kidding, of course. But only about the sneaking out
part. Blockbuster has indeed made that guarantee, which is great,
but even better . . .
</P>
<P>
   Even better . . . ``a smart buyer could make out like a bandit
on this thing,'' said Allen Auchenpaugh, general manager of Media
Play in Alpharetta.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there's the Kate-and Leo-festooned GiftCard, good for $5
off subsequent transactions, that Blockbuster offered purchasers
who reserved a video early. The free ``Titanic'' calendar (trust
us, real Leo fans will never want to leave February) that Best Buy
dangled before potential buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Titanic'' whistles, just like the one Rose blew on while
bobbing amidst the frozen bodies, that will go to a limited number
of Media Play customers after midnight. Or the sweepstakes entries
(the grand prize is a cruise anywhere in the world) each
Blockbuster store will award to the first 100 customers between
midnight and 2 a.m. Some would-be purchasers especially fretted
over the reservation issue. Did they really have to plunk down $5
in advance to be assured of getting a copy Tuesday?
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them they should,'' Auchenpaugh said last week, clearly
enjoying all this Titanicism. ``You don't know what will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   If this all sounds like so much smart marketing _ ``Will there
be enough videos?!'' from the same folks who brought you the ``Will
there be enough lifeboats?!'' movie _ to some extent, it is.
Auchenpaugh, for one, admits that when his Media Play's initial
supply of several thousand videos starts to run low, ``I can get a
(replacement) shipment the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet hype can't exist in a vacuum, anymore than movies can
continue playing to empty theaters. Last week, nine full months
after it was first released on the big screen, ``Titanic'' was
still playing in six metro theaters. One woman in her early 30s has
paid to see it ``at least 45 times,'' confided an employee at
Gwinnett County's Venture Mall Cinema 12.
</P>
<P>
   It's all the stuff of urban legend by now: the unidentified
metro Atlanta resident who's supposedly seen ``Titanic'' every
single day since it opened. The youngster who Xeroxed the words to
``My Heart Will Go On'' and made everyone on the school bus sing
``Titanic's'' theme song. The boys who essentially hijacked their
carpool driver when she wouldn't stop incessantly blasting that
Celine Dion ballad on her CD player.
</P>
<P>
   The 11-year-old twins who are determined to see ``Titanic'' 10
times each before it leaves area theaters. Oops, that one's
verifiable. Derek Schaffer likes the story line, as well as the
acting. So does Shauna. But like practically every other young girl
in America, Shauna also really likes DiCaprio. Enough to have 28
photos of him decorating her bedroom. Enough to make Derek
half-groan, while sitting on a bench in a nearby mall with Shauna
and their friend, Lindsey Barwick: ``She's trying to put them in
the car.''
</P>
<P>
   But not enough, apparently, to put him off the movie. You may be
blase about many things. But not Titanic. And especially not
``Titanic'' on video.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to buy it so we can watch it every day,'' Derek
said urgently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two hundred times,'' Shauna added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day for a lifetime,'' Lindsey sighed happily.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we need,'' Derek confided, ``is Mom to drive to the video
store.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
