<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Retailer Blames Consultant for 2000 Computer Glitch
</P>
<P>
   In one of the first instances in which a company has tried to
blame consultants or computer vendors for installing a system that
will not recognize dates after Dec. 31, 1999, the apparel retailer
J. Baker is asking Andersen Consulting to reimburse it for the cost
of a computer system installed about 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Andersen has asked a Massachusetts court to rule
that Andersen met its contractual obligations when it installed the
system.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley May Sell Research
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter is expected to announce this week
that it has decided to sell access to research by its stock
analysts to customers of its Discover Brokerage Direct Internet
service. The move will be the first time that any of the major
brokerage firms has given same-day access to research to customers
who do not pay full commissions for their stock trades.
</P>
<P>
   Explosion Rocks Satellite Industry
</P>
<P>
   The Delta 3 rocket that exploded shortly after takeoff on
Wednesday night was a setback for Boeing, which made it, as well as
Hughes Electronics, which made the advanced communications
satellite on board, and Panamsat, which intended to use the
satellite. The accident appeared to slow the pace of the United
States' aerospace industry in its race to become the dominant
global player in the market for commercial satellite launchings.
</P>
<P>
   A Scarcity of Technology Managers
</P>
<P>
   Start-up companies and venture capital funds are struggling to
find and lure top executives, especially to Silicon Alley in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Deal Reached for Football Ad Rates
</P>
<P>
   The four networks that broadcast pro football games wanted to
increase the cost of commercial time by 25 percent or more this
season, but advertisers balked. The healthy give and take between
the two industries has resulted in a compromise, and the increases
the networks asked for were held to an estimated 8 percent to 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   MTV Returns to Its Musical Roots
</P>
<P>
   Judy McGrath, the president of MTV, began refocusing the network
about a year ago, and the additional emphasis on music is paying
off. MTV has seen its Nielsen ratings jump 22 percent in the second
quarter from the corresponding period of 1997, and analysts are
forecasting ad growth of about 20 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Few Buyers for Major TV Networks
</P>
<P>
   Rumors about the sale of CBS or NBC are heard often, but despite
the glamour of owning these networks, the roster of potential
buyers is small.
</P>
<P>
   Patent for a Plain-Talking Invention
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Dahlgren, a computational linguist, and her colleague,
Edward Stabler, say that they have built an Internet search engine,
dubbed Inquizit, based on natural-language searching, which means
that it retrieves and stores information in much the way that
people talk.
</P>
</TEXT>
