<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: FEW BIDDERS FOR NETWORKS DESPITE GOOD CURB APPEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hardly a week goes by without a new rumor of an imminent sale or
merger involving CBS Corp.'s television business or General
Electric's network, NBC.
</P>
<P>
   The president of CBS, Mel Karmazin, who announced a partial
spinoff of the company's radio and outdoor advertising businesses
last week, is looking for ways to lift the share price of CBS in
the face of widespread investor pessimism about the future of
television. NBC's president, Robert Wright, has already said his
company is looking for new revenue opportunities for its
programming, including joint ventures with cable programmers.
</P>
<P>
   And though both Karmazin and Wright say they intend to hang onto
their networks, the future of the broadcast networks appears
uncertain with broadcast programming costs on the rise and
audiences continuing to defect to cable _ hence the sale rumors.
Only ABC, still being digested by Walt Disney Co., seems immune
from such speculation.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the merger talk, why has no bidder emerged so far?
Certainly there is at least one interested party with an obvious
strategic incentive for owning a broadcast network: Barry Diller's
USA Networks. And three other big media companies _ Sony, Time
Warner and Viacom _ might have their own reasons for buying one.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the glamour of owning such powerful companies, the
roster of potential buyers is small.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are new advantages ever since the Federal Communications
Commission allowed network companies to own their programming and
share in the sale of rerun rights,'' said David Londoner, an
analyst at Schroder &AMP; Co. ``In this market, everybody talks to
everybody else. And sure, anyone would love to buy them at the
right price. But you could drive a truck between the bid and the
ask.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Anderson, president of the Yankee Group, a consulting
firm in Boston, added: ``Owning networks ain't what it used to be.
When the prime-time players had 85 percent of the prime-time
audience, you were buying into a monopoly. Now they are at 50
percent market share. There is sticker shock over advertising
prices. And the Internet is eating away at the youth market.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Anderson said, ``companies have proven that they
can launch their own networks for far less money.''
</P>
<P>
   Both NBC and CBS own television stations and operate programming
businesses, while NBC also owns the CNBC cable network and the
MSNBC cable network in a partnership with Microsoft. But while TV
stations and cable services generate large amounts of cash,
broadcast networks typically yield profit margins of only about 10
percent at best. And at worst, as in the current environment, CBS
is losing money and NBC is expected to see a drop in profits in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   For purely financial players in the media industry, like Hicks,
Muse, Tate &AMP; Furst, the growth potential of a network is too
limited and the risk too great to justify the price. Either CBS or
NBC and their businesses might cost close to $10 billion _ or
roughly 18 times cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   That would seem to leave strategic buyers or partners like USA
Networks, Viacom, Sony and Time Warner. Yet each faces different
obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   USA's chairman, Diller, has already sought a merger deal with
NBC. USA owns some television stations, a home-shopping service and
the USA and Sci-Fi cable channels. And as a result of the venture
struck this year with Seagram Corp., USA owns Seagram's Universal
television production business, and Seagram owns 44 percent of USA.
</P>
<P>
   NBC in particular would assure Diller that Universal's
television shows would get distribution on its network, which has
been the prime-time leader for the last four years. An NBC deal
would also add to USA's stature in the cable industry because of
NBC's cable services.
</P>
<P>
   But Diller is no longer entirely the master of his own fate.
Seagram's chairman, Edgar Bronfman Jr., objected to a deal that
would have diluted Seagram's USA stake, and Diller himself
reportedly had concerns about the price. And though Diller
undoubtedly would still welcome a merger, the 25.2 percent drop in
USA's share price since July 31 must be sobering.
</P>
<P>
   Sony, whose movie studios also make television programs, might
be a logical entrant to the network game. But as a foreign company,
it can own no more than 25 percent of a network, leaving the giant
company a passive minority investor.
</P>
<P>
   As for Viacom and Time Warner, both have taken years to recover
from big mergers: Time Inc. with Warner Communications in 1989 and
Viacom's takeover of Paramount Communications in 1994, which in
each instance resulted in heavy debt that dragged down their share
prices. And while Viacom's Paramount is a leading producer of
television programming, Viacom's fledgling UPN network is already
giving the company a limited broadcast distribution system.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A full-fledged network like CBS would ensure greater
distribution of Paramount's programs, but at a lofty price. And
Viacom has said publicly that it is not interested in buying CBS.
</P>
<P>
   As to an NBC takeover by Viacom, ``I would be shocked at a
deal,'' said John Tinker, a media analyst at Nationsbanc Montgomery
Securities. ``It would hurt their stock because the whole corporate
theme has been focusing on de-leveraging and improving the bottom
line.''
</P>
<P>
   And what of Time Warner, whose television programming operations
include the Warner Brothers studios? A company spokesman said on
Friday that his company was not interested in acquiring or merging
with a network company. Certainly any merger would be difficult
because Time Warner, as an operator of cable systems, cannot own
television stations _ although Time Warner could spin off the
stations or simply buy the network portion. But that does not rule
out some type of joint venture. One theory floating around Wall
Street would have Time Warner's CNN and a broadcast network combine
their costly news operations, generating savings that some experts
estimate as high as $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   And as Dennis Leibowitz, an analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette, put it: ``Time Warner is the only one that could afford
to buy the network without the stations since it would provide
guaranteed distribution for Warner Brothers television programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner Brothers does, of course, own a fledgling broadcast
system, the WB network. But ``to the extent that a network is a
platform for programming, Time Warner could get more value from CBS
or NBC than from the WB network,'' Leibowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Where does all this leave the potential sellers?
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, when Karmazin, announced that CBS would spin off 20
percent of its radio and outdoor advertising businesses, he
insisted that he wanted to keep CBS's television business. Still,
many on Wall Street think he would welcome a sale if he could get
the right price.
</P>
<P>
   And one person said the spinoff of 20 percent of the radio
company, which would make it easier to determine the market value
of the entire radio business and _ by interpolation _ of the
television operation, could make it easier to set a price.
</P>
<P>
   As for NBC, in the view of at least one media expert, GE's
chairman, John Welch, should have sold a year ago, before the
network lost ``Seinfeld'' and was laden with the $850 million
expense of ``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't want to sell in part because of the glamour
quotient,'' the media expert speculated. ``But maybe when he is
finally ready to sell, the same glamour factor will undoubtedly
help convince a buyer to step in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
