u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-REPUBS-NYT &LR;      08-30 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO COMPANIES ACCUSED OF PROMISING GOP SENATORS AD MONEY FOR
VOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department is reviewing whether tobacco
companies promised some Senate Republicans that they would pay for
television advertisements if the senators voted to defeat the
tobacco bill.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisements were not to have been direct endorsements of
the senators, but were meant to explain the tobacco issue in a way
that might provide the senators with ``political cover'' for their
vote, said a complaint filed with the Federal Election Commission
by an advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.C., the minority leader, received a letter
dated Aug. 17 from the Justice Department confirming that it was
reviewing charges that several companies violated federal election
law, his spokeswoman, Ranit Schmelzer, said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The allegation that tobacco companies may have promised
favorable political advertising in exchange for senators' votes on
specific legislation raises separate concerns under bribery and
gratuity statutes,'' Anthony Sutin, an Assistant Attorney General,
wrote to Daschle. ``The criminal division is presently examining
this allegation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutin's letter was first reported by The Baltimore Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle raised concerns about the tobacco companies' offer in a
letter to the Justice Department on July 2, after he learned of the
complaint by the Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids, an advocacy group
based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department spokesman Michael Gordon acknowledged that
the department was ``looking at the concerns raised in Senator
Daschle's letter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call it an investigation yet,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Williams, a spokesman for the tobacco industry, said
Sunday that the accusations were ``without merit'' and that the
tobacco companies had run only ``substantive'' advertisements. No
money has been spent on advertisements for candidates, Williams
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus of our ads has been to deliver a substantive
message, not a political one,'' he said. ``These are straight
advocacy ads that talk about excise tax increases and black market
cigarettes and other ramifications of the McCain bill.'' Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., was the tobacco bill's lead sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   On June 29, the Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids, which supported
this year's tobacco legislation, filed a report with the Federal
Election Commission accusing the tobacco industry of violating
campaign laws.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint, which was based on news articles, including a
Wall Street Journal report, said that on June 17, hours before the
Senate took a critical vote on the tobacco bill, Sen. Mitch
McConnell of Kentucky, who heads the Republican senatorial campaign
committee, held a private meeting with the Republican senators
present.
</P>
<P>
   At that meeting, the complaint says, McConnell told senators
that the industry was promising to run advertisements that gave
``political cover'' to senators who voted to kill the legislation.
The bill, which would have raised the price of cigarettes by $1.10
a pack, was defeated after the Senate fell three votes short of the
60 votes needed to cut off debate.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint also stated that the tobacco industry had expanded
its $40 million television advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisements could violate federal election law that bars
corporations from making direct contributions to a candidate's
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Issue ads cross the line into electoral politics when it's
done with any degree of coordination or cooperation with the
candidate,'' said Matt Myers, a lawyer for the Campaign for
Tobacco-Free Kids. ``The promise to run them to provide political
cover stripped the veneer of any claim that these were just issue
ads.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Steurer, McConnell's press secretary, said Sunday, ``What
Senator McConnell said was a statement of the obvious: that the
companies would continue to fight for their interests, and they
have.''
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to the Justice Department, Daschle stated that the
complaint filed by Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids ``makes a
persuasive case that this next phase of advertising is solely
intended to affect the outcome of federal elections, not public
policy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
