</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNSCREEN-LEGEND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    E-mail myth: Sunscreen won't cause blindness
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Did you hear the one about the kid who went blind
after getting sunscreen in his eyes?
</P>
<P>
   Well, it didn't happen. At least not from what anyone can tell.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other ``urban legends'' _ startling fictional yarns
just plausible enough to be repeated as fact _ this one gained
currency via the Internet. A letter that's being e-mailed around
the Net purports to be written by a concerned, but unnamed, parent.
</P>
<P>
   The letter writer says his 2-year-old son, Zack, went through an
ordeal after he got sunscreen in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The ``parent'' says water didn't flush out the lotion because
the sunscreen was waterproof. Zack was rushed to an emergency room,
the letter says, where ``special medications'' were used to flush
out his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The letter goes on to say that every year, many kids lose their
sight to waterproof sunscreen. Poor Zack lost his for two days.
</P>
<P>
   The American Association of Poison Control Centers in Washington
has received numerous calls and e-mails about the warning. Last
month it alerted local poison control centers to the hoax.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Gorman, assistant director of Georgia Poison Control, said
she wasn't shocked to learn about the e-mail, but she was
disappointed that people would believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reassured everyone that they don't need to worry,'' Gorman
said.
</P>
<P>
   One place where the bogus story landed is the Dunwoody, Ga.
KinderCare Learning Center, a day care. Management there, however,
was not convinced the story was real.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told a few parents, but we didn't post it,'' said Michele
Mitchell, assistant director.
</P>
<P>
   The Cosmetic, Toiletry and Fragrance Association confirmed that
the sunscreen scare ``is an unsubstantiated story.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no evidence, scientific or otherwise, that any such
harmful effects have ever resulted from the use of sunscreens,''
the trade group said. ``Sunscreens are safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
