</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More questions than answers surround Louchiey move
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Falcons cut their roster to the
NFL-mandated 53 players Sunday, and by putting Corey Louchiey on
injured reserve with a dubious groin injury, the team left itself a
big question: Which rookie is going to play right tackle in
Sunday's opener at Carolina?
</P>
<P>
   The team also reached an injury settlement with veteran
linebacker Eddie Sutter, and waived undrafted rookie defensive
lineman Ben Huff.
</P>
<P>
   The move with Louchiey is most significant, and means more
roster moves are possible.
</P>
<P>
   Right tackle was an offseason priority, and the team gave
Louchiey a two-year, $3.5 million contract after he started 13
games in three years for Buffalo. But he missed the first two
preseason games, and played poorly the last two.
</P>
<P>
   By going on IR, Louchiey becomes ineligible to play for the
Falcons this season, and leaves Atlanta nine offensive linemen _
one less than coach Dan Reeves has said he wanted to keep.
</P>
<P>
   It also means rookie Ephraim Salaam, a 6-foot-7, 298-pound
seventh-round draft choice, or undrafted rookie Jose Portilla (6-6,
320) probably will become the only rookie to start at Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever doesn't start becomes the only backup tackle. Reeves
said 10-year veteran lineman Dave Widell, the backup center, would
not move to tackle.
</P>
<P>
   That's why team officials were scouring waiver wires Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ''We may do something,'' Reeves said. ''A lot depends on who's
available. ''It'll probably be Eprhaim (who starts). He worked real
hard. He showed athleticism. And most of the negative things he did
can be corrected.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons wanted to cut Louchiey and Sutter Saturday. But both
players said injuries impaired affected their chances of making the
team. Sutter has been bothered by a hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than risk the players filing grievances, Reeves said,
''We talked to their agents, and this is how it worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Once doctors say Louchiey is healed, the team can waive him, and
he can play for another team.
</P>
<P>
   Half his $500,000 signing bonus counts against this year's
salary cap, and while he is on IR, the Falcons are responsible for
his $500,000 salary, or about $29,412 for every week.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are more than $2.75 million under the cap.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves later this week will announce whether second-year man
Tony Graziani or 44-year-old Steve DeBerg is the No. 2 quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' roster includes nine rookies _ eight of nine draft
choices, and Portilla _ and nine veterans who were not with the
team last year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
