u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEBSITE-PRIVACY-800(2     08-30 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBSITE-PRIVACY-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW FEDERAL WEB SITES OBSERVE U.S. PRIVACY GUIDELINES
</HEADLINE>
   (ll) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When it comes to online privacy, it seems that the
Clinton administration has not been practicing what it preaches.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of the administration's sites on the World Wide
Web post the kinds of privacy guidelines that the Federal Trade
Commission recently criticized businesses for failing to post, and
none of the administration's sites offer the special protections
for children that the government recommends for commercial sites.
</P>
<P>
   Even the White House Web site does not meet the standards
recommended by the FTC and endorsed by the administration.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the White House site collects e-mail addresses _
and in some cases, home addresses _ through links that allow
visitors to send electronic messages to President and Mrs. Clinton
and Vice President Al Gore and Mrs. Gore. Yet, it does not provide
any notice about how that information will be used by the White
House. Nor does the site ask visitors to its special children's
pages to consult their parents before divulging personal
information, as the administration has recommended.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the FTC released a survey of commercial Web sites along
with a report that was highly critical of industries that gather
information online and, without notifying the visitors to their
sites, use or sell the data for marketing purposes. The report's
findings, particularly with respect to children, prompted the FTC
to recommend that Congress pass a law requiring that online
businesses and Web site operators obtain parental permission before
gathering e-mail addresses or other information from children under
the age of 13.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike operators of commercial sites, federal agencies do not
collect or sell personal data for marketing purposes. The issue,
critics say, is more one of leading by example.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a matter of practicing what they preach,'' said
David Banisar, senior policy analyst and staff counsel at the
Electronic Privacy Information Center, a public interest research
group in Washington. ``They have been pushing notice and consent,
and they can't even do it themselves. They really have a dismal
record on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Banisar also pointed out that while the White House might not be
using the information for marketing purposes, the data could be
transferred to the Democratic National Committee or used for other
political ends.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has endorsed child-protection legislation
that was introduced in response to the FTC report. It has also
endorsed new self-regulation guidelines and enforcement procedures
recently proposed by the Online Privacy Alliance, a coalition of
businesses and associations that seeks to foster privacy
protections. Those guidelines call for all Internet businesses to
clearly post policies concerning the use and collection of personal
information, and they require Web site operators to obtain parental
approval before gathering data from children.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite the administration's support for these measures,
the White House Web site collects information from children without
parental notification. Within a special children's section on the
site, a White House tour led by cartoon caricatures of the ``First
Pets,'' Buddy the dog and Socks the cat, ends with an invitation to
send e-mail to President Clinton, Hillary Rodham Clinton or Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The electronic form asks for the sender's name, age, e-mail
address, grade at school, the school's name and, from those
visitors who want a response, a home postal address. The site does
not advise children to ask their parents before divulging that
information.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the Federal Emergency Management Agency has an area
for children, like that of the White House site, that offers the
opportunity to send an e-mail message, yet does not display a
privacy policy or request that children seek parental permission
before giving out e-mail addresses.
</P>
<P>
   The White House Web site provides links to 70 Web sites of
federal agencies, Cabinet departments and White House offices and
commissions. Of those 70 sites, only 12 had posted privacy policies
as of Friday afternoon. That amounts to 17 percent of the sites
surveyed, only slightly better than the 14 percent of commercial
sites that, according to the FTC's report, had clearly posted
privacy policies earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, the vice president's office and Mrs. Clinton's
press office did not respond directly to questions about the Web
sites' lack of a posted privacy policy. But administration
officials stressed that in May, Clinton ordered the Office of
Management and Budget to conduct an agency-by-agency review to
ensure that new technologies were not violating the Privacy Act or
otherwise eroding privacy protections.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Office of Management and Budget said the
agency was drafting guidelines for federal Web sites.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's top adviser on Internet issues, Ira Magaziner, said on
Thursday that the administration was working ``to get its own house
in order.'' Magaziner also noted that unlike the private sector,
government agencies are bound by the Privacy Act to protect
personal data.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are privacy principles being followed,'' Magaziner said.
``And we are taking steps to ensure that government agencies are in
fact in a more visible way confirming that.''
</P>
<P>
   Government departments and agencies _ but not the White House _
must comply with the Privacy Act, which establishes controls over
personal information collected by the federal government. The act
requires that each agency that maintains records on individuals
inform the person whose data are being collected, by notifying the
individual of that fact either on the form that is used to collect
the information or on a separate form that the person can keep.
</P>
<P>
   Ari Schwartz, a policy analyst for the Center for Democracy and
Technology, a Washington advocacy group, said, ``When they collect
specific information about people, they have to give notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a technical violation of the law,'' he added. ``They
should be posting privacy policies.''
</P>
<P>
   The security of online information obtained by them is crucial,
said Kathryn Montgomery, executive director of the Center for Media
Education, a nonprofit organization has been pushing for
legislation to protect both adults and children on line
</P>
<P>
   ``Where government is concerned,'' Ms. Montgomery said, ``we
need to be very, very careful about data collected on line.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Montgomery also emphasized that she saw a clear
distinction between commercial and noncommercial Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``One issue,'' she said, ``is whether we would make a
distinction between commercial enterprises that are collecting
data, selling it and coming back with exploitive personal
advertisements, and noncommercial uses of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the White House has taken a hands-off
approach to Internet commerce, saying that industry should police
itself on issues like consumer privacy. In that arena, the
administration has encouraged online merchants and marketers to
post clearly how the information they collect from consumers is
used and to adopt mechanisms to enforce stated privacy policies.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the FTC has the most prominent privacy policy
of all of the federal Web sites. The agency declined to comment on
the lack of clearly posted policies by other agencies, saying its
jurisdiction _ and its survey _ covered only commercial sites.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz, of the Center for Democracy and Technology, who helped
write a report on federal Web site privacy policies a year ago,
said the government ``generally has been better'' than the private
sector in keeping private information confidential. And most
government Web sites that take applications for things like
volunteers and disaster relief, he said, do post privacy policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's a question of whether all sites in general that
collect personally identifiable information should have privacy
policies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the administration, Schwartz said, ``They should lead by
example.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
