<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: HEALTH-CARE ROAD TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Miss., Pa., Tenn.)  (lb) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two new mobile health vans and a couple of support vehicles will
leave from New York on Monday on an eight-day, nine-state caravan
that sponsors hope will call attention to the plight of millions of
American youngsters who are not getting adequate health care.
</P>
<P>
   International events and the problems plaguing the Clinton
administration have taken the spotlight away from many serious
issues, and children's health care is one of them. There are 74
million youngsters under the age of 18 in the United States. More
than 20 million do not have what advocates describe as reliable
access to comprehensive health care. Eleven million are completely
without health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Irwin Redlener, the president of the Children's Health Fund,
which is sponsoring the caravan, explained how gaps in health care
that may not look particularly serious can have dire consequences.
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``The asthma epidemic we are dealing with in New York
City, which is part of a larger national problem with asthma, is to
a great extent related to the fact that a lot of kids are not
getting an early diagnosis and they are not getting their asthma
managed. They are ending up in droves in emergency rooms, in
hospital beds, and in some cases they are dying.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that last year the White House trumpeted the high
childhood immunization rates that have been achieved nationally.
But what has not been focused on, he said, are ``the pockets of
immunization crisis'' that continue to exist in poor urban and
rural areas, where immunization rates are in the 40 percent to 50
percent range.
</P>
<P>
   ``These children are unprotected against a large number of
vaccine-preventable illnesses,'' Redlener said. ``So they are at
risk for whooping cough, measles, polio _ all those diseases that
one could be protected from with immunization.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also important to understand that, in addition to the
specific risk factor, a low immunization rate is a profoundly
important marker of poor access to health care in general.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``There is also the problem of anemia, especially
iron-deficiency anemia, which is much higher _ double the rate
among poor children, Hispanic kids, African-American kids _ than it
is among most white kids. If you do not have a regular source of
health care, anemia doesn't get diagnosed and then doesn't get
treated. Kids with chronic anemia will have everything from
weakness and fatigue to poor mental and academic functioning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Health Fund was established in the 1980s by
Redlener and the singer-songwriter Paul Simon. Using vans as
rolling clinics, the fund provides medical services for tens of
thousands of poor and often homeless children.
</P>
<P>
   The vans in the caravan are being delivered to programs serving
poor children in Arkansas and Mississippi. Blue and 35 feet long,
they are fully equipped pediatric clinics on wheels. Each has a
pair of examining rooms, waiting areas, nurses' stations and
state-of-the-art computer systems that will contain all of the
records of all of the children who are seen.
</P>
<P>
   In its effort to highlight the needs of medically underserved
children and alert families to health care programs that have only
recently become available, the caravan will make stops in
Philadelphia; Washington; Nashville, Tenn.; Memphis, Tenn.; and
several other locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to make a big thing out of it,'' Redlener said.
``We hope to break through this wall that has hidden from sight a
lot of the issues that affect kids and families, and show people we
still have major issues to confront with children.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal legislation approved last year will provide $24 billion
over five years for health coverage for uninsured children.
Redlener applauded that move and is trying to make as many families
as possible aware of it. But he also noted that millions of
children are not eligible for that program, and many families
``live in medical shortage areas where even with insurance, doctors
and hospitals simply are not available.''
</P>
<P>
   Children without health care can easily find themselves in
devastating trouble. Redlener and others on the caravan hope to
persuade more people to look out for them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
