<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS TRIBUTE DISTRACTS ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Don't get them wrong, the Angels said, Ted Williams
deserved to be honored. It was the timing that bothered them.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the start of the bottom of the fourth inning Sunday,
the Red Sox honored Williams _ watching on TV from his home in
Florida _ by singing happy birthday on his 80th.
</P>
<P>
   What the Angels didn't like is that it took place after pitcher
Jeff Juden was finished making his warmup pitches, forcing him to
wait a few minutes before beginning the inning.
</P>
<P>
   On Juden's second pitch of the inning, Nomar Garciaparra ripped
a home run.
</P>
<P>
   Juden, a Boston native, said he's as big a fan of Williams as
anybody. But he said the timing hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was a little kid out there,'' he said. ``Maybe
they shouldn't have done that. Maybe I should have hit Nomar in the
neck. It was weird, it was definitely a distraction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our pitcher warmed up, then they made him stand out there,''
Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``Then they wouldn't let him
take any more (warmup pitches).''
</P>
<P>
   In command: Shigetoshi Hasegawa has made significant improvement
from last season _ his first in the majors _ to this season. He won
Sunday's game with 31/3 scoreless innings, improving to 7-3 with a
2.85 ERA and impressing his manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he does is make pitches,'' Collins said. ``It's the
age-old question: What does it take to pitch in the big leagues?
It's command of your fastball. He does that, which sets up
everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   One notable adjustment Hasegawa has made is learning to stay
away from the power zone of many American hitters. Hasegawa said in
Japan, power hitters like the ball inside. But in the U.S., the
power hitters like the ball out over the plate so they can extend
their arms.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Hasegawa pitches inside more, and if he misses with a
pitch, it's inside and off the plate.
</P>
<P>
   He still doesn't get the attention the other Japanese pitchers
in the majors receive, but that's OK, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, nobody here,'' he said, referring to the Japanese media.
``(Masato) Yoshi (of the Mets) and (Hideki) Irabu (of the Yankees)
are pitching today.''
</P>
<P>
   More help on the way: The Angels will add a group of players
Tuesday in Cleveland when rosters can be expanded. Expected to join
the club from Triple-A Vancouver will be infielders Justin Baughman
and Chris Pritchett and pitchers Mike Holtz and Jason Dickson.
</P>
<P>
   Activated from Double-A Midland will be catcher Charlie O'Brien,
pitcher Steve Sparks and outfielder Reggie Williams. Sparks and
Williams never actually left the team but needed to be moved off
the roster to make room for Ken Hill and Gregg Jefferies.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Ex-Angel Cecil Fielder is hitting .143 (3 for 21) since
signing with the Indians.... Center fielder Jim Edmonds' X-rays on
his ribs Saturday night were negative, but he didn't start Sunday.
He entered the game on defense in the bottom of the ninth.... On
one side of the Angels clubhouse after Sunday's game, the majority
of the team gathered to watch the end of the Rangers-White Sox
game. On the other side, Tim Salmon watched the USC football game.
Salmon's brother Mike is a former Trojans defensive back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
