<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS BEAT RED SOX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The more the Angels play, the more they look like a
playoff team.
</P>
<P>
   After taking three of five from the Yankees in New York to begin
the trip, they left Boston and headed for Cleveland on Sunday night
having taken two of three from the Red Sox, including Sunday's 8-6
win before 31,476 at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   And they did it on an afternoon when their starting pitcher
couldn't make it out of the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Keyed by a four-run third inning, the Angels gave Jeff Juden a
7-2 lead. But the 6-foot-8 right-hander, a Boston native pitching
at Fenway Park for the first time, allowed a solo homer to Nomar
Garciaparra, a three-run homer to Mo Vaughn and was yanked with two
out in the fifth and a 7-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox did not score again, shut down by Shigetoshi
Hasegawa (31/3 scoreless innings) and Troy Percival (scoreless
ninth for 38th save).
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa (7-3) allowed only two hits, struck out three, did not
walk a batter and lowered his ERA to 2.85.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hasegawa was brilliant,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said.
``He gave us exactly what we needed. He helped us get to Percy. I
really believe you've got to make pitches in this park. One thing I
know Shige can do is make pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of Troy Percival, Hasegawa has been our MVP out of the
bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   With the win and Texas' loss, the Angels increased their lead in
the AL West to three games. Sunday's game was big, they said,
because they're all big this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of them we play from now on out is bigger than the
day before,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Juden, pitching on three days' rest, gave up a triple to Darren
Lewis and home run to John Valentin to start the first inning and
put the Angels in a 2-0 hole.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels got it back in the second when Garret Anderson
hit a two-run homer, wrapping the ball around the right-field foul
pole, an estimated 305 feet from home plate.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, the Angels got a couple of walks from
knuckleballer Tim Wakefield (15-6) to start the inning. Then Darin
Erstad and Tim Salmon had infield dribblers that went for hits,
Salmon's driving in Orlando Palmeiro from third for a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Jefferies (3 for 5) followed with a two-run double and
Anderson had an RBI groundout for a 6-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our best two hitters got a combined distance of 86 feet,''
Collins mused.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're on a roll, you get those breaks,'' Salmon said.
``Those are the things that are going to happen during the season,
but the timing couldn't be better. This is the road trip of the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary DiSarcina had an RBI single in the eighth inning to give
the Angels an 8-6 edge, which Percival surely appreciated. Percival
gave up three runs in the ninth inning Friday, but luckily for him
the Angels had a four-run lead and held on.
</P>
<P>
   Percival said Friday wasn't on his mind when he took the ball in
the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to look back,'' he said. ``I've given up three or
four runs in the past. I want the ball every day. Whether I gave up
three or shut the door the previous time, I want to be back out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning two of three from the Red Sox showed Collins something
he said he was hoping to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real proud of the guys,'' he said. ``One of my biggest
concerns was coming out of New York there'd be a letdown
emotionally. They didn't do that. (Saturday) night after the second
rain delay Pedro (Martinez) was throwing great and we sunk. But we
came out today and needed a big game going into Cleveland.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
