<HEADER>
A9641 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-RDP-530(2TAKES     08-30 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-RDP-530(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PARLIAMENT'S SQUABBLING POLITICIANS MAKE LITTLE PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-U.S. and RUSSIA-ASSESS) 
(js) 
 By Michael Gordon   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ With great fanfare, Kremlin aides and Russian lawmakers
announced a new accord Sunday that would ease the bitter standoff
over power-sharing between President Boris Yeltsin and the
Communist-dominated parliament.
</P>
<P>
   But within a few hours, the much-celebrated breakthrough _ which
was intended to pave the way for Viktor Chernomyrdin's confirmation
as prime minister _ broke down, as the nation's political leaders
squabbled on national television.
</P>
<P>
   With Chernomyrdin's nomination scheduled to come before the
parliament on Monday and U.S. President Bill Clinton set to arrive
for a summit meeting the following day, Russian politics swung from
statesmanship to farce.
</P>
<P>
   Gennady Zyuganov, the Communist leader, set the tone by
declaring in a live debate on the NTV television network that he
had not authorized his party's representative to endorse the accord
in the talks early on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Zyuganov said he did not trust Yeltsin to adhere to the accord
and then declared that he would order party members to vote against
Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole faction will vote against Chernomyrdin,'' Zyuganov
said sternly. ``Mr. Chernomyrdin is an accomplice with Yeltsin in
the destruction of the past years.''
</P>
<P>
   That brought a tart rejoinder from Alexander Shokhin, the leader
of Chernomyrdin's parliamentary faction, who summoned up the
specter of a complete political and economic meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   Shokhin warned ominously that the Communist refusal to approve
Chernomyrdin and back the accord could eventually lead to the
dissolution of the parliament, although the compromise agreement
was intended to preclude just that.
</P>
<P>
   Grigory Yavlinsky, the leader of the liberal Yabloko party,
punctuated the raucous debate by proclaiming that he was ashamed of
Russia's politicians and financial barons for their inability to
exercise a modicum of statesmanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say that I am ashamed about everything I hear around
me now,'' said Yavlinsky, who then insisted on treating the nation
to a lengthy sermon on his own political platform and who said that
he would join Zyuganov in opposing Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   Then the live debate over the future of Russia's economic and
political system was suspended so the network could present a
Sylvester Stallone action film. Live coverage of the debate resumed
in the evening, as the politicians took telephone questions from
skeptical viewers, who have watched helplessly in recent weeks as
Russia's currency has shrunk in value, prices have soared, Yeltsin
has fought off a chorus of demands that he resign and his previous
prime minister, Sergei Kiriyenko, was unceremoniously ousted.
</P>
<P>
   In the helter-skelter world of Russian politics, it was possible
that much of this was posturing and that with a few tweaks and
symbolic concessions, the delicately balanced compromise could be
put back together again.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Chernomyrdin's nomination is defeated in the parliament
on Monday, it might be nothing more than a prelude for more
negotiating over jobs and policy. It took three tries for
parliament to approve Kiriyenko in April.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With Russia's economy spinning out of control, however, the
nation does not appear to have time for politics as usual. Seen
through the filter of Sunday night's television debate, Russia's
political system seemed at times to be on the verge of a nervous
breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   This was not the way the script was supposed to read. With its
currency plunging and its banks slipping into bankruptcy, Russia's
politicians had sought a truce that would enable them to try to put
the nation's house in order.
</P>
<P>
   After days of behind-the-scenes negotiations, they had hoped to
proclaim a kind of nonaggression pact that would guarantee a
measure of political stability over the next 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the parliament would promise not to seek
Yeltsin's impeachment. He would agree, in turn, not to dissolve the
legislature. Chernomyrdin would become prime minister and Yeltsin
would restrain his proclivity for mass firings.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of power-sharing, the accord would have preserved much
of the president's prerogatives. He would have retained his right
to hire and fire the heads of Russia's so-called ``power
ministries,'' the Foreign Ministry, the Defense Ministry and the
Interior Ministry. That would enable the executive branch to
conduct foreign policy and prevent disorder at home.
</P>
<P>
   There would, however, have been some unspecified constitutional
changes. Within a month the parliament was to have drafted
constitutional amendments to shift some power from the executive to
legislative branch.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how this was to be done was unclear, and Vladimir
Zhirinovsky, the nationalist agitator, complained Sunday night that
by the time amendments were written, Yeltsin would have his prime
minister in place and would be free to ignore them.
</P>
<P>
   A new commission was to be set up under the accord to monitor
state-owned television networks, which the Communists complain is
biased against them.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin himself suggested that he did not envision speedy
changes. He said in a recently taped interview that was shown on
television Sunday night that the process of amending the
constitution could take a year _ an eternity in Russian politics.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to promote his candidacy, Chernomyrdin sought to portray
himself as the man to unify the nation during its moment of crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ruble is hanging on a thin thread,'' Chernomyrdin said.
``Time must not be lost. The country cannot function without a
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin's words did little to hide the fact that he has not
presented anything remotely like a plan to extract the nation from
one of its worst financial crises since the collapse of the Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   A poll of 25,000 Russians conducted by the NTV network Sunday
indicated that 90 percent of them did not believe Chernomyrdin, the
once _ and, perhaps, future _ prime minister, would be able to end
the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   While Chernomyrdin was trying vainly to rally the nation, the
roof fell in.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Communists were in disarray as well. In
repudiating the accord, Zyuganov broke with Gennady Seleznyov, the
Communist speaker of parliament, who was among those who heralded
the accord earlier Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the parliament's other left-wing parties _ the
Agrarian Party and People's Power _ said they were stunned by
Zyuganov's decision to turn against the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Ryzhkov, head of People's Power, said Zyuganov's move
was ``not only unexpected but also not understandable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Communists decided to torpedo this document then they
should not have pulled everyone into working on it,'' Ryzhkov
added. ``Many many hours deep into the night were spent on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Boris Berezovsky, the tycoon who has been trying to orchestrate
Chernomyrdin's return to power, expressed confidence that
Chernomyrdin would ultimately be approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my forecast that Chernomyrdin will be prime minister
irrespective of the way the Duma is going to act,'' Berezovsky
said, referring to the Communist-dominated lower house of
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky, however, also could not resist the temptation to
settle some political scores. He denounced Russia's leading free
market reformers _ Yegor Gaidar, a former prime minister;
Kiriyenko; and Anatoly Chubais, who was recently sacked by the
Yeltsin government as the representative to the International
Monetary Fund _ as villains who had carried out economic policy
``by Bolshevik methods.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, for his part, had been expected to endorse the
compromise accord formally on Monday. But after the Communist
flip-flop, it was no longer clear what he would do.
</P>
<P>
   Not all viewers waited through the movie to catch the resumption
of the petulant political debate. Tatyana Ptushkina, a 49-year-old
administrator of a construction company, said she was too appalled
to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was shameful,'' she said. ``No words can describe what I
just saw. I had to leave the room.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
