<HEADER>
A9645 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROWDY-RIVER-RIDERS-AR     08-30 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROWDY-RIVER-RIDERS-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TOWN LOOKS TO TONE DOWN WILD RIVER RAFTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS, Texas _ William Mayo has seen just about
everything from his wooden deck overlooking the oak- and
cypress-shaded Guadalupe River.
</P>
<P>
   Once, two young women in bikinis floated down the river on a
four-poster bed. More than one oversized recliner has bobbed past
carrying a giddy, beer-guzzling vacationer. There was the group
that built an entire wet bar on a raft, including the stools. And
the Swan Lady has been floating down the river for 10 years,
sitting astride a big white swan figure and announcing her presence
by yelling out, ``It's me, the Swan Lady!'' as she is carried along
the brisk current.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time, we had some folks who'd set an entire Early American
sofa on four inner tubes and were floating down the river on it,''
said Mayo, who is the president of the county's Water Oriented
Recreation District, which oversees the recreational uses of the
river. ``I called up my friends downriver and told them to grab a
drink and get outside, because they're not going to believe this
one. Look, it's wonderful. It's inventive. It's weird. That kind of
fun, I can handle all day on the river.''
</P>
<P>
   But other kinds of fun are harder to stomach for some residents
along the Guadalupe around New Braunfels, a city of 27,000 people
30 miles northeast of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Davis, who has lived on the river since 1975, said: ``They
get enough drinking in them and they start taking off their bathing
suits, or trespassing on people's property to go to the bathroom,
or yelling obscenities at people. One neighbor went out in her back
yard and there were two couples out there, you know, making out, if
you know what I mean, and she hollered at them to get back in the
river. It can get pretty raunchy out here at times.''
</P>
<P>
   It has become something of a rite of passage for thousands of
people, many in their late teens and 20s, to spend part of their
scalding summer sitting on rafts or inner tubes and floating down
this bucolic waterway in the Texas Hill Country. On an average
summer weekend, 10,000 to 15,000 will float down the winding
22-mile stretch between Canyon Lake Dam and New Braunfels.
</P>
<P>
   On holiday weekends, the numbers explode. County officials
estimated that over this year's Fourth of July weekend 50,000
people floated along the Guadalupe. One Memorial Day weekend, Mayo
said, the number was 115,000.
</P>
<P>
   On such days, this part of the river, which is about 40 yards
wide, can be an almost endless procession of raucous beer-drinking
parties of people carting coolers, boom boxes and a deep desire to
act up.
</P>
<P>
   The battle to clean up the Guadalupe gathered steam after
residents were outraged by some particularly lewd behavior over the
Fourth of July weekend. Public meetings were convened to decide
what to do about it.
</P>
<P>
   So the Sheriff's Department plans to triple the number of
officers on the river this Labor Day weekend, to 30 from the normal
10, and back them up with 30 more security officers hired just for
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents are demanding that the county ban all alcohol on
the river, a proposal that has upset the sensibilities of some
Texans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had public meetings with 350 homeowners, and I think
two-thirds of them are clearly in favor of banning alcohol,'' said
the county judge, Carter Casteel. ``The other third just say, look,
increased law enforcement can handle the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayo, who has lived on the Guadalupe for 16 years, said he did
not think banning alcohol was the answer and contended that such a
step would discourage many tourists from using the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``You simply cannot enforce it on 22 miles of river,'' he said.
``This country already tried banning alcohol once, during
Prohibition. It wasn't very effective, and it won't work any better
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayo asserts that a big part of the problem is caused by
homeowners who stalk into the river and confront the rowdy tubers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're getting in these people's faces and telling them their
bathing suits are too skimpy or something, and it becomes a
psychological thing,'' he said. ``It makes people act up even more.
Let's face it, nobody buys property on the Guadalupe River
expecting Walden Pond.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Recreational rafting down the Guadalupe did not begin until the
Canyon Lake Dam was built in the early 1960s, turning the stretch
of river below the dam into a vista of cliffs and tree-thick banks.
</P>
<P>
   Problems on the river have been cyclical, Casteel said. In the
early 80s, cars blocked the narrow River Road, but a parking ban
solved that problem. By the early 90s the issue was litter, a
situation that has been somewhat improved by handing out plastic
mesh bags to tubers and banning glass, Styrofoam and polystyrene
containers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Casteel said, the locals will have to find a way to stop
rowdiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The river is nothing but a reflection of our society, in some
regards,'' the judge said. ``You know, do your own thing, get drunk
and nobody's going to say anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow,'' she added, ``we've given that impression as a
society that it's OK to act like that. But you know what? I'm not
sure we can solve society's problems on the Guadalupe River.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
