<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American League Week in Review
 &HT;    (EDS: Due to this story moving early to the wires, updating
outstanding games may be necessary.)
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Yankees 4-3 (98-36), Blue Jays 5-2 (71-66), Red Sox
3-3 (79-55), Devil Rays 4-3 (53-84), Orioles 0-5 (69-66).
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: Yankees starter David Wells spent $75,000 on
three dozen diamond rings he presented to his teammates, coaches
and owner George Steinbrenner in recognition for his perfect game.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: The Yankees have scored 823 runs, that's 46 more
than the next club (Texas) and 320 more than expansion Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: The Yankees have three pitchers _David Cone,
Wells and Andy Pettitte _ with 15 wins or more for the first time
since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Toronto's Dave Stieb, who is 41, won for the
first time since 1993, beating the Twins 14-7 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Toronto's Pat Hentgen missed his start Saturday
because of tendinitis in his right shoulder, ending a string of 183
consecutive starts.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: The Red Sox would like to give pitcher Bret
Saberhagen a new deal that will guarantee him at least $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's happening this week: Cone has gone 92 straight starters
without back-to-back losses, the fifth-longest streak this century.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Royals 4-2 (63-73), White Sox 4-3 (60-75), Indians
3-3 (74-61), Twins 2-4 (59-76), Tigers 2-5 (52-84).
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: Twins veteran Paul Molitor collected his 600th
double, joining Ty Cobb and Honus Wagner as the only players in
history to reach 3,000 hits, 600 doubles and 500 stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Indians first baseman Richie Sexson, filling in
for the injured Jim Thome, hit two homers Saturday and one Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: The White Sox have the worst ERA in the league
at 5.35.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: The White Sox and Rangers tied a league record
Friday night by combining for 14 homers in a doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Royals outfielder Shane Mack continues to be
bothered by a bulging disc in his neck.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: Tigers owner Mike Ilitch praised general manager
Randy Smith for his work this season but had less glowing comments
about manager Buddy Bell.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's happening this week: The Indians need to get hot or
will likely end up playing the Yankees in the first round if
Cleveland's record is worse than the team that wins the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   WEST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: A's 3-3 (63-74), Angels 5-3 (76-62), Mariners 2-4
(61-73), Rangers 4-2 (72-63).
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The Angels acquired outfielder Gregg Jefferies
from the Phillies for a player to be named as their lead in the
division has been trimmed to three games.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Ken Griffey Jr. emerged from his homer drought
with five in the last eight days, including two Sunday. The A's
have 50 hits over their last three games.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: He may have only 10 wins, but Anaheim's Chuck
Finley has the third-best ERA in the league at 3.04.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: The Mariners have decided to move Paul
Spoljaric to the rotation for the rest of the season and may use
him there next year.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Angels outfielder Jim Edmonds continues to be
bothered by a strained muscle in his upper back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: The Mariners have hit 200 or more homers in three
straight seasons, making them the first major league team to do so.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's happening this week: The Angels open the week in
Cleveland and then come home for three with Kansas City. The
Rangers are at Detroit and then back at home against the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
