<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NL-WEEK31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National League Week in Review
 &HT;    (EDS: Due to this story moving early to the wires, updating
outstanding games may be necessary.)
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Braves 4-2 (90-46), Mets 3-3 (75-61), Marlins 2-5
(47-90), Phillies 2-5 (66-71), Expos 2-5 (53-85).
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The Mets gave up on their plan to convert Todd
Hundley into an outfielder and placed him on the disabled list. He
was experiencing irritation in his surgically repaired right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: In his return to Dodger Stadium, Mets catcher
Mike Piazza hit a homer and scored the winning run Friday in a 5-4
win over the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Braves left-hander Tom Glavine picked up his
18th win, the first in the league to reach that mark.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: The Marlins are 0-26 against Cincinnati, San
Francisco and Milwaukee but 4-3 against the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The Braves placed outfielder Danny Bautista on
the disabled list with a partially torn medial collateral ligament
in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: Saturday's loss was the 89th for the Marlins, the
most ever for a defending World Series champion.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's happening this week: It's Greg Maddux against Houston's
Randy Johnson on Wednesday at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Reds 6-1 (65-72), Astros 5-1 (86-51), Cubs 5-3
(75-62), Pirates 3-3 (64-71), Brewers 2-4 (64-72), Cardinals 1-4
(63-72).
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The Reds extended the contract of manager Jack
McKeon through the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Chicago's Sammy Sosa has pushed his home run
total to 54, even with Cardinals first baseman Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Astros starter Jose Lima has won six straight.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: The Brewers have gone 72 straight games
without throwing a complete game. That's two short of a league
record, set in 1977 by the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The Cubs placed Jeff Blauser on the DL with a
right elbow irritation.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: The Television Shopping Network has offered
$250,000 to the fan who catches the baseball that breaks the Roger
Maris home run record. Of course, the fan will have to turn over
the ball.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's happening this week: The next time he steals a base,
Pittsburgh's Jason Kendall will become just the 11th catcher ever
to steal 20 in a season.
</P>
<P>
   WEST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Padres 5-2 (88-49), Giants 4-3 (73-64), Rockies 3-4
(63-75), Dodgers 3-3 (67-69), Diamondbacks 3-3 (52-85).
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The wild-card race keeps getting crazier as
three teams (Giants, Cubs and Mets) are two games within each
other.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Colorado's Larry Walker and Dante Bichette are
tied with the Mets' John Olerud for the league lead in hitting with
a .342 average.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Padres left-hander Sterling Hitchcock struck out
a club-record 15 Saturday in a 3-1 loss to the Expos.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: San Diego starter Andy Ashby is falling out of
the Cy Young race, allowing 16 runs in his last two starts.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Padres outfielder Tony Gwynn is eligible to come
off the DL but will rest his injured Achilles tendon for at least a
few more days.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: Word is Dodgers president Dan Garziano would like
to hire Braves executive Dean Taylor as his new general manager.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's happening this week: Beginning today, the Giants host
the Phillies, the Mets go to Los Angeles and Chicago gets the Reds
at Wrigley.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
