<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-LB ZAMANO MAY RETURN IN '99
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Two years after nearly losing his leg, former UCLA
linebacker Anselmo Zamano is walking without a limp and considering
a return to football.
</P>
<P>
   He's not ready yet. But next year, the unthinkable could become
reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the injury he had, he's done fantastically well,'' UCLA
surgeon Gerald Finerman said. ``If he's able to recover his speed
to where he can contribute, then we'll have to look (at getting
clearance for Zamano's return). He's much, much further along than
I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter of a 1996 loss at Michigan, Zamano severed
the artery behind his right knee _ cutting circulation and forcing
emergency surgery to stabilize the leg. In addition, Zamano ripped
all ligaments and cartilage in the knee. The only thing keeping his
lower leg attached was skin.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Zamano wouldn't return, the Bruins placed him on the
medically retired list _ a means of keeping him on financial aid
without counting him against the 85-scholarship limit. For Zamano
to return, UCLA must petition the NCAA for reinstatement.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did was in fair intent, so I don't think that will be
a problem,'' Finerman said of a possible petition. ``From where he
was, in need of vascular repair, we didn't think he could return.''
</P>
<P>
   Zamano, a Fontana native, is trying to temper his enthusiasm
while increasing his weight and running workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's looking great,'' Zamano said. ``But we'll have to see how
it responds to lateral movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodbye, byes: The Bruins open Sept. 12 against Texas _ later
than any team in the Pacific-10 _ and play 11 consecutive weeks,
culminating with USC on Nov. 21.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time since 1992 they do not have a bye. That
year, they also started on the 12th and ended Nov. 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're healthy it's good because you get in a rhythm and
go,'' coach Bob Toledo said. ``If you have a lot of byes and start
early, it's a long season.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas tickets: UCLA expects a crowd of more than 70,000 for the
opener. The first 10,000 fans entering through tunnels on the east
(sun) side will receive a visor and bottle of water.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason to arrive early: the Arroyo Seco is not a model
for traffic flow, as the Washington game (86,000 spectators) proved
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Parking is available outside the Arroyo at the Parsons
Engineering Building in Pasadena (shuttle service to the stadium)
and inside the Arroyo at the Brookside Golf Course.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
