<SLUG> BC-NORTHWEST-STRIKE-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHWEST SAYS FINAL OFFER REALLY IS FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NORTHWEST-DAKOTA, moved in ``a'' category.) 
(lb) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Setting the stage for what could be a long
standoff, Northwest Airlines said Sunday that it would not alter
the dollar value of the final offer it made to its pilots before
they walked off the job on Saturday and grounded the carrier's
1,700 daily flights.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest's management seems resolved to stand firm because, in
addition to its 6,200 pilots, the airline is embroiled in contract
negotiations with about 45,000 other union workers, including its
maintenance crews, customer-service agents and flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality of this is once the union goes on strike, the
company can't really move from its last tabled position,'' said
Richard Hirst, chief labor negotiator for Northwest, which has its
headquarters near here. ``If we do, we will have to take strikes in
every other contract negotiation. We have to draw a line in the
sand.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the pilots are equally determined to obtain an
``industry-leading contract'' from the company, the walkout could
last longer than the brief period many analysts had predicted
before the strike began. That is, unless President Clinton reverses
his position and decides to intervene, a move that Northwest would
clearly welcome.
</P>
<P>
   New negotiations have not been held since the pilots walked out
early Saturday morning and none are expected for a few days, though
that could change quickly. Each side says it is waiting for the
other to make a move.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest has already canceled all its flights through the end
of Tuesday, and it will begin laying off some workers Monday. The
number of layoffs was uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Laying off all its workers would save the company valuable cash,
but it also would delay getting the airline up and running for as
long as two weeks if the pilots returned. Northwest plans to keep
as many workers as it needs to be able to restart the airline
before Friday, in the hope that the White House will order the
pilots back to work in time for them to fly at the Labor Day
weekend, which is traditionally a busy travel period.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Department of Transportation, who monitored the
strike's impact all weekend and have been briefed by the federal
mediator supervising the negotiations, are scheduled to meet
officials at the White House on Monday. So far the disruption
caused by the strike appears to have been unexpectedly moderate,
diminishing the chance that Clinton will step in.
</P>
<P>
   A long strike raises the question of whether Northwest will lose
more money as a result of the walkout than it would have to pay the
pilots by simply agreeing to their demands. The differences between
the last two offers on the table before the walkout are $70 million
a year over the life of a three-year contract according to the
pilots, and about $100 million a year according to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Northwest lost about $150 million in the month
before the strike began, as nervous travelers, aware of the
possibility, booked tickets on other airlines. The carrier will
lose about $25 million in revenue for each day it does not fly.
Analysts estimate that the net loss will be between $10 million and
$15 million a day if Northwest lays off most of its workers,
because the carrier will avoid outlays for its payroll, taxes and
fuel bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's $10 million a day, a seven-day strike pays for one
year of the contract,'' said Paul Omodt, the spokesman for the
pilots union.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The pilots gave up $365 million in wages and other concessions
in 1993 to help save Northwest from bankruptcy. In return, they
received 14.4 million shares of stock and a seat on the airline's
board of directors. Since then, Northwest has registered four years
of record earnings, while the pilots' pay has not risen beyond
where it was before the cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Having grown increasingly embittered as negotiations dragged on
for two years, the pilots want a 15.5 percent pay increase, more
generous pension and retirement benefits and stronger job
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   Hirst said that Northwest was willing to compromise on
noneconomic issues, such as the number of regional jets it can buy,
but that it could not afford to pay the pilots more than their
peers at the other major airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts generally agree with management. While the airline
industry has had its best years recently, industry profit levels
are still below the average for industrial companies.
</P>
<P>
   And Northwest, the United States' fourth-largest airline,
generates 30 percent of its annual revenue from Asia _ the largest
percentage of any domestic airline. As a result, since the Asian
economy began to founder last summer, Northwest has seen its
profits decline faster than its competitors'.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Northwest's stock, which has already fallen more than
50 percent from its peak in the spring, will probably not be hurt
too badly when trading begins Monday morning for the first time
since the walkout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quarter in which a strike takes place is very much like if
an airline cashed a plane and wrote off the loss,'' said Kevin
Murphy, an airline analyst at Morgan Stanley. ``Its a one-time
event. Historically, it is a very good time to buy airline stocks,
because it is just a temporary phenomenon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-98 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
