<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TOBACCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE DROPS OUT OF TOBACCO PACT TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Frustrated with what he calls foot-dragging by the
tobacco industry, Attorney General Scott Harshbarger has pulled out
of negotiations between nine states and cigarette makers trying to
reach an out-of-court national tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   After completing another round of talks in New York on Friday,
Harshbarger said he decided to walk away and focus instead on
winning a potential multibillion-dollar settlement for
Massachusetts in state court. He is expected to announce today that
he has ordered his tobacco litigation team from the table and
directed it to focus on the state's civil suit in state Superior
Court that is seeking billions of dollars for Medicaid costs to
treat smoking-related diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations that began last month have stalled, as the
cigarette makers, apparently emboldened by recent legal and
political victories, backed off earlier commitments to fund efforts
to curb teenage smoking and reduce advertising and promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts' withdrawal is significant because Harshbarger's
court case is considered among the strongest of those set for
trial. The industry, which has not lost a trial verdict after
scores of cases involving health care costs, is particularly
concerned that it not suffer a court setback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear to me that the industry is not serious about those
issues,'' Harshbarger said. ``So we are walking away and focusing
solely at beating them on trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger said that the state, if successful, would win a huge
settlement at trial and that the only purpose of negotiating with
the industry was to extract commitments on the public health
initiatives and antismoking measures. In an earlier national
settlement deal that fell through, Massachusetts stood to get $7.3
billion over 25 years in recovered medical costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can win money by winning our case,'' Harshbarger said.
``The purpose of pursuing negotiations has always been to secure
lasting protections for children and the public health.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Tobacco's tougher negotiating style is directly related to
recent developments in the national tobacco wars. In the last
several months, the industry has won significant legal battles and
has scored a political victory in its effort to kill what it
considered a damaging national agreement in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   With those developments, the manufacturers have been less
willing to concede on some major points they had agreed to
incorporate in the national settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, two of the nation's large tobacco companies,
R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. and Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp.,
decided to pull out of the negotiations, which resumed on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   People familiar with Harshbarger's decision say he was
particularly upset the industry had backed off a plan that it would
pay financial penalties against any failure to reduce youth smoking
rates.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, according to people close to the talks, the
cigarette makers are refusing to drop their opposition to President
Clinton's efforts to bring cigarettes under Food and Drug
Administration regulation. An appeals court in Virginia this month
ruled against the presidential directive.
</P>
<P>
   The firms also would not agree to drop a suit against
Massachusetts' tobacco ingredient disclosure law, the first such
law in the nation. A federal judge has put a hold on the state's
implementation of the statute, known as the Tolman Law.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger's decision to walk away from the negotiations comes
after six weeks in which attorneys general from nine states and the
cigarette makers have been meeting to rescue last year's proposed
national agreement in which the industry would have paid $368.5
billion over 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   That deal, struck in June 1997 and which would have included
broad protection for the industry against liability suits,
collapsed two months ago when Congress failed to act on it. In
mid-July, states such as Massachusetts with pending civil suits
began direct talks with the industry.
</P>
<P>
   According to those familiar with the New York negotiations, the
industry offered between $180 billion and $200 billion to be split
among 46 states. The payment would be financed through a cigarette
increase of 35 cents a pack.
</P>
<P>
   The current negotiations also coincide with Harshbarger's
campaign to win the Democratic gubernatorial nomination. Some
antismoking leaders have feared that Harshbarger, hoping to boost
his candidacy, would cut a deal that excludes some of the major
antismoking initiatives in order to announce a multibillion-dollar
windfall for Massachusetts in the middle of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Four states _ Mississippi, Minnesota, Texas, and Florida _ have
settled their lawsuits, and the industry paid a total of nearly $37
billion. But since then, the industry has won some key court
rulings that have weakened some of the suits and raised doubts on
their outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Massachusetts suit is considered to have the best
chance of any to create serious concern among the manufacturers. It
is being argued in Middlesex Superior Court, where the attorney
general has won favorable rulings in the case from Judge Martha B.
Sosman. It is currently scheduled for trial in February.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the industry is likely to face a hostile
environment in Massachusetts, a leader in the national antismoking
movement.
</P>
<P>
   A jury pool from Middlesex County, which has a generally upscale
population, is likely to be less sympathetic than most to tobacco
firms, legal analysts say. Those potential jurors also have been
subjected to years of a state-financed multimillion-dollar
antitobacco media blitz, some of it aimed directly at the
companies' business and marketing practices.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with those prospects, some analysts expect the industry to
try to cut a separate out-of-court settlement with Harshbarger's
office to avoid what would be a major legal setback if it were to
lose at trial.
</P>
<P>
   The ongoing negotiations were led by the attorney general of
Washington state, Christine Gregoire, whose suit against the
industry is next to go to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the table were representatives from attorneys general
from Colorado, New York, California, North Carolina, Oklahoma,
Pennsylvania, and North Dakota. Harshbarger said he does not fault
the other states to continue the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``My colleagues think they are doing what they think is best,''
Harshbarger said. ``Each state has to make its own decision based
on its case and its own interests.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
