<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9670 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      08-30 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: IN RUSSIA, WILL LACK OF POLITICAL CONSENSUS LEAD TO
PARALYSIS? 
</HEADLINE>
  (With RUSSIA-RDP, RUSSIA-U.S.) 
(sw) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Judging by how the grand and improbable alliance
between Russia's pro-capitalist leadership and its Communist
critics exploded Sunday evening _ on television, spectacularly, in
a crossfire of accusations and threats _ one might think these
people hadn't a clue about what to do with their country.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin's government and the Communists who
pretty much run parliament have plenty of ideas for keeping the
country from sliding into insolvency, social chaos and Third World
status. The problem is that their ideas are diametrically opposed.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to conduct government by consensus if there is no
consensus. And seldom, it seems, have two political bedmates been
more incompatible than these two.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the mismatch going to disappear, even if global pressure
in the form of President Clinton, who arrives on Tuesday, persuades
the two sides to glue together some sort of an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Westerners have no right to snicker. A glance at the last six
years of divided government in the United States shows that
democracy in action is not an especially appetizing sight.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, of course, is that most Western democracies accept
the rule of law and the division of powers among executives,
legislators and courts. Despite huge strides, Russia is still a
place where rumors of coups are taken seriously and where the
popularity of a leader _ or his unpopularity _ affects not only his
power but his legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a few contradictions: Yeltsin and his acting prime
minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin, have concluded that Russia's
salvation hinges on adoption of Western market capitalism, even if
Russified by a coterie of tycoons. The Communist Party, led by the
legislator Gennady Zyuganov, wants to renationalize major
industries and the banks.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin has pledged to do what it takes to persuade the
West's line-of-credit officer, the International Monetary Fund, to
continue doling out portions of a $22.6 billion loan package agreed
to last month. Zyuganov said on Sunday that he wanted the terms of
the package rewritten to ease its bite on ordinary Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin talks of a Europeanized Russia. Zyuganov dreams of
Soviet days gone by, and parliament's nationalist bloc still fondly
recalls the czars.
</P>
<P>
   Zyuganov wants Yeltsin gone and substantial power shifted to
parliament via a new constitution. Whatever Chernomyrdin thinks,
Yeltsin is still president, and he is dragging his feet on those
questions. That may have been the clincher that led Zyuganov to
reject so publicly the power-sharing agreement on Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative _ approval and fulfillment of the accord _ might
have turned out in some ways to be as strange as the scene that
unfolded on television Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   It is surprisingly easy to forget, seven years into democratic
Russia, that Yeltsin became president by ousting a Communist system
that he has repeatedly called cruel and despicable. For his part,
Zyuganov has long been organizing a nationwide strike against
Yeltsin's government scheduled for Oct. 7.
</P>
<P>
   If that mongoose-and-cobra alliance had been arranged, the new
government would have melded Zyuganov's Communists with a president
backed by free-market theorists and a prime minister whose most
ardent supporter is Boris Berezovsky, a capitalist in the bloodless
image of Commodore Vanderbilt.
</P>
<P>
   Many Russians, though disillusioned, still hope for a democratic
future. But a hard core of 25 percent or so would still support a
Communist system of government, and an unknown number of others
look for an autocrat to lead them out of troubled times.
</P>
<P>
   One of the things that makes Russia's fiscal collapse so
devastating is that it has laid bare that absence of consensus
about where Russia should be going next.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin was re-elected in 1996 with 53.8 percent of the vote but
has seen his popularity go into precipitous decline. Zyuganov, who
lost with 40.3 percent of the vote, wants not only a change in
economic policy but a rewrite of the constitution as well.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he will get it is now questionable. Sunday night's
breakdown seems to mean that the parliament will vote to reject
Chernomyrdin's appointment when it meets on Monday. If no
compromise is reached, Yeltsin could dissolve the parliament and
call for new elections, hoping to win a few new supporters to his
side.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, Russia remains oarless at a point when almost
everyone agrees that there is no time to waste. Chernomyrdin said
on Sunday that he knows where to begin to resolve the crisis, but
that ``time must not be lost. The country cannot function without a
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Aleksander Lebed, the retired Army general, once and future
presidential candidate and leading prospect in some eyes to become
Russia's next autocrat, is even more blunt. ''The choice is
simple,'' he said on Sunday, ``the confirmation of the prime
minister, formation of a new team of energetic people and the
presentation of a program for leading Russia out of crisis _ or a
total break-up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
