<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9672 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-YELTSIN-BOS &LR;      08-30 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-YELTSIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVENTS OVERTAKE CLINTON-YELTSIN SUMMIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and w coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  WASHINGTON _ In what is shaping up to be a bizarre exercise
in diplomacy, President Clinton's scheduled summit with Russian
President Boris N. Yeltsin in Moscow this week could underscore
their political weaknesses rather than buff their images.
</P>
<P>
   When the two-day summit was planned earlier this summer,
Clinton's advisers saw it as an opportunity for the president to
boost Russia's economic reform efforts and address a range of
global issues, from stockpiles of Russia's ``loose nukes'' to
ethnic conflict in Kosovo, as well as a temporary escape from his
own domestic troubles. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   But events have so overtaken that agenda that the value of the
trip has been called into question by critics. For example, House
Speaker Newt Gingrich called the upcoming trip imprudent and
questioned the value of any agreements made by two such politically
damaged leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Both presidents remained in seclusion much of last week _
Clinton on Martha's Vineyard and Yeltsin at his suburban dacha.
Clinton emerged in Worcester on Thursday in embarrassed silence
about the Oval Office sex scandal, while Yeltsin appeared on
television Friday to quash rumors that he would resign because of
his inability to cope with his country's economic collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid this summit is going to be a terrible
embarrassment,'' said David Kramer, associate director of Russian
and European issues at the Carnegie Endowment for Peace in
Washington. ``It's about the worst time for Clinton to go. He is
landing in a country in absolute turmoil ... meeting with leaders
who are increasingly irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   The upcoming summit will be nothing like the tightly
orchestrated Cold War-era events where speeches were scripted,
agreements were struck months in advance, and the two nations were
the unquestioned global superpowers.
</P>
<P>
   This time, expectations for the summit became less clear as
political and economic events in Russia spiraled out of control.
``The conditions for the summit are hollow and it will be nothing
more than a blip,'' said Morton Abramowitz, a senior fellow at the
Council on Foreign Relations.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin appears to be president without portfolio, having
dissolved his Cabinet and handed over some powers last week to his
newly appointed prime minister, Victor S. Chernomyrdin, whom
Yeltsin reinstalled after dismissing him as a reformer only five
months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment followed Yeltsin's decision last week to devalue
the ruble and delay foreign debt repayments. Speculation that the
economy was collapsing gained ground as the ruble went into free
fall and foreign exchange was suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin has yet to be confirmed by the Russian parliament.
His confirmation is expected, but confidence in his ability to
implement the kind of economic and tax measures demanded by the
International Monetary Fund has been weakened by his lethargic
record, the firing of leading reformers last week, and the
likelihood that he will cut power-sharing deals with both the
Communist party and the financial and industrial elite.
</P>
<P>
   At a press briefing Friday, the Clinton administration attempted
to characterize the trip as a necessary show of support for Russia
in its time of crisis, as well as an opportunity to push for reform
at a critical juncture.
</P>
<P>
   ``In public and private, the president intends to reinforce the
importance to Russians and the world of holding fast to a
democratic path and economic reform in the face of new
challenges,'' said Samuel R. Berger, the president's national
security adviser. ``The Russian people should know that
particularly in times of difficulty, the US will not turn away.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia is likely to press for more aid as well as to push for
the IMF to release another $4.3 billion infusion in September, but
national economic adviser Gene Sperling made it clear the
administration will tie all monetary support to measurable economic
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Economists say Russia has already wasted most of the first
installment of a $4.5 billion loan, part of a United States-backed
international debt rescue package worth $22.6 billion _ in part
because Yeltsin plunged ahead with reforms without a legal
structure in place.
</P>
<P>
   Critics worry that the summit could simply underline the
weakness of both presidents and highlight what some analysts have
long criticized as Clinton's short-sighted, personality-driven
approach to Russian policy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton would do well to use the event to begin to ``change the
American policy of obsessive support for Yeltsin,'' said Dimitri K.
Simes, president of the Nixon Center, a think tank in Washington.
Berger noted that Clinton would be meeting with a range of regional
and political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, fighting for his political life, is unlikely to focus
on crucial security and arms control issues. US officials, however,
insisted the president would press ahead by pushing for
ratification of Start 2, the nuclear arms control agreement that
would reduce deployed nuclear weapons by 60 percent, and the
beginning of Start 3 talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes are the entire future of nuclear arms reduction,''
said Matthew Bunn, a Harvard University nuclear weapons specialist.
</P>
<P>
   This is just one crucial issue likely to end up on the back
burner. Others include:
</P>
<P>
   _Clamping down on Russia's nuclear exports to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   _Coordinating a response to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   _Coping with Kosovo's civil war.
</P>
<P>
   _Finding jobs for thousands of unemployed nuclear scientists as
well as a safe market for Russia's stockpile of uranium and
plutonium
</P>
<P>
   _Rebuilding Russia's crumbling early warning system for nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Specialists who often advise the White House on policy have for
months warned that a summit would be too risky until Russia's
economic situation resolved.
</P>
<P>
   But canceling the summit at this point would further destabilize
Russia, said Senator John F. Kerry, who sits on the Foreign
Relations Committee. The Massachusetts Democrat said the summit
could at least spotlight crucial security and arms control issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is extraordinarily important for us to be dealing with
Russia as a critical player,'' Kerry said. ``It would be
dramatically worse not to put something together, as perilous as
the situation is.''
</P>
<P>
   Bracing for the political fallout, analysts already are
developing worst case scenarios, including one that sees the summit
closing as a public relations disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shudder at the thought of a joint press conference,'' said
the Carnegie Endowment's Kramer. ``It will be the media's first
opportunity to ask about Monica Lewinsky, and to ask whether
Clinton puts his support behind Yeltsin, who is pretty much
irrelevant now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-98 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980830.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9673 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRICANE-EROSION-NYT     08-30 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-EROSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE POINTS TO LOSING BATTLE AGAINST BEACH EROSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH TOPSAIL BEACH, N.C. _ In the aftermath of Hurricane
Bonnie, officials looking across the flat stretches of beach that
once held sand dunes can see that they may be fighting a losing
battle against erosion.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane, which pummeled the North Carolina coastline last
week, took with it about 60 percent of the dune line along North
Topsail Beach, the northernmost stretch of Topsail Island north of
Wilmington. Erosion has chipped away at the 25-mile-long barrier
island, and in a few places, its width has been whittled to about
150 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The disappearance of parts of the dune line after large storms
is not surprising, said Orrin Pilkey, a geologist at Duke
University in Durham.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most dangerous island community in North Carolina
and one of the most dangerous along the East Coast,'' Pilkey said.
``The dunes are all artificial and extremely fragile, and, all in
all, it's an island community that should not have been developed
if common sense were to prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   The island, once undeveloped and a haven for surf fishermen, has
grown rapidly in the last few years as developers have built
condominiums and resorts. Even Hurricanes Fran and Bertha two years
ago, which knocked down first and second rows of houses in places
on the beach, did not deter development.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has taken time for homeowners to rebuild and for
businesses to recoup losses, new houses replacing those damaged by
the storms are scattered on the island. The hurricanes also took
much of what remained of the island's maritime forests, which help
slow erosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've not seen a hurricane have a big impact on development
just other than to bring in bigger and better buildings,'' Pilkey
said. ``That's really fundamentally the impact these things have.
It's really an urban renewal project.''
</P>
<P>
   But hurricanes, development and the natural give and take of the
tide have taken their toll on the dunes. While the southern end has
maintained a larger natural berm, other parts of the island's dune
system have had to be rebuilt. Sand from the island has repeatedly
been bulldozed into 10-foot high piles, which offer some protection
from the tides, but are not as stable as natural dunes and have to
be replaced after storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be willing to bet they lost 120 feet in the last 20
years,'' said Bill Cleary, a professor of geology at the Center for
Marine Science Research at the University of North Carolina at
Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Hammond, the town manager of North Topsail Beach, said the
cost of replacing the dunes was justified if it saved houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dunes that had the vegetation seem to have held up
better,'' Hammond said. ``The ones with the limited vegetation
didn't do as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Pilkey said Topsail Island was never intended to accommodate
development.
</P>
<P>
   The constant chipping away of sand is proof that the island is
doing what nature intends, he said. The island has a small natural
sand supply and is at a stage where it is beginning what he calls
true migration. Barrier islands such as Topsail become thin from
erosion and begin over washing, which moves sand into the sounds
that separate them from the mainland. The over washing widens the
side closest to the mainland while the opposite side erodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That translates into island moving,'' Pilkey said. ``This is
an island that wants to migrate.''
</P>
<P>
   But homeowners do not like island migration. For several years,
the town has used bulldozers to pile up the sand, creating an
artificial dune system.
</P>
<P>
   After Hurricane Fran, the Federal Emergency Management Agency
reimbursed North Topsail Beach $1.6 million of the $2 million cost
of creating an emergency berm, by bulldozing sand displaced by
storms, said Jay Eaker, an agency spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Although these efforts will cause the island to migrate more
slowly than it would naturally, Pilkey said, the process is
inevitable. If hurricane activity increases as predicted _ and
brings them to the North Carolina coastline with the regularity of
the 1950's, when the state was nicknamed Hurricane Alley _ it could
work against their best efforts to slow the process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-98 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
