<HEADLINE>
MORGAN STANLEY WILL OFFER RESEARCH TO TRADERS ON INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Morgan Stanley Dean Witter has decided to sell access
to research by its top-ranked team of stock analysts to customers
of its Internet service, Discover Brokerage Direct.
</P>
<P>
   The move, which the company plans to announce this week, will be
the first time that any of the major brokerage firms has given
same-day access to research to customers who do not pay full
commissions for their stock trades.
</P>
<P>
   The price difference for such trades can be enormous. Discover
Brokerage will charge $14.95 for a trade that Morgan Stanley's
full-service brokers might charge as much as $3,600 to make.
</P>
<P>
   Discover Brokerage, which is ninth in the online brokerage race,
wants to win business by emphasizing the resources of its larger
parent. Morgan Stanley's research team was rated second to Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co. in the annual poll of big customers by Institutional
Investor magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The online discount service will not offer the full range of
search that is available to Morgan Stanley's full-service
customers.
</P>
<P>
   For $19.95 a month, Discover Brokerage customers can specify up
to 20 companies they want to follow. They will receive an e-mail
notification within about an hour of the time the firm has changed
its recommendation about those companies' stocks or has published a
new report. They can also read summaries of the new reports online.
</P>
<P>
   Customers also have the option to follow 40 companies for $34.95
a month. Initially, Discover will offer online research for 400
companies but it plans to increase that to about 1,000 companies by
the end of the year. Customers can change their list of stocks once
a month.
</P>
<P>
   But online customers will not have access to the full reports
nor can they see the firm's list of recommended stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recommended list is traditionally a mainstay of the retail
broker,'' said Thomas O'Connell, an executive vice president of
Discover Brokerage. ``To distribute it away from them would not be
right.'' He said that Morgan Stanley wants to keep a clear
distinction between the two services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not trying to replicate everything in the full-service
channel and do it at a discounted price,'' O'Connell said.
</P>
<P>
   The other firms that have tiptoed into offering some research
online have not provided same-day access to their Internet
customers and have typically placed various other limitations on
the offerings. Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette lets only those
customers with more than $100,000 in their accounts read its
research. They can read reports on all the companies the firm
covers, but one or two days after they are published. That delay is
critical, because a rating change by a top-ranked analyst can send
a stock soaring or tumbling, depending on the point of view.
</P>
<P>
   The two largest full-service firms _ Merrill Lynch and the
Salomon Smith Barney unit of Travelers Group _ do not offer
separate Internet trading at a discount. But Salomon does have an
arrangement to distribute summaries of its research to customers of
Fidelity Investments. Fidelity customers can subscribe to a daily
summary of Salomon's recommendations for $50 a month or a weekly
summary for $20 a month. Fidelity does not offer Salomon reports on
individual companies.
</P>
<P>
   The online brokerage firm E-Trade offers immediate access to an
unlimited number of research reports by BancAmerica Robertson
Stephens to customers who sign up for its $24.95 a month premium
service. But Robertson Stephens analysts are not among the top 20
as ranked by Institutional Investor.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Charles Schwab pulled back from a plan to
provide delayed access to reports from a number of big brokerage
firms. Those reports would have been provided by First Call, a firm
that sends the reports electronically to institutional clients. But
the plan was tabled after the brokerage firms complained, and
Schwab now says it is working on a new plan to offer research from
several brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley's choice to charge a separate fee for its
research is likely to inhibit people from using the service, said
K. Blake Darcy, the chief executive of a competing online service,
DLJ Direct. ``People on the Internet believe that information
should be free or close to it,'' he said. He said that research has
proved to be only a modest attraction for those DLJ customers who
qualify for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than half the people who could don't use it at all,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, stock research is a draw for a group of customers that
some firms find attractive, said Julio Gomez, the founder of Gomez
Advisers, a firm that follows online brokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investment bank research has been among the most coveted
services, not for the day trader, but for the serious investor who
fancies themselves in the mold of Warren Buffet or Peter Lynch,''
Gomez said. He said that such customers now represent about 30
percent of the online market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
