<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MUST PATCH TOGETHER A DAVIS CUP LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite a plethora of Davis Cup veterans like Pete Sampras,
Andre Agassi, Jim Courier and Michael Chang, the United States
continues to suffer embarrassment when it needs to field a reliable
lineup. This time, with the Davis Cup semifinal against Italy less
than a month away, the team captain, Tom Gullikson, has found
himself in the familiar predicament of having to start from scratch
after being deserted by his singles stars.
</P>
<P>
   Gullikson confirmed Sunday that Sampras, who previously hinted
that his 1998 schedule would not accommodate Davis Cup play, has
provided ``a definitive no'' about his semifinal availability, as
have Agassi and Courier. Gullikson said that 26th-ranked Todd
Martin had agreed to play singles and doubles against Italy and
that he was trying to persuade the 15th-ranked Chang to take the
other singles role.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mr. Chang says no, then we move on,'' said Gullikson, who
mentioned 42nd-ranked Vince Spadea, 56th-ranked Jan Michael Gambill
and 66th-ranked Jeff Tarango as possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Although Agassi and Courier volunteered for singles in the first
two rounds of 1998 play, neither will be available for the Sept.
25-27 competition in Milwaukee. The 28-year-old Courier, who
withdrew from the U.S. Open after first-round losses in two summer
hardcourts events, has been plagued by what Gullikson calls ``a
chronic case of dead arm.'' Agassi took himself off the semifinal
squad because of a scheduling conflict with the yearly charity gala
in Las Vegas for which he is the host.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, who will be in black tie at the MGM Grand on Sept. 26,
said he would have sandwiched the Davis Cup around the gala had the
U.S. Tennis Association selected a West Coast site. ``God bless
Milwaukee, but it's something they should discuss with the
players,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi shares Sampras' view that the Davis Cup should be held
every other year rather than annually, and he has agreed with Chang
that players should have a greater say in site selection.
</P>
<P>
   Gullikson said the USTA tried and failed to find a suitable
semifinal venue in or near Las Vegas. ``It's not that easy to do,
and I'm sure he knew when Davis Cup was when he booked the date for
his gala,'' Gullikson said of Agassi. ``It's just an unfortunate
conflict of scheduling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-98 2049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
