<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AIDES DEVELOP DETAILED DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-DEMOCRATS) 
(mk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's top legal and political
advisers said Sunday that they had developed a detailed defense to
what they anticipate are the four arguments that Kenneth Starr, the
Whitewater independent counsel, might use to mount a case of
obstruction of justice against the president.
</P>
<P>
   The mobilization of the president's lawyers and political
advisers is part of the preparation for the battle over Starr's
expected report to the House of Representatives about issues
stemming from Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky, a former
White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   According to lawyers who say they are familiar with Starr's
plans, the report is expected to be completed by late September,
after which the House Judiciary Committee will be obligated to
consider whether to undertake impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   There are four areas of possible obstruction of justice for
which the Clinton advisers have developed detailed
counterarguments.
</P>
<P>
   The first concerns the ``talking points,'' a memorandum Ms.
Lewinsky gave to her onetime friend Linda Tripp, seemingly to help
her alter, in a way favorable to the president, an account of her
knowledge of an encounter between Clinton and another woman.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue is the help given Ms. Lewinsky by friends of the
president in finding her a job.
</P>
<P>
   A third concerns any abuse of power by the president in using
the White House's arsenal of lawyers and officials to maintain the
deception that there was no improper relationship between Clinton
and Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The final area concerns the gifts given by Clinton to Ms.
Lewinsky, and whether the president conspired with her to conceal
them from lawyers for Paula Jones, who sought the gifts in
connection with her sexual misconduct lawsuit against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fight, in large measure, has shifted from the legal arena
to the political,'' said a senior legal adviser to Clinton.
Nonetheless, the adviser, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
said that the defenses developed would first seek to defeat any
anticipated obstruction of justice charges Starr might make.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the whole obstruction of justice case is stripped away,''
another senior adviser said, ``all Ken Starr is left with is a
report about an inappropriate relationship and an understandable
effort to conceal it.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House team's arguments appear strongest on the talking
points. Lawyers familiar with the testimony say Ms. Lewinsky has
told the grand jury that she wrote the talking points herself with
some help from Mrs. Tripp. Although Mrs. Tripp has denied any role,
Starr has apparently been unable to find any evidence that Clinton
or any of his associates were involved in drafting the document.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time, the `talking points' were supposed to be the
smoking gun of the obstruction case,'' said one adviser. ``Now that
Starr has been unable to tie it to anyone in the White House, it's
like sand falling through his fingers.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House contends that helping Ms. Lewinsky find a job
had nothing to do with any effort to buy her silence. Essentially,
the argument of Clinton supporters is one of timing: that Ms.
Lewinsky began getting high-level help in finding a good job before
anyone knew she was even a potential witness in the Jones case, so
the career help could not have been part of an effort to persuade
her to lie.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the evidence about the timing is complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones, a former Arkansas clerical worker, had brought a
sexual misconduct suit against Clinton, contending that when he was
governor of Arkansas he had her summoned to his hotel room in
Little Rock and then made a crude sexual advance. In an effort to
bolster their case, Mrs. Jones' lawyers sought other examples in
which the president might have engaged in sex with female
subordinates, and they sought information about Ms. Lewinsky, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyers learned on Dec. 5, 1997, that Ms.
Lewinsky might be called as a witness in the Jones lawsuit. Vernon
Jordan Jr., the president's close friend, has said that on Dec. 8
he began helping Ms. Lewinsky find a job in one of the companies
with which he has connections, including American Express and
Revlon.
</P>
<P>
   While that may seem at first not to help Clinton, the
president's advisers contend that there may be documents showing
that Jordan's recollection is flawed and that he began helping her
before Dec. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, they argue, the other Clinton associate who tried to
help Ms. Lewinsky was Bill Richardson, the ambassador to the United
Nations, who interviewed her nearly two months before her name
surfaced on Dec. 5.
</P>
<P>
   White House advisers also say they are increasingly confident
that the issue of gifts can be interpreted in Clinton's favor.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty Clinton must overcome is that, according to
lawyers, Ms. Lewinsky has testified that he encouraged her to
ignore a request from Mrs. Jones' lawyers to turn over any gifts
she got from him. Lawyers said that Ms. Lewinsky testified that the
president told her she could avoid turning over the gifts if she no
longer possessed them and that Betty Currie, his secretary, then
showed up at the Lewinsky apartment to retrieve them.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has testified that he told Ms. Lewinsky she had no
choice but to comply with the subpoena for the gifts.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the White House argument is the credibility of Ms.
Currie, who has been widely portrayed as a decent and honest
witness. According to lawyers, Ms. Currie has offered testimony
that conflicts sharply with that of Ms. Lewinsky, telling the grand
jury that Clinton did not send her to pick up the gifts, but that
she went to the apartment at Ms. Lewinsky's request. The suggestion
is that Ms. Lewinsky orchestrated the return of the gifts herself,
and that Ms. Lewinsky gave them greater value than did the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, these were impersonal things, these gifts,'' one Clinton
strategist said regarding the hatpin, souvenir blanket, brooch,
T-shirts and signed copy of the State of the Union address he gave
her. ``It's not as though he gave her a diamond tennis bracelet or
something that said, `Bill loves Monica.'''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said they may counter accusations of a
widespread abuse of power as an understandable effort to conceal a
private relationship that the president has since acknowledged was
improper.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the issue of obstruction of justice, Clinton may
still face additional problems, including whether he committed
perjury when he denied having had sexual relations with Ms.
Lewinsky when he testified under oath in a deposition in the Jones
case on Jan. 17.
</P>
<P>
   He has argued that under the definition of sexual relations that
was approved by the judge that day, his answers were ``legally
accurate'' if misleading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
