<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS CRUSH YANKEES, 13-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The emotional release of clinching a playoff berth
causes men to act like Little Leaguers, form giant human piles and
spray each other with carbonated substances. Scott Brosius was
somewhat more subdued Sunday morning when he learned from a
reporter that in beating Seattle Saturday the Yankees had clinched
a spot in the American League playoffs, the earliest clinching date
in the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I can plan on extending my lease another month,'' said
Brosius, his face still puffy from sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Word that the Yankees had clinched seemed anticlimactic, because
of the team's extraordinary record and because nobody realized the
accomplishment until reporters re-examined the standings long after
Saturday's game. Andy Pettitte learned of the feat while watching
television at home Saturday evening. Yankees general manager Brian
Cashman read about the berth Sunday morning while eating a bowl of
Cap'n Crunch. Most of the Yankees were told by reporters Sunday,
before the Seattle Mariners blasted them, 13-3, before 55,341 at
Yankee Stadium. Ken Griffey Jr. launched his 46th and 47th home
runs in the game, the first amid a barrage of hits against Hideki
Irabu (11-7).
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are 98-37 and could reach 100 victories when they
play host to Oakland in a two-game series Tuesday and Wednesday.
Qualifying for the playoffs became a foregone conclusion long ago,
as had winning the AL East; the Yankees began play Sunday leading
the Boston Red Sox by 18 1/2 games.
</P>
<P>
   In winning so many games so quickly, the Yankees have raised the
bar of expectations for themselves beyond simply making the
playoffs. ``We're trying to get everything back to playoff-type
thinking,'' said Tim Raines, the veteran outfielder. ``It would be
kind of tough to say we have the best team in baseball, that we won
130 games or whatever in the regular season, and then not win
anything in the postseason. The focus is more toward winning the
World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the players had realized they had clinched a spot in the
playoffs _ the first step toward success in the postseason, and
essentially what they have been playing for since the end of spring
training _ they probably would not have celebrated too much. ``Some
high-fives and stuff,'' Brosius said.
</P>
<P>
   They probably will not go crazy when they clinch the East,
either, in the next 10 days or so. ``We have high standards for
ourselves,'' said Joe Girardi, the Yankees' catcher. ``Not that you
take things for granted, but you expect that you're going to win.
The expectations in this room are different than any team I've
played on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees clinched the moment Chad Curtis caught David Segui's
fly ball to close Saturday's game, and, not realizing the game had
any significance, Curtis flipped the ball into the stands. There
was no bedlam, no Champagne. ``I did drink an ice water,'' Brosius
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams knew nothing about the clinching until he was
approached by reporters Sunday morning. Somebody asked Williams
what was the best way to celebrate a clinching one day late?
Thoughtful as always, Williams considered the question before he
said, ``Maybe just win this game today.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't exactly work out, either. On Friday, the Yankees led
by 10-1 after four innings, then on Saturday by 11-0 after four
innings. But Sunday, Seattle jumped ahead by 10-0 in the first five
innings, pounding Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander has struggled to come back from a bruise on his
foot that he sustained on Aug. 15, and is doing all the right
things to insure that he will not be given a meaningful role in the
postseason. He allowed 10 hits and eight runs in three and
one-third innings and most every ball hit was hit hard. Mel
Stottlemyre, the Yankees pitching coach, explained later that
Irabu's split-fingered fastball was ineffective, and he could not
finish hitters off once he was ahead in the count. ``A bad game,''
Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``A bad pitching performance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and the Mariners, whose heated rivalry has generally
been defused this season by the Yankees' dominance over Seattle,
engaged in two bench-clearing incidents that resulted in exactly no
punches being thrown, and a lot of chest-thumping. In the third
inning, Curtis exchanged angry words with Seattle shortstop Alex
Rodriguez near second base after Rodriguez completed a double play
throwing past Curtis; Rodriguez thought Curtis should have slid or
got out of the way more quickly. As the two yelled at each other
and drew close, other players milled around them, but nothing came
of it.
</P>
<P>
   But after Brosius was hit in the middle of the back by a
fastball in the bottom of the seventh, the Yankees' Mike Buddie
skipped a fastball past the feet of Seattle's Rob Ducey, who stared
at the pitcher suspiciously. Then Buddie hit him in the leg, the
message clear to all: This was retaliation on behalf of Brosius.
</P>
<P>
   Players and coaches from both benches and the bullpen gathered
at the mound, Seattle's Segui shouting that hey, the Yankees beat
up the Mariners in the first two games of this series, so why
couldn't they take their lumps in this game? Tino Martinez
retorted, but nobody really wanted to fight. Chili Davis and
Griffey playfully pushed each other, the same with Derek Jeter and
Rodriguez. Buddie, ejected immediately, was not available for
comment afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are friends on both sides,'' David Cone said. ``I'm just
glad it didn't get out of hand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
