</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USAMATR31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kuehne sips sweet success as Amateur champ
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. _ His turbulent past allowed no champagne to be
sipped from the Havemayer Trophy Sunday night. No problem. Let
others do it for him. After beating alcoholism three years ago at
age19, Hank Kuehne has secured a U.S. Amateur championship.
</P>
<P>
   Winning his battle with 44-year-old Tom McKnight on the 35th
hole Sunday at Oak Hill Country Club, Kuehne, 22, officially
prevailed 2 and 1, completing a remarkable journey from despair to
delirium.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 3, 1995, the last time his lips touched alcohol, Kuehne
lay in a Stillwater, Okla., hospital after a one-car accident, his
life as shattered as his ribs. Today, after overcoming a touch of
relative adversity in his match with McKnight, he holds the most
prestigious amateur golf title in the world.
</P>
<P>
   By now, the collective tear ducts of the Kuehne family are
nearly spent. When McKnight conceded a two-putt par at the 17th
hole to Hank _ Henry to his close friends _ the scene became a
tearful hugfest between the winner, brother Trip, his caddie, and
father Ernie. It's a family whose joy realized Sunday was virtually
impossible to measure.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the second greatest victory in my life,'' said Hank, a
senior at Southern Methodist. ''No matter what I do the rest of my
life, sobriety will always be my No.1 victory.''
</P>
<P>
   For Trip, who lost a U.S. Amateur final to Tiger Woods in 1994,
there was significant solace in sharing part of Hank's victory
Sunday. In the black hole that used to be Hank's life, he was
drowning from his own disease. Admittedly, both Trip and sister
Kelli, a two-time women's amateur champion, were frightened for his
life.
</P>
<P>
   ''It tops off a long journey,'' said Trip, 26. ''Henry had won
before he even got here. Golf is very easy for him. Staying sober
is his challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I started crying because we know what Henry has been through,
being 22 years old and overcoming alcoholism,'' said Kelli, who
could watch the final hole of the Amateur after missing the cut at
the LPGA Rail Classic. ''I've always been a big believer in Henry.
I think Trip would even tell you that Henry's always had more
ability than Trip and I both.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelli said she was well aware of his brother's drinking problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was pretty scary,'' she said. ''He hit rock bottom. I saw
him at a lot of parties. I told him he drank too much, but, well,
he was a senior...We were the golfing family and we could pretty
much get away with anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Hank Kuehne has the world ahead of him. Already in the
Masters by making the finals, he now ensures a Thursday pairing
with defending champion Mark O'Meara. He'll play in the U.S. Open
with O'Meara and defending champion Lee Janzen.
</P>
<P>
   McKnight, a petroleum distributor and convenience store owner
from Galax, Va., could barely hit a fairway all day and hit only 13
of 35 greens, but remained alive by periods of one-putting magic.
Kuehne was 3-up after the morning round, but the match took several
turns after lunch. Six holes into the second round, McKnight had
four birdies and was 1-up. Kuehne was unraveling and needed a
break. It came at the 8th hole, when his drive banged into two
trees and kicked into the middle of the fairway. McKnight lipped
out to even the match, starting a trend that would lead to three
straight bogeys to start the back nine, and Kuehne never trailed
again.
</P>
<P>
   ''On 8 there, when the monkey threw it out of the tree,'' Hank
said, ''it was pretty great to say the least.''
</P>
<P>
   Accepting the good fortune, Trip told his little brother,
''Let's just act like you hit a 4-iron out there and right this
ship.''
</P>
<P>
   McKnight, though seriously disappointed, still enjoyed the ride.
Selling propane gas and heating oil just won't be much of a rush
after this.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm happy as hell for Henry,'' he said. ''I think it's great
for he and his family. It would have been great for me and my
family, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
