<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gordon claims victory _ again
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. - Just when Mark Martin thought he might put
together a winning streak of his own, up jumped Jeff Gordon to
spoil his fun again.
</P>
<P>
   Martin all but had his name on the CMT 300 trophy Sunday at New
Hampshire International Speedway until he crossed paths with Rich
Bickle, bringing out the caution that gave Gordon a chance to break
his heart again.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon took on only two tires and got back onto the track as the
race leader. That was the last anyone else - including Martin, who
had led 193 laps - saw of the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's about the only racing we did today, those last 60
laps,'' Gordon said. ''There at the end, we just tried to get in
the top five. Once we got to fifth, that caution happened to come
out at the right time for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was Gordon's ninth of the season, fifth in the last
six and six in the last eight. As Bobby Hamilton said, ''I'm not
particulary surprised Gordon won. I saw (country singer) Jerry Reed
this morning. What was his big song? 'When you're hot, you're hot.'
And he's definitely hot.''
</P>
<P>
   It was too hot for Martin to handle. It was his to lose, and he
did, when he tangled with Bickle in turn four. Martin escaped, but
Bickle hit the wall, bringing out the caution Martin didn't need.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just got outrun,'' Martin said. ''I don't think anything
went wrong. At the end of the race, the 24 car (Gordon) was just
faster than we were. He just outran us. Some people said I had a
handful at the end, but I was just trying to drive as fast as
Gordon was and I couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the $205,400 Gordon won the Winston Cup Leader
bonus worth $20,000. It was the seventh time that Gordon had won
it.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's average speed was 112.134 miles per hour; the margin of
victory .664 seconds and the attendance 90,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''Winning boils down to who has trouble, who gets in wrecks or
who gets stuck on the outside and goes back to 17th and doesn't
come back up there,'' Gordon said of the difference in winning and
losing.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no one else to chase Gordon at the end. John Andretti
finished third, but never was a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett was fourth. He has four straight top five finishes,
but has lost 39 points to Gordon over that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ''Like I said, if you plan on gaining points in this this thing,
you gotta win the race and we weren't able to do that,'' Jarrett
said. ''That was probably the best we've run in a while, but it
just wasn't quite good enough. But, we can make some adjustments
from here and see if we can get a little better next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
