<SLUG> BC-Y2K-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSULTANT IS SUED FOR EXPECTED COMPUTER MALFUNCTION IN 2000 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   J. Baker Inc., a large apparel retailer, is demanding that
Andersen Consulting reimburse it for the cost of a computer system
installed nearly 10 years ago because the system is expected to
malfunction in the year 2000, officials at the consulting firm said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   To try to ward off a possible lawsuit by J. Baker, Andersen
asked a Massachusetts court on Friday to rule that the consultants
had met all their contractual obligations when they installed the
merchandising system for the retailer. The installation was
completed in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The case is significant because it is one of the first that
tries to blame consultants or computer vendors for installing a
system that will not recognize dates after Dec. 31, 1999 _ the Y2K
problem. If such a suit succeeded, it could expose Andersen
Consulting, the world's largest consulting firm, as well as dozens
of other consultants and computer companies to billions of dollars
in liability.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Jackson, a spokesman for Andersen Consulting, said the firm
had repeatedly tried to resolve the matter with J. Baker. The firm
decided to ask the court for a declaratory judgment, he said, after
Baker hired a law firm to work on the matter for a fee contingent
on any final settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``J. Baker is unreasonably demanding reimbursement for a system
they used successfully for nearly a decade,'' Andersen said in a
written statement. ``We felt there was no choice left but to ask
the court to help resolve this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Baker did not return telephone messages left for
them on Friday and Sunday. But according to the consulting firm,
the company is arguing that it would have insisted in 1989 that the
system be ready for the year 2000 if the consultants had then
brought up the subject. The consultants say any such claim by Baker
is groundless.
</P>
<P>
   ``We completely stand behind our work, will defend our position
and fully expect to win this case,'' the consulting firm's
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   J. Baker officials had approved of the computer's design when it
was installed, Jackson said. And they even agreed to praise the
project's success to other companies considering whether to hire
Andersen Consulting.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, based in Canton, Mass., owns hundreds of retail stores
around the country, including the Casual Male Big and Tall chain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
