A9703 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-NASRAIL31-COX     08-30 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASRAIL31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nascar Rail
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An analysis of the CMT 300 at New Hampshire International
Speedway
</P>
<P>
   The First 100
</P>
<P>
   In typical New Hampshire fashion, four different drivers led the
first four laps - Jeff Gordon led one, Bobby Labonte two, Ken
Schrader, who then got selfish and led lap four to 33. From there
it was follow the leader, that being Mark Martin, who carried the
field to lap 77 before the first caution fell, allowing Dave Marcis
his lone appearance at the front of the pakc.
</P>
<P>
   During that 77-lap charge, Jeff Burton, who won here in June,
wound his way through the field, from 25th to 17th in 10 laps, but
that was all he had. He hung on on to finish fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Martin took the lead on lap on lap 79 and nourished it for 89
laps, signalling that a second conscutive victory might be in
store.
</P>
<P>
   Lap leaders: Gordon (1), Bobby Labonte (2), Ken Schrader (3),
Mike Wallace (30), Mark Martin (64), Dave Macis (2). Retired: Steve
Park (wreck). Under Caution: 4 laps
</P>
<P>
   Second 100
</P>
<P>
   Martin picked up in the second segment where he left off the
first, leading. He kept his Ford in the lead through lap 167,
turning it over to Terry Labonte for a pair. Two laps later, Wally
Dallenbach became the first to exit due to mechanical problems. His
engined expired. Things began to heat up The days second caution
came on lap 178 when Rusty Wallace and Schrader got together in the
midle of turn three. Schrader slammed into the wall and was gone
for the day. There was more riding than racing in this segment,
evidenced by big gaps throughout the field. Bill Elliott developed
a small grease leak, which becomes serious on lap 125. He loses
four spots and pits, taking his Ford behind the wall for 43 laps
and finishes 37th. Three cautions slowed this 100-lap segment. Jeff
Green hit the wall in the middle of turns one and two; Terry
Labonte broke a piece in his engine and Rich Bickle crashed in turn
four after coming in contact with Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Lap leaders: Martin (128), Jarrett (2), Terry Labonte (1),
Robert Pressley (1), Martin (60)
</P>
<P>
   Retired: Ken Schrader (wreck). Under caution: 10 laps
</P>
<P>
   Final 100
</P>
<P>
   Gordon makes his first appearance in the top five since lap 167
and takes fifth place on lap 211. At the same time, Jarrett is
closing in on Martin, moving thrgh lapped traffic and pulling
within a car length on lap 228. He took the lead when Rich Bickle
spun out in turn four on lap 232. Leaders pit, but Gordon and Jeff
Burton take only two tires for track position. Gordon comes out
with the lead for te first time since the first lap, and never
gives it up rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Lap leaders: Dale Jarrett (1), Jeff Gordon (66). Retired: Jeff
Green (wreck), Terry Labonte (engine), Rich Bickle (accident).
Under caution: 11 laps
</P>
<P>
   Who Was Hot: Jeff Gordon won for the fifth time in six races. He
came from nowhere over the final third of the race, leading the
last 67 laps.
</P>
<P>
   Who Was Not: Mark Martin. He led 193 lap and came out second
best.
</P>
<P>
   Points Update: Jeff Gordon lead Mark Martin by 67 points. He has
3,597 to Martin's 3,530. The top five: Gordon, 3,597; Martin,
3,530; Dale Jarrett, 3,359; Rusty Wallace, 3,175; Bobby Labonte,
3,083.
</P>
<P>
   Today's Impact: After finishing second last week at Bristol and
seeing his four race winning streak broken, Gordon showed he's
still riding a high on the Winston Cup circuit. Also, the way he
won could impact other drivers who haven't had his ''luck'' this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
