<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RUSSIA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
CLINTON TO MEET YELTSIN AS RUSSIA TEETERS ON EDGE OF CHAOS
<TEXT>
<P>
   By NANCY MATHIS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
c. 1998
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WASHINGTON _ President Clinton arrives in Moscow tonight eds.
Monday night to begin an awkward summit with President Boris
Yeltsin just as Russia teeters on the edge of chaos, and the United
States can offer little but reassuring words.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, suffering from his own troubles at home, begins a
weeklong overseas journey with a stop in Russia before heading to
Northern Ireland and Ireland to champion their efforts toward
peace.
</P>
<P>
   The session between Clinton and Yeltsin comes at a critical, if
not ill-timed, moment in which the Kremlin faces one of its
toughest challenges since the 1991 demise of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, which has struggled to define its place in the post-Cold
War world, now finds itself in a political and economic free fall,
facing instability and uncertainty; its citizens turning against
the market reforms and turning toward anti-American rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday morning, Russian officials announced an 18-month truce,
between the Communist-led Duma and the Yeltsin government, which
would allow a new Cabinet to be installed and strip away Yeltsin's
powers. Only hours later, the Communists denounced the pact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear that it signifies a triple setback, a setback for
economic reforms, a slowdown of democratization and a setback for
American advocacy both of reforms and of democracy in Russia,''
said Zbigniew Brzezinski on ABC's This Week. He served as President
Carter's national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say Clinton must meet with Yeltsin to
show support for democratic and economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants a weak Russia beset by crisis,'' said Samuel
``Sandy'' Berger, the president's national security adviser.
``American has a strong interest in preventing Russia from
backsliding and in promoting its stability and success.''
</P>
<P>
   But few experts expect any significant agreements to spring from
the session.
</P>
<P>
   Into this unsettled cauldron steps an American president
weakened by domestic scandal and a Russian president who twice
sacked his Cabinet in five months and who defies wholesale calls
for his ouster, but then again, maybe already has agreed to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have two presidents who are extremely weak domestically,
each of whom has a legislature that isn't in much of a mood to give
them anything. You've got elites in both capitals calling for each
president to step down. You've got investors fleeing Russia. You've
got social unrest growing. And so the Bill and Boris Show is not a
particularly compelling spectacle,'' said Jim Goldgeiger, a
political science professor at George Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Goldgeiger said, ``It is important for the president to
go on this trip, despite the fact the timing isn't great, because
the stakes are larger than simply the current economic crisis in
Russia, and he does need to reaffirm the Western commitment to this
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a growing breach between the United States and Russia
on several major issues.
</P>
<P>
   On the economic front, Russia has resisted Western demands for
greater market reforms, instead seeking to prop up the ruble with
installments from the $23-billion bailout provided last month by
the International Monetary Fund. Still, the ruble tumbled last
week, amid an enormous government debt and a failing banking
system, and sparked panic among Russians and investors.
</P>
<P>
   To contain the economic free fall, Yeltsin turned again to
former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, a go-slow advocate whom
Yeltsin had dismissed only five months ago. Communists, who now
dominate the Duma, also made a resurgence, calling for greater
state control and the nationalization of some industries.
Chernomyrdin pledged anew to stick with a market economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The choices that Russia makes in the next few weeks and the
next several months will be crucial in determining its economic
future and, as the president has said, the way in which the Russian
people define their greatness,'' said Larry Summers, deputy
treasury secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our belief that a move back towards centralized
planning, based on price controls and administrative allocation of
goods and systematic controls would be a serious policy error, and
very unfortunate with respect to Russia's economic prospects going
forward,'' Summers said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the IMF nor Western nations could offer hope of another
bailout because of a lack of money. In the United States, Congress
has little stomach for providing any aid to Russia, especially
because of its military sales to Iran and India.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and the United States also have differences on Kosovo,
Iraq and the bombing of terrorists' camps in Afghanistan. The Duma
also refuses to pass START II, the nuclear arms reduction pact.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's financial participation into the construction of the
international space station also is in question. Its control over
nuclear proliferation and its own weapons has sparked concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russian military is performing almost none of the
traditional missions that a military is supposed to perform,
whether it's internal control, prevention of internal
disintegration or border control, air surveillance, space
surveillance, protection of Russian territory from possible
convention invasions ... to nuclear deterrents,'' said Bruce Blair,
a Russian military expert at the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., who will accompany the president to
Russia, suggested Sunday on ABC's This Week that Clinton and
Yeltsin may sign a pact to reduce the amount of plutonium each
country has for use in nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to strike some agreements or tentative
agreements,'' said Domenici. ``This is a rather big announcement
with reference to our relationship regarding nuclear weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will meet with Yeltsin, Chernomyrdin and Duma leaders
during his time in Russia. He and Yeltsin also will hold a news
conference on Wednesday which will be the first time Clinton has
faced reporters since admitting an ``inappropriate relationship''
with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will travel to Belfast, Northern Ireland, on Thursday
and later visit with victims of the recent Omagh car bombing. He
will visit Dublin and Limerick before leaving Ireland on Saturday,
after playing golf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
