u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUTH-MARCH-LEADER-AR     08-30 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUTH-MARCH-LEADER-ART-760(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KHALLID ABDUL MUHAMMAD, HEAD OF MILLION YOUTH MARCH: FROM PUBLIC
EYE TO OBSCURITY AND BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., N.Y., Texas)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Few people outside the Nation of Islam knew much
about Khallid Abdul Muhammad in November 1993, when, as the top
aide to Louis Farrakhan, he railed so viciously against whites,
Jews, Catholics, homosexuals and black civil rights leaders in a
lecture at a small New Jersey college that Congress denounced him
and Farrakhan eventually dismissed him from his post.
</P>
<P>
   Until a few weeks ago, it seemed he was well on his way back
into obscurity. Now, however, fresh from victory over Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani in a federal courtroom last week, where a judge cleared
the way for his Million Youth March in Harlem Saturday, Muhammad is
about to take center stage. It promises to be his most visible
platform yet.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad's improbable return to the public eye may surprise or
disappoint those who dismissed him as a hatemonger on the lunatic
fringe, a rabble-rouser on the college lecture circuit, a pointed
but powerless reminder of how much remains unhealed in U.S. race
relations.
</P>
<P>
   But while New Yorkers are finding that they must deal with
Muhammad, or at least with his venomous words, precisely who he is
and what he represents have long been largely a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with friends, followers and others who have known
Muhammad since he was an aspiring Methodist minister in his teens
named Harold Moore Vann depict a man of exceptional abilities and
ambition. He grew up amid segregation and Jim Crow, came of age in
the turbulent 1960s and quickly fell under the spell of the
charismatic Farrakhan, perhaps his first and certainly his most
influential father figure.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Muhammad, who is 50 but looks 35, displays his talents in
every speech, combining a debater's knack for argument with a
preacher's rhythms and tones, a stand-up comic's ear for ethnic
mimicry and an actor's awareness of his own physical presence. His
agenda for the Million Youth March explicitly evokes the black
radicalism of the 1960s: ``Black power, black nationalism,
Pan-Africanism, and black liberation theology.'' He tells close
associates that he is reprising Malcolm X's role as the
ultranationalist heir apparent of the Nation of Islam, literally
doing the math to show the similarities in the generation gaps
between the two and their mentors.
</P>
<P>
   And he at every turn seems preoccupied by his estranged
``spiritual father,'' seeking Farrakhan's approval, disapproving of
his move toward the mainstream, hoping aloud for a rapprochement
but at the same time challenging him for the hearts and minds of
young, disaffected inner-city black men.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad's past is rife with contradictions. By all accounts a
brilliant student in high school, he left college without a degree
and abandoned Christianity for a religious movement whose
interpretations of history, human genetics and even Scripture have
been attacked by mainstream scholars again and again as misguided
at best, intellectually dishonest at worst. He is described as
having boundless love for his people and Islam. But while minister
at a mosque in Atlanta in the late 1980s, facing federal charges
that he had lied on a mortgage application, he pressured a follower
to perjure herself to cover up his own crime, a law enforcement
official said. The official said he then ordered other congregants
_ including the woman's husband _ to shun her.
</P>
<P>
   Though Muhammad clearly exults in the language and theater of
violence, wishing grisly deaths to his enemies and brandishing
assault weapons for photographers, even some followers have begun
to doubt there is more to this than bluster.
</P>
<P>
   And while Muhammad displays a showman's concern for hype and
presentation _ having inflated his own credentials in claiming an
apparently unearned doctorate, or instructing a group of Harlem
children to embrace him when a photographer approached last week _
he appears conflicted about cultivating his own celebrity. After
agreeing to, and then refusing, a lengthy interview for this
article, he explained that he had no time. He also rejected an
offer that a reporter follow him as he promoted the Million Youth
March. ``To travel from city to city with a white man, who's trying
to do this kind of story on me, that other white folk can develop a
psychological profile from?'' he asked. ``I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he conceded that he had given such interviews to black
reporters for mainstream news organizations, he dropped the
subject. ``I'm just not sure I want white folks to know that much
about me,'' he said. ``I'd rather in some cases be an enigma. It's
safer.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad's origins are murky. He was born Harold Moore Jr. in
Texas in January 1948. But he may never have known his namesake. At
age 40, he called himself a ``poor widow's son.'' In a recent
television interview, he said he had been raised by another couple
entirely, but did not elaborate. And he has told others he was
raised by an aunt. ``There was always some missing link there, in
terms of that whole family structure,'' said a friend from his
youth, the Rev. Bob Hayes. ``It was a checkered kind of
background.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever may have troubled him at home, young Harold was a child
prodigy in church. ``From a little boy, I used to stand on the
porch and preach out to the cars as they would pass by,'' he told
Gil Noble of WABC's ``Like It Is'' last month. ``I preached my
first Sunday 11 o'clock hour sermon when I was about 11 years old.
They turned the big pulpit over to me.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he entered the all-black Phyllis Wheatley High
School in Houston in 1962, Harold Moore Jr. had become Harold Moore
Vann. He would graduate in 1966 as president of Houston's Methodist
Youth Fellowship, captain and quarterback of Wheatley's football
team, president of the drama club, an Eagle Scout, a star debater,
class officer and parliamentarian of the Beau Brummels _ a select
group of male student leaders chosen for their character and
potential.
</P>
<P>
   But despite his considerable charisma and popularity, Harold,
nicknamed ``Preacher,'' never seemed to develop any close
friendships, recalled the Rev. Thomas Wallace, a teammate who went
on to play a season with the Dallas Cowboys. ``He was a
quarterback, and a motivator,'' he said fondly. ``In the huddle,
he'd be really animated, and have this grim face all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Aided by church leaders in his hometown, Harold Vann won a
scholarship to Dillard University, a Methodist school in New
Orleans, and has said he fully intended to enter the ministry. He
studied sociology and, he told Noble, spent a semester or two at
Harvard on an exchange program. But he found himself moving away
from the church and gravitating towards the black liberation
theology that had been gaining adherents since the assassination of
Malcolm X in 1965. He says said he slowly began to realize ``what
the white man did with Christianity, and how he used the good name
of Jesus, the black revolutionary Messiah...to justify slavery and
oppression, and to justify conquering the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad's conversion, he has said for years, became complete
one day in 1967, when Farrakhan paid a visit to the Dillard Campus.
Farrakhan was then a top aide to Elijah Muhammad, leader of the
Chicago-based Nation of Islam, then known as the Black Muslims. ``I
had never heard such an exegesis of Scripture,'' he would say.
Farrakhan, meanwhile, apparently saw in the fierce young Texan an
ideal protege.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said to me that day, `You're going to be a great, great
help in the salvation of our people, and the freedom and
independence of our people,' Muhammad recalled on ``Like It Is.''
``I said I'd never be a member of the Nation of Islam, but the next
time I saw him, after doing a lot of research and trying to
disprove him, and taking professors from the campus to disprove
him, I had pretty much converted myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaving Dillard without a degree in 1970, Muhammad entered the
Nation of Islam in Chicago and quickly rose through the ranks,
using the names Harold 2X and Maleek Rashadeen along the way. But
when Elijah Muhammad died in 1975, his son took charge of the
Nation of Islam and renounced black separatism. Farrakhan went into
seclusion. Muhammad, disillusioned, quit a year later and moved to
Africa, where he traveled extensively and where he says he flirted
with a career as a mercenary soldier.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, after the Nation of Islam had all but dissolved in
financial disarray, Farrakhan determined to revive it and rebuild
it. One of the first people he called on for help was his former
protege, who quickly returned home. For the next three years, the
two drove across the country organizing study groups and mosques in
big cities and backwaters. In 1981, Farrakhan announced the rebirth
of the Nation of Islam. Khallid Abdul Muhammad, one of his top
lieutenants, would begin to move from city to city and mosque to
mosque, raising money, training members in paramilitary groups,
organizing security patrols in inner-city housing projects _ and
always preaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things they did effectively was to point out that
black people were not the villains in the drama between blacks and
whites in America, but the victims,'' said a close associate of
both men who insisted on anonymity. ``To do that, they dramatized
it with their speech. They called the white man the Devil. The
reason was most of the black people they were speaking to were
Christians. The point was not to get blacks to hate white people,
but to stop loving them.''
</P>
<P>
   But the message was filled with hatred nonetheless, particularly
of Jews, whom Farrakhan accused of playing a disproportionate role
in the slave trade _ a theory that has been broadly debunked _ and
oppressing blacks through what he has characterized as Jewish
control of the publishing, banking and entertainment industries. By
the 1990s, Muhammad was a regular on the campus lecture tour, where
many black students cheered his ethnic chauvinism and news coverage
naturally focused on his hate-filled tirades. He reserved some of
his harshest words, in fact, for black civil rights leaders and
elected officials who showed any signs of apologizing, conciliating
or compromising with whites. By contrast, he presented himself as a
pillar of strength. He would say the most outrageous things _
claiming that ``hook-nosed, bagel-eating, lox-eating,
perpetrating-a-fraud so-called Jews'' had planted AIDS in Africa _
and would never back down.
</P>
<P>
   His 1993 speech at Kean College in Union, N.J., however, would
drive a wedge between Muhammad and Farrakhan, who had begun to
soften his own rhetoric in hopes of forging an alliance with the
NAACP and other mainstream black leaders. Though Muhammad's tirade
was nothing new, critics of Farrakhan seized upon it to show he had
not changed. The Anti-Defamation League published excerpts from the
speech in a full-page ad in The New York Times in January 1994.
Facing a barrage of criticism, Farrakhan suspended Muhammad from
his position as national spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Muhammad has continued to shock audiences on the
lecture circuit, but had otherwise largely disappeared from the
news. Moreover, he always speaks glowingly of Farrakhan, keeping
speculation alive that theirs was a divorce of convenience, a
charade for white consumption. Asked about this, Muhammad recently
likened their relationship to that of an estranged father and son
whom, he hoped, might one day reconcile. But he confirmed that he
had been permanently barred from Nation of Islam mosques.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in the last three years, Muhammad, whose sources of
income are unclear, moved to New York and bought a brownstone on
Striver's Row in Harlem. Aides say that he is divorced. He has a
13-year old son who is helping to organize the march.
</P>
<P>
   Once banished by Farrakhan, Muhammad began formulating a new
strategy, his associates said _ one that would draw on his roots in
1960s radicalism, his grassroots organizing in the 1970s, his
courting of rap artists in Los Angeles in the 1980s and the mass
demonstrations organized by his mentor, Farrakhan, beginning with
the Million Man March in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   He surrounded himself with acolytes and continued reaching out
to young Nation of Islam members across the country, sensing that
many would respond to his angry, defiant words more than to
Farrakhan's somewhat less strident oratory. Yet the size of
Muhammad's following is impossible to know, despite his and his
aides' claims of mass appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful that he could neither seek nor expect mass defections
from the Nation of Islam, Muhammad branched out, helping to
organize the New Black Panther Party and the New Black Muslims in
Texas. In June, for example, he and several dozen armed members of
the groups marched in Jasper, Texas, to protest the murder of James
Byrd, a black hitchhiker dragged to his death behind a car by three
men who allegedly belonged to the Ku Klux Klan. But his appearance
angered local residents and the victim's family.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Muhammad has gotten what he wanted so far. In
provoking Giuliani over the Million Youth March he galvanized
support in Harlem for what had been a virtually unknown event. But
that support has come with loud disclaimers of Muhammad's beliefs.
It remains to be seen whether even a large showing on Saturday will
produce masses of volunteers for the army that Muhammad hopes to
build.
</P>
<P>
   But those who have known him longest say that Muhammad's moment
in the sun may be an end in itself. ``I really don't know which is
the true Khallid, or which one is there for the show,'' said Hayes,
his childhood friend from Houston. ``I know that he has a passion
for what he's doing, but where does that passion stop, and where
does the desire for attention begin?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
