<SLUG> BC-FERRARO-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERRARO FINDS TEPID TURNOUT ON CAMPAIGN STOP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEDFORD, N.Y. _ Ignoring the other Democratic candidates who
hope to run against Sen. Alfonse D'Amato in November's general
election, Geraldine Ferraro leveled an attack on Sunday against the
Republican incumbent as if the race between them were a foregone
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Calling herself ``the best alternative to 18 years of D'Amato,''
Ms. Ferraro referred only obliquely to her opponents in the Sept.
15 Democratic primary: Mark Green, the New York City public
advocate, and Rep. Charles Schumer of Brooklyn. She sharply
criticized D'Amato's record on health care, education, gun control,
abortion and campaign finance. She noted that D'Amato had raised
millions of dollars for his re-election while repeatedly voting
against changing campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been horrendous raising funds for this campaign,'' said
Ms. Ferraro, who supports requiring full disclosure of all campaign
finance information and providing free television air time for
candidates, among other changes. If raising funds ``doesn't
corrupt, it certainly gives the perception of corruption,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But if Ms. Ferraro had hoped to revitalize the primary race with
strong words, she may have been disappointed. Her appearance here
in Westchester County was lightly publicized, and only a few
passersby stopped to listen as she spoke on the village green. Most
of her speech, which lasted 20 minutes, was delivered to three
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Even afterward, reaction was tepid at a private brunch where,
along with a gubernatorial candidate, Betsy McCaughey Ross, and an
attorney general candidate, state Sen. Catherine Abate, Ms. Ferraro
spoke to about 100 local Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Weisberg, who had driven to Bedford on an
antiques-buying trip, noticed Ms. Ferraro speaking on the village
green and wandered over to ask her whether she thought D'Amato's
fight against Swiss banks on behalf of Holocaust survivors had been
motivated simply by political opportunism. She responded that
whatever the motive, D'Amato's achievement was undeniable.
</P>
<P>
   ``She projects an honesty that could be very good for
Congress,'' Weisberg said later.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ferraro, who once taught school, promised if elected to
fight for 100,000 more teachers statewide. She pledged to protect
Social Security and to push for a higher minimum wage, each an area
where she said D'Amato had let down the electorate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
