<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-575(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM MOSTLY WRONG TO JUST ABOUT RIGHT  
 EX-COLUMNIST WON'T JOIN BOOK TOUR THIS FALL  
 CALIFORNIA COUPLE SUE HORSE-SAVVY AUTHOR  
 AN HBO ADVERTISEMENT MAKES THE FRONT PAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Calif.)  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Evidently, being right can excuse at least a few sins.
</P>
<P>
   Seven months ago, when word emerged that President Clinton might
have had a sexual relationship with the former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky, public reaction to the news coverage was
overwhelmingly negative.
</P>
<P>
   A public opinion poll by the nonprofit Media Studies Center in
early February found that 36 percent of the respondents said the
media had done a ``good'' or ``excellent'' job on the subject.
Eighty percent of those surveyed said the coverage had been
``excessive.''
</P>
<P>
   Another poll done at the same time by another nonprofit
organization, the Pew Research Center for the People and the Press,
found that 60 percent of the people said the press was not being
objective enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of public opinion was close to outrage in early
February,'' said Andrew Kohut, research director of the Pew
Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a confession makes.
</P>
<P>
   Two surveys released last week, based on polls conducted after
Clinton's recent admission that he did have an ``inappropriate''
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, found that the public's opinion of
the media coverage had improved measurably.
</P>
<P>
   The Media Studies Center reported that almost half of the people
surveyed now say the news media have done a ``good'' or
``excellent'' job. The poll also found that more people now said
they believed that Clinton and Ms. Lewinsky were treated fairly.
</P>
<P>
   A poll by the Pew Research Center found a similar change.
Fifty-five percent now gave an assessment of ``excellent'' or
``good'' to the coverage, up from 42 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public was saying, `You told us too much about it, but on
reflection you were right and therefore we think you did a better
job than you were doing in January,''' said Bob Giles, executive
director of the Media Studies Center.
</P>
<P>
   _ DYLAN LOEB MCCLAIN
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Columnist Won't Join Book Tour This Fall
</P>
<P>
   When it comes time to promote ``Africans in America'' this fall,
one co-author will be missing in literary action from Harcourt
Brace's planned eight-city tour to promote the weighty book about
slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Smith, the former Boston Globe columnist _ who helped
write the book as a companion to a four-part public television
documentary on slavery _ will not participate in a book tour,
because her personal trouble could overshadow news coverage of the
title, said the editor in chief of Harcourt's adult division, Jane
Isay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to talk about the book and not her situation,''
Ms. Isay said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith was forced to resign from The Globe this summer after
admitting that she had fabricated characters in four recent
columns. A review by the newspaper turned up evidence of
fabrications in 48 other columns.
</P>
<P>
   Before her resignation, Ms. Smith submitted the manuscript for
``Africans in America,'' a nonfiction account of slavery from the
landing in Jamestown to the Civil War. The account was based on
material gathered by a documentary research team for WGBH in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith's co-author, Charles Johnson _ who won the National
Book Award for ``The Middle Passage'' in 1990 _ wrote short fiction
stories inspired by the same WGBH research.
</P>
<P>
   The final manuscript was reviewed by WGBH, said Ms. Isay, who
praised Ms. Smith's writing as ``outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been checked and double-checked and we stand by it,'' Ms.
Isay said.
</P>
<P>
   _ DOREEN CARVAJAL
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   California Couple Sue Horse-Savvy Author
</P>
<P>
   The gushing publicity for the best-selling author Monty Roberts
likens him to a compassionate ``real-life horse whisperer'' who is
a hybrid of gentle James Herriot and straight-talking John Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   But Roberts, a well-known horse trainer and author of ``The Man
Who Listens to Horses,'' is now facing a lawsuit filed by a wealthy
California couple who say that their thoroughbred suffered a broken
leg and improper treatment during a controversial experiment
presided over by Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   The suit grew out of a BBC documentary, which filmed Roberts
last year as he demonstrated horse-gentling techniques on a wild
mustang, which ultimately was allowed to choose between returning
to the California desert of the Cuyama Valley and joining with
tamed horses.
</P>
<P>
   Charging fraud and negligence, Carolyn and Christopher Carradine
_ the brother of the actor Keith Carradine _ say they boarded their
horse, Big Red Fox, at Roberts' 186-acre Solvang farm because of
his humane training techniques. But they contend that Roberts used
their horse initially in the wild mustang project without their
permission.
</P>
<P>
   During the documentary's second stage, the couple permitted
their horse to participate, but they contend that Roberts
unexpectedly released Big Red into the wild and offered only
minimal care after the horse was found later with bruises, cuts and
a broken leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're outraged,'' said Gerard Fox, a Los Angeles lawyer who
filed the civil lawsuit for the Carradines in Santa Barbara
Superior Court in April. ``They feel that their horse was used as a
guinea pig, and Monty showed a very aggressive side. You're talking
about two very sophisticated individuals who felt they were being
sold a bill of goods.''
</P>
<P>
   The Carradines are seeking up to $100,000 for expenses like
veterinary care, plus an unspecified amount in punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, who earlier this year was honored for his humane
treatment of horses by the American Society for the Prevention of
Cruelty to Animals, did not respond when messages were left seeking
comments on the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   His publicist, Diana DeRosa, said she was with Roberts during
the BBC filming and witnessed his efforts to care for Big Red.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was extremely attentive, and a vet was right there,'' Ms.
DeRosa said. ``It was the middle of the night and they ended up
driving about a hundred miles to the closest vet because the owner
wanted a second opinion. The vet was right there when it happened
and he was not overly concerned. He took care of it and said this
is not a bad wound.''
</P>
<P>
   _ DOREEN CARVAJAL
</P>
<P>
   An HBO Advertisement Makes the Front Page
</P>
<P>
   A newspaper's front page as advertising space?
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 21, the front pages of the metro and late city editions
of The New York Post read: ``U.S. to Terrorists: Take That!''
</P>
<P>
   But on the front page of a few thousand specially printed vanity
editions that turned up on the desks of media executives,
television critics, restaurateurs and other New York taste makers
was an advertisement for HBO's movie ``The Rat Pack.''
</P>
<P>
   The headline read: ``Comin' At Ya Sat. 9PM HBO.''
</P>
<P>
   Calls placed to editors on the Post's news desk that night
yielded more questions than answers: ``I don't know what you're
talking about. What advertisement? Maybe it was a hoax.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   The 3,000 or so papers with the HBO headline were a promotional
stunt paid for by HBO, a subsidiary of Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was simply a paid promotion,'' said Howard Rubenstein, a
spokesman for Rupert Murdoch, chairman of The Post and its parent,
News Corp. ``From time to time, the New York Post prints a few
thousand copies for advertising purposes at the end of a run.''
</P>
<P>
   The papers were not distributed to the public or sold at
newsstands, Rubenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   _ CHARLIE LeDUFF
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
