<SLUG> BC-BBN-DRUG-INFOBOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACTS ON ANDROSTENEDIONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Sidebar with BBN-MCGWIRE-DRUGS) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Androstenedione is called a precursor to testosterone, the male
hormone, because it is converted to testosterone in the body.
Scientists say there have been hardly any independent studies of
androstenedione. Promotional literature, citing reports from East
Germany, where androstenedione was first synthesized, says it can
temporarily triple testosterone levels from normal in a typical
male who has taken 100 milligrams. High testosterone levels are
said to speed recovery from workouts and help build muscle mass
during the workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists disagree on whether those testosterone levels can be
further elevated with higher doses, or whether _ as the
manufacturers contend _ the body has a built-in ceiling. The
companies say that precursors can boost testosterone only so far
and that anything more is flushed from the body. Other scientists
say they are not so certain, and their concern is that people in
training will take far more than the recommended dosage.
</P>
<P>
   Sustained artificially high levels of testosterone in men have
been linked to a long list of problems, from shrinkage of the
testicles and development of breast tissue to decreased sperm count
and hair loss. In women, high levels can cause growth of facial
hair, loss of menstrual periods and deepening of the voice. They
can lead to stunted height in teen-agers because of changes in bone
growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
