<HEADER>
A9742 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIANA-MEMORIAL31-COX     08-30 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIANA-MEMORIAL31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One year after Diana's death, mourners gather in Paris
 &HT;    By Bert Roughton Jr.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Catherine Jones solemnly set out the 36 candles she
crafted in Diana's likeness around the golden ``Flamme de la
Liberte'' on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, an artist from Vancouver, Canada, painted each of the
8-inch likenesses of Diana, her crowned blond head bowed shyly over
an evening dress, and brought them to the Place de l'Alma to give
expression to her feelings about Diana. There was one candle for
each of Diana's years at the time of her death last Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to do something through my art to take note of
one of the most important global happenings,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The Place de l'Alma lies above the tunnel where the black
Mercedes Benz bearing Diana, her boyfriend Dodi al-Fayed, a driver
and a bodyguard crashed, killing all but the bodyguard.
</P>
<P>
   The golden flame was a gift from Americans to thank France on
the centennial of its presentation of the Statue of Liberty, but
over the past year it has become a monument to the princess of
Wales. Messages to the late princess are scrawled all over the
20-foot-tall gold-plated sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday the flame became a focal point for people marking the
anniversary of Diana's death. Throughout the day people brought
flowers and cards, photographs, teddy bears, and even hairbrushes,
to leave at the shrine.
</P>
<P>
   At the exact moment of Diana's death _ 12:26 a.m. local time
Monday (6:26 EDT Sunday) _ the 36 candles circling the base of the
sculpture flickered in a soft Parisian breeze. But the candlelight
was washed out in the glare of TV cameras on hand to capture the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Although the unofficial commemoration was touted as a major
event expected to draw 10,000 mourners, the crowd _ not counting
the mass of reporters, cameramen and photographers _ rarely
exceeded 40 to 50 people. Of those, most were tourists attracted to
the flame by the lights glinting off its gold skin.
</P>
<P>
   The proportion of reporters to tourists and mourners at times
was such that TV crews waited in line to capture the observations
of people with guidebooks in their pockets and cameras dangling
around their necks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much emotion, is there?'' observed Martin Buckley,
a Tewkesbury, England, resident who watched attentively from a
nearby bench. ``I have seen only a few people actually come here to
mourn and show feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Buckley spent three nights sleeping outside
Westminster Abbey in London in order to be at the front of the
crowd gathered for Diana's wedding. He and his parents were among
the first to tour Althorp House, on the family estate where Diana
is buried. He intends to write a book chronicling his personal
journey through Diana's death.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Auberge, who stayed an hour at the flame with her two
small children, said she came because of her feelings about Diana.
``She was so wonderful, so human, with all the human frailties and
qualities that make people interesting,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' said the woman as she hoisted one of her little ones on
a hip, ``she was a wonderful mother.''
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony in Paris, organized by a private group called Paris
Odysee, began a series of events that some in London have come to
call ``Diana Day.''
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, state flags will fly at half-staff, there will be
prayers at Westminster Abbey, and a fountain commemorating the
princess and Dodi will be unveiled at Harrod's department store,
owned by Dodi's father, Mohammad al-Fayed.
</P>
<P>
   Bouquets of flowers were placed outside Kensington Palace, the
scene of massive displays of grief a year ago. Even though the
London newspapers were reporting on the ``Diana fatigue'' brought
on by media overkill of the anniversary, each of them devoted
substantial space to remembering the princess.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Althorp House in Northamptonshire, 3,000 people lined up
to tour the estate before it is closed to the public Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, the royal family will hold a private ceremony in
Balmoral Castle in Scotland, where Diana's sons, William and Harry,
were informed a year ago of her death. Prime Minister Tony Blair
and his wife, Cherie, also are expected to attend the service.
</P>
<P>
   There have been few public comments from members of the royal
family or other important public figures on the subject of Diana's
death.
</P>
<P>
   Buckingham Palace issued a brief statement Sunday afternoon.
``The queen and the royal family, particularly the prince of Wales,
Prince William and Prince Harry, would like to thank people for
their messages and kind gestures of sympathy at this sad time and
for sharing their remembrances of the princess of Wales.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
