 SPORTS COLUMN: McGWIRE LET HIS TEAM _ AND HIS FANS _ DOWN  
(EDS: In the quote in graf 13, ``owe'' is correct.) 
(lh) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Mark McGwire, a protagonist in one of the best
pieces of theater in America, pulled the curtain down on himself
Saturday afternoon even though the performance had hardly begun. He
did so in a most bizarre, if not selfish and silly, manner, and
within just a few feet of his son.
</P>
<P>
   Ten-year-old Matthew McGwire, wearing his father's name and
number _ 25 _ on the back of his Cardinal uniform, has served as a
batboy for parts of the summer: when he comes to town from San
Diego to visit his dad, one Mark David McGwire, a k a Leading
Contender in the Great Home Run Record Chase. On Saturday
afternoon, young McGwire, along with a near-capacity crowd of
47,627 in Busch Stadium, witnessed a remarkable event.
</P>
<P>
   No, he did not see his dad hit yet another home run _ McGwire
had 54 going into Sunday night's game against the Atlanta Braves,
even with Sammy Sosa of the Cubs and eight behind Roger Maris, the
record-holder since 1961. He witnessed his dad being thrown out of
a game, in the first inning, of all things, after arguing a called
third strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was good for Matthew to see that his father has
emotion,'' McGwire said before Sunday night's game. ``It was in the
heat of competition. I was doing whatever I can. I felt the umpire
took an at-bat away from me. So I let them know.''
</P>
<P>
   While emotion is surely part of the makeup of a champion, you
can hurt your team, disappoint a multitude and even damage to a
degree your chances at a historic record as a result of allowing
emotions to get out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Plate umpire Sam Holbrook beseeched Tony La Russa, the
Cardinals' manager, who came onto the field to defend his player:
``Tony, please get Mark out of here. I don't want to throw him out
of the game.'' McGwire admitted later that Holbrook had given him
the same warning directly three times.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was in the heat of competition, but the difference
between a professional and an amateur _ at least, the difference
between a professional's response and an amateur's response _ ought
to be that the professional keeps his head.
</P>
<P>
   Cus D'Amato, the late boxing trainer, said that the killer
instinct is something you seek to eliminate, because the fighter
should never lose his poise in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   And McGwire had to have had a good notion of what he was doing.
If the umpire had told him, for example, ``If you say one more
word, it's the magic word, and a piano will fall on your head,''
the odds are McGwire would have exited voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   The slugger has professed that the home-run chase is secondary
for him, that the team's results come first. He did not help his
team, however, by being thrown out _ they lost to the Braves, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   When Tom Glavine, the Braves' left-hander, whistled a 3-2 pitch
at or below McGwire's knees, and on or just inside of the plate,
Holbrook shouted strike three as McGwire was already moving toward
first base in anticipation of a ball-four call. Matthew watched
from near the on-deck circle as his father erupted in a fit of
pique. When his dad was thrown out, the fans grew unruly.
</P>
<P>
   They booed until they were hoarse, and then, if Holbrook still
hadn't gotten the drift, flung onto the field baseballs, bottles
and anything else they could find short of themselves. In the old
American tradition, the first thing the fans in the ball park
desired was to moider the umpire. Imagine throwing out the star
attraction, the very person people came from hundreds of miles
around to pay to see, for the fan base of the St. Louis Cardinals
covers nine states, from Arkansas to Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   It was a mass, ugly, stupid tantrum, but it was a macrocosm of
the tantrum thrown by McGwire. ``I said things to the umpire you
can't say on TV,'' he said. ``Did I cross the line? Yeah, I
probably crossed the line. I owe up to it. He had a right to throw
me out. I'm not any bigger than the game.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't heed the warning. The ump then had no choice. ``You
are not supposed to argue balls and strikes,'' McGwire said. ``The
umpire did his job. I'm not any bigger than the game.''
</P>
<P>
   This is noble. But McGwire is well aware that a majority of the
fans came solely to see him in his pursuit of the record. When
Humphrey Bogart asked Spencer Tracy what he believed a performer
owed the fans, Tracy replied, ``A good performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 30 people asked for their money back when McGwire was
ejected. There might have been thousands more _ people who paid
from $6 for a bleacher seat to $24 for a field box _ if it wasn't
clearly stipulated at the ticket window that all sales are final.
</P>
<P>
   While McGwire, whose salary is $8.3 million a season plus
incentives, can't reasonably refund the fans who wanted their money
back, he might donate, say, a buck a fan, or $47,627, to a charity
of his choice, as an expression of his acknowledged special
responsibility as a performer.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew McGwire would surely understand that emotion, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
