<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXTENT OF POLICY DIFFERENCES AMONG DEMOCRATIC CANDIDATES ARE AN
ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With a remote control clicker in his hand and a
television monitor at his back, Mark Green, a Democratic candidate
for U.S. Senate, whirled through campaign advertisements of one of
his opponents, Charles Schumer, the other afternoon, disputing
Schumer's claims at every frozen frame.
</P>
<P>
   With each pause, Green sought to demonstrate that on many
issues, there was a chasm between himself and Schumer, two of the
three Democrats seeking to unseat Sen. Alfonse D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   On topics including regulating health maintenance organizations
and assuring the future of Social Security _ issues that Schumer,
Green and the third Democratic Senate candidate, Geraldine Ferraro,
say are central to the Sept. 15 primary _ Green asserted that he
held a different and more traditionally Democratic position than
Schumer.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Democrats question Green's assessment, and Schumer
himself disputes it. ``There are some differences between us, but
the number of agreements overwhelm the number of differences,'' he
said. `'Overall, his attacks have been specious or trivial.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the actual extent of difference between these two
candidates _ Ms. Ferraro has been absent from this argument, giving
a speech on Sunday in Westchester County that focused entirely on
D'Amato _ has emerged as an ongoing dispute in this otherwise
subdued contest.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, the attacks by Green, who asserts that he is the
only true progressive in the race, are not surprising. Green, New
York City's public advocate, has little money for television
advertisements and so has become the squeaky wheel on the political
train, trying to capture the attention that the famous Ferraro can
take for granted and that Schumer can afford to buy through
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   But as a matter of policy, the question is decidedly more
complex.
</P>
<P>
   On a handful of issues, the record shows significant differences
between Schumer and Green. But in combing through Schumer's 18
years as a congressman from Brooklyn, Green has seized on sometimes
isolated votes or bills to try to place Schumer on the wrong side
of an issue. Schumer asserts that in some instances Green has
misrepresented his position or taken a vote out of context.
</P>
<P>
   Green, as New York's public advocate, is immune from such
attacks: he has not cast a legislative vote in his public life.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has so far involved only Green and Schumer. Green
has largely ignored Ferraro _ aides say he now views Schumer as the
leading candidate _ while Ferraro's campaign has for the most part
not engaged in a detailed discussion of issues. Ferraro's office,
in response to a request, provided her positions on the issues that
are now being debated by Green and Schumer.
</P>
<P>
   There are some issues on which Green and Schumer hold clearly
different views. Schumer, who is on the House Banking Committee,
voted in May for legislation to lift many of the Depression-era
restrictions on banks, insurance companies and securities firms.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer argued that the bill accommodated the changing terrain
of the financial industry and would promote competition and
commerce. ``In my view, competition benefits consumers,'' Schumer
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Green asserted that the bill made it easier for banks to raise
consumer fees and to deny loans in poor and minority neighborhoods.
``Here's a bill that the White House opposed, that the majority of
Democrats opposed, that the congressman voted for, and it passed by
one vote'' in the House, Green said. He asserted that Schumer was
motivated less by ideology and more by the stream of contributions
from the banking industry, a charge Schumer denied. Ferraro would
have voted against the banking bill, her aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Green and Schumer also hold contrary views on 1995 securities
legislation that restricted the ability of shareholders to sue
corporate officers, accountants and underwriters. Schumer voted
with the majority in the House in overriding Clinton's veto.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said legislation was needed to guard against frivolous
and harassing lawsuits directed at corporations. Green called it an
``anti-shareholder'' bill. Ms. Ferraro would also have opposed the
bill, her office said.
</P>
<P>
   Green has also attacked Schumer for supporting the line-item
veto sought by President Clinton (and backed, as Green likes to
note, by Newt Gingrich, the speaker of the House.) Ferraro opposes
the line-item veto.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer supported legislation prohibiting the federal government
from imposing mandates on local governments without financing them,
and voted against making an exception in cases involving ordering
schools to clean up asbestos. Green opposed the measure. Ferraro
supports the so-called unfunded mandates law, but would have
supported the exemption, her aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Green opposes the death penalty, while Schumer, who once shared
Green's view, has come to support it, as does Ferraro.
</P>
<P>
   But the differences become far more murky on other matters. For
example, Green attacked Schumer on Sunday for supporting an
immigration restriction bill in 1996 that included a provision that
barred the legally born children of illegal immigrants from
attending public schools. Schumer said he opposed the provision,
but supported much of the rest of the bill. He said he voted to
send it to conference in hopes the offending provision would be
stricken, and opposed the final bill when it was not.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Green attacked Schumer for the vote, and challenged
his explanation. ``Did he say that at the time?,'' Green asked.
``When he says that as an election-year response to me, I'm a
little suspicious.'' Schumer's office noted that, in fact, he had
written a letter to Congress at the height of the debate explicitly
opposing the provision.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Green points to a handful of votes Schumer cast in
the 1980s against cutting off funds for the Strategic Defense
Initiative, the so-called Star Wars missile defense program.
Schumer said they were isolated votes, and that he had since, in
words and votes, repeatedly stated his opposition to the program.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said this was a case of Green's invoking a deceptively
outdated vote, while Green called it an example of Schumer's
changing his position in preparation for the campaign. ``The key
votes on SDI did occur a decade ago,'' Green said. ``So when the
issue was ripe, the congressman did oppose amendments to the
Pentagon budget that would have curtailed the Reagan star wars
program.''
</P>
<P>
   Green's most recent attacks on Schumer have been on two
subjects: First, that he is not committed to Clinton's call to use
projected federal surpluses to shore up Social Security, and
second, that he wavered on giving patients the right to sue their
HMOs. In both cases, Green backs up his assertion by pointing to
bills Schumer introduced over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Green asserted that Schumer was trying to change his political
profile to adjust to the dynamics of this Senate race, for example
to Social Security legislation Schumer introduced days after Green
first raised the issue. ``It raises questions about whether he's a
consistent progressive advocate on all these issues, or whether
he's more a politician trimming his sails to adjust to the
political winds,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   But Schumer said that Green was again invoking early drafts of
legislation, and that he had in fact made clear, in later bills and
public statements, that he believed patients should have a right to
sue and that the surplus should go first to Social Security. ``From
the day the president said, `Let's put the surplus to Social
Security,' I was for it,'' Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sort of reminds me of when I was in the anti-war movement
in college, and there was a small group of people who said, `They
weren't against the war in 1965, they came out against in 1966, so
we shouldn't work with them,''' Schumer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
