<SLUG> BC-TEN-SAMPRAS-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS CLOSES IN ON TENNIS HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If he could, Pete Sampras would work undercover:
punch in unnoticed, punch out with Grand Slam titles at a clip his
contemporaries cannot come close to matching. But like it or not,
and he is trying to, this year is different. This year, the
cosmopolitan, and cosmic, side he never knew he had has been
showing up everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   All around Manhattan, his larger-than-life body, caught in
midlunge and brandishing a racquet fit for a giant, is stretched
across the flanks of city buses advertising his starring role at
the U.S. Open, which begins Monday. At every newsstand that stocked
GQ's August issue, he could be seen as a cover boy swathed in
Armani and Jil Sander, smiling the same quizzical smile that shores
up his milk mustache in that unavoidable ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And not least of all, in this intensively record-conscious
summer of sport, he is surrounded by talk of his chances to make
tennis history the next two weeks. All he has to do is live up to
rank and reputation to tie Roy Emerson's career mark of 12 Grand
Slam titles by commandeering the Open a fifth time in his peerless
career.
</P>
<P>
   Since winning his fifth Wimbledon championship in July, a title
that put him on history's doorstep, there has been a lot for a
low-key guy like Sampras to download and downplay. And that is why
he repaired home to Orlando, Fla., where his house on a Lake Nona
fairway is so close to the airport that he can practically hail
airplanes like cabs, to spend the final week before the Open,
deprogramming his mind and reminding his body that there is lots of
best-of-five-set work to be done just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   His neighbors Nick Faldo and Jim Courier called and tempted him
with afternoon golf outings. But there was to be no golf for
Sampras, who did not like the way his energy fizzled at this year's
Australian Open and moved to Orlando solely to be within arm's
length of Pat Etcheberry, a Marine-minded conditioning specialist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever a Grand Slam comes around, everything else in my life
just stops dead,'' said Sampras, who takes a 1-0 record against
Marc-Kevin Goellner of Germany into the Open's opening round.
``There's something significant and historic about the Slams, and I
put a lot of internal pressure on myself to do well in them. That's
why I'm so miserable when I lose a Slam.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to talk about who's going to be No. 1,'' said
Sampras, who can break the record he shares with Jimmy Connors if
he ends the year at the top for the sixth straight season, ``I
think it's going to come down to who wins the Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the metaphysical implications of having his
bus-sized self chugging around the city that is host to the Open,
Sampras _ who has not, for the record, ever set foot on a city bus
_ responded with a wince. Asked about his stint as a model, the
27-year-old Sampras rolled his eyes and said: ``It was all right,
but it's probably something I'll do about once every 27 years.
Everybody wants to know if I kept the clothes: Nope.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the possibility of moving out of his tie with Rod
Laver and Bjorn Borg for second place and into a tie with Emerson
for the Grand Slam record, Sampras brightened. Is he tired of
talking about closing in on Emerson's record? Sure he is. But that
does not mean he isn't thrilled by the opportunity to make history.
</P>
<P>
   He never saw Emerson play, and became acquainted with Laver's
feats on videotape only because his former coach, Pete Fischer,
insisted that Laver, the only man to twice win the Grand Slam of
tennis in a calendar year, was worth emulating.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had no holes in his game, had every shot and could win on
all the surfaces,'' said Sampras, who is well aware that Laver
might have collected ``15 or even 20'' Grand Slam titles had he not
been barred from Grand Slam competition for nearly a decade after
turning pro.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It's not like I was going to actually play like him; he's a
lefty, I'm a righty, and I don't really think you can compare this
era to that one. But it's more the attitude he had; that's what my
coach and my father wanted for me. To have class like the Emersons,
Rosewalls, Lavers.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Emerson, who does not seem terribly upset about the
prospect of sharing his record, Sampras turned out to be the
perfect candidate to eclipse the Grand Slam inroads that he and his
fellow Australians made at midcentury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Records are made to be broken,'' Emerson said last week from
Boston. ``In my day, you were trying to win the Slams in order to
get a professional contract. Pete's playing now for love of the
game and the Slams, and probably to win the one he hasn't won yet,
the French. He's a complete player, a great sportsman, and he's no
actor out there. He gets on with it the way Rosewall and Laver got
on with it. They made the ball talk. People have to respect Pete's
game; I know I do.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Sampras, who lives in a $1.1 million house with
ceilings so high that Julius and Turquoise Irving were among its
prospective buyers, is just plain astounded that his racquet has
made the ball talk all the way to 11 Grand Slam titles. ``I never
thought anything like this would happen to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But other people did.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, with the entire Sampras family at the dinner
table, Sampras' iconoclastic first coach, Fischer, a California
pediatrician who is now serving a three-year prison term for
molesting a patient, held sway with his over-the-top
prognostications for the player's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, I didn't think it was realistic, what he
predicted would happen to me in my tennis career,'' said Sampras,
who has stood by Fischer and stays in contact by letter. ``The rest
of us would be sitting there eating, and he'd say things like,
`When Pete's done playing, people are going to forget about Laver.'
I just sat there and never said a thing. Here I was, this
13-year-old kid, eating my macaroni and cheese and thinking, `Wow,
what's this guy smoking?'''
</P>
<P>
   The player wasn't the only skeptic at the table. His father,
Sam, had his doubts as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad wasn't sure I had the heart and the whatever, I guess
the guts, to go along with the talent,'' Sampras said. ``I think
there was a question in his mind about how important it all was for
me.'' For a time, it was a valid question. The definitive step did
not come until the 1992 U.S. Open final, in which he surrendered to
Stefan Edberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad it happened because everything clicked in after
that,'' Sampras said. ``Until then, I wasn't sure if I hated to
lose, and in that match, I felt myself cave in and kind of give it
to him in the fourth set, like just being there was enough for me.
In the aftermath, I analyzed what I'd done, and it became real
clear that coming in second won't get you anything, just isn't good
enough. I've never caved in at a Slam since. I haven't won every
match, but at least I've made the other guy earn it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Sampras, who needs goals the way normal mortals need oxygen,
wins this Open and ties Emerson's record, then what?
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it gets interesting,'' he said. ``I mean, people love to
see people break records. I know I do. It's just a little
overwhelming that it's me who's doing it, that guys I always looked
up to, like Borg and Connors, now I'm up there with them.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's in passing gear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-98 2145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
