<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9762 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SYNAGOGUE-FIRE-NYT     08-30 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SYNAGOGUE-FIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFERS OF HELP POUR IN FOR DAMAGED SYNAGOGUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two days after a roaring fire devastated the historic
Central Synagogue on Manhattan's East Side, the senior rabbi of a
congregation suffering something akin to mourning looked beyond the
charred timbers and ruins of a magnificent landmark on Sunday and
saw some reasons for hope.
</P>
<P>
   There were offers of sites for his displaced congregation to
worship during the High Holy Days, starting on Sept. 20. There were
messages of condolence and support from across town and around the
world. And there were generous offers of help to rebuild the
126-year-old Moorish Revival temple, which lost its roof and much
of its interior on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn a great deal through every experience,'' the senior
rabbi, Peter Rubinstein, said in a telephone interview from his
study in the temple's community house across the street. ``There
are relative tragedies and traumas in life. But life itself is of
the utmost importance.''
</P>
<P>
   Terrible as the fire was, Rubinstein said, no one had been
killed or seriously hurt. Moreover, no irreplaceable Torah scrolls
or historic archives were lost, most having been removed earlier in
the summer for a renovation project. And the fire brought out the
best in people, from the firefighters and police officers on the
scene to government officials, religious colleagues and even
strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Rubinstein spoke of ``the extraordinary importance of friendship
and community as people have come forward, Jew and non-Jew alike,''
and recalled that ``among the first on the scene were some of my
Christian colleagues.'' He mentioned Cardinal John O'Connor and
``friends from other churches and synagogues,'' and added: ``They
were the source of my strength as I watched the building burn.''
</P>
<P>
   With the High Holy Days only three weeks off, Rubinstein said he
had received nearly 50 offers from churches, synagogues and the
city for places where his 1,400-member congregation _ and as many
as 3,500 others who join them during the 10 days that are Judaism's
most sacred _ could gather to worship.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the Central Synagogue, at 55th Street and Lexington
Avenue, has not had the capacity to accommodate more than its core
membership, and has had to hold two or more services daily during
the High Holy Days, the rabbi said. While no decision on a meeting
location has been made, Rubinstein said he hoped to find a space
large enough for the regular congregation and those who join them
on the High Holy Days.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity,'' he said. ``We're going to try to
keep the congregation together, to worship together, for the first
time in decades. At this time in particular, I think it's
important.''
</P>
<P>
   With multimillion-dollar rebuilding costs looming, he said, many
members of the congregation had made ``tremendous offers of
financial assistance'' to help restore the synagogue, a national
and city landmark.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how much the repairs will cost or how long they
might take, the rabbi said. One immediate task will be to cover the
roofless synagogue's gaping interior to prevent further damage.
Beyond that lay the removal of debris, a damage assessment, plans
for restoration and fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``My objective is to move as quickly as circumstances might
permit,'' Rubinstein said. ``It's not just technical and repair
work. There will be an artistic effort to restore the magnificent
interior. We plan to keep the building in character with its
history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
