<DOCNO> NYT19980830.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9781 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-KILLER-PROFILE-100     08-30 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KILLER-PROFILE-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFESSED KILLER WAS `NIGHT AND DAY, GOOD AND EVIL' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Vt.)  (mk) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joanne Donovan remembers how Gary Evans, her friend and lover
for the last eight years, ate. He was like a 10-year-old, she said,
subsisting on gallons of milk and boxes of Cocoa Puffs and
Freihofer's chocolate-chip cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Robbin Evans, his sister, remembers how he skateboarded with her
son and bounced on a trampoline as joyously as a child.
</P>
<P>
   Several other women who knew Evans described him as quiet,
gentle and caring. He bolstered their confidence. He liked to draw
mountains and write poems about freedom and the stars and pure
love.
</P>
<P>
   But police in Rensselaer County, N.Y., say something very
different: that Gary Evans, a professional antiques thief, was a
brutal multiple murderer who killed five men as coldly and
deliberately as an executioner.
</P>
<P>
   Jailed in May on charges relating to a theft, Evans, 43,
confessed to each of these killings over the summer, police say,
revealing the details bit by bit and directing officers to the
graves he had dug. Reports about the Evans case appeared all summer
in local newspapers and on TV news. To people in Troy, a
once-thriving industrial center about 15 miles north of Albany, and
throughout Rensselaer County, it was riveting.
</P>
<P>
   And two weeks ago, on the way from an Albany courthouse to the
jail in Troy, Evans provided a spectacular ending to his story.
Shackled hand and foot, he kicked out the window of a police van,
jumped out, hobbled to the edge of a bridge and plunged 65 feet to
his death in the rocky shallows of the Hudson River. In a note to
his lawyer, opened after his death, he had written: ``Stars
surround me and peace and love are mine. They cannot be taken or
touched. I win.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, an autopsy revealed that Evans had hidden a handcuff key
in one nostril and a sliver of razor in the other. The bizarre
story was reported around the country _ often with an old photo of
Evans, naked to the waist, with the physique of a bodybuilder. At
home, the most common reactions were anger and relief. Some people
were outraged that a killer in custody had managed to orchestrate
his death under the noses of police guards, but nearly everybody
was relieved to be rid of him.
</P>
<P>
   Then, amid the exclamations, some quieter voices emerged: a
dozen or more women who had been Evans' friends, and, in some
cases, lovers. They expressed shock and horror at the killings. The
person they were mourning, from their descriptions, was the
opposite of a ruthless killer.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Evans would not be the first killer with female
friends and relatives who loved him and knew his better qualities.
There are mothers, wives and girlfriends with nothing but good to
say about their men on death row.
</P>
<P>
   But the range of Evans' behavior was unusual, according to
professionals who work closely with murderers. He killed with the
easy viciousness of a disturbed child dismembering a bug, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his female friends remember him as a sympathetic listener
who went out of his way to encourage and help them. ``A woman and
kid protector,'' said Ms. Evans, his sister.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Donovan, 34, who reported him to police last spring when she
realized he may have murdered an acquaintance, said: ``He was very
affectionate and sweet to my daughter. He liked to play Nintendo
with her. He was always happy, always energetic. He made me feel
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Women who knew him as a teen-ager said that in some ways he was
as wholesome as a Boy Scout. At parties, when others were drinking
beer and smoking marijuana, he would bring a quart of milk to
drink, one woman said. As a teen-ager and an adult, he refused to
touch meat or alcohol or drugs, even aspirin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called him `Owl,' the wisest,'' said one 39-year-old woman,
a state administrator in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the death of Evans', a 34-year-old woman, who
spoke on the condition of anonymity, described an affair she had
with him 10 years ago. She was a young mother trapped in a bad
marriage when she met him one afternoon at a local pub and agreed
to see him. He took her to art museums and bought her son a red
tricycle. But mainly, he urged her to leave her abusive husband and
discussed the logistics of finding an apartment, a job and drawing
up a budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave me the courage to go out and make a new life for
myself and my son,'' she said. After nine months, she left her
husband. Within a week or so, Evans disappeared, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she said, she is happily remarried and has a good job.
``This man made me believe in myself again,'' she said. ``I was
going down the tubes. He gave me back my self-esteem. I could never
repay him.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time that he was restoring her confidence, Evans
committed his first murder. The victim, Michael Falco, 30, had
grown up in his neighborhood and occasionally lent him a hand
during thefts. After shooting Falco in the head to keep him from
talking about a burglary, he stuffed the body in the trunk of his
car, drove to Lake Worth, Fla., and buried it. Investigators found
the body this summer after he directed them to the grave site.
</P>
<P>
   Evans' long-ago lover said she felt numb, trying to fit the
killer with the caring friend she knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's night and day, good and evil,'' she said. ``I feel so
much sympathy for those victims. But I can't envision him as a
murderer. How can he be so kind and yet so brutal?''
</P>
<P>
   Evans had grown up with brutality, his sister said. Their father
frequently beat both children and their mother, who tried many
times to kill herself. When her brother was 7, Ms. Evans said, he
grabbed a butcher knife and tried futilely to stab his father, who
had been beating their mother.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, all of Evans' friends, even in high school,
were women; later, all of his victims were men.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the causes of his violence, one expert said that Evans'
seeming kindness was as cold and calculated as his killings. James
Merikangas, a Yale neurosurgeon and forensic psychiatrist, said
that a killer like Evans was ``incapable of feeling human
emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``They may appear to be caring,'' he said. ``But it's a
practiced deception.'' It is not possible, he added, for anyone to
feel empathy and also callously commit murder. The actions of a
sociopath like Evans, he said, are attempts to manipulate and
control anyone he deals with.
</P>
<P>
   According to law-enforcement authorities, Evans killed to
silence witnesses _three partners in thievery and two shopkeepers
during burglaries _ who might testify against him.
</P>
<P>
   But what did he gain by being kind to women _ and, for that
matter, children and animals? Probably it made him feel powerful,
Merikangas said. All the women he befriended were in vulnerable
situations. From the number of friends and the strength of their
feelings, it seems that Evans was able to mime sympathy much more
convincingly than most killers.
</P>
<P>
   He persuaded Ms. Donovan when Damien Cuomo, an antiques thief
and her live-in lover, disappeared in 1989. ``He'll be back,''
Evans assured her. ``He'll be back sometime.''
</P>
<P>
   Shattered at her lover's apparent desertion, Ms. Donovan came to
look forward to Evans' increasingly frequent visits. ``I started to
like him as a friend,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After a while, Evans practically moved in with her, and
eventually she realized she was in love with him. ``He was easy to
get along with,'' she said. ``He would lay on the couch and not
talk. He liked swimming and laying in the sun and relaxing.''
</P>
<P>
   He showed off his daredevil stunts for her, like diving 80 feet
into a lake. They went antiquing in Massachusetts. ``He bought me
things to make me laugh,'' she said. ``A stupid metal flower for
$15 _ ugly, ugly, ugly. I said, `Why?' And he started laughing and
I started laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   He talked to her about the dream house in Vermont that he was
going to build, on a mountaintop. And, to her distress, about his
thefts, confiding in greater detail as the months passed. She knew
that he, like Damien, was a thief, but wanted to know as little as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last year, after seeing an extremely agitated Evans drive
off with Timothy Rysedorph, another Troy friend, and return,
frantic and crazy-eyed, in Rysedorph's car alone, she figured it
out. That fall weekend in 1997, Evans fled Troy, violating his
probation and becoming a fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   When a police investigator approached Ms. Donovan a few weeks
later about Rysedorph's disappearance, she agreed to help. The
thefts did not particularly bother her, but murder did.
</P>
<P>
   It was months before she was able to turn Evans in. But in the
spring, he finally called her and asked her to meet him in St.
Johnsbury, Vt., where he was living the rugged life of a
survivalist.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over _ when police who accompanied her to Vermont
had arrested Evans before she could even give him a hug _ Ms.
Donovan felt ``crushed.'' With seven felony convictions, and facing
life imprisonment, Evans began confessing to the killings. One
victim was Ms. Donovan's live-in lover, the father of her child _
Damien Cuomo, whom he had forced to a remote area, handcuffed and
shot several times in the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I protected him all those years,'' Ms. Donovan said. ``But how
was I going to protect him when he killed my boyfriend?''
</P>
<P>
   But Evans, it seems, facing a life in prison _ even before any
murder charges _ had given up hope of life and was planning his
death. If he committed suicide in prison, Ms. Donovan said, he
thought they would have won. But if he could kill himself outside,
he would win.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had nothing to lose,'' she said. ``He wanted to go out with
a bang. He wanted to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
