</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Right field beats bench for Colbrunn
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Drafted as a catcher, converted to a first baseman,
Greg Colbrunn made his Atlanta debut as a right fielder Sunday
night. He was hardly about to complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new position,'' Colbrunn said. ``I've never played it
before. It's not like I'm going to be real comfortable out there or
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   So why go?
</P>
<P>
   ``Get some ABs.''
</P>
<P>
   Steady work has been hard to come by for Colbrunn since he
returned to Atlanta. He has been with the team for 28 games since
being acquired from Colorado July 30 and has had only 13 at-bats.
Sunday's was just his second start, having subbed for Andres
Galarraga for one game Aug. 2 after the regular first baseman was
bruised up from being hit by pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday, Colbrunn had one at-bat in the last eight games.
That he is hitting .385 since rejoining the Braves has not helped
him get to the plate more frequently.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have to use him (in the outfield) someday in the playoffs
or something, at least he's been out there,'' said manager Bobby
Cox. ``You never know.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies had used Colbrunn in the outfield four times this
season, though most of his training for the position has come from
shagging fly balls during batting practice. Cox had considered
using him there Thursday against Kent Mercker but backed off
because of Mercker's strong numbers against right-handers. Donovan
Osborne, St. Louis' starter Sunday, was a better fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way to get into the lineup,'' Colbrunn said. ``Any time
I get in the lineup, I'm very happy about it, whether it's
outfield, first base, whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   The lineup
</P>
<P>
   With Gerald Williams leading off and Colbrunn batting second,
Cox used his 63rd different lineup of the season, which may sound
like a lot but actually isn't. Cox utilized 87 lineups last season,
the second fewest variations in the National League. St. Louis'
Tony La Russa, by comparision, has used 119.
</P>
<P>
   Exploring with Rudy
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Seanez is in unfamiliar territory. After breaking in with
Cleveland in 1989, he has never spent a full season in the majors,
most often sidelined by injury. He just completed his third month
with the Braves and has shown no sign of wear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm starting to understand how they feel, going through a
full season,'' he said. ``The longest I've been around is July or
August.''
</P>
<P>
   With 30 innings pitched in 28 appearances entering Sunday,
Seanez has not yet passed his 1995 season for service (34 2/3
innings in 37 appearances for Los Angeles). But his 43 strikeouts
are a career-high and his 2.40 ERA is almost a third of his career
6.00 ERA accumulated over 91 games the previous nine years. And he
remains as strong physically as he ever has in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Seanez has been able to work on successive days three times this
month without incident. He has pitched in 13 games in August, one
fewer than Kerry Ligtenberg, who sat out the weekend with a
fatigued arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just don't get the pitch count up too high,'' he said. ``I've
felt good. I might need a little more time to warm up or something,
but it's been good.''
</P>
<P>
   A town gone mad
</P>
<P>
   There is no overestimating how enthusiastically the city of St.
Louis has followed Mark McGwire's home run rush. The Sunday edition
of the St. Louis Post-Dispatch included 12 stories about McGwire,
ranging from the debate on Andro to a profile of Sam Holbrook, the
umpire who ejected the first baseman in Saturday's game. Also
included was a full photo page devoted to Saturday's mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates on the value of the ball McGwire hits to break the
record are ranging from $1 to $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Earning a Buck
</P>
<P>
   Nice pregame moment at Busch Stadium. Jack Buck, who has
broadcast Cardinal games since 1954, was honored with the unveiling
of a statue of his likeness, which will stand outside the entrance
to the team offices at the stadium. Buck was inducted into the
broadcaster wing of the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
