<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves on deck: Houston Astros
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: Tonight, Tuesday and Wednesday at 7:40 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Turner Field
</P>
<P>
   _ TV: TBS will telecast tonight's and Tuesday's games. Fox
Sports South the telecast Wednesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Probable starting pitchers: Tonight, RHP John Smoltz (13-2,
3.32; 14-12, 3.06 lifetime vs. Astros) vs. LHP Mike Hampton (10-6,
3.79; 3-6, 3.51 lifetime vs. Braves). Tuesday, LHP Denny Neagle
(13-11, 3.62; 4-4, 4.42 lifetime vs. Astros) vs. RHP Sean Bergman
(11-7, 3.56; 1-3, 7.03 lifetime vs. Braves). Wednesday, RHP Greg
Maddux (17-6, 1.98; 17-8, 2.19 lifetime vs. Asrtros) vs. LHP Randy
Johnson (5-1, 1.17; 0-1, 13.50 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   _ Series history: Atlanta leads the all-time series 279-259 and
is 26-23 against Houston over the past four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   _ Past meetings: The Braves are 4-4 versus the Astros this year,
having just split a two-game series in the Astrodome last week.
They also split a four-game series in Houston May 15-18. This will
be Houston's first and only visit to Atlanta this year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Astros leaders (through Saturday: Avg. _ Craig Biggio (.328);
HRs _ Moises Alou (38); RBIs _ Alou (115); SBs _ Biggio (44). W _
Shane Reynolds (16); ERA _ Randy Johnson (1.17). Saves _ Billy
Wagner (25). Strikeouts _ Reynolds (167).
</P>
<P>
   _ Quickly: The Braves have found the Astros to be a far
different team from the one that they swept in last fall's
divisional playoffs. Moises Alou's presence in the middle of the
order has converted this lineup to the highest scoring team in
franchise history, the addition of Randy Johnson has tranformed the
rotation into a rival of Atlanta's, and the bullpen remains one of
the best in the league. ... In the best season in franchise
history, the Astros are 86-51, seven wins better than the 1986
Astros, which had previously posted the club best record after 137
dates. Houston has won 21 games in August, the most wins in any
month in franchise history. ... Atlanta has been muzzled by Astros
pitching this season. The team has hit .216 against the Astros and
.277 against everyone else. Javy Lopez has been the exception. He
was 4-for-7 last week in Houston with two home runs, a double and
three RBIs. ... Hampton pitched one of his best games of the season
last Tuesday against the Braves, holding them to two runs on six
hits through eight innings. He struck out a career-high 12 batters,
baffling the Braves with a hard slider. Strangely, the victory was
just his second in 12 starts. He remains 2-2 since the All-Star
break. ... On the DL: RHP Ramon Garcia (strained right elbow
ligament), RHP Chris Holt (right shoulder surgery), RHP Jose
Cabrera (sore right shoulder) INF Jack Howell (broken left wrist),
OF Pete Incaviglia (sore back).
</P>
<P>
   _ Who's hot: Moises Alou and Brad Ausmus went into Sunday
hitting a combined .429 (9-for-21) on their last homestand. Sean
Berry had nine hits in 17 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   _ Who's not: Tim Bogar is in an 0-for-19 slump. Carl Everett was
3-for-15 during their last homestand. Bill Spiers had two hits in
his last 17 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
