<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-OPEN-DENT-NYT &LR;      08-30 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-OPEN-DENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAYLOR DENT, 17 AND SON OF TENNIS PRO, IS READY TO GO PRO, TOO
</HEADLINE>
   (ll) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Taylor Dent's 6-foot-2-inch, 195-pound physique says
he belongs in the U.S. Open. So does his last name: his father,
Phil, was once a Grand Slam finalist and a Davis Cup stalwart for
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   But Taylor Dent's birth certificate tells a different story. At
17 years 4 months, he is the youngest player in the main men's
draw. And when he takes the court against Alex Radulescu of Germany
in the first round on Monday, he will be discarding the safety net
of amateur tennis for good.
</P>
<P>
   As a professional, Dent is now eligible for plenty of prize
money and plenty of pressure; for complimentary hotel rooms and
complementary expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But then Dent has been dealing with economy-sized expectations
since he won the United States Tennis Association's 14-and-under
and 16-and-under national titles in consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gullikson, the USTA director of coaching, said: ``I think
he's got an incredible amount of ability. I think he's got a big
game and the potential to do very well on the pro tour.''
</P>
<P>
   As one of an extremely small group of American boys now
considered to have such potential, Dent has been swarmed by agents;
he has heard the encouraging words of elders, and now he and his
father/coach are convinced that the time is right to make the leap:
not straight into the top 10, mind you, but into the arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've beaten all the best juniors, and I think the pros is the
next step for me,'' Dent said with a wide, can't-miss grin and not
the slightest hint of trepidation. ``It's the right timing because
I'm right there with the top guys. Last week at Long Island, I beat
some guy who was ranked 58th in the world. Regardless of what
anybody says, when you're ranked that high, there's not much
separating the top.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It would be different if I was getting blown out of
matches, just getting smoked. But I'm holding my own, and I just
need the consistency of competing with these guys day in and day
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Dent, who has a powerful all-court game, a huge serve and a
one-handed backhand that he can slice or drive effectively, did
beat the world's 58th-ranked player: Mariano Puerto of Argentina.
He also pushed the former Wimbledon semifinalist David Wheaton, now
ranked 210th, to three sets in the first round in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone agrees that Dent is ready. Dick Leach, the
father of the professional Rick Leach and coach at Southern
California, said Dent could benefit from a year or two of college
tennis. But Phil Dent, who has coached his son since he began
playing at the age of 11, has a different perspective, although he
is very quick to emphasize that his son's game is a work in
progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to blow this out of proportion because he's not
ready,'' Phil Dent said. ``I know the expectations are there
because there aren't many American guys, really. But in my eyes, if
his potential level is a 10, he's probably only at a 4 right now.
He's just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every guy playing in the U.S. Open junior event here except
for the Americans is basically a pro. They get money from agents
and clothing firms. They play money tournaments. All going pro
excludes Taylor from doing is playing tennis in college and maybe a
couple of national junior tournaments. It does not necessarily mean
he will not play any more junior events. But I think he's ready to
be out there on the tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Marketability was also a factor in the Dents' decision.
</P>
<P>
   With American prospects scarce, Taylor's appeal to sponsors is
magnified. And though the Dents say they have yet to sign any
deals, negotiations on a multimillion-dollar contract are well
under way with at least one firm.
</P>
<P>
   Though Taylor spent several years in Australia as a child, he
was born and spent most of his life in Southern California. The
only time he sounds Australian is when he imitates his father, who
reached the Australian Open final in 1974. Taylor has never seen
film of his father at his best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've hidden all the film,'' Phil Dent said.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is that both of Taylor's parents were worth
watching. His mother is Betty Ann Stuart, a former top-20
professional player. Dent and Stuart divorced when Taylor was 12.
Since then, Taylor has lived with Phil.
</P>
<P>
   Father and son are close, teasing each other about their
respective tempers and respective laundry habits, and they will
soon be in even closer quarters as they roam the world in pursuit
of tour computer ranking points.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Dent is not concerned about his son's ability to adapt to
the nomadic life that he knows so well.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth,'' Phil Dent said, ``Taylor even likes
airline food.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
