<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980830.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9804 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      08-30 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OKLAHOMA: A DEAD CANDIDATE COMPLICATES A RUNOFF  
 ILLINOIS: POLLS GIVE INCUMBENT A REASON TO WORRY  
 MICHIGAN: LOSING GROUND, EVEN IN HIS OWN PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In last Tuesday's primary to pick a nominee to run against Sen.
Don Nickles this fall, they gave Don Carroll, an air-conditioner
serviceman, the most votes. But they did not give him a clean
majority of the votes _ only 46 percent of them _ so under Oklahoma
law a runoff will be necessary, pitting Carroll against the
second-place finisher, Jacquelyn Morrow Lewis Ledgerwood.
</P>
<P>
   The problem: Mrs. Ledgerwood, a 69-year-old homemaker, died of a
heart attack in July, too close to primary day for her name to be
struck from the ballot. But in a low-turnout contest in which the
four Democratic contenders were mostly inexperienced, underfinanced
and underorganized political unknowns because no big-name Democrat
was willing to take on a Republican incumbent as popular as
Nickles, Mrs. Ledgerwood captured 21 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   What to do?
</P>
<P>
   Some Democratic leaders suggest dropping any idea of a runoff,
considering that Mrs. Ledgerwood remained on the ballot only
because of a time technicality. They also argue that there
otherwise is no reason for a runoff because the outcome essentially
is already known, Carroll having pulled twice as many votes as Mrs.
Ledgerwood the first time around.
</P>
<P>
   But most party leaders and state officials say that the law is
the law, that the votes of Mrs. Ledgerwood's supporters cannot be
arbitrarily tossed out and that in any case there is no guarantee
that Mrs. Ledgerwood would lose a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   What if Mrs. Ledgerwood should win the runoff, remote as that
possibility might be?
</P>
<P>
   The consensus _ if there is one _ seems to be that Oklahoma law
provides that she would then face Nickles in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   But because she is dead, some voters have begun asking, why
couldn't party leaders name a substitute for her at that point, a
procedure followed in many states when a nominee dies or otherwise
cannot run?
</P>
<P>
   There is no provision in Oklahoma law for naming a substitute,
most state and party officials agree. Anyway, they add, if there
were, the party might then be sorely and divisively tempted to
abandon Carroll in the primary runoff, back Mrs. Ledgerwood all
out, then try to find a big-name Democrat to substitute for her in
the fall race against Nickles.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the ultimate question: What happens if Mrs. Ledgerwood
wins the runoff and goes on to defeat Nickles in the general
election?
</P>
<P>
   Again, the consensus, if there is one, seems to be that in that
unlikely event, the Senate seat would be declared open immediately
after her victory and a whole new election would be scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe,'' said Robert Kerr III, the chairman of the Oklahoma
Democratic Party. ``We don't know for sure yet. We've got a real
mess out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Moseley-Braun of Illinois breezed to victory in 1992 when
she became the first black woman to win a seat in the U.S. Senate.
But six years later, dogged by questions about campaign financing
and why she paid visits to an African dictator, she finds herself
struggling as she seeks a second term.
</P>
<P>
   And things seem to be getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   From the start of the race, national Democratic leaders have
been nagged by worries that Ms. Moseley-Braun might be the most
endangered of Democratic senators running. Now, confirming the
worst of those worries, after months of trailing in the polls, her
Republican opponent, state Sen. Peter Fitzgerald, has pulled close
to even in several polls and leads in at least one.
</P>
<P>
   Equally serious, polltakers say more voters now hold a negative
view of Ms. Moseley-Braun than a positive view. They also report
that among women, a powerful constituency in the senator's 1992
victory, about as many plan to vote for Fitzgerald, a conservative,
as for Ms. Moseley-Braun, a liberal.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald is gearing up a television advertising blitz that is
expected to cost as much as $4 million over the next several
months, maybe more if he decides to tap deeper into his personal
fortune of $40 million or so. (He spent $7 million of his money in
winning his party's nomination.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Moseley-Braun, by contrast, is down to about $1 million in
her campaign coffers, according to her latest campaign finance
report.
</P>
<P>
   Political pros caution not to count the senator out yet, as she
has been a pretty good fund-raiser and campaigner in the past and
is far better known than Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   But given how deep Fitzgerald's pockets are and the momentum he
seems to be building, this race appears to be a toss-up.
</P>
<P>
   A month after winning the Democratic nomination in the Michigan
governor's race, Geoffrey Fieger trails the Republican incumbent,
John Engler, by almost two to one in the polls and seems to be
steadily losing ground.
</P>
<P>
   Fieger, a rogue-mouthed lawyer best know for representing Dr.
Jack Kevorkian, the advocate of physician-assisted suicide, tried
to reach out over the weekend to two crucial constituencies, naming
a running mate with close ties to big labor and calling for the
election of a black person as Michigan's secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   But many political analysts and top Democrats say the damage
already done by Fieger's stick-in-the-eye campaign rhetoric _ he
has called the popular governor a ``racist,'' ``fat'' and a
``moron'' _ might be beyond repair. Some analysts and party leaders
say he might run so poorly that the entire Democratic ticket could
suffer as a result.
</P>
<P>
   After conducting a poll 10 days ago for The Detroit News that
found Engler leading the race by almost 30 points, about 10 points
more than in some earlier surveys, Steve Mitchell of Mitchell
Research told the paper, ``Fieger is not just an albatross around
the neck of Democrats; he's an anchor that could bring a lot of
Democrats down with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Worried by that prospect, some party members have begun to
publicly back away from Fieger or put him at political arm's
length.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be associated with him,'' state Rep. William
Callahan of St. Clair Shores, a Detroit suburb, said the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bart Stupak of Michigan's 1st Congressional District, on
the Upper Peninsula, declared, ``I've not endorsed him, probably
won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Another member of Congress, Rep. James Barcia of the 5th
District, north of Detroit on the Lower Peninsula's thumb, called
upon Fieger over the weekend to be ``less personal'' in his verbal
assaults.
</P>
<P>
   Fieger's response to all this:
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   And Engler's take, as proffered by his spokeswoman, Maureen
McNulty:
</P>
<P>
   ``Fieger's running against his own mouth. He's not running
against John Engler.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
