<SLUG> BC-TEN-HAMLET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAFTER SERVES UP A WARNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMMACK, N.Y. _ Patrick Rafter celebrated his Hamlet Cup victory
Sunday long enough to hoist the glass trophy and pose with his
poster-size $45,000 check.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's it,'' he said. `'I'm ready for the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   No postmatch beer. No golf. Rafter has a U.S. Open title to
defend.
</P>
<P>
   The second-seeded Rafter confessed that his mind began wandering
to the Open before he put away eighth-seeded Felix Mantilla of
Spain, 7-6 (7-3), 6-2, in the Hamlet final. Rafter has captured
five tour championships this year, the most by an Australian since
John Newcombe won nine in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter takes rocket-like momentum into his first-round match
against Hicham Arazi of Morocco on Tuesday. Rafter, ranked No. 3 in
the world, dropped one set all week and surrendered one service
break. Since mid-June, he has won 26 of 29 matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope that physically I'm still fresh,'' Rafter said.
``I'll take a good rest tonight and tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter tried to shorten the points against Mantilla in the
energy-zapping humidity. Mantilla showed his vulnerability by
nearly dumping two service games in the first set, but he battled
back in both to force a tie breaker.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter built a 4-0 lead in the tie breaker _ mostly on his
assault at the net _ then let Mantilla climb back to 4-3 with a
missed dink shot, a half-volley into the net and a clunky return of
serve that landed long.
</P>
<P>
   But the Australian responded by smacking a volley winner, a
service winner and sweeping Mantilla wide with a volley, forcing
him into an awkward backhand that hit the net.
</P>
<P>
   Mantilla's waning upset hopes crumbled quickly in the second
set. He double-faulted in the first game to hand Rafter the first
of two service breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he broke me, he served better and better,'' said
Mantilla, who pocketed $26,000.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter, the crowd favorite at the Hamlet Golf and Country Club,
shed his sweaty wristbands and spare shirts after match point and
hurled them into the crowd of 4,526. One man caught a wristband and
tried to hand it to his female companion. She shook her head no.
Even Rafter-mania has its limits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-98 2203EDT &QL; 
