<SLUG> BC-GLF-WORLD-SERIES-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL WINS HIS THIRD TOURNAMENT OF THE YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AKRON, Ohio _ He led from start to finish Sunday, unfazed by the
pressure and the intimidating names that were chasing him.
</P>
<P>
   This was David Duval at his best, taking on all comers,
relentlessly making machine-like shots with his eyes hidden behind
dark sunglasses. Since October, Duval has been the most consistent
winner on the PGA Tour, a player who reacts like a shark that
smells blood when he smells a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Becoming the first three-time winner on tour this year, and
reclaiming the top spot on the money list, Duval captured another
trophy for his mantel by winning the World Series of Golf by two
strokes over Phil Mickelson. Shooting a steady 2-under-par 68 at
the difficult Firestone Country Club, Duval finished at 11-under
269 for the tournament, two strokes ahead of Mickelson, who also
shot a 68 Sunday. Davis Love III finished third, three shots back,
after making a final-round run with a 65.
</P>
<P>
   With the $405,000 first-place check, Duval passed the $2 million
mark in season earnings ($2,070,283) faster than anyone in golf
history. If not for Mark O'Meara's victories at the Masters and the
British Open, Duval would have the inside track for player of the
year honors. Yet, with six victories since last October, the
27-year-old Duval showed he is a player with special ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``When crunch time came, I hit the shots I had to hit, made the
putts I needed to make,'' said Duval, who became the first player
since Nick Price in 1993 and '94 to win at least three events in
back-to-back seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he would react if someone called him the best young
player on tour, Duval said: ``That's flattering, but you have to
have a lot of arrogance to say you're better than Tiger Woods,
better than Phil Mickelson and Jim Furyk and Justin Leonard. I just
don't have enough arrogance to do that. There's an awful lot of
good young players on tour, and an awful lot of good older players,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday's victory was particularly impressive because it came
against an elite field of 44 golfers who qualified by winning at
least one tournament during the past 12 months. The final round
started with Duval holding a one-stroke lead over John Cook, a
two-stroke lead over Mickelson, a three-stroke lead over O'Meara,
and a four-stroke lead over Woods. A lesser player might have been
rattled being pursued by those names. But Duval gave some insight
into his mental toughness on Saturday, when he talked about how he
would approach Sunday's round.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to sound stupid, but it doesn't matter who
you're playing against,'' Duval said. ``The lowest score is going
to win. That doesn't matter if you're playing against Tiger, or
against someone else you might call a lesser name. It doesn't
matter. I don't get caught up with who I'm competing against. I get
nervous like anybody else, but getting too worked up and getting
upset is counterproductive to what I'm trying to accomplish.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Duval accomplished exactly what he wanted Sunday, while others
faltered. Cook, who shot a scintillating 62 on Saturday, never
approached that level Sunday, shooting a 71 and finishing fourth at
7 under par. A crowd favorite who went to Ohio State, Cook left
disappointed for the second consecutive year. Cook was the
third-round leader last year, but he eventually finished tied for
third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I did right yesterday was the opposite today,''
said Cook, who played in the final group with Duval and admired his
playing partner's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``David drove the ball beautifully,'' he said. ``There's no
mystery as to why he's at the level he is. He and a couple of other
guys are the future of golf.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also a disappointing final round for Woods, who shot a 70
and finished tied for fifth. Woods has 12 top 10 finishes in 18
starts on tour this year, yet he has only one victory. Why is Woods
having so much trouble finishing what he starts? He wishes he knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need some time off,'' said Woods, who has played four
consecutive weeks. ``I've been right there, week in and week out.
It's frustrating that I haven't won. It's just a matter of time.''
</P>
<P>
   It took 87 starts, including seven second-place finishes, for
Duval to win his first tour event, but he has now won six of his
last 22 tournaments. Last year at this time, people were
questioning Duval's ability to close out a tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never viewed myself as a failure,'' he said. ``I always felt
I was progressing. There's a pretty impressive list of people who
took a lot longer to win than me. I always found it ironic that I
was getting knocked about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Six victories later, no one is knocking him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
