<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARM-OLD-MACHINERY-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD FARM MACHINERY ATTRACTS A DEVOTED CROWD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending to add art note)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ll) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOLEDO, Wash._ There's something about the sound of a World War
II-era John Deere tractor, a graceful two-step in a field of thuds
and idling rattles. Of course, there are farmers who disagree.
</P>
<P>
   At the 34th-annual Cowlitz Prairie Grange Steam Threshing and
Gas Show, the opposition came from fans of other tractors, like the
Farmall, the Case and the Massey.
</P>
<P>
   But the people who came to the show all agreed that the
collecting, refinishing and displaying of antique farm machinery _
or ``iron'' _ is an engaging and honorable pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   In the field of Bob Herren's farm, with Mount Rainier to the
north and the stump of Mount St. Helens to the east, the Threshing
Bee, as the show is known for short, attracted about 8,000 people
on Saturday and the same number on Sunday, the organizers said. In
addition to a tractor pull and a flea market, there were lots of
tractors driving around, several of them driven by children who
kicked switches with their feet because they were too little to
reach the clutch.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the day was the threshing (pronounced
``thrashing'' here) done on the hour, using machinery from earlier
in the century.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Zion of Kent, Wash., helped pitch oats into a 1946 John
Deere thresher, which was powered by a belt from a tractor about 50
feet away, while his cousin, Ben Klein of Sequim, dozed on the back
of the grain cart. With seven belts looped around one another in a
giant cat's cradle and pistons flying, the thresher worked like a
charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the serial number, it's supposed to be one of the last six
made,'' Zion said. ``It pretty much stays in the family.'' He said
he expected to be showing off machines like this and demonstrating
how they separate oats from chaff when his father gets too old to
do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the equipment was made before I was born,'' said Zion.
``Our grandfather did this in Colorado.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the iron collectors, the John Deere fans seem to be the
most loyal. ``About half of them are like me,'' said John Fields,
president of the Southwest Washington 2 Cylinder Club. ``I've got a
small farm, and my newest farm tractor is a 1958. I'm able to enjoy
playing with the old farm machinery and do the farming that I
really enjoy too.''
</P>
<P>
   Fields and Ted Blair of Elma, Wash., a past president of the
club, showed off an elegant 1960 620 orchard tractor, with a
swooping fairing to keep dropping fruit out of the machinery. It
was one of 202 ever made.
</P>
<P>
   Fields helped Blair start his 1944 John Deere bulldozer,
succeeding on the second try after a dozen energetic pushes to the
flywheel. Blair, who was wearing green and yellow John Deere
suspenders, doesn't use the machine for work anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to have fun with,'' he said. ``It's too old to get parts
for them, and if you broke something major, it would be down.'' The
engine putted along steadily.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing at the engine, Fields said: ``It's that sound right
there. The others go BRRRRRR. This has a little split sound right
there, and that's what attracts people to it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the end of a long row of humming engines and spinning
flywheels, Dennis Leischner of Boring, Ore., who wore a T-shirt
proclaiming him a ``Gas Engine Nut,'' explained that farm engines
were often kept on wheels so they could be used all over, to pump
water, grid feed or separate cream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the sound of them,'' Leischner said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Herren, who provided the oats for the Threshing Bee,
displayed a gas engine _ ``about a horse and a half'' _ that he
once used for pumping water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We threshed the old-fashioned way, and I plowed the whole
field with a 14-inch plow, seven miles of walking to the acre,''
Herren said.
</P>
<P>
   Threshing 40 acres took all winter. Herren remembered when one
thresher served all the neighborhood farms and took 20 men to run
properly. There was suspicion when the first combines appeared, and
Herren said he still believed that the old threshers are better in
some ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``The grain gets to dry out a bit, and a stationary thresher can
do a cleaner job than a combine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing at a red Waterloo Boy, he said: ``This came out of the
cemetery. It was used to pump water in the cemetery in Vader.''
</P>
<P>
   He used to find old engines when surveying properties, but, he
said, ``I don't find them very often anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   A South Dakota family gave the 1946 thresher to Zion's family,
which had to find a low-boy truck to haul it to Washington. When he
was done threshing, Zion let a handful of oats fall through his
hands, rolled one between his fingers and pulled back the husk.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' he said, ``is the beginning of breakfast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
