<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BBO-LITTLE-LEAGUE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMETOWN GIVES LITTLE LEAGUE CHAMPIONS A HERO'S WELCOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending to add art note)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ED GUZMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOMS RIVER, N.J. _ Last December, Ken Kondek's wife, Chris, was
planning a September trip to Las Vegas to celebrate a friend's 50th
wedding anniversary. Kondek, the assistant coach of the Toms River
East Little League team, refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I don't want to go because I'm going to
Williamsport,''' Mrs. Kondek said, referring to the Pennsylvania
town that is the site of the Little League World Series. ``And this
was in December!''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was wishful thinking on the part of Kondek, since he
was planning to retire from Little League coaching this year after
20 years and wanted to go out right. Or maybe he really knew
something about these young players, seeing as the Kondeks live
right across the street from the Toms River East Little League
complex.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it was, Kondek could not have envisioned what played
out last week in Williamsport, a week that was capped on Saturday
by Toms River's 12-9 victory over Kashima, Japan, to win the 52nd
annual Little League World Series championship.
</P>
<P>
   Nor could he have envisioned the hero's welcome the team
received on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   As the team bus rolled off the Garden State Parkway at Route 37
about 1:45 p.m., accompanied by a police escort, several hundred
well-wishers who had been waiting since the morning lined the south
side of the road. Along the route, the team disembarked from the
bus and got on top of a fire truck to ride on to the Little League
complex, where they were met by an estimated 2,000 residents who
were finally getting a chance to greet their young heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you believe this?'' asked Charlie Frazier, a vice
principal of Toms River South High School and the father of Todd
Frazier, who hit four home runs in the Series and was the winning
pitcher in the championship game. ``They could have gone to the
beach today, and instead they came here.''
</P>
<P>
   They came to celebrate not just a local team, but the first U.S.
team to win the Little League World Series in five years. Many of
the boosters who lined the road waved American flags against a
backdrop of strip malls and tire stores.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the boisterous throng also brought signs and banners,
including one hanging from the side of a camper van that read:
``Marry me Chris Cardone. Love, Alexa.'' But Chris, who hit the
game-winning home run in the sixth and final inning of Saturday's
game, does not necessarily need to stock up on wedding clothes yet
_ Alexa Manforti is only 7.
</P>
<P>
   From the first game in Williamsport in which she saw Chris,
Alexa was smitten. When her father, Al, a chiropractor, told her he
knew Chris _ he treats Chris' family _ she got even more excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all started with the first game,'' Manforti said of Alexa's
infatuation. ``She said he was really cute. She wanted to get rid
of her first-grade boyfriend.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chris' mother, Lucy, said of the sign: ``Not yet. I want to
hold on to him a little bit longer.''
</P>
<P>
   In a departure from the even-keel demeanor he displayedin the
Series Mike Gaynor, the team manager who coached another Toms River
team to Williamsport in 1995, thanked each of his players
individually with a touch of emotion..
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said that if I came back, I would have more
success,'' he said. Then, turning to the team and smiling, he said,
``It kind of worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the champions, while basking in the adulation,
were clearly exhausted and not very talkative. None addressed the
crowd at the rally. Still, the second baseman, Joey Franceschini,
told reporters, ``It was awesome to have all the fans cheering you
on.''
</P>
<P>
   While a number of public appearances await, the players from
Toms River said on Sunday that they simply wanted to go home and
regain some normalcy in their lives, perhaps not fully
understanding the scope of their accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know when it's going to hit them?'' Mrs. Kondek said.
``When they're 40 and they have kids. Right now, it's awesome, and
five years from now it'll be cool. But right now, they just don't
know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
