<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-COEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 FABIO COEN, 80, EDITED ACCLAIMED CHILDREN'S BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fabio Coen, a children's book editor, died on Aug. 19
at his home in Manhattan. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   Coen worked with many leading writers and illustrators of books
for children and young adults, among them Roald Dahl, Roger
Duvoisin and Robert Cormier. Until his retirement in 1979, he was
editor in chief of the juvenile list at Pantheon Books and Alfred
A. Knopf.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier years, he worked as an editor at McDowell Obolensky,
and it was there, in 1959, that he encouraged a friend, Leo Lionni,
to write and illustrate a children's book.
</P>
<P>
   Lionni, who was then the art director of Fortune magazine,
produced ``Little Blue and Little Yellow,'' which was notable for
its innovative use of collage and was followed by such critically
acclaimed books as ``Swimmy'' and ``Frederick.''
</P>
<P>
   Coen, who was born in Rome and raised in Trieste, immigrated to
the United States in 1940. He worked briefly as a stage manager
with the Barter Theater in Virginia before being inducted into the
Army, where he served in the psychological warfare division and was
eventually stationed in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   His first wife, Silvana Siega, with whom he founded and operated
the Package Library of Foreign Children's Books, died in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Adri; two sons from his first
marriage, Axel, of New York City, and Paul, of Locke, N.Y.; and two
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
