<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SARATOGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AWESOME AGAIN EXTENDS HIS STREAK
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ On a day when the thrills and echoes of
the Travers Stakes were still settling over the old Saratoga race
track, Awesome Again lived up to his name Sunday when he stalked
the leaders into the homestretch and then swept past to win the
Saratoga Breeders' Cup by three lengths and score his fourth
straight victory.
</P>
<P>
   He is a 4-year-old son of Deputy Minister and has had a pretty
good run of success in August the last couple of years. Last year,
he won the Jim Dandy Stakes and ran third in the Travers. This
year, he won the $400,000 Whitney Handicap three weeks ago and
returned to win the $300,000 Saratoga Breeders' Cup. He is 4 for 4
this year and hasn't lost since last September.
</P>
<P>
   ``This horse just loves this race track,'' said Patrick Byrne,
trainer of Awesome Again. ``I couldn't have asked for more. The
Breeders' Cup Classic in November is definitely in mind, and that's
what we're shooting for. We'd like to get him to the Classic
undefeated this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Day, winning his sixth stakes of the Saratoga meeting, kept
his horse tucked in behind Dogwood Stable's Early Warning and
George Steinbrenner's Concerto for a mile, and then made his move.
</P>
<P>
   ``We relaxed off Concerto,'' Day said, ``but we didn't want him
to get too far away from us. At the three-eighths pole, we had him
in our sights. Coming to the three-sixteenths pole, we had him
where we wanted. I just bided my time from there, and called on him
at the sixteenth pole.''
</P>
<P>
   Awesome Again ran the mile and a quarter in 2:03, paid $2.50 for
a $2 bet as the heavy favorite and earned $180,000. At the end, he
led Concerto by three lengths, and Concerto had a neck on Early
Warning.
</P>
<P>
   3-Horse Photo, 3-Race Choice
</P>
<P>
   It took a three-horse photo to decide the 129th Travers, but the
trainer Shug Mcgaughey said Sunday that ``Coronado's Quest is doing
fine.'' Next for the star of the 3-year-old class, who has a
winning streak of five stakes races: either the $500,000 Woodward
at Belmont Park on Sept. 19, the $500,000 Pegasus at the
Meadowlands on Sept. 25 or the $500,000 Super Derby at Louisiana
Downs on Sept. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop, who ran second in the Kentucky Derby, the
Preakness and the Travers, ``ran a great race once again,'' said
his trainer, Elliott Walden. He also was considering the Super
Derby, but was not committed.
</P>
<P>
   Archers Bay, who finished fourth, and Grand Slam, who ran fifth,
might find grass in their future. Or, maybe shorter races for Grand
Slam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the mile and a quarter was beyond his scope,'' said
his trainer, D. Wayne Lukas. ``Cutting him back in distance seems
to be logical.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
