<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GIANTS' RUNNING TRADITION IS IN QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only once in the last 30 years has someone other than a running
back led the New York Giants in total yardage gained, and that was
tight end Mark Bavaro during the statistically quirky 1987 season.
</P>
<P>
   For 62 years, Giants football has meant running the football.
From Tuffy Leemans in the 1930's to Alex Webster to Frank Gifford
and on through Ron Johnson, Joe Morris, Ottis Anderson and Rodney
Hampton, Giants running backs have customarily been the team's
all-purpose yardage leaders, a category that excludes a
quarterback's passing statistics. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One wonders whether the 1998 version of the team is going to be
able to uphold the tradition. In the four-game preseason just
concluded, Giants running backs, especially those operating behind
the first-string offensive line, consistently failed to rush the
football effectively.
</P>
<P>
   When your team was the seventh best rushing team in the National
Football League last season, and when running the football has been
your main formula for gaining field position since players' helmets
were leather, that's a problem.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know why the Giants starting offense has looked
so poor in the preseason, look at the production of the running
backs on first and second downs. Tiki Barber and Gary Brown, the
backs who have three-fourths of the rushing attempts with the first
team, have combined to average just 2.8 yards a carry.
</P>
<P>
   On third down this year, on average, the Giants starting offense
has faced third-and-7.
</P>
<P>
   Not too many teams convert on third down from that distance.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise then that in two preseason games, the losses to
Baltimore and Jacksonville, the first-string offense didn't pick up
a first down on any of its third-down attempts. Exclude the
preseason game with the Jets, when the Giants' offense played
superbly, and the Giants third-down conversion rate this month was
just 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminds me of early last year,'' Giants coach Jim Fassel
said over the weekend, recalling the Giants' 1-3 start to the 1997
season. ``We must have had more second-and-long and third-and-longs
than any team in the history of the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were rescued a year ago when they got fullback
Charles Way more involved in the offense, the offensive line played
more consistently and quarterback Danny Kanell took over to improve
the short and medium-range part of the passing attack.
</P>
<P>
   All those things may have to happen again if the Giants expect
to successfully begin the defense of their National Football
Conference East title Sunday against the Washington Redskins.
Because it will take a lot more than the Giants showed in Friday's
tuneup against the Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   As Fassel said of his offense on Sunday: ``We didn't get
anything accomplished. A lot of those guys didn't even need a
shower when that game was over.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel put a lot of blame for Friday's 14-6 loss on the starting
offensive line, which is the same five players who blocked
effectively a year ago. With that experience, it's likely that the
line will return to its 1997 form. The running back situation,
however, remains unstable.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the carries against Washington will continue to be split
between Barber, Brown and Way; but Tyrone Wheatley, the odd man out
now for four seasons, gained more rushing yards than any other back
in the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Wheatley ran for 112 yards, usually operating behind the second-
and third-string linemen. Wheatley also averaged more yards per
carry (3.9) than any other back.
</P>
<P>
   Individual preseason statistics are always hard to judge,
especially late in games because it's hard to evaluate the level of
the competition. But Wheatley's production and his situation with
the team seem to be the eternal paradox.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel withholds praise from Wheatley, saying he needs to see
more consistency. Wheatley stays out of the debate publicly, but
his friends on the team say he believes he needs 20 to 25 carries a
game to find a groove and to wear the other team out _ the big-back
formula carved for the Giants by Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   But Fassel won't give Wheatley carries based on the potential of
what might happen on the 20th carry. He wants immediate production,
like most coaches, and besides, he wants to spread the carries
around to involve Barber, Brown and Way. But Barber and Brown have
struggled.
</P>
<P>
   And so, around and around goes the discussion of the Giants
running back by committee.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it ends up at third-and-7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-98 2219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
