<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CAMPAIGN REFORM'S NEXT HURDLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Aug. 31:
</P>
<P>
   The Senate returns to Washington this week, more consumed than
ever by the anguished debate over President Clinton. But lawmakers
are living in a dream world if they consider themselves immune to
Americans' general displeasure over ethics in public life. A recent
New York Times poll showed that while most Americans have a low
regard for Clinton's ``moral values,'' fully 65 percent thought his
integrity was the same as or better than that of most politicians.
</P>
<P>
   There is one very big thing that Congress can do to restore
voter confidence, and that is to finish the job of overhauling the
campaign fund raising system, eliminating ``soft money'' and other
abuses that undermine the integrity of American politics.
</P>
<P>
   There has never been a more favorable moment for reform. The
public wants it. The House passed the Shays-Meehan bill earlier
this month. A clear majority favors the bill in the Senate, where
it would pass if Trent Lott, the majority leader, permitted a vote.
Instead, he and Mitch McConnell of Kentucky seem ready to use a
filibuster, as they did earlier in the year, to frustrate popular
will.
</P>
<P>
   The need for change was obvious even before the end of the last
election, when the first disclosures of abuses in Clinton's
re-election campaign began to spill out. It turned out that
millions of dollars in foreign money had reached both Republican
and Democratic campaigns, in apparent violation of the law. But
foreign money was largely a function of the ability of both parties
to manipulate a legal loophole to raise outlandish sums from other
sources as well.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans remain outraged over the way Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore used the White House for ``coffees,'' sleep-overs
and telephone calls to raise money _ activities that clearly merit
examination by an independent counsel. Yet even now the Republicans
themselves hold meetings and receptions in return for big
donations, often from businesses with an interest in weakening
regulations or tax laws.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 election cycle, the two political parties raised
$260 million in unregulated ``soft money'' from corporations,
unions and rich individuals _ money that the law requires to be
used only for so-called party-building activities, but which both
parties channeled directly into ad campaigns for Clinton and his
opponent, Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   The post-Watergate reforms of 1974, particularly the strict
ceilings on contributions by individuals and political-action
committees, were important steps in the long, uneven struggle to
purge the political system of special-interest money.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1988, the system broke down as George Bush and Michael
Dukakis discovered the soft-money loophole, and changed the history
of fund raising by accepting the unlimited sums allowed for
political parties and diverting them to their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, they destroyed the central compact embodied in
the post-Watergate laws, under which presidential candidates would
accept public money while agreeing to spending limits. This was
merely a warm-up for Clinton and Dole, who each took $75 million in
public money but also raised and spent huge sums outside the
federal limits.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the latest round of public revulsion will be followed by
reform depends on Congress. If reform dies, soft money could double
to $500 million or more in the next presidential election, spawning
even more corruption.
</P>
<P>
   It is important to remember that the legislation banning soft
money is not revolutionary. It is the spiritual successor to the
reforms of 1907 and 1947, which banned corporate and union
contributions, as well as the Watergate reforms of 1974, and as
such reflects the historic American yearning for a cleaner
politics.
</P>
<P>
   All that is needed is eight Republican votes to shut off the
filibuster that Lott and McConnell are sure to engineer this month.
The responsibility for finding those votes falls on Sens. John
McCain of Arizona and Russell Feingold of Wisconsin, who championed
the cause earlier this year and now must pick it up again.
</P>
<P>
   Is it too much to ask that this Congress, on the eve of the next
century, return to the spirit that has fired reformers since the
beginning of this century?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
