A9841 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-OBSERVER--NYT &LR;      08-30 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER--NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: DID THE ECONOMY BRING DOWN A PRESIDENCY? 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 BY FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton's ability to maintain strong approval ratings
for the job he is doing, if not for himself as a person, has
mystified some commentators. It certainly stands in sharp contrast
to the tumbling poll numbers shown by Richard Nixon during the
Watergate investigation that ultimately led to his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   One explanation for this phenomenon is that Americans think sex
is a private matter, and are as much offended by the fact that
Clinton was forced to testify about sex as by the possibility that
he committed perjury. Perhaps it is not offensive to cover up
conduct that never should have been made public to begin with. By
contrast, Nixon's conduct was a violation of the Constitution, and
his efforts to cover it up stirred a public that eventually turned
on him.
</P>
<P>
   All that makes sense. But it may not be the whole explanation.
Other things were happening in 1973 and 1974 when Nixon's approval
ratings were plunging. Most notably, the economy and the stock
market were putting in their worst performance in a generation, in
large part due to an international crisis that might have been
better handled.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to separate out the effects of Watergate and
economic maladies on Nixon's falling ratings because they were
occurring simultaneously. In October 1973, Arab armies attacked
Israel, which asked for and got massive U.S. aid to prevent defeat.
On Oct. 20, a day after Nixon made public the extent of the aid,
Arab oil producers declared an oil boycott. On the very same day,
he fired the Watergate special prosecutor, Archibald Cox, in the
Saturday Night Massacre.
</P>
<P>
   The Arab oil boycott led to a sudden increase in the price of
oil and sent much of the Western world into recession. The stock
market, already weak before the Middle East War broke out, entered
into the worst bear market since the Depression, a decline that did
not end until two months after Nixon resigned in August. By then,
the Dow Jones industrial average was down 45 percent from its peak.
</P>
<P>
   History is never run twice, so it is impossible to know what
would have happened had the Nixon administration pursued a
different course before and during the Middle East War. There were
people in the Nixon administration who were aware of the growing
U.S. dependence on Arab oil. But those concerns were not paramount
either before the war broke out or during it, when U.S. aid to
Israel inflamed Arab opinion. Would things have been different if
the president not been preoccupied by scandal? Probably not, but
there is no way to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   To return to 1998, the U.S. economy and the president's poll
ratings have been doing very well. But economists have been
surprised by the depth and the duration of the Asian problems, and
financial markets are worried that they will spread to Europe and
the United States. The collapse in Russia has unnerved investors,
as soaring oil prices did a generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear what the Clinton administration could have done
to prevent the Russian collapse, or what it should do now. But the
threat to the U.S. economy is now greater than at any time in the
Clinton presidency, and at a time when there is reason to doubt the
president's attention is strictly on his job.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, just perhaps, Clinton's ability to survive this scandal
will depend more on how well his administration deals with the
Russian economic crisis than on whether he is proved to have lied
about sex. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
