<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URBAN TEENS HELP KEEP `BLADE' TOPS AT BOX OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``a'' national news file.) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Blade'' continued its sharp performance at the
nation's box office with an estimated $11.1 million at 2,351
theaters during the Friday-Sunday period for its second straight
weekend victory, studio sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blade,'' based on a Marvel comic hero who is a human-vampire
hybrid, benefited from strong recommendation levels among
moviegoers as its weekend-to-weekend decline was only 35 percent _
a far better return than most recent similar entries. ``Blade's''
10-day cut is an impressive $34.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Blade' is performing well among urban teens and young male
adults,'' said Robert Bucksbaum, president of Reel Source.
``Blade,'' which carries an estimated $45 million price tag, could
reach $60 million by the end of its domestic run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blade'' outgrossed the combined take from the weekend's two
lukewarm openings _ Miramax's ``54,'' a look back at Studio 54's
rise and fall, with $6.4 million at 1,859 sites, and Warner Bros.'
``Why Do Fools Fall in Love,'' focusing on singer Frankie Lyman,
with $4 million at 1,369 screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``54'' and ``Fools'' finished fourth and fifth, well behind 20th
Century Fox's seventh weekend of ``There's Something About Mary''
with $8.4 million at 2,401 theaters and DreamWorks' sixth weekend
of ``Saving Private Ryan'' with $8.3 million at 2,774 locations.
Fox added 209 screens, leading to a 9 percent gain from the sixth
weekend in what Bucksbaum described as a savvy tactic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fox was pretty smart to add theaters to take advantage of the
fact that the new movies wouldn't be that strong,'' he said.
``Mary'' now has $116.2 million after 47 days and could hit $150
million, given the lack of strong new entries in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan,'' which saw its screen count grow by 103,
has totaled $155.5 million after 38 days, placing it 52nd on the
list of all-time domestic grossers after ``The Sting.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's fifth weekend of ``Ever After'' may edge ``Why Do Fools
Fall in Love'' for sixth place with $3.9 million at 1,912 theaters
to give Drew Barrymore's ``Cinderella'' revamp nearly $49 million
after 31 days. Finishing a close seventh was Paramount's fourth
weekend of ``Snake Eyes'' with $3.7 million at 2,243 sites,
followed by Fox's third weekend of ``How Stella Got Her Groove
Back'' with $3.6 million at 1,383 locations.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the top 10 were Disney's fifth weekend of ``The
Parent Trap'' with $3 million at 2,041 theaters, followed by Sony's
second weekend of ``Dance With Me'' with $2.95 million at 1,467
locales. Paramount's second weekend of collegiate comedy ``Dead Man
on Campus'' may have also cracked the top 10 with $2.9 million at
1,830 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing 12th was Disney's ninth weekend of ``Armageddon'' with
$2.4 million at 1,324 theaters. The disaster-fest has reached
$188.6 million and ranks 27th on the all-time domestic list behind
``Toy Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Two offbeat films posted impressive results in their second
weekend of limited release _ Gramercy's ``Your Friends and
Neighbors'' with $374,000 at 69 screens and Miramax's ``Next Stop:
Wonderland'' with $360,000 at 45 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Year-to-date business is nearing $4.5 billion and is 13 percent
ahead of the same period last year. Summer business, from Memorial
Day weekend to Labor Day, is on track to hit $2.5 billion, or 12
percent up from last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount's ``Titanic,'' source of much of 1998's improvement,
drew $385,000 at 502 theaters in its 37th weekend to push its
overall domestic total to $600.4 million after crossing the $600
million mark Thursday night. The epic, which comes out on home
video Tuesday, leads ``Star Wars'' as top all-time domestic grosser
by nearly $160 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blade,'' ``There's Something About Mary'' and ``Saving Private
Ryan'' face competition over Labor Day weekend from Sony's opening
of ``Knock Off,'' starring Jean-Claude Van Damme battling
terrorists in Hong Kong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
