<HEADLINE>
SEMINOLES' EARLY TEST DOESN'T FAZE BOWDEN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ It is August and a football weekend in
New Jersey, so the Florida State Seminoles are talking about a
national championship. They can't help it. Their coach, Bobby
Bowden, says he is tired of finishing Nos. 2, 3 and 4 and, shoot,
finishing on top in January is all that matters anyway. Besides,
the one and only title he owns began right here with a 42-0 rout of
Kansas in the 1993 Kickoff Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a loss hurts us one bit for a national title,''
said Bowden, reasoning that his team's 1993 championship withstood
a November loss to Notre Dame. ``If we aren't good enough, we need
to know now. There's no use bluffing our way through five games.''
</P>
<P>
   The man who will stand across the field from him on Monday night
at Giants Stadium for the 16th rendition of the Kickoff Classic
matches Bowden's Southern drawl syllable for syllable. But Texas
A&AMP;M Coach R.C. Slocum has his sights set more modestly. He simply
wants to get back to the Big 12 Conference championship game.
</P>
<P>
   But isn't it daunting to start a season against the team that is
ranked No. 2 by both coaches and the news media in the preseason
polls?
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win the game, then it's a big deal for Texas A&AMP;M,'' said
Slocum, whose team is ranked 15th by the coaches and 14th by the
news media. ``If we lose, then folks will say, `Well, FSU beat
another team.' There's no downside.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither the coaches nor their teams want to lose such
opportunities. But a proposal to eliminate such preseason matchups
is awaiting a vote by the National Collegiate Athletic Association
in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where good teams play meaningful games,'' Slocum said.
</P>
<P>
   The clash between the two Southern powers here before an
expected crowd of 60,000 takes on added meaning now that the Bowl
Championship Series is in place and promises to match the teams
ranked No. 1 and No. 2 in a title game, this year in the Fiesta
Bowl. While Seminole players talk about avoiding pitfalls, Slocum's
Aggies are focusing on opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of talent and depth, but we're young and
untested,'' said safety Dexter Jackson, one of only 10 seniors on
the team. ``We have some question marks. One mistake, and we're out
of what we spend every day thinking about: winning it all.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The biggest question is perhaps Chris Weinke, the 26-year-old
sophomore quarterback, who will start his first football game since
1989 after spending six years in baseball's minor leagues with the
Toronto Blue Jays organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real mature, very vocal kind of leader,'' said wide
receiver Peter Warrick, an all-America candidate who leads one of
the most talented receiving corps in the nation. ``He gets on us
and tells what we need to do. He'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   He will get a stern test. Even after sending Andre Wadsworth,
Sam Cowart and five others to the National Football League, the
Seminole defense will probably defend its title as the nation's
stingiest defense against the run. Tackle Jerry Johnson and
linebacker Lamont Green, certain to be high picks in next year's
NFL draft, lead a unit that Bowden says is the quickest he has ever
had.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a young, nasty and intense unit,'' Green said. ``Those
young guys at Texas A&AMP;M better come out ready to play us, or it's
going to be a long night for their offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies will start the freshman center Seth McKinney on a
line that returns only two starters. Dante Hall, D'Andre Hardeman
and Sirr Parker combined for more than 2,200 yards last year while
giving defenses three different looks to prepare for.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-8-inch Hall (a junior) is a duck-and-dive-style of
runner, Hardeman (a senior) is a bruiser and Parker (a senior) is a
breakaway threat who, Slocum said, ``can take it to the house''
every time he touches it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rotate so much that we wear defenses down,'' Parker said.
``And our line is just as good as it was last year. Nobody should
count us out of this game.''
</P>
<P>
   But the traditional strength of A&AMP;M has been defense, and the
Aggies once more have a swarming unit led by the undersized
linebacker Dat Nguyen. At 6-1 and 213 pounds, the senior is a
Butkus award candidate who has averaged 10.6 tackles a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just flat-out fun to watch,'' Bowden said. ``He's got
tremendous heart.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens on Monday, Bowden is not taking back the
talk about the national championship. ``Please remember after we
lose our first or second game that I said, `We have excellent
potential,''' he said. ``Now we'll see how good we are.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
