<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
     WHERE ARE THEY NOW?
<TEXT>
<P>
   - The Austrian newspaper Kro-Nenzeitung, which has a circulation
of 2.8 million, has canceled
 &UR; Hillary Clinton &LR; 's syndicated column because she hasn't commented
on the scandal that has plagued her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the world is continuously confronted with new details
about the president's sex scandal,'' said a note from the
newspaper's editors to its readers, `` &UR; Bill Clinton &LR; 's wife writes
about hurricanes. ... This is the reason we have decided to
discontinue `What Hillary Thinks.' ''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Paula Jones &LR; , forceful political advocate, is scheduled to
appear as guest of honor at a fund-raising banquet in October for
 &UR; Steve Arnold &LR; , who's running for re-election as a commissioner in
Guilford County, N.C. ``Paula Jones is an all-American middle-class
wife and mother,'' Arnold told the Greensboro (N.C.) News and
Record, ``whose only crime was to be seen and approached by Bill
Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   - Washingtonian magazine reports that  &UR; William Ginsburg &LR; , who
became famous as  &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR; 's lawyer, has agreed to take
part in a Funniest Celebrity contest this November. The event
raises money for the Child Welfare League.
</P>
<P>
   - And the Washington Post notes that brothers &UR; Bob Bennett &LR; , who
represents Bill Clinton, and  &UR; Bill Bennett &LR; , whose new book, ``The
Death of Outrage,'' is a best-seller, are making money off both
ends of the current scandal.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR;  &LR;  - In 1978, the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms
rejected a proposed Kenwood Winery label designed by
 &UR; David Lance Goines  &LR; because it depicted a nude woman reclining in a
vineyard. ``Obscene and indecent'' was the official ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, for a 20th anniversary bottle of the Artist Series
Cabernet Sauvignon, Kenwood resubmitted the original design,
approved this time with no fuss at all.
</P>
<P>
   - A journalist who interviewed  &UR; Willie Nelson &LR;  before a
performance in a Long Island, N.Y., music venue last week told the
New York Post he was so stoned afterward, from breathing in
second-hand smoke from ``at least six joints'' smoked by Nelson,
that he couldn't find his car. ``When I left the bus my head was
spinning. ... I was forced to get a hotel room in a Holiday Inn
across the street.'' A spokesman for the singer told the Post the
incident was ``possible.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Cher &LR; , who told Newsday ``We all have to move on,'' is having
her tattoos removed.
</P>
