<SLUG> BC-BKW-MERCURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTORY ELUDES THE PHOENIX MERCURY IN CHAMPIONSHIP SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 By MELANIE HAUSER    
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It was seven minutes away from winning the Women's
National Basketball Association title Saturday night. The Phoenix
Mercury had spent the first 33 minutes playing the way its coach
talks _ big and brash _ and was up by 12 points on the defending
champions' court.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as though Phoenix coach Cheryl Miller had been right a
month ago when she predicted that her team would upstage the
Houston Comets in the championship series and ``win that bad boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of cruising, the Mercury collapsed under the Comets'
pressure. Not just a press, but an all-out,
turn-it-up-down-the-stretch performance from Cynthia Cooper on
down. And, even though Phoenix did force overtime, it wound up
passing on what might have been the opportunity of the season as
Houston evened the two-of-three-game championship series with a
74-69 victory and forced a final showdown Tuesday here at the
Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the game, it was like, we were almost there,''
said guard Michelle Timms, who helped stake Phoenix to the lead,
which the Mercury held until late in the second half. ``You've
never got a game won against a team like that. We executed, but we
didn't come up with the offensive boards and we fell right into
their hands and what they love to play, the transition game. They
just jumped us. We just have to stay positive and play with a
passion down the stretch. After all, we were the ones who were 12
up.''
</P>
<P>
   A cut on Timms' left cheek and scratch marks across her neck
showed the intensity of Game 2. Phoenix's Jennifer Gillom also
appeared to have taken a beating. Gillom, who beat Houston on a
last-second jumper in Game 1, was 3 for 15 from the floor Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a difference between being double- and triple-teamed
and when you're actually being beat up,'' Gillom said. ``I've
experienced double- and triple-teams my whole life, but the way
they played me last night told me they were going to make sure I
didn't win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillom was so upset after the game Saturday that she did not
talk to reporters, nor did she go back to the hotel with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she went out to dinner with her family and let them
pick her up. But, she cautioned, she did not want to get too
relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still a little angry and still frustrated,'' she said on
Sunday. ``I need that going into Tuesday's game. I don't want to
forget about it. I feel like I let my team down and that's not a
good feeling. I've got to prove that pressure can't frustrate me.
I'm not going to try to score 30 points, but I am going to play the
best I can.''
</P>
<P>
   While Houston practiced Sunday, Miller gave her team a day away
from the court. The Mercury was in this same situation in the
semifinals a week ago and beat Cleveland in Cleveland. So, Miller
said, don't try to say the pressure is on her team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure's on both teams,'' Miller said. ``We're used to
it. This team is used to playing under pressure. We know what it
takes and that's 40 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   She paused and stared straight at a television camera from a
Houston station before she said, ``And I like our chances.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-98 2243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
