<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NEWHAMPSHIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIT CREW HELPS GORDON RALLY TO ANOTHER VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Once again, the efficient work of the pit crew
and a gutsy call by the crew chief Ray Evernham sent Jeff Gordon
off pit road with the lead late in the race. And once again, Gordon
held on to take the checkered flag.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon came back after falling to 17th place Sunday, winning his
second straight CMT 300 at New Hampshire International Speedway.
The victory was his ninth this season and gave him a slim 67-point
lead in the championship standing over Mark Martin, who finished
second to Gordon for the fourth time in the last six races. John
Andretti finished third.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon came into the pits in fifth place on Lap 232 of 300, and
he emerged leading, a result of quick work by his pit crew and a
crucial decision by Evernham, who put on just two right-side tires.
Martin, driving a Taurus, and Andretti, driving a Pontiac, both
burned time by taking on four new tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rainbow warriors and Ray have won a lot of races for us
this year,'' said Gordon, referring to the crew that wears rainbow
colors and works on his rainbow-colored Monte Carlo. ``And they did
it again today. I'm fortunate to have a guy like Ray making those
calls. I just had to be smooth with it, and not waste my tires.''
</P>
<P>
   Evernham said: ``I knew we had a good car. Going with two tires
just seemed like the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Evernham had made the same decision late in the Pennsylvania 500
last month, putting Gordon back in the lead ahead of Martin and on
his way to a victory.
</P>
<P>
   A week after cutting into Gordon's championship lead, Martin,
who led the most laps Sunday with 193, watched helplessly from his
pit stall as Gordon pulled out ahead of him. Again.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the race, the 24 car was just faster than us,''
said Martin, who brushed the wall at least once in the closing
laps, trying to catch up with Gordon. ``He just outran us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who had won four races in a row before finishing fifth
last week at Bristol, did something Sunday that had never been
accomplished: winning from the pole at New Hampshire. Gordon won
last year's race from 13th on the starting grid.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon led the opening two laps Sunday, but fell out of the
draft on the next lap and dropped to eighth. It was not long before
he was challenging the leaders, however, running in third and
closing in on Martin and Dale Jarrett, who finished fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon moved up to second after another efficient effort by his
pit crew on Lap 76, but had trouble finding his gears on the
restart. Again, he fell out of the lead draft, and this time slid
back to 17th.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were several times we were out of it,'' Gordon said.
``But we never gave up. That attitude won the race for us today. I
was pretty worried there for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett continues to keep himself in the chase for the
championship, having scored four straight top-five finishes. ``We
had a good race car,'' said Jarrett, driver of a Taurus, who fell
238 points behind Gordon. ``We got a top five, but again we lost
points. If you plan on gaining points in this thing, you have got
to win races. I guess we can't consider it a success.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-98 2243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
