<SLUG> BC-HORSE-ABUSE-DENY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN SAYS SHE NEVER HURT HORSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MELISSA SCHMITT  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A woman charged with cruelty to horses says she
has never mistreated animals of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   Renae Ferguson, 28, of suburban Tarzana declined comment on
allegations that she solicited donations to help a needy-children's
camp, then sold the donated horses.
</P>
<P>
   But she did refute claims she mistreated the horses, saying she
had spent her life caring for and loving them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were well cared for,'' Ferguson said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson and her parents, Ed Reddeck, 56, and Darlene Craig, 48,
were arrested on suspicion of cruelty to animals last week.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson has been charged with 13 misdemeanor counts of cruelty
to animals in Los Angeles County and also awaits trial in Ventura
County on two felony counts of cruelty to animals in a separate but
similar case.
</P>
<P>
   Reddeck said Thursday that the charges were part of a conspiracy
by government officials against his family.
</P>
<P>
   Police and animal regulation officials said the allegations stem
from horse donations solicited by Ferguson for what she said was a
riding camp for underprivileged children.
</P>
<P>
   Police said she neglected the horses while they were in her care
and then sold them.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson said the cruelty charges are false.
</P>
<P>
   She said she fed the horses regularly, and when a veterinarian
she hired checked the horses out after animal regulation officials
impounded them, the doctor gave the animals a clean bill of health.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson, Reddeck and Craig are free on $8,500 bond each.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-98 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980830.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9870 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHYLOCK-NYT &LR;      08-30 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHYLOCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHYLOCK AS AN UGLY CARICATURE WITH A HOPEFUL MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.) (ll) 
 By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENOX, Mass. _ The first sound heard in the outdoor production
of ``The Merchant of Venice,'' presented by Shakespeare &AMP; Co. here
this month was an Islamic call to prayer; the last was the Jewish
Yom Kippur chant, Kol Nidre.
</P>
<P>
   In between were plenty of other invocations of ethnic and
religious identity. A scimitar-wielding Moroccan and a buffoonish
Spaniard strutted the stage. Mentions were made of the foppish
French, the arrogant English and the drunken Germans.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there was the Jewish usurer Shylock, out for his
pound of flesh, seeming to care more about his ducats than his
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The framing incantations were the devices of the director, Tina
Packer, but the rest is all Shakespeare. This conglomeration of
what would now be called ethnic humor makes it thoroughly plausible
to see the play as Ms. Packer did: a work less concerned with a
carnivorous Jewish villain and his Christian victim than with the
relationships between minority cultures and their dominant hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Venice, after all, was one of the great trading cities of the
Renaissance, where citizens of many nations encountered one
another, submitting to a common law despite difference in dress,
manners, character and prose. It was also a society, as Shakespeare
showed quite deliberately, fraught with caricature and distrust. It
was, in other words, a culture very much like our own.
</P>
<P>
   In our contemporary version of Venice, questions about minority
cultures, their special rights and injuries have become a major
preoccupation, sometimes at the expense of common culture and
language. The Other, as the member of a minority culture is often
called, is now our conscience in debates about affirmative action
and school curriculums.
</P>
<P>
   Lessons about the mistreatment of the Other are common even in
the arts. The title of one film that opened earlier this month,
``Gadjo Dilo,'' directed by Tony Gatlif, means, rather loosely,
``crazy outsider'' in the Romany language of the movie's Gypsies. A
young Parisian is gradually welcomed into Gypsy society, but not
before he is greeted by suspicions more familiarly aimed in the
opposite direction. ``He's a thief!'' calls out one Gypsy. ``The
foreigner will take our women and children!'' shouts another.
</P>
<P>
   Shylock is treated that way as well; he is spit upon and called
a dog by the very man who comes to borrow his money. Fears about
the continuing legacy of such treatment even figured into debates
about this production of ``Merchant of Venice.''
</P>
<P>
   For two months before it opened, The Berkshire Eagle was
publishing letters rehearsing the familiar historical debates about
this play that has done so much to codify anti-Semitic caricature.
One correspondent suggested that the ``shrill voices'' strenuously
objecting to the play were so preoccupied with the Holocaust that
they could ``only give credence to the Shylock stereotype.'' That
unwitting application of the stereotype inspired another round of
argument.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of this contemporary battleground of Others, there
are real wounds suffered and real debts incurred; there are
sensitivities to attend to and histories to interpret. The
accounting of all this Otherness has taken on an obsessive life of
its own. Can our latter-day Venice thrive with such a continuous
accounting? After all, the problem faced by Shakespeare's
multicultural city is not how to give each Other his due, but how
to maintain a rule of common law in a society ruled by uncommon
difference.
</P>
<P>
   This is why Shylock's bond was taken seriously by the Venetian
court. His claim for flesh could not be simply dismissed because
the ``course of law,'' a ``commodity'' as it is called in the play,
was what allowed ``the trade and profit of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem the play poses for modern interpretation is that we
can hardly consider this law purely virtuous. We might cheer the
court's decision not to award Shylock his flesh, but otherwise the
judgment that Shylock should lose his worldly goods and be forced
to convert to Christianity seems to undercut the hope of a society
of Others bound by law. This is why Ms. Packer went to such trouble
to insert the final Jewish prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the dramatic bluntness here, Kol Nidre declares null and
void all rash oaths and bonds made to God during the year,
including, perhaps, Shylock's forced conversion. The prayer's
inclusion signaled the production's recognition of an injustice
latent in Venetian justice.
</P>
<P>
   But often that is as far as we take it. To a contemporary
audience, this injustice might even seem proof that the attempt to
create a transcendent set of laws and values is doomed. The play,
though, is far more subtle. One of its recurrent questions is not
just how law can work in Venice but how trade can.
</P>
<P>
   In a commercial society, standards of measurement and judgment
need to be consistent. Are the goods what they seem? Do containers
reveal or hide their contents? Such standards are not just
important for commerce. In a diverse society, how do we learn to
judge our fellow citizens? How can character be discerned from
appearance?
</P>
<P>
   This is why the subplot of Portia's marriage is so prominent. A
suitor must choose either a gold, silver or lead casket; hidden
within one is Portia's portrait and the promise of her hand in
marriage. Each suitor must judge substance from surface, discern
meaning from appearance. ``Mislike me not for my complexion,''
pleads the black Prince of Morocco before he makes a choice of
caskets, referring to yet another stereotype linking appearance to
character. Caricature, prejudgment by appearance, is not to be
trusted.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the play is full of such mistakes (and even Shakespeare got
it wrong when it came to the Jews). Lorenzo thinks Jessica ``true''
at the moment of her greatest lie; Antonio thinks Shylock most kind
when he is most vengeful. ``The world is still deceiv'd with
ornament,'' declares Portia's suitor, Bassanio. In law, he
continues, a corrupt and evil plea might be camouflaged by using a
gracious voice; in religion, ``damned error'' can be hidden by
``fair ornament.'' One almost begins to wonder about the gracious
voice and fair ornament of Portia's famous speech about mercy that
``droppeth as the gentle rain from heaven,'' spoken just before she
lowers the boom on the Jew.
</P>
<P>
   So there are more ambiguities in this play than there seem at
first. But despite its flaws, despite its having tapped into some
of the deepest strands of racial hatred in Western culture, the
play is relentless in its preoccupations with the possibility of a
common law and shared standards. The play accounts for the
difficulties and sometimes embodies them, but the effort is
unrelenting. In our cultural climate, that makes it more than worth
its burden of caricature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
