<DOCNO> NYT19980830.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9989 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-PURDUE-USC-LADN     08-30 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PURDUE-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC BEATS PURDUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was officially deemed the start of the Paul
Hackett era, but his USC debut was overshadowed Sunday by what
probably was the birth of the Carson Palmer era.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett accomplished what no USC coach had in 47 years _ he won
his opening game. But it was the unexpected boost from Palmer that
lifted the Trojans' morale and woke up USC's struggling offense.
</P>
<P>
   The true freshman quarterback entered the game in the third
quarter and supplied the passing and momentum to surge the Trojans
past Purdue 27-17 in the Pigskin Classic before 56,623 at the
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dramatic comeback performance for Hackett's opener, and
the energetic coach seemed relieved and excited after earning his
first victory at USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``One down,'' Hackett told his players at the center of the
field immediately after the game. Then he raced across the field
and up the Coliseum tunnel waving a ``V'' sign with his fingers to
the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you win coming from behind, and the team believes in
itself, it feels great,'' Hackett said. ``We've taken a step. One
step.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been some pretty good football coaches that haven't
won their first game since Howard Jones in 1951.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Jones coached from 1925-40, but it was 1951 when Jess
Hill won his opener, something the next six USC coaches were unable
to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming up the tunnel, the players told me, `We'll find a way
to get you a win,''' Hackett said. ``It's just very hard the first
time out.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a difficult and sloppy victory, but around USC, no one
complains about style points anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Especially when someone as precocious as Palmer lifts the team's
spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer entered the game with 5:03 left in the third quarter and
the Trojans trailing 17-10. His fourth snap from scrimmage, he
lofted a perfect 41-yard pass to wide receiver Larry Parker that
set up the game-tying touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   USC scored a field goal on his next series to take a 20-10 lead.
Not bad for a guy who didn't know he was playing until five minutes
before kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, yeah, I was pretty surprised. I didn't know I was
going to play,'' Palmer said. ``It was just a great feeling. I
expected to be really nervous, but I wasn't. I wasn't half as
nervous as I was in high school.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Hackett described himself in training camp by saying,
``I'm not a rotate-the-quarterbacks kind of guy,'' he decided
before the game to play Palmer in the third quarter instead of
starter Mike Van Raaphorst.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a plan ahead of time, the third series of the third
quarter, Carson would get two series,'' Hackett said. ``All along
we've had a plan with Carson. Carson will see playing time, but
Mike is the starter.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer completed 3 of 6 passes for 79 yards while Van Raaphorst
completed 11 of 22 for 89 yards and an interception. Hackett
sounded like there was no controversy, but he rarely tips his hand
on such matters, so there should be plenty of speculation in the
next two weeks about who is USC's No.1 quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a coach's decision,'' Van Raaphorst said. ``You've got to
talk to him to see what he wants to do. You like to stay in there,
if you can. I'm going to go out and battle. There's no adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst was sorer after the game from a couple of hits he
took from Purdue defensive end Rosevelt Colvin, but it's clear the
Trojans' quarterback position is more in doubt today than at any
point during training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Even Palmer's teammates noticed a difference as soon as he
entered the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounded like the crowd gave him a standing ovation or
something. I personally got fired up,'' wide receiver Billy Miller
said. ``One day, this guy might be up for the Heisman.''
</P>
<P>
   If Palmer ignited the offense, the Trojans' defense also
regrouped in the second half. After allowing 17 points in the first
half, the defense shut out Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Chris Claiborne and defensive back Antuan Simmons
intercepted quarterback Drew Brees, and linebacker David Gibson
recovered a fumble as the Trojans solved Purdue's single-back
scheme.
</P>
<P>
   It was a far cry from the first quarter, when Purdue had the
ball for nearly 13 minutes and led USC in first downs 8-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first quarter, that was unexpected. You've got to expect
the worst, and that was the worst,'' defensive end Sultan
Abdul-Malik said. ``We weren't being aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   USC was also foolish, with several offsides penalties and even
the dreaded 12-men-on-field infraction. Only Chad Morton's 98-yard
kickoff return saved the game from getting away from the Trojans,
and Purdue led just 17-10 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   But the USC defense was nearly flawless in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our defense said, `Let's set our jaw and play our base
defense and just play,''' Hackett said. ``We needed something to
turn the tide. (The turnovers) just charged up our sideline.''
</P>
<P>
   If Hackett wanted to put his stamp on the Trojans, maybe just
winning a game with a second-half comeback is something unique. USC
teams have routinely been worn down or squandered leads in the
second half the past two seasons, and the players noticed the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we rallied in the second half, it sticks out in my
mind a lot,'' Miller said. ``It was a situation where something was
going wrong in the fourth quarter, and we'd lose in the end. I
doubt this will happen this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
