<P>
   (NYT10) TOMS RIVER, N.J. -- Aug. 30, 1998 -- BOO-LITTLE-LEAGUE,
8-30 -- Toms River players basking in the adulation of their town's
residents on Sunday, one day after winning their first Little
League World Series. Many in the boisterous throng brought signs
and banners, including one hanging from the side of a camper van
that read: ``Marry me Chris Cardone. Love, Alexa.'' Chris, who hit
the game-winning home run, does not necessarily need to stock up on
wedding clothes yet -- Alexa Manforti is only 7. (Chang W. Lee/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Aug. 30, 1998 -- YOUTH-MARCH-LEADER, 8-30 --
Khallid Abdul Muhammad, fresh from victory in a federal courtroom
last week, where a judge cleared the way for his Million Youth
March in Harlem Saturday. While New Yorkers are finding that they
must deal with Muhammad, or at least with his venomous words,
precisely who he is and what he represents have long been a mystery
to many. ``I'm just not sure I want white folks to know that much
about me,'' says Muhammad. ``I'd rather in some cases be an enigma.
It's safer.'' (Michelle V. Agins/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) TOLEDO, Wash. -- Aug. 30, 1998 -- FARM-OLD-MACHINERY,
8-30 -- Stuart Zion of Kent, Wash., pitching oats into a 1946 John
Deere thresher while his cousin, Ben Klein takes a break. Vintage
farm machinery, like the 1946 thresher, was the main attraction at
the annual Cowlitz Prairie Steam Threshing and Gas Show. ``By the
serial number, it's supposed to be one of the last six made,'' says
Zion. ``It pretty much stays in the family. Our grandfather used to
work like this in Colorado.'' (Larry Davis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNIONDALE, N.J. -- Aug. 30, 1998 -- EPA-TESTING-2, 8-30
-- Paul Maresca, a senior research associate for OSI
Pharmaceuticals, will soon be using advanced automated techniques
to test chemicals found in everyday products from plastics to
pesticides for potentially harmful effects on people and wildlife.
OSI Pharmaceuticals, using much the same techniques, already
screens 7 million chemicals a year looking for potential new
medicines. (Vic DeLucia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNIONDALE, N.J. -- Aug. 30, 1998 -- EPA-TESTING-1, 8-30
-- Steel-clawed robots at OSI Pharmaceuticals screen seven million
chemicals a year looking for potential new medicines. Under
contract to the Environmental Protection Agency, OSI has is gearing
up for one of the most ambitious projects ever proposed, to show
how the drug industry's advanced automated techniques for hunting
down useful compounds could also be used to quickly screen
thousands of everyday chemicals found in products for harmful side
effects. (Vic DeLucia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PRISTINA, Serbia -- Aug. 30, 1998 -- KOSOVO-SERBS, 8-30
-- A photo of Dragan Smigic, when he was in the Yugoslav Army, was
found in the Serbian family's destroyed home in Leucina, Kosovo.
The Smigics and nearly every ethnic Serbian family that lived in
areas controlled by the rebels have fled or disappeared. More than
80 Serb civilians are missing and human rights workers believe that
they have been killed. Many say that the kidnappings and terror are
part of the strategy of ethnic Albanian rebels. (Staton R.
Winter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) HARBIN, China -- Aug. 30, 1998 -- CHINA-ARMY, 8-30 --
Chinese soldiers guarding two makeshift dikes that protect the city
of Harbin from the Songhua River. The city's main dike is
submerged. With hundreds of thousands of soldiers as the backbone
of the nation's defense, this summer's record breaking floods have
provided the scandal-prone People's Liberation Army with both a
challenging battle and a golden opportunity for image burnishing.
(Elisabeth Rosenthal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- Aug. 30, 1998 -- VIOLIN-PRODIGY-2-B&AMP;W, 8-30 --
Joshua Bell, now 30, the superb American violinist, practicing as a
child. Although great scrutiny has fallen on the psychological
perils of prodigyhood and the difficulties of parlaying an early
start into a mature career, Bell's current success shows that those
pitfalls are by no means inevitable or insurmountable. (New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Aug. 30, 1998 -- VIOLIN-PRODIGY-1, 8-30 --
Joshua Bell, the superb American violinist, who began performing
widely in his teens. Despite the boyish demeanor he retains at 30,
Bell has long since established himself as a mature artist. ``From
my point of view, there really wasn't any kind of transition to
make,'' says Bell. ``I never started to play 100 concerts a season
until much later, and I had worked my way up. I didn't feel
pressure from my parents, my teacher or anybody, and I always loved
to play.'' (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Aug. 30, 1998 -- TV-COP, 8-30 -- Mike
Sheehan, 50, a former New York Police Department undercover officer
and detective for 25 years, now reports for Fox 5 news. Sheehan is
from the old school. No handlers. No agents. Shoot from the hip.
``The hardest part of accepting this job, was convincing some of
the past pinheads and pencil-necked geeks -- journalists with
little street knowledge -- that I wasn't some dumb slob, but a
trained investigator who knows the streets,'' says Sheehan.
(Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
