<DOCNO> NYT19980830.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0009 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-DODGERS-NYT &LR;      08-30 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DODGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS DEFEAT METS, 4-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After rallying for two come-from-behind victories
at Dodger Stadium the past two days, the New York Mets had a chance
to jump on one of their former teammates, Dave Mlicki, early on
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   But even though they rocked Mlicki for eight hits, including two
home runs, in the first five innings, the Mets had only a two-run
lead to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   And then the Dodgers rallied for two runs off Masato Yoshii in
the fifth and again in the seventh, en route to a 4-2 victory.
Mlicki (8-6) had nine strikeouts and no walks, and he retired the
last 13 batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   The loss evened the Mets' record on this nine-game Western swing
at 3-3. More important, it dropped the Mets (75-62) back into a tie
in the National League wild-card race because Chicago had defeated
Colorado earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the Mets jumped out to an early lead. After Mike
Piazza had removed himself from the game after taking an Eric Young
foul ball off his right shoulder in the top of the first, Carlos
Baerga drilled a 3-1 pitch from Mlicki into the left-field pavilion
with one out in the second for a 1-0 lead. The home run was
Baerga's sixth of the season and first since May 31, snapping a
string of 279 at-bats without one.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Edgardo Alfonzo led off the top of the third with his 13th
homer, his second in two days, a solo shot that landed in the
left-field pavilion and gave the Mets a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets failed to capitalize on many other opportunities.
They left runners on first and second with nobody out in the first,
stranded a runner on second in the second and a runner on third in
the third. And even though they had pounded eight hits off Mlicki,
it was still a 2-0 game heading into the bottom of the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Then Yoshii ran into trouble for the first time. He had allowed
just two singles over his first four innings. But Bobby Bonilla led
off the fifth with a fly out to the warning track in center. Mark
Grudzielanek followed with his second sharp single to left and then
took third on Tom Prince's ground-rule double to left.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii struck out Mlicki for the second out of the inning, but
Young grounded the first pitch past Rey Ordonez and into left field
for a two-run single to tie the score. Young took second on the
throw, and Yoshii was able to strike out Trenidad Hubbard after a
long at-bat to preserve the tie.
</P>
<P>
   Both starters set the side down in order in the sixth. But,
after the Mets went down in order in the top of the seventh, Yoshii
allowed a leadoff single to Bonilla and a double inside of third to
Grudzielanek, the Dodger shortstop's third hit of the game, and
that was it for Yoshii, who dropped to 5-8. On came Turk Wendell,
who surrendered a one-strike double to Prince, which cleared the
bases and gave the Dodgers a 4-2 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
