</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QB CONTROVERSY BREWS AT USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After thousands of fans fled the frying pan known
as the Los Angeles Coliseum at halftime Sunday, they didn't miss
only the next 30 minutes of USC football.
</P>
<P>
   They missed the next (ITAL)four years(END ITAL) of USC football.
They missed a glimpse of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well, they'll have lots of chances to catch Carson Palmer's
act in more comfortable conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Write this down: By season's end, when the brisk breezes of
winter replace the 99-degree heat of opening day, Palmer will be
the Trojans' starting quarterback and they'll be a better team
because of it.
</P>
<P>
   The towering, tow-headed, 18-year-old freshman from Santa
Margarita High in Laguna Niguel made that kind of impression when
he relieved third-year sophomore starter Mike Van Raaphorst in the
third quarter of the game against Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   In two offensive series, he led the Trojans to a tying touchdown
run by Petros Papadakis and a go-ahead field goal by Adam Abrams.
He didn't win the quarterback job then and there; Van Raaphorst
returned to the field for two unproductive possessions.
</P>
<P>
   But in the fourth quarter, Palmer was back for one more series,
and the result was a Chad Morton touchdown sprint that ensured a
27-17 USC victory in front of about two-thirds of the original
56,623 fans.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad way to break in: three possessions, 17 points, and
eye-catching pass completions of 42 yards to Larry Parker and 28
yards to Billy Miller on a crucial third down.
</P>
<P>
   So let's see what we have here: two quarterbacks, one young yet
experienced and the other younger yet stronger, shuttling on and
off the field, and the backup outplaying the starter. This has all
the makings of a quarterback controversy, an early public-relations
test for new USC coach Paul Hackett, a well-known wizard of the
passing game.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said after Sunday's game, ``This is Mike's team. He's
earned the opportunity.'' He added: ``But we're in the process of
developing a really fine young quarterback (Palmer) and we need to
give him some playing time.''
</P>
<P>
   So I ask you: Where's the controversy?
</P>
<P>
   If the 6-foot-5 Palmer continues to measure up, learns to run
Hackett's varied offense as quickly as expected, it's only a matter
of time before he's starting. Hackett will know when that time
comes.
</P>
<P>
   He knew when Palmer's time came Sunday because he scheduled it.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes before the kickoff, Hackett told both quarterbacks of
his plan to insert Palmer for the second and third series of the
second half, regardless of the numbers on the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   It just happened that the Trojans needed a lift at that moment,
having gone punt-interception-punt since the second-quarter field
goal that cut Purdue's lead to 17-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right when I was going in, I was thinking, `Don't mess up the
first play,''' Palmer said. Then he messed up the first play by
overthrowing an open Ted Iacenda.
</P>
<P>
   The second play made up for that. A crisp pass nailed Mike
Bastianelli on a slant pattern for 9 yards. After Morton ran for a
first down, Palmer dodged one rusher, threw flat-footed over
another and hit Parker for 42 yards inside the Purdue 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed that he stepped up and put it right on the
money,'' Hackett said of the play of the game. ``The amazing thing
was that he kept it to the outside (of the defender). That was all
arm. Normally a ball like that will die on you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans were energized. So were their fans _ the ones who'd
been wilting in the heat and the ones who by then were listening on
the radio in air-conditioned cars.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer's and Van Raaphorst's teammates said the right things
later, claiming there really wasn't a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the difference is that Mike has more experience,''
Morton said. ``But as you can see from Carson's performance, that
doesn't seem to matter much.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst (11 for 21 for 89 yards and an interception) was
gracious, saying Palmer's heroics were ``good for the team, and
that's that.'' But he wished he'd been allowed to pass more.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer (3 for 6 for 79 yards) admitted making some mistakes and
talked about ``team.'' Sure, he said, his personal goal is to be
the starting quarterback, but there's a bigger objective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to go to the Rose Bowl,'' Palmer said. ``And I think we
have a team that can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: If the Trojans go to the Rose Bowl, they'll do it
with Carson Palmer at quarterback. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
