</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC DOESN'T WILT IN HEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES - The men in black shoes looked cooked 16 minutes
into their season opener against Purdue, and not just because their
soles might as well have been steaks on the backyard grill in the
118-degree heat on the Coliseum field.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-five seconds into the second quarter of the Pigskin
Classic, the USC football team trailed Purdue by 10 points. At that
point, the Trojans had minus-1 yard of total offense to Purdue's
133 yards and zero first downs to Purdue's eight.
</P>
<P>
   To put it kindly, their feet were about all that was sizzling.
The Trojans would adjust their defensive scheme and tinker with
their personnel in the second half but there would be no changing
the footwear that made them feel like they were walking barefoot on
a blazing beach.
</P>
<P>
   Black shoes, after all, are one of the few traditions that
haven't gone the way of Student Body Right.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in decades past, the Trojans no longer can be counted on
to churn out the Pac-10's finest running backs while contending for
national championships. For at least one sweltering day, though,
they gave their faithful reason not to sweat the team's prospects
for 1998 and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans scored 20 unanswered points - 17 of them in the
second half - for a 27-17 win over the Boilermakers, an aptly-named
opponent considering it was so hot the 56,623 spectators could have
been forgiven for wondering if that was Traveler V or a camel being
ridden around the field after each of USC's three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Chad Morton brought the Trojans' equine mascot galloping
out of the tunnel the first time, running back Purdue's first
kickoff 98 yards to tie the game at 7. Purdue regained the lead
with a 39-yard scoring drive and padded it with a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   USC trimmed the deficit to a touchdown by halftime on a 60-yard
drive that culminated with the first of senior placekicker Adam
Abrams' two field goals. The stands thinned noticeably during the
intermission as the fans fled from the heat and probably also from
still-fresh memories of so many second-half meltdowns.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 USC football team that finished 6-5, failed to advance
to the postseason for the second consecutive season and cost coach
John Robinson his job wore down noticeably as their games wore on.
They were outscored 96-48 in the second half of their eight Pac-10
contests under Robinson, who was neither a paradigm of fitness nor,
apparently, a stickler when it came to his own players'
conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   After assessing his troops during spring practice, new field
general Paul Hackett decided the players needed a summer vacation
less than they did a voluntary boot camp. He left them with
conditioning suggestions and a stern warning that training camp
would be devoted to getting the playbook down pat, not getting in
shape.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 75 players took Hackett's words to heart and stayed in
L.A., gathering daily to do sprints and crunches. Cook and the
others lifted weights and, when required, one another's spirits.
</P>
<P>
   They built stamina and muscles and camaraderie. Then they
reported to UC Irvine for training camp and for three weeks Hackett
and his accomplice, strength and conditioning coach Matt Schiotz,
totally tore them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Camp Hackett was so hard, I got physically ill,'' said junior
guard Travis Claridge, the anchor of an inexperienced offensive
line. ``There were some times, I was throwing up even before
practice because I was just exhausted. What we went through there
was literally hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Miller, a senior receiver from Westlake Village, caught a
team-high four passes to help make Hackett's head coaching debut a
success, then admitted there were times in the days leading up to
the opener when he felt hate in his racing heart for Hackett
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times I was sweating, I was dehydrated and I was so
tired I was thinking to myself, `I hope this pays off,''' Miller
said. ``And you know what? It did.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not kidding. All four of Miller's receptions came in the
second half when all of his leg muscles should have been
complaining vehemently.
</P>
<P>
   But then, all the Trojans seemed to turn up their intensity even
as Mother Nature was turning up the heat.
</P>
<P>
   The USC defense recorded both its sacks in the second half when
it should have been bent over at the waist, wheezing. Linebacker
Chris Claiborne and Antuan Simmons each intercepted Purdue
quarterback Drew Brees in the final two quarters when the only
things they should have been trying to catch were their breaths.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Schiotz wound up with a game ball for his
contributions to the win.
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne's pick in the waning moments of the third quarter set
up a 45-yard field goal from Abrams that put USC ahead for good at
20-17. Quarterback Carson Palmer, showing a poise that belied his
true freshman status, led the Trojans on their final scoring drive,
which was highlighted by a 28-yard pass to Miller and punctuated by
a 13-yard run by Morton.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer earlier had led the offense to its first score. He
spelled incumbent starter Mike Van Raaphorst with five minutes left
in the third and threw a 42-yard strike to Larry Parker to set up
Petros Papadakis' first collegiate touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, preferably sooner than later, Palmer will be
handed the keys to the USC offense. But for now, Hackett said, the
starting job belongs to the sophomore, Van Raaphorst, who can read
defenses and body language well enough to know the game was USC's
long before the final seconds ticked off the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were wearing down a little bit in the second half,'' he
said. ``I think the smog might have had a little something to do
with it. And I think we were in better condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that, a USC team built to last. For a program looking to
regain its past glory, that's a good start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-98 2353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
