r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     08-30 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QB CONTROVERSY BREWS AT USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What would life be at USC if there wasn't some
controversy, some football pot boiling over with suggestions and
speculation from the alumni and media?
</P>
<P>
   Game one of the Paul Hackett era wasn't even three quarters old
Sunday before the pundits threw out the first debate. In the season
opener against Purdue at the Coliseum, where a sweaty time was had
by all, Hackett started sophomore Mike Van Raaphorst at quarterback
but ended with true freshman Carson Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   The early returns after a 27-17 win showed Palmer being the
quarterback of record for 17 of the 20 points the Trojans' offense
scored. In the world of instant analysis, we have a meaningful exit
poll.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett will have none of this, of course. He has no desire to
look upon game one as the equivalent of the New Hampshire primary.
Van Raaphorst is the starting quarterback, but Palmer and Dominguez
High's Jason Thomas are going to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the mistake a lot of coaches make is to put one
quarterback on a pedestal and treat the rest of the quarterbacks as
backups,'' said the hyperactively sincere Hackett after becoming
the first USC coach since 1951 to win his debut. ``You have to
coach the kids the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the quarterbacks learn by sitting in the same room.
We've adjusted the repetitions (in practice) so it's 50-50 for Mike
and Carson.'' Thomas is injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, here we have one guy who has been here three weeks
(Palmer) learning a complex offense, and he's doing real well, and
we have another (Van Raaphorst) who is a 3.8 student who has a good
spring behind him and knows the offense,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have Mike for three years, and Carson for four years, and
Jason for four years. My goodness gracious, we're going to go
recruit us some linemen.''
</P>
<P>
   That shouldn't be a problem, as long as the quarterback issue
doesn't become one. USC, after all, lost two in fall drills. John
Fox moved to tight end and Quincy Woods to receiver after seeing
the crowd under center.
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst, who led USC to a 45-21 win over Stanford in one
of his two starts last season, didn't necessarily do anything wrong
Sunday. The offense in the first half simply flunked rhythm. It ran
a grand total of six plays for minus-one yard in the first quarter.
Van Raaphorst completed four of five passes on a second quarter
drive to a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst was intercepted on USC's first second half drive,
and the second drive sputtered at midfield. The next time USC got
the ball, Palmer replaced Van Raaphorst.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said the plan always was to insert the Santa Margarita
High product after the first two series of the third quarter. It
was serendipity that his insertion would come with USC trailing
17-10 and turn out so meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer overthrew Ted Iacenda on his first play. ``I was praying
all day that I wouldn't screw up my first play,'' said Palmer,
``and that's exactly what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer then hit Mike Bastianelli for nine yards on the next, and
then showed why he was shared the title of best quarterback in the
prep class of '98 with Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   He took a straight drop, stepped up from a hard backside rush,
replanted himself, and, with a Purdue linemen in his face, threw a
strike to Larry Parker for 42 yards. USC scored three runs later to
make it 17-17.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the deep ball, I saw Larry with a shorter cornerback on
him,'' Palmer said. Everything else, the nice footwork, the ensuing
touchdown, is a blank. ``All I remember is Larry catching the ball
and my jumping around.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a true freshman.
</P>
<P>
   It is only proper to insert a word of caution here. It's not
like Palmer just won himself as Rose Bowl. Hackett admitted that
Palmer was working off a short sheet of plays, too. He still has a
lot to learn.
</P>
<P>
   And two of the last three USC quarterbacks to win a Rose Bowl
were fellows who never graced a prep All-America list, Tim Green
and Brad Otton. The third was Todd Marinovich, who hit all of the
notes, high and low, during his USC career.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer didn't really play a major role in the rest of USC's
offense Sunday. The ensuing series to the go-ahead field goal was
set up by a Purdue turnover. Van Raaphorst then returned for the
next two series.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer was reinserted for the run-out-the-clock finale. His
third down, 28-yard completion to Billy Miller ended Purdue's hopes
and led to USC's clinching touchdown. But that pass was more shot
put then spiral.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Mike's team,'' said Hackett. ``But you're not going to
not let a guy like Carson in the game. You can see his skill and
ability. When he's ready to play more, he'll play more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any quarterback will tell you he'd like all the reps and
playing time,'' said Van Rasphorst. ``But my mom would smack me if
I wasn't (respectful of Palmer). I was raised to respect people.
It's not an antagonistic relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Controversy is what you guys will talk about. We'll get along.
All you ever have is each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming off two bowl-less seasons, maybe USC can afford letting
any quarterback debate play itself out, and in trusting the
judgment of the old quarterback coach, who is the new head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, quarterback is the one position I'm familiar with,'' said
Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-98 2354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
