<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0034 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-SOSA-HOMERUNS-1ST     08-30 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SOSA-HOMERUNS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA HITS 54TH HOMER AS CUBS BEAT ROCKIES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 4th, 5th and 16th grafs for updating)  (nk) 
 By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Sammy Sosa's 54th was a long one. Cubs fans Mike and
Karen Bressler were settling into the last row at Coors Field when
the ball sailed over their heads like a plane taking off for
Chicago. The line drive bounced off the scoreboard girders about
four stories above the field, producing a rugby scrum in search of
a souvenir.
</P>
<P>
   ``One guy had just gotten his hot dogs and fries and everybody
ran him over,'' said Mike Bressler, 41, who moved to Denver from
Wheaton, Ill. ``There were hot dogs everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of the pile emerged a bruised but glorious T.J. Salvador of
Ft. Collins, Colo., with a Cubs souvenir to match his Cubs shirt.
He offered the ball to Sosa after the game, but the slugger let the
fan keep it.
</P>
<P>
   The Ruthian clout, estimated at 482 feet, was the longest home
run of the 171 hit so far this year at Coors Field. And it
temporarily tied the Chicago Cubs right fielder with St. Louis'
Mark McGwire, eight homers from breaking a record that is older
than they are: Roger Maris' 61 home runs in 1961. McGwire was born
in 1963, Sosa in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night in St. Louis, McGuire moved back ahead, hitting
his 55th in the seventh inning of the Cardinals' game with the
Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   In his first-inning at bat, Sosa missed a fastball to fall
behind 1-2 in the count. He waited for right-hander Darryl Kile's
next pitch, a slider that stayed over the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see where it landed,'' Sosa said. ``I'm just trying
to be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-run home run drew a devotional ovation from the home
crowd of 48,255, and respect from the Rockies players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It silenced the dugout,'' said Rockies Manager Don Baylor.
``No ballpark's going to hold that ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The home crowd was disappointed in the finish, a 4-3 Cubs'
victory, but also because Sosa hit only one home run. He popped out
in the third, struck out swinging in the fifth and walked in the
eighth, only to be thrown out trying to steal second.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Sosa declined to assume the role of favorite to
pass Maris, repeating his mantra: ``This is the Mark McGwire show.
If I get it first, God bless America.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa could cool off and still break the record with ease. He
needs a home run in about one out of three remaining games. In the
past three months he has hit better than one home run in every two
games (45 home runs in 84 games, beginning with two home runs on
May 25). In August he has stepped up the pace, hitting eight homers
in his past 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire and Sosa each need just two more homers to tie the
National League record, which is also the Cubs' record, 56, set by
Hack Wilson in 1930. In 123 years of National League games, only
Wilson has hit more than 54 home runs. Ralph Kiner of Pittsburgh
also had 54, in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sosa's second home run in six games this year in
Colorado, where home runs are plentiful. The Cubs and Rockies
splattered 23 home runs and 164 hits in six games there. Other
homers Sunday came from Gary Gaetti (his 13th) and Jose Hernandez
(21) of the Cubs, and Larry Walker (20) of the Rockies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For Cubs Manager Jim Riggleman, the best part of Sunday's game
was pitching, despite the homer onslaught. Kevin Tapani, now 16-7,
gave up only two runs in seven innings. Cubs pitchers had an ERA of
6.91 in the previous 11 games. Sunday, the Cubs got outs from
left-handers Felix Heredia and Terry Mulholland. Then Rod Beck
pitched through another harrowing ninth inning, walking two before
putting away his 39th save. Kile (10-15) was the loser.
</P>
<P>
   The victory helped the Cubs tie the New York Mets in the
wild-card race. The Mets lost to the Los Angeles Dodgers on Sunday,
4-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs clubhouse was all smiles as the players watched the
Giants lose to the Phillies. The Cubs now are 76-61. Last year at
this point they were 55-82.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs were packing their bats for Wrigley Field, where on
Monday night Kerry Woods will pitch against Cincinnati's Brett
Tomko, who surrendered a home run to Sosa just last week. They
leave town with a 5-1 record at Coors Field, where last year they
failed to win a game.
</P>
</TEXT>
